<HEADLINE>
MERCEDES SL500 TAKES THE HIGH ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's one of the best privileges of wealth, the Mercedes-Benz
SL500, a showy bauble most likely spotted on Scottsdale Road or in
the front row of nightclub parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, like the well-equipped Sport version, serving as
a companion for an interesting romp over a mountain road.
</P>
<P>
   The SL500 is one of the broadest statements of disposable
wealth, serving notice to the world that you have arrived. Or, if
you prefer to swim even farther upstream, there's the 12-cylinder
SL600 for a cool $45,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   SL500 shoppers should rejoice that Mercedes has dropped the
price a full 11 percent under last year's V-8 model, which comes to
a $10,000 reduction. Or about one Chrysler Neon.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, under the new dynamics of the Chrysler-Benz
megamerger, the SL might be going up against one of its own, the
awesome V-10 Dodge Viper sports car. And if you count the Viper and
Mercedes' hot C43, the merged company will have sporting cars
powered by V-6, V-8, V-10 and V-12 engines.
</P>
<P>
   The SL500 is not exactly a sports car, though it has more than
four decades of sporting history behind it, going back to the
glorious 300SL Gullwings and roadsters, raced in the '50s by such
stars as Stirling Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mercedes' image machine is more of a heavy cruiser among
fast GTs, endowed with enough style and panache to make performance
something of a secondary issue.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car was set up with the Sport package, basically a
$5,000 package of performance tires and wheels plus aerodynamics
additions. The aero add-ons do little more than make the Benz look
more rakish, but the huge 18-inch rims and low-profile Z-rated
tires seem to have a major effect on the roadster's ride and
handling.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they give the heavy car a much sportier edge. In a
fast drive on Arizona 89A over Mingus Mountain and back again, the
SL soared through the many hairpin curves with an excellent feeling
of balance and steering precision.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with an SL that I drove over the same route a couple
years back, the new car felt more poised and responsive, and not
nearly as encumbered by its 2-ton heft.
</P>
<P>
   The slick silver roadster had a noticeably firmer ride than
``normal'' SL500s, undoubtedly the result of the low-profile tires.
</P>
<P>
   Derrieres more used to luxury rides might find the bumps and
rumbles objectionable, but I thought the stiffness made the car
feel more edgy and ready to run.
</P>
<P>
   The mountain grades were no match for the strong V-8, which
roars in an aggressive race-car timbre when pushed into the upper
revs. This is a sweet engine, with lots of torque throughout its
range.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed automatic, which adjusts electronically to
accommodate driver's inputs from sedate to aggressive, and even
road grades, performs flawlessly, mating well with the flexible
engine power.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes' customary ``gated'' shifter makes it easier to shift
manually, which is helpful when downshifting for curves, but it
seems a shame there's no stick shift available for this car.
</P>
<P>
   The test SL was equipped with Mercedes' Electronic Stability
System, or ESP, that can sense skidding and apply the brake to any
one of the wheels to restore control. It's designed to keep drivers
from getting in too much over their heads, though some drivers
might find it an unwelcome intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for the traction-control system, which senses rear-wheel
spin, then brakes or cuts back engine power to restore traction.
Although appreciated in snow or other slippery conditions, this
system also can intrude, feeling like someone suddenly dropping the
anchor.
</P>
<P>
   The car also was equipped with a special brake-assist system
that actually shortens stopping distance, particularly in a
panic-stop situation. On initial input, though, the brake pedal
feels weird, as if the brakes might not grab. They do, of course,
and work very well, but that fleeting panic is disconcerting.
</P>
<P>
   Other safety systems include twin roll bars that pop up behind
the seats if the car senses an impending flip, and a sensor in the
passenger seat that turns off the right-side airbag unless somebody
weighing 26 pounds or more is sitting there. Also, a special baby
car seat can be purchased that automatically shuts off the
passenger side air bag when it's belted into place.
</P>
<P>
   The interior of the SL is attractive, solid and functional, in
usual Benz fashion, with an overall feel of refinement and
sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   One complaint, and it's a common one for Mercedes: The leather
seats are just too flat and hard, becoming decidedly uncomfortable
after a couple of hours. These seats do break in nicely after a
while, but it would be nice if they started out comfortable, too.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. The front apron for the aerodynamics package
turns out to be unacceptably fragile. After just 4,000 miles, the
test car's apron already had suffered two incidents of cracks and
damaged supporting structures from minor encounters with curbs,
each of which required repairs at a dealership.
</P>
<P>
   The test car came equipped with an attractive hardtop, one of
three tops available for the SL, including a fabric top that
disappears into the trunk with a touch of a button and a new
tinted-glass hardtop that allows an unobstructed skyward view.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with the hardtop: It didn't allow me the opportunity
to travel in the open air, the best way to appreciate an SL.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the SL500 is prohibitively expensive for most people, but
it does serve as a technological tour de force for Mercedes-Benz
even while upholding the German marque's sporting tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Solid and well-built, it can last for decades, as most of them
have, while holding its value and eventually becoming collectors'
items. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mercedes-Benz SL500 Sport &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vehicle type: &QL; 
Two-passenger, two-door convertible, rear-wheel drive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Base price: &QL; 
$79,500. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Price as tested: &QL; 
$88,580. &QL;
</P>
