<HEADLINE>
NEW LAKERS ARE ALL SMILES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Tony Battie is a man in search of a new name
tag.
</P>
<P>
   The player dubbed ``El Busto'' in Denver arrived in Los Angeles
on Friday to receive a purple-and-gold jersey and a new start on
his NBA career. A fresh label should accompany his fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Smile-o'' might be more appropriate now. Maybe ``Sir
Grin-a-lot.'' Battie could hardly contain his relief and joy at
becoming a Laker, flashing a gap-toothed grin often during his
introduction to the media at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been praying, not for a trade, but for something
positive to happen to me.... I guess my prayers were answered,''
said Battie, dealt from the 11-win Nuggets to the 61-win Lakers on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The second-year forward, a No. 5 pick in 1997, and rookie point
guard Tyronn Lue were acquired Wednesday night in the trade that
sent Nick Van Exel to Denver. Battie and Lue passed their physical
exams Friday morning, then took part in the meet-the-media session,
along with draft picks Sam Jacobson and Ruben Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are high on all four prospects _ ``We think we've
added some tremendous players here,'' executive Jerry West said _
and the foursome was thrilled to join a championship contender.
None more so than Battie, who got the fateful phone call shortly
after the draft ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``My phone rang. It was Denver saying they'd traded me to the
Lakers, and I've been awake ever since,'' Battie said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-11 forward was highly regarded coming out of Texas
Tech but had difficulty fulfilling expectations on the undermanned
Nuggets. Commentator and now general manager Dan Issel gave him the
bust label, and the fans turned as well as Battie and the Nuggets
underachieved their way to the worst record in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Having given up an All-Star to get Battie, the Lakers have
expectations too. But he doesn't have to carry the team here _
Shaquille O'Neal and Eddie Jones take care of that _ and Battie
might be able to relax a little in his second NBA campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a comfort zone there, I think,'' he said. ``The
picture has already been put together, and I'm just a piece of the
puzzle. I'll just contribute any way I can.''
</P>
<P>
   That could mean spotting O'Neal at center or even starting at
power forward depending on how he performs and on what other
changes the Lakers make before the season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Lue figures to be the primary backup to Derek Fisher at point
guard unless Kobe Bryant becomes a passer in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream come true,'' Lue said. ``Right now I'm still
shocked that I'm even in the NBA, and to get a chance to play for a
great organization like the L.A. Lakers, that's another big step.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson hopes to find time at off guard behind Jones, assuming
Bryant increases his minutes at small forward. And Patterson, an
energetic and athletic defender, could bolster the Lakers' small
forward ranks if Rick Fox doesn't return.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson already has the Lakers mindset down pat.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me, Eddie and Kobe out on the floor at the same time,
they better watch out,'' he said. ``There's gonna be some
Showtime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
