<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-INDIANS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bullpen offers no relief for Astros
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CLEVELAND _ The sweet smell of Colon combined with the stench of
their own bullpen created an aroma that has become all too familiar
for the Astros on this road trip.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive day, the Astros failed to sniff out a
victory. And Mike Magnante was again the fall guy in Friday night's
4-2 loss to the Cleveland Indians at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Indians rookie Bartolo Colon vaporized the Astros with his
warp-speed fastball, and his teammates made a one-run Astros lead
disappear. The three-game losing streak ties the Astros' longest
slide of the season.
</P>
<P>
   They hadn't dropped three in a row since April 12-15 against Los
Angeles and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Astros, the second-place Cubs (six losses in
a row) are struggling, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the way we wanted to open this series,'' said Pete
Schourek, who started for the Astros on Friday. ``After losing
those two games in Colorado, we didn't need to drop this one. We
have to come out and get it going tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, who have won six in a row, average 5.7 runs a game
and are theoretically vulnerable on nights when they score only
four. But four turned out to be more than enough with Colon on the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine most teams that face a guy like that are going to
struggle to score runs,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``He
throws the ball harder than anyone else, and he doesn't walk
anyone. He's pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Astros' offense wasn't exactly clicking on all
cylinders even before Colon slammed the brakes on them. The Astros
are hitting just .220 in the first three games of the trip _ 53
points below their season average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of firepower but haven't really shown it
lately,'' said Astros shortstop Ricky Gutierrez, who struck out to
end a classic 20-pitch confrontation against Colon in the eighth
inning. ``We're not getting enough guys on base to put pressure on
the other pitcher. We know our offense is better than what we've
been showing. We just have to forget about this one and try to
break out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Magnante (3-3) would love to forget Friday's turn of events. In
fact, he might not be opposed to wiping the first half of the
season out of his memory.
</P>
<P>
   This latest rough outing escalated his ERA to 6.37; at this
point, he doesn't look much like the pitcher who was 3-1 with a
2.27 ERA for the Astros in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly not the pitcher he was last season, but I'm not
going to give up on him,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros held a 2-1 lead until the Indians scored three times
off Reggie Harris and Magnante in a decisive seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Shawon Dunston started the rally with a one-out single off
Harris and moved to second on a throwing error by Gutierrez. After
Manny Ramirez hit into a fielder's choice, Dierker called on
Magnante because two of the Indians' next three hitters were
lefthanded.
</P>
<P>
   Magnante walked both lefties he faced and served up an RBI
double to righthanded-hitting Sandy Alomar between the two free
passes.
</P>
<P>
   After jumping ahead 1-2 in the count to Mark Whiten, Magnante
couldn't finish the job. Whiten's two-run single to left gave the
Indians all the runs Colon and two relievers would need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a base open on both of the walks, and I didn't want to
give in,'' said Magnante, who has walked nine in his last 16
innings. ``I thought I made some good pitches; they (the hitters)
just didn't go after them. I was ahead of every batter every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whiten didn't crush that ball, but he got enough of it to hit
it where we weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored only in the second inning, when Craig Biggio
drove home Gutierrez with an RBI single and Brad Ausmus scored as
Bill Spiers hit into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen sabotaged a gritty effort by Schourek, who held the
Indians to one run before reaching his pitch limit after five
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians loaded the bases against Schourek with no outs in
the first inning and seemed poised to bust the game open early. But
Schourek got two strikeouts and a line drive to the infield to
escape.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, who threw 102 pitches, allowed five runners to reach
scoring position. Omar Vizquel was the only Indian who scored
during his watch, coming home on Ramirez's ground ball to
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete did a great job of holding those guys down,'' Dierker
said. ``But because of his elbow (offseason surgery), we're still
keeping his pitches at around 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept us in there. When we hold this team to four runs, we
have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros couldn't get anything going against Colon after the
third inning. The rookie retired 16 of the final 18 batters he
faced with perhaps the best combination of velocity and command
this side of the Chicago Cubs' Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do much on offense, but that's because that kid
ain't easy to hit,'' said Astros right fielder Derek Bell, whose
career-best 14-game hitting streak came to an end. ``There really
wasn't anything we could do except tip our hats to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Colon (8-4) held the Astros to five hits and struck out seven in
eight innings before relievers Paul Assenmacher and Mike Jackson
finished off the Astros. Jackson retired the meat of the order _
Bell, Jeff Bagwell and Moises Alou _ for his 17th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
