</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-BUSINESS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COMPANIES POST A MIXED RECORD IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs 8th graf to change $20 billion to $36 billion)  (ART ADV.: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-TIBET, CHINA-TIANANMEN,
CHINA-RUBIN) 
(ja) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To learn more about the state of relations between the United
States and China, look at a few of the things that are not
happening during President Clinton's nine-day trip to China.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has an official delegation of 1,000 people, not one
represents an American company. Some U.S. companies will sign
contracts during the visit, but Clinton does not plan to attend
that ceremony. The president considered stopping by a new General
Motors Corp. auto factory in Shanghai, but decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   None of that means business has fallen off the U.S.-China
agenda. In fact, Clinton may be downplaying commercial links
precisely because they have become such a dominant bilateral issue:
The political scandal made up of China's business ambitions,
high-tech exports and campaign contributions has dogged him at
home.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the fact that the president's trip focuses on
diplomatic strategy, culture and tourism instead of commerce is a
sign that business ties have in some ways outgrown the
contract-by-contract nurturing required during the 1980s or the
early 1990s, when many visiting American dignitaries traveled with
planes full of chief executives seeking high-level contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is not exactly virgin territory for American business,''
said Robert Kapp, president of the U.S.-China Business Council.
``They are there in force. It is not as though they need the
president to let them in on the best kept secret in world trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, when the Occidental Petroleum Corp., the
former American Motors and a handful of other pioneers first
planted stakes in China, China investment has gone from adventurous
to ordinary. More than half of the Fortune 500 companies have
operations there, and smaller companies are also active, down to
entrepreneurs whose only business is in China.
</P>
<P>
   In the early part of this decade, many companies set up
factories in China to manufacture goods for export or began
aggressively marketing their products in China, a spree that shows
few signs of letting up despite China's slowing economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, American companies had two-way trade with China
valued at about $75 billion. They have invested a cumulative $36
billion, eight times as much as they had committed when George Bush
visited China in 1989, the last American president to make the
trip. Among Asian countries, only Japan has a bigger business
relationship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Like the broader relationship, the state of commercial ties has
long been described in absolutes. Chinese government officials are
seen as either friends or foes of business. The Chinese market is
called a salvation for some companies and a sinkhole for others.
</P>
<P>
   But after two decades of investing, hyperbole has given way to
sober assessments of the pluses and minuses of doing business in
what many call the world's most challenging emerging market. SOme
American companies have been runaway successes; others have proven
dismal failures. Most big companies say they are there for the long
term and are prepared to take their lumps along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak Co. is a good example. The company struggled for
years to distribute its film in China, while many local companies
sell lower-grade products and enjoy government protection. But
earlier this year, Beijing approved Kodak's longstanding request to
buy out three Chinese competitors, to open two factories and to put
its bright yellow boxes on store shelves nationwide. Kodak has
announced plans to invest $1 billion over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us several years to get the deal we wanted. You have
to have patience and the willingness to stick it out,'' said David
Swift, president of Kodak's China operation. ``But since we got the
license, everything has been superb.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodak claims to sell more film in China than any other company,
domestic or foreign. Moreover, China has become Kodak's No. 3
worldwide market, behind the United States and Germany and ahead of
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Massive advertising has helped many American brands gain ground
in China. Four out of five Chinese consumers surveyed by the Gallup
Organization knew Coca-Cola, more than recognized any other foreign
brand name. Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.'s Head and Shoulders shampoo and
Chrysler Corp.'s Jeep sport-utility vehicle, made in China by the
American companies, were also in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Profits have followed, though not as reliably as some investors
might have hoped. Figures are hard to track, as many U.S.
multinationals decline to break out sales and profits by country.
But the evidence suggests that businesses can operate profitably in
China provided they do what they would need to do anywhere else:
Develop good business plans, make products people can afford to buy
and beat the competition.
</P>
<P>
   One survey conducted by A.T. Kearney, a Chicago-based consulting
firm, asked the bosses of 70 multinationals how their ventures in
China were performing. They responded that 2 out of 5 of their
China ventures _ many have more than one _ were operating in the
black.
</P>
<P>
   They said they expected the rest to break even within three
years of their start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   China's Finance Ministry has reported similar results. A survey
completed last year found that 40 percent of foreign businesses
earned profits in 1996. The rest broke even or ran losses. Given
the huge volume of investments in the mid-1990s, which funded tens
of thousands of new ventures along China's eastern coast, some
analysts say they are surprised that so many can operate
profitably.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone finds it easy,'' said Rich Miskewicz,
Kearney's managing director for greater China. ``But they are
sticking it out and many are reaching profitability within the time
frame they planned, sometimes even faster.''
</P>
<P>
   But for every success story there is at least one bitter memory.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritech Corp., the Chicago-based Baby Bell, sought to get into
the business of providing cellular phone service in China,
investing $20 million in a venture there. But last year the company
pulled out, citing persistent regulatory obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar Inc., the heavy equipment maker, gave up on a
troubled joint venture with a Shanghai company, saying it had badly
overestimated the market in China for diesel engines. It remains
committed to China however, with several other factories there.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool Corp. opened four factories in China to make household
appliances in the mid-1990s, but closed two last year. The company
said the local competitors proved tougher than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Among other persistent complaints, businesses say China has a
weak legal system that does not enforce contracts reliably.
</P>
<P>
   American companies lose billions of dollars a year there because
Chinese companies make illegal copies of Prozac, Windows 95,
``Titanic,'' and many famous drugs, software, movies and music that
carry American trademarks and copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some areas where American companies have shown
themselves to be fierce competitors elsewhere in the world are
effectively off-limits to foreign investors in China. Retail and
distribution, banking and transportation are a few industries where
bans or restrictions make it difficult to invest.
</P>
<P>
   American officials complain that such barriers help China run a
$50 billion trade surplus with the United States, second only to
Japan's, creating political waves in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all investors in China face some political risk, both
in China and at home, though many have learned to keep their heads
down when tensions rise. Some companies expanded through the
political repression during and after the Tiananmen Square protests
of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Those that have withdrawn have sometimes regretted it. Levi
Strauss &AMP; Co. closed up shop in 1994, saying Beijing's violations
of human rights made it an unfit place to invest. The company
returned this spring, saying it wanted to ``untie its hands'' and
resume doing business in one of the world's biggest market for
jeans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-CULTURE-1STL     06-27 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-CULTURE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOLARS LOOK AT BASEBALL AND SEE THE AMERICAN ESSENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (fixes position of Yastrzemski; he was outfielder and
first-baseman, not a catcher) 
(duplication warning: also sent with `s' code) 
 bl)  
 By EDWARD A. GARGAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ Beyond the chalk lines that arrow into lush
green outfields, beyond the packed dirt and the pristine white
bases, beyond the dugouts and the scoreboards that chart wins and
losses, and beyond the thousands of baseball players who have
lashed away at pitched balls, there is a grander Elysian field: it
is, simply, the idea and meaning of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Every June for the last decade, a gaggle of academics
historians, anthropologists, linguists and sociologists gather at
this shrine to the game of summer to talk baseball, not as it is
played but what it means, how it shapes a culture, how it
conditions language, how it touches the soul. They come, these
scholars, in baseball hats clamped over bald pates or white hair,
and polo shirts stretched over bellies more intimate with beer than
situps, to ruminate on the game of which Walt Whitman wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well it's our game; that's the chief fact in connection with
it: America's game; it has the snap, go, fling of the American
atmosphere; it belongs as much to our institutions, fits into them
as significantly as our Constitution's laws; is just as important
in the sum total of our historic life.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophizing about baseball has not, of course, remained the
preserve of academia; indeed, from political pundits like George
Will to Canadian novelist W.P. Kinsella, the stadium of rumination
remains vast. But for scholars, particularly scholars who may once
have dreamed of walking onto the field of a major league ball park,
the game and its place in American life is rich in both symbolism
and meaning; it is for many, despite its many problems, an axis on
which the American experience turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what is written about baseball is very narrow,'' said
Peter Rutkoff, a professor of history at Kenyon College in the
small Ohio town of Gambier, ``or baseball nuts writing for baseball
nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We say right up front,'' chimed in Alvin Hall, now a dean and
historian at the Union Institute in Cincinnati and founder of the
yearly symposium, ``that we're not interested in baseball as
baseball, but baseball as part of American culture. Baseball is
regarded as a quintessential American sport. So to understand
American culture, you have to understand baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet because these scholars claim they come here not so much to
praise baseball, there was at first a grumble of skepticism from
the guardians of the Hall of Fame about a group of (nearly all) men
who didn't care so much about scores and earned run averages or who
was the best shortstop of the 1950s. Why should the Hall, where
greatness is arrayed on bronze plaques in a nave of marble and
bleached wood, admit philosophers and linguists and historians into
its embrace, it was said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Hall, ``I think we demonstrated to them the
educational function of a meeting like this. And the museum at the
Hall is the broader base of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the symposium, which is sponsored by the Hall of Fame and
the State University of New York at Oneonta and whih draws between
70 and 120 scholars each year, is as much a part of Cooperstown's
summer rituals as the All-Star Game is to major league ball.
</P>
<P>
   Over three days in mid-June, the scholars, who hailed from both
coasts and much in between, surveyed the landscape of American
culture and the role of baseball, from issues of sexuality to
notions of leadership theory, from unionization to melancholy in
American life.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the outfield of ideas and reflection about baseball
seems to be without fences. Part of the Americanizing ritual
smoldering just below the surface of baseball, Thomas Altherr, a
historian at Metropolitan State College in Denver, told his
colleagues, is the pervasive sexuality that surrounds the game.
</P>
<P>
   From the reckless and relentless womanizing of many players to
condoms carrying the image of Ted Williams (the last batter to hit
over .400), even to ancient baseball-like fertility rituals.
</P>
<P>
   How ancient? ``In Mesopotamia, on the first of May, young women
underwent a puberty ritual in which they batted a rock across a
field and ran around it to ensure fertility,'' Altherr said, ``In
an additional rite, the women circled a path of four bases, each
corresponding symbolically to their own infancy, childhood,
adulthood and finally full womanhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Altherr pointed out, in the 19th century, baseball was
shrouded in a culture of prudishness, so much so that Ladies Days
were held so that women in the stands could provide a calming
effect on frenzied male fans. That, of course, has given way, he
said, to endless braggadocio of sexual prowess among ball players,
beginning most notably, and perhaps most appropriately, with Babe
Ruth, arguably the greatest batter of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Where this evolution of attitudes will lead, Altherr says, is
uncertain. ``Will baseball be more sexualized?'' he asked. ``How
long will it be before we have Dallas Cowboy cheerleaders? So far,
thank goodness, there's nothing like that glitzy sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton Green, a bearded anthropologist from Pittsburgh's
Clarion University, argued that baseball, as an Americanizing
ritual, is a very important part of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the chronicle of immigrants to this country,'' Green
suggested, ``baseball has been very much a mirror of the rise and
assimilation of ethnic groups, from early Irish to the most recent
arrivals, the Japanese. The transition from Jackie Robinson to Nomo
_'' a celebrated but now troubled Japanese pitcher ``_ is a fairly
interesting reminder of this country's immigration pattern. Now,
Latin American and Asian ball players are the new immigrants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequence,'' he said, ``is that the next generation of
baseball will be more global than we're used to.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Green said there is a second, and ultimately more troubling
question, however, and that is whether the game will cease to
remain a lynchpin between generations, a vehicle by which the
elements of American culture are passed from grandfather to father
to son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball has played a role in transforming children, at least
boys, into adults,'' he explained. ``Now, that's less true.
Baseball is not so much part of that initiation anymore.
Generations are cut off more. As Margaret Meade has pointed out,
the generation gap is really a culture gap, a gap in passing on
culture from one generation to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, Green argued, this is because baseball has itself
changed and, as a result, what it means to children, mostly boys,
today is different from the meaning and role in children's lives in
previous generations.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, he suggested, it has become very difficult to
identify individual players with individual teams simply because
ball players move relatively easily from one team to the next. On
the other, the presentation of baseball has been transformed from
one where the game itself remained the centerpiece to a spectacle
of gifts, flashing scoreboards, dancing grounds keepers. ``Kids
want to go to the game for whatever trinket they're getting, not
for the baseball,'' he said, somewhat ruefully. ``Baseball was part
of my initiation. That's not so true anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is so, he asked, it is an open question whether baseball
will continue to remain central to the Americanizing experience of
earlier immigrant generations.
</P>
<P>
   For some at the symposium, baseball touches the most profound
emotional level of existence. ``While the game displays a
significant physical beauty and radiates a spiritual
transcendence,'' said George Grella, a professor of English at the
University of Rochester, ``it also expresses the parallel
paradoxical quality of sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   Although such cultural observations veer dangerously toward the
mawkish (or worse, the pompous), a decided risk when people unleash
their rhetorical powers on the game of baseball, Grella and others
strove to cement their arguments with evidence.
</P>
<P>
   And for Grella, the stuff of sadness is voluminous, from the
solitary positioning of fielders to the wreckers' ball at Ebbets
Field. As Carl Yastrzemski, the great Boston Red Sox outfielder and
first-baseman who was the last man to win the Triple Crown, said:
``I loved the game. I loved the competition. But I never had any
fun. I never enjoyed it. All hard work, all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In an essay he called ``The Melancholy of Baseball,'' Grella
suggested to his fellow scholars and baseball fans that the
ambiguity of the game echoes the voices of mainstream culture. ``If
baseball celebrates youth,'' he said, ``it also reminds us of
mortality; if a game can last forever, it is also an ephemeral
endeavor; it usually inspires lyric poetry, but also lends itself
to the elegiac mode. . . . it instructs us in two crucial American
concepts, the loneliness of space and the sadness of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates an immense green field, a gorgeous vista invoking
the pastoral, the agricultural, even the peaceable kingdom, but it
hints that the lush green garden may also be a vale of tears.
Baseball is the saddest game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so sad, though, that the scholars refrained from crowding
around Clete Boyer, a former Yankee great, who graced the occasion
with his presence. And not so melancholy that a game of Town Ball,
an early 19th-century precursor of the modern game, played by
competing squads of slow-moving academics, ended in a redemptive
tie, 21-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two sides to this conference,'' laughed Kenyon's
Rutkoff, a gangly man whose eyes glitter at the sight of a bat and
ball. ``There's the academics. But there's also the little kid
worshipping their heroes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
