<HEADER>
A9795 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-AZR &LR;      06-27 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECT AGAIN MOVES INTO EMPTY APACHE JUNCTION HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only two weeks after being evicted from government-owned houses
in Mesa, defiant members of a religious sect this week took over a
privately owned Apache Junction house that had been left vacant by
its owner for renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Sect members, who had occupied the private residence for two
days, agreed to leave peacefully Friday afternoon after Apache
Junction police and a federal investigator threatened to arrest the
couple for trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How in the world can this even happen?'' an infuriated Mikel
Vander Molen said Friday after the illegal occupants packed a
pickup truck with belongings and left her home as police watched.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Molen bought the house from the U.S. Department of
Housing and Urban Development. The sect, led by a prison convict,
has taken over at least seven Valley houses since early spring.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors say the sect members forced their way into Vander
Molen's house with a crowbar Wednesday night and began moving
furniture in. When neighbors called police to the scene, the sect
members flashed a copy of a bogus deed to the house.
</P>
<P>
   Police at that time took the deed at face value, but one member
of the sect was arrested on an unrelated warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Molen bought the house from HUD in January. She had not
moved in yet because it was, until a few weeks ago, being
renovated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a violation of my rights _ it's harassment!'' Vander
Molen said. ``This is absolutely ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of friends and family, Vander Molen said she
planned to stay in the house with a loaded weapon until she can
move her possessions in and be certain nobody will try to take it
over again.
</P>
<P>
   Located in the heart of Apache Junction with a splendid view of
the Superstition Mountains, the house is at least the seventh in
the Phoenix area that members of Regency House Church have tried to
claim as their own.
</P>
<P>
   In every case, sect members identify a vacant government-owned
house, record phony ownership claims with the Maricopa or Pinal
County recorders' offices, then break in and move in.
</P>
<P>
   In Vander Molen's case, a phony deed was filed with the Pinal
County recorder on June 23, claiming the property belonged to
Regency House. The sect apparently was unaware that the house had
been bought months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The signature on the fake deed, ``Jason Corey Bullard,''
appeared to have been signed and initialed by another sect member,
James Smithart, acting on Bullard's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Smithart said he was representing Bullard on the matter, but
otherwise declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The deed assigned the property to a sect member named Annette
Long, who police said was one of the two people sent packing
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Molen's was the first house targeted by the sect that
belonged to a private homeowner. In all other cases, the houses
were in the hands of government agencies awaiting resale after
government-insured loans were foreclosed.
</P>
<P>
   While sect members voluntarily dropped their claims to two
houses when challenged, HUD had to seek eviction orders from the
Maricopa County Superior Court in four cases because Mesa police
considered the matter a legal dispute and would not force sect
members from the homes.
</P>
<P>
   Three eviction orders were carried out two weeks ago when sect
members were forced out by members of the Maricopa County Sheriff's
Office. A fourth eviction case involving a Mesa house now is
wending its way through court.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, HUD officials consider every incident a clear case
of trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, HUD delivered a letter to Mesa police asking the
department to arrest any sect member who set foot on HUD property
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, ``it's going to continue to happen,'' Rebecca
Flanagan, HUD's deputy state coordinator, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bullard, who uses the title ``reverend'' and claims to lead the
sect, is a convicted con man serving a lengthy fraud sentence at
the Arizona State Prison at Perryville. He claimed in interviews
and court records to be guided by God in claiming the houses in the
sect's name.
</P>
<P>
   Bullard appeared in shackles in Superior Court last Wednesday to
argue against his sect's eviction from a Mesa HUD house, saying the
sect had bought aging federal land patents on the property. A judge
is expected to rule in that case next week.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after that court appearance, Bullard's supporters
tried to occupy another vacant HUD house in Mesa. As they drilled
out the locks, neighbors say, police arrived to run them off and
sent away a moving van full of sect members' possessions.
</P>
<P>
   In Vander Molen's case, sect members moved in Wednesday and on
Thursday tried to transfer to their own names the telephone and
utilities that Vander Molen had hooked up at the house. Fortunately
for Vander Molen, the phone company called her Thursday to find out
whether she approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `No, not at all, you've got the wrong place,' '' Vander
Molen said. But the phone company told her something shocking: the
call for the switch came from a phone line inside her new house.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Vander Molen raced over to find the sect's ``no
trespassing'' signs posted, the locks changed, sheets on some
windows and someone else's belongings inside. She couldn't confront
sect members because no one was home.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Molen, her companion and her brother returned Friday
morning. Again, nobody was home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to break back into her house, just to reoccupy it,''
said Tony Deblon, Vander Molen's companion. ``Possession is
nine-tenths of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   They sat inside until after noon, when sect members arrived and
Apache Junction police were called. The sect members told police
and Vander Molen that they had paid for the right to move in,
police and federal investigators are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Police are expected to follow up next week, HUD's Flanagan said,
and decide whether the person who broke into Vander Molen's home
Wednesday can be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal and county prosecutors will be briefed to
determine whether sect members can be prosecuted for other crimes
related to the filing of the bogus deeds, Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, this can happen to anyone now, it seems like,''
Flanagan said. &QL; 
 &UR; Pat Flannery may be reached by telephone at 444-8629 or at
 &UR; pat.flannery &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
