<HEADER>
A9798 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERLIN-AIRLIFT-2NDTAK     06-27 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-AIRLIFT-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Soviets tried again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think as an air force we have appreciated how much
that (the airlift) contributed to winning the Cold War,'' Brower
said.
</P>
<P>
   He credits Maj. Gen. William H. Tunner with getting the airlift
into a routine that was responsible for its success. Tunner oversaw
``the Hump,'' a wartime airlift of supplies to China from India and
Burma over the Himalayas. Keeping the Chinese supplied kept about a
million Japanese occupied, Brower said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Berlin airlift began, the U.S. Air Force had been an
independent branch of the military for a mere nine months. The
airlift demonstrated that air power alone could achieve a military
objective, Brower said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the systems put in place in the two airlifts still
affect air traffic, Brower said, including the aggressive use of
radar for en route air traffic control, separating planes by
altitude and time, and aggressive flight safety programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets were blindsided by the airlift's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original perceptions were we would not be able to sustain
this for very long,'' Brower said. ``The Russians thought we
ultimately would give in, but I think that misunderstands the
American culture and our desire to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the Germans knew the importance of the airlift.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what time of the day or night, there would always be
people peering at the airplanes,'' he said. ``The Germans really
understood what was going on, and they really appreciated it.''
</P>
<P>
   The airlift allowed West Berliners to feel that freedom was
within their grasp, and they developed a strong sense of resistance
to Russian involvement and domination, Brower said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Allies had thrown in the towel in Berlin, he said, the
Germans might have reached a different kind of accommodation with
the Soviets. And the world would be a very different place today.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about the Berlin Airlift, go to
www.konnections.com//airlift//index.html.
</P>
<P>
   For information about the Berlin Airlift Veterans Association,
write to Box 800-111, Converse, Texas 78109.
</P>
</TEXT>
