<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-2NDLD-WR     06-27 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RECEIVED BY CHINESE PRESIDENT NEAR SITE OF MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to include additional material throughout, including
press conference)  (See also: CHINA-TIBET, CHINA-TIANANMEN, CHINA-RUBIN) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
( bl ) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton was received by Chinese President
Jiang Zemin on Saturday in a military ceremony on Tiananmen Square,
the vast expanse through which modern Chinese history has flowed,
from the declaration of the communist state in 1949 to the crushing
of protest 40 years later.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton stood mute throughout, as is customary at such
arrival ceremonies. Clinton and Jiang then inspected army troops
and reviewed an honor guard on ground that human rights advocates
around the world consider stained with the blood of martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks later, Clinton referred to the site of the
student-led demonstrations that ended in terror and bloodshed on
June 3 and 4, 1989, when Chinese troops center mowed down hundreds
of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of our agreements we still disagree about the meaning
of what happened then. I believe, and the American people believe,
that the use of force and the tragic loss of lives _ was wrong. I
believe, and the American people believe, that freedom of speech,
association, and religion are, as recognized by the U.N. Charter,
the right of people everywhere and should be protected by their
governments,'' Clinton said after his meeting with Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   He did not abandon the human rights issue, but went on to say:
``We have developed a relationship of openness and candor. When we
differ, as we do from time to time, we speak openly and candidly.
It is well known that the principal area of our difference in
recent years is over questions of human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the joint news conference was harmonious and
the announcements of a series of agreements including a pledge to
redirect the nuclear-tipped ballistic missiles now aimed at each
other's cities.
</P>
<P>
   The step is largely symbolic, because such weapons can be
changed back in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang also agreed that China would ``actively study'' joining
the Missile Technology Control Regime, an international agreement
governing the sale of certain missiles and missile technology.
China has resisted the pact because missile exports are a key
money-maker for the military. No timetable was set for China's
actually joining the regime.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries also announced an agreement on a joint
statement on the nuclear arms race now under way in South Asia,
including pledges not to export to India or Pakistan any missiles,
missile equipment or materials capable of delivering nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement covers only medium- and long-range missiles,
however, not battlefield rockets or antitank weapons, a U.S.
official involved in the summit talks said.
</P>
<P>
   China has also agreed to permit inspections of Chinese sites
receiving high-technology equipment from the United States to
assure that it is being put to its intended use and not diverted
for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
   This provision has gained increased importance in recent weeks
with disclosures that China may have used commercial satellites for
military communications, and earlier revelations that computers
supposedly for industrial applications had been diverted to
military installations.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no concrete progress on a number of American human
rights concerns, including the treatment of Tibet and an accounting
for hundreds of political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. official said he was hopeful that signs of progress on
rights might come in the weeks and months after Clinton leaves
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things are not announced at the summit, but happen
afterward,'' this official said.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also agreed to expand the Peace Corps presence here
and to work toward new cooperation on legal reforms, environmental
programs and a new clean energy project to reduce the emissions of
coal-burning power plants.
</P>
<P>
   The summit results amount to a ``pretty substantial package,''
the official said. But many of the military and nonproliferation
items were expected and represented at best incremental steps.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has defended his appearance before the Great Hall of the
People on the edge of Tiananmen Square as the expected behavior of
a state visitor to China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stood stiffly as the People's Liberation Army band
played ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' and an evocative 21-gun
cannonade rang out across the square. The gunfire continued through
the playing of the Chinese national anthem, ``March of the
Volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   As the two presidents finished reviewing the troops, they turned
and walked along a red carpet toward the steps of the Great Hall of
the People, smiling and chatting. In 13 minutes, the ceremony,
which stirred such memories and generated such controversy, was
over.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony came at the start of a one-day summit meeting that
has already been marred by the detention and harassment of several
Chinese political dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute forced Clinton and his senior aides into a defensive
crouch and threatened to undermine China's central goal of the
summit _ a portrait of a ``new China'' of greater economic and
personal freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance on the square Saturday morning dramatized
China's struggle between memory and forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese leadership hopes to consign to history the events of
June 1989, when indelible images of blood-letting in the streets
and of a lone protester standing before a column of tanks were
broadcast around the world. The events are the subject of a
continuing dispute in China, even at high levels of the party.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the party's Central Committee, Zhao Ziyang, who
has been under house arrest since he was ousted as Communist Party
chief at the time of the Tiananmen incident, challenged the
nation's leaders to admit that the incident was reprehensible as
well as an immense political blunder.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, harshly criticized in the United States for lending his
prestige to Beijing's leaders by attending the ceremony, hopes that
his presence here will force the world to remember that bloody
night.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the White House sharply criticized Beijing for the
harassment of dissidents on the first day of Clinton's state visit,
calling the detentions ``thoroughly unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton did not take steps to impose any punishment or
withhold any favors in response.
</P>
<P>
   Using unusually harsh language, National Security Adviser Samuel
Berger said the Chinese internal security apparatus was ``doing
what comes naturally'' by harassing outspoken opponents of the
government who officials fear might embarrass Beijing during the
president's visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not debris to be swept up for a visitor,'' Berger
said at a briefing for reporters Friday in Xian, before the
presidential entourage flew to Beijing for the summit meeting. ``We
certainly will not accept this.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups reported that four dissidents were detained
in two Chinese cities and one removed from Xian in the hours before
Clinton's arrival Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   China demonstrated little concern about the detentions, denying
that anyone had actually been ``arrested'' and offering U.S.
diplomats no explanation for their actions. Chinese authorities
routinely round up dissidents and other potential troublemakers
before important events.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities added to the friction Friday night by
impeding two Asian-American White House staff members who were
trying to load the president's luggage aboard Air Force One at
Xian's airport.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Mike McCurry attributed the incident
to ``over-eager'' Chinese security officials who were not expecting
to find Asians in the presidential party.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was resolved in a few minutes and the stewards were
allowed to board the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Berger tried to explain Beijing's crackdown on dissidents as a
remnant of its police-state past, a preference for order over
political freedom. He said the repression was diminishing, if
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is changing, but there are still forces that are pulling
the other direction, that are resisting,'' Berger said. ``I think
China's human rights record is terrible. I think China is an
authoritarian nation, as I've said before. I think there's been
some progress in human rights, but it has been not nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the area of public dissent, they are still totally
unacceptable. I don't think this is directed at President Clinton.
The fact that it happens generally in connection with these kinds
of visits, it is not appropriate, it is not necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton said he found reports of the
detentions ``disturbing,'' but gave no indication that he would
change his approach to China in response. ``I think it makes the
case, it makes it all the more important that we continue to work
with the Chinese and engage them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jendrzejczyk, director of Human Rights Watch Asia, said the
administration's unwillingness to respond with more than words was
a sign that the White House was ``desperate not to offend the
Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration is walking on eggshells, determined to
demonstrate that this visit represents a major breakthrough in
relations,'' Jendrzejczyk said. ``The Chinese are being tough. They
know their bottom line, and the administration seems willing to
accommodate them at any cost.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on the president to signal his displeasure by
withholding something the Chinese want, such as the planned visit
to the United States later this year by Prime Minister Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   But Berger said the United States planned nothing beyond verbal
protests. He said it would be against U.S. interests to impose any
punishment or withhold any agreements as a result of the police
action. And he offered a partial excuse for the Chinese action,
saying it was not as severe as previous roundups of dissidents
before the arrival of important foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their instinct _ the instinct of some at least _ is to let
their desire for order overwhelm their ability to permit
expression,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the White House was defending the Tiananmen Square
appearance and the overall value of the summit meeting to
U.S.-Chinese relations, there appeared to be little Chinese
movement on issues the United States considers central to the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been pressing for China to permit the live,
nationwide broadcast of Clinton's Monday speech, in which the
president is expected to deliver his strongest message on human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has resisted, and White House officials said Saturday
that it appeared the speech would be seen everywhere in the world
but China.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, even the most ardent fans barely got a
glimpse of the ceremony. The central area of Tiananmen Square
itself was swept clean of any spectators, leaving only a retinue of
security guards and plainclothes officers. Chinese spectators were
kept on the north side of the square by the entrance to the
Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't see anything,'' said Wang Jie, 32, a shoemaker.
``It would have been better to watch TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang's colleague Li Changping, said most Chinese have warm
feelings for Clinton and wanted to see him. ``We got up at 3 in the
morning to come here,'' said Li. ``We like Clinton a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
