</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-AIRLIFT-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALF A CENTURY AGO, BERLIN AIRLIFT BEGAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEAN BUCHANAN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Nobody thought it could be done. Not the Americans. Not
the British. Not the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   The task at hand: Deliver enough food, medicine and coal by
plane to keep 2.5 million people alive indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the Berlin Airlift, one of the great showdowns of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 tons of goods were delivered on that first day, 50
years ago Friday. And the numbers grew steadily: 70,000 tons
delivered by the end of July 1948, 147,000 tons delivered that
October, 251,000 tons delivered in May 1949.
</P>
<P>
   A 32-cent commemorative postage stamp that marks the 50th
anniversary of the Berlin Airlift was to be issued Friday and on
sale nationwide starting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It not only was a huge humanitarian effort,'' said retired Air
Force Col. Charles S. Allen of Leavenworth, Kan., an airlift pilot,
``it was the...first time they (Russians) really saw our resolve
that we were not going to let them drive us out of Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   It also established the fledgling Air Force as a vital part of
the U.S. defense system. And it changed the way Americans viewed
Germans, from the hated enemy to oppressed allies.
</P>
<P>
   When World War II ended, the United States, France, Britain and
Soviet Union carved Germany into four sectors. Although Berlin was
in the Soviet sector, the four powers were to share control of the
capital city.
</P>
<P>
   Military traffic on land, rail and water was supposed to be
allowed to move freely from the Allied sectors of Germany to
Berlin. The Allies also had access through three 20-mile-wide air
corridors.
</P>
<P>
   But the Soviets wanted the Allies out. They delayed or blocked
rail and road travel. They interfered in elections. They stripped
Berlin of valuables and sent them into the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   They also printed currency willy-nilly, resulting in rampant
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   When the Allies secretly planned a new currency, the Soviets
decided to starve them into submission. They blocked traffic by
land, by water and by rail into the Western sector of the city.
They cut off electricity except for two hours a day, between 11
p.m. and 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Allies, including U.S. President Harry S. Truman, were
determined to maintain their presence in Berlin. The commander of
the U.S. Air Force in Europe, Lt. Gen. Curtis LeMay, promised that
the Air Force could deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Planes were summoned from all over Europe, from Panama, Guam,
Japan and the United States. Within four days, British and American
planes were delivering more than 2 tons of goods daily. The effort
was dubbed Operation Vittles.
</P>
<P>
   Planes landed on the runway at Tempelhof in West Berlin every
eight minutes. At the airlift's peak, planes would land every three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the Allies intended to sustain only the occupation
forces, said Col. John Brower, a professor at the Air War College
at Maxwell Air Force Base, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have difficulty saying no to someone in need,'' he
said. ``It was very difficult for us to turn that aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilots were pulled from behind desks to fly in the airlift. When
it became clear that more pilots were needed, a field duplicating
the conditions in Berlin was laid out in Great Falls, Mont. Fighter
pilots and pilots with no troop carrier or multi-engine experience
were sent to Great Falls for training, and then to Germany, said
Allen, 75.
</P>
<P>
   Ground crews were assembled and sent to Germany, too. The
airlift was hard on the planes, and the mechanics and crews
``worked like dogs'' to keep the planes operational, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody was on a 24-hour-a-day schedule. The Allies were
trying to supply the Berliners with enough to eat, and soon they
would be needing lots of coal so they wouldn't freeze during the
winter. A proposal to drop coal in bags from the air was discarded
after the coal turned to dust in test runs.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the airlift assumed the characteristics of an
assembly line. Planes took off one after the other, day and night.
Pilots had only one opportunity to land in West Berlin. If they
missed their approach they had to take their cargo back to West
Germany. Otherwise, the traffic stacked up over Berlin and precious
time was lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was organized,'' recalled Allen, who joined the
airlift in April 1949. ``Planes were packed nose to tail. They'd
unload the first plane, the line would move up. When you stopped
and the door flew open, immediately there was a crew of German
unloaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Their goal was to be back in the air in 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh M. Tosone, 68, of Gladstone, Mo., was one of the people
working to keep the planes flying. He arrived in Germany in
September 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just 18 years old, and I was convinced the Russians were
coming over the next hill,'' he said. ``They issued us rifles...but
to show what kind of confidence they had in us, they didn't give us
any bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosone was stationed at Rhein-Main, one of the bases in the
American zone. The other was Wiesbaden.
</P>
<P>
   His squadron took engines from the planes used in the airlift to
Mobile, Ala., to be overhauled, and then flew them back to
Frankfurt to be reinstalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a lot of worldly ideas about what we were
doing,'' said Tosone, who later became a physicist and worked for
Boeing in Wichita, Kan., for 35 years. ``It was just a matter of
getting your job done every day...just keeping the airplanes going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure some of us thought it was a world-shaking effort, but
as a young person I just considered it a job.''
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly a year, but in the end, the Soviets conceded,
allowing rail, truck and ship traffic to resume to the western
sectors of the city. The airlift continued until September 1949 as
the Allies stockpiled supplies in case the Soviets tried again.
MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
