<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO END OF CAR TAX PUTS KANSAS GOVERNOR, LEGISLATOR ON SAME
PAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Kansas tax-relief crusader Phill Kline can be excused
if he happens to be feeling a bit smug these days.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Bill Graves last week made scrapping the property tax
on cars by 2003 an early centerpiece of his re-election campaign,
the guv validated the Johnson County legislator's unrelenting
crusade to cut Kansas taxpayers an even break. It's been a long and
often lonely struggle for the Republican legislator from Shawnee,
but it's not politics alone that makes for strange bedfellows.
</P>
<P>
   Election year politics, it would seem, make for really weird
bedfellows _ at least in Kansas this year. Who would've thunk, for
instance, that the governor would have ever become as enthusiastic
a champion of tax relief as the House Taxation Committee chairman
with whom he has often been at odds on tax-cut initiatives?
</P>
<P>
   Kline was the House point man in the campaign to lighten the
onerous car-tax burden. Taxpayers in Johnson and Wyandotte counties
who had been in the habit of writing substantial checks for car
taxes in years past no doubt have noticed more recently how nice it
is to write smaller car-tax checks with each passing year. Now the
prospect of not writing any such checks is something that will make
taxpayers sit up and take notice anew.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities are certainly something perceptive politicians
notice. Graves, it's safe to say, probably has been impressed with
how Virginia's new governor rode the promise of car-tax relief to
victory as a long-shot social conservative candidate last year.
Interestingly enough, Graves is facing a primary challenge from
former Republican Party Chairman David Miller, who also carries the
social conservative label.
</P>
<P>
   As the executive director of the Kansas Taxpayers Network, Karl
Peterjohn, recently pointed out, it's remarkable how far Graves has
come on this tax issue. Not only has the governor frequently
clashed with Kline over aggressive tax-cutting proposals, but
Democratic gubernatorial candidate Jim Slattery also was
characterized as fiscally irresponsible when he proposed modest
car-tax relief during his 1994 contest with Graves.
</P>
<P>
   Now Graves not only is calling for elimination of the property
tax on cars at an estimated revenue cost of $259 million over five
years, but is making noises about cutting other taxes.
</P>
<P>
   It probably wouldn't do, however, for Kline and his fellow
tax-relief crusaders to view this as Topeka's version of anybody
getting struck blind on the road to Damascus. Kline, et al, have
every reason to be gratified by the governor's willingness to
concede the need to return more of the burgeoning revenue windfall
to the taxpayers. However, it's a good bet there are no born-again
tax-cutters out there.
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders who have grown accustomed to perceiving tax
revenue as something needed more by government than by the people
paying the taxes are usually set in their ways. No matter how much
tax-cut talk is bandied about during the coming election campaign,
the only numbers that should matter are how much government
spending is increasing relative to real personal income growth.
</P>
<P>
   Any spending number that surpasses the gains of working folk is
unacceptable. Thus, it will be the never-ending challenge of Kline
and other champions of overburdened taxpayers to keep the scales
balanced between the state's fiscal interests and the economic
interests of taxpayers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9804 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      06-27 0107
