<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHINA'S RUDE RECEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(updates to incorporate Clinton' remarks)  (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 27:
</P>
<P>
   The ceremonial part of President Clinton's welcome may be fit
for an emperor, but other aspects of the Chinese government's
behavior have looked like calculated insults. By detaining several
democracy advocates during the president's stop in Xian and
imposing heavy surveillance on other democrats in Beijing, Chinese
leaders have seriously embarrassed Clinton. He must respond
personally, publicly and bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   As Beijing well knows, Clinton took considerable political risks
to go through with this trip. By making his presence a pretext for
picking up political activists, China's leaders demonstrated
indifference to his efforts on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton politely but clearly deplored the detentions before
leaving Xian on Friday. His national security adviser, Samuel
Berger, spoke more sharply, warning that ``people are not debris to
be swept up for a visitor.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, after China's disdainful rebuff of a diplomatic protest
from Ambassador James Sasser, Clinton must forcefully register his
unhappiness with his Chinese hosts over the incident. His remarks
about human rights and the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre earlier
Saturda morning were welcome. But he needs to say more about
China's current behavior as the political heart of the visit
unfolds in Beijing this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeping potential demonstrators away from international
visitors is a sadly familiar Chinese practice. But that repressive
tradition is not something a U.S. president can accept without
public protest when it is waved in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   President Jiang Zemin wanted Clinton to visit China this year as
a symbol of improving ties between Beijing and Washington. But real
improvement is retarded when China flaunts its methods of stifling
dissent during this visit.
</P>
<P>
   Responding strongly to these detentions is not simply about
damage control in Washington. It is an integral part of building a
healthier relationship with China, which should be Clinton's main
goal on this visit. Such a relationship cannot be built on the
premise that Beijing is free to deliver angry diatribes whenever it
feels offended but that Washington must always be deferentially
polite.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of double standard invites dangerous diplomatic
misunderstandings. It also builds resentment among the American
people, who are already uneasy over charges of Chinese interference
in the 1996 presidential campaign and lax U.S. supervision of
Chinese satellite contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's preference was to avoid any appearance of rudeness on
this trip. But Beijing's lack of courtesy compels him to raise his
voice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
