<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-PADRES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FALL TO PADRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Anaheim Angels first baseman Cecil Fielder walked
into the visiting clubhouse at Qualcomm Stadium on Friday
afternoon, took a look at the uniform jerseys hanging in the locker
stalls and proclaimed: ``Oh man, they're tired.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres promoted their game with the Angels on
Friday as ``Retro Night.'' Both wore uniforms from the 1978 season,
disco music played during batting practice and between innings, and
even a few Padres players got into it by wearing giant Afro wigs
before the game.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing uglier than the Padres' brown-and-yellow
jerseys was the way the Angels played in a 6-3 loss before 40,621.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jason Dickson (8-5) wasn't nearly as sharp as he
had been of late, his seven-game winning streak coming to an end.
But a more notable problem was the Angels defense.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Dave Hollins and second baseman Justin Baughman
made errors, and just as glaring were the mental errors made by
Hollins and Fielder in the Padres' decisive three-run sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Fielder let a sacrifice bunt attempt by Kevin Brown roll past
him, hoping it would go foul. It didn't, and Brown was safe at
first with a single.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the inning, the Padres had the bases loaded with one
out when Greg Vaughn hit a one-hopper to Hollins. Ed Giovanola
started the play on third base, but broke back to the bag thinking
Hollins might have caught the ball on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins, though, didn't throw home. He looked at first, then
eventually tagged out Tony Gwynn going from second to third,
allowing Giovanola to score.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from the way the Angels had been playing. They
had won 21 of their previous 25 before Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Angels and Padres had winning records in 1978, both
teams would prefer to look ahead, not back. The Padres went into
Friday's game tied with Atlanta for the best record in the National
League, and the Angels are second only to the Yankees in the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of both teams would be getting ahead of themselves to start
dreaming of an I-5 World Series, but this would have to do for now.
</P>
<P>
   Brown had an Angel on his side in the early innings, but not one
from Anaheim. Brown had seven strikeouts through the first four
innings, all seven coming on called-third strikes by homeplate
umpire Angel Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (9-3) finished with nine strikeouts in six innings to get
the win. After Dan Miceli walked two Angels on eight straight
pitches with one out in the eighth, Trevor Hoffman came on for his
24th save and 32nd straight dating to last year. Hoffman struck out
three in 12/3 scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   Through three innings, Brown was nearly perfect, yielding only a
first-inning single to Hollins. But in the fourth, Hollins got
things started with a double.
</P>
<P>
   After a walk to Jim Edmonds, Fielder hit one halfway to Anaheim.
One pitch after Brown brushed him back, Fielder hit his 13th home
run of the year into the second deck in left-center field for a 3-0
Angels lead. The distance was estimated at 443 feet.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 18th home run to reach the second deck in the
stadium's history, the eighth by a Padres opponent, and the first
opponent to do so since the Dodgers' Mike Piazza did it on Sept.
22, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres cut into the Angels lead quickly, however. Ken
Caminiti hit Dickson's first pitch in the bottom of the fourth
inning over the fence in left for is 11th homer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the same inning extended by a Hollins throwing error at
third, Brown singled home Wally Joyner to cut the Angels' lead to
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres tied it in the fifth inning on Vaughn's two-out RBI
double, a drive that Edmonds got a glove on before crashing into
the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Todd Greene has consulted with doctors, talked to manager
Terry Collins and general manager Bill Bavasi and finally he's made
up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   No surgery _ at least, not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who has what trainer Ned Bergert called ``internal
impingement caused by instability in the right shoulder,'' will
begin a rehabilitation program immediately and has set a target
date of Aug.1. If the shoulder doesn't show significant improvement
by then, Greene likely will have the surgery and still have enough
time to recover in time for spring training next season.
</P>
<P>
   But Greene, after visiting Drs. Lewis Yocum, Frank Jobe and
James Andrews, is convinced he can come back this season. Not as a
catcher, but to play first base, the outfield or DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intent is to help this team win games this year,'' Greene
said. ``However I can do that, I'm willing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
