<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-PERKINS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERKINS THINKING ONE MORE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sam Perkins moved slowly but with a bounce in his step
while walking into Garfield High School on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Sonic forward has his way, that is exactly how the
summer will go _ slowly, only with a basketball to bounce at the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, who turned 37 on June 14, is at a crossroads in his
14-year career. Conventional wisdom suggests that his age plus the
Sonics' youth movement might equal Perkins' retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says Big Smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more year is probably left in me to be an effective
player,'' Perkins said during a break from Friday's Seafirst
Jammin' Hoops Camp in Seattle's Central Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still had fun (last season),'' Perkins said. ``If I don't
have fun, then it's time to go. But it's so irrational for me to
make a decision about retiring right now. More than likely I'll
probably come back and play.''
</P>
<P>
   But where will Perkins end up?
</P>
<P>
   Perkins becomes a free agent Wednesday. He made more than $3
million last season. The Sonics are not likely to pay that much for
a veteran on the down side of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins averaged 7.2 points per game last season but shot 41
percent _ the second lowest shooting percentage of his career. He
snared just three rebounds a game and appeared a step slow on
defense. But Perkins remains one of the league's better 3-point
shooters.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he lands, it is likely Perkins will have to accept a
one-year contract for the league minimum _ roughly $500,000. Jerome
Kersey was in a similar situation last year when he signed with the
Sonics for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's worth it, I can do that,'' Perkins said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Perkins wonders if the Sonics will offer him a contract
at all. They have expressed a strong desire to have a younger
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, when free agency begins, so will an NBA lockout. Teams
will not be permitted to pursue any free agents without a
collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Perkins planned to meet and greet new coach Paul Westphal on
Friday. Perkins figured he would leave with an idea of the team's
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy Seattle,'' said Perkins, ``but I'm not going to be on
their door step. If I'm not in their plans, I'm not in their plans.
There are so many options for them and me to take into
consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said he would prefer to play with an NBA contender. He
also will consider location and his role as a backup. Even though
it is widely believed that he is linked with ex-Sonic George Karl,
Perkins doesn't mind that Westphal was hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised they fired George,'' Perkins said. ``It's
sad that we just didn't (win) together. That's the only down side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, Coach had his favorites. Among those were Nate
(McMillan) and Detlef (Schrempf). He had a married-with-children
relationship with Gary (Payton). . . . I just laughed with him
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins chuckled after mentioning that he played against
Westphal his rookie season _ 1984-85.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's a cool guy,'' Perkins said of Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins drew the same reaction from more than 1,600 kids he
interacted with at the basketball camp. Perkins, teammate Dale
Ellis, the the Seattle Reign's Kate Starbird and former NBA great
Bill Walton participated during the second day of the three-day
camp.
</P>
<P>
   The free program began in 1990 and will visit 24 cities this
summer. Seafirst uses NBA stars such as Perkins to stress the
importance of education and staying away from drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm moving slow because it's early in the morning,'' Perkins
said. ``I was up until 2 o'clock in the morning making plans (for
the summer events around Seattle). But it's cool. I'm having a good
summer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
