<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PIRATES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT PIRATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There was no shocking news to report Friday in the
Los Angeles Dodgers' never-ending off-the-field soap opera. Nor was
there any lackluster play or blown lead that has been the norm
recently.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, the Dodgers quietly took care of business by
simply doing something they have dreamed of for some time _ playing
good, drama-free baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the rejuvenated pitching of Chan Ho Park, the Dodgers won
just their second game in their past seven outings with a 5-2
victory over the Pittsburgh Pirates in front of a sold-out
Fireworks Night crowd of 52,934 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was just last Sunday when Park endured the worst outing of
his major-league career that really got rolling in 1996. The
right-hander allowed 10 runs on eight hits in 51/3 innings during a
loss at Colorado that was also the last game for manager Bill
Russell and general manager Fred Claire.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Park's tough outing, new Dodgers pitching coach Charlie
Hough didn't try to make any drastic changes with him. Instead, the
former knuckleballer told the right-hander to relax, forget about
Colorado and stop putting ``Opening Day pressure'' on himself.
</P>
<P>
   In 62/3 innings, Park (6-5) did just that as he allowed two runs
on 10 hits, one walk and struck out four for the win. Park, who
threw 120 pitches, won for just the second time in his last eight
outings. He also allowed the fewest number of runs since giving up
one in his last win against Oakland on June 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy,'' Park said. ``It was good win for me, us and
pitching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Park retired his first two batters before
hitting Jason Kendall with a pitch. Kevin Young followed with RBI
single that gave Pittsburgh a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Park loaded the bases with no outs. However, a
fielder's choice, a groundout and a popout helped him survive the
ugly jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan Ho battled the whole game,'' Dodgers manager Glenn
Hoffman said. ``The second inning was key. He turned it up a notch
and kept us in the ballgame. The bullpen did a tremendous job
tonight and defense was the key. When we needed to make the big
plays, we did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't get the big hit,'' said Pirates manager Gene
Lamont. ``Especially in the second inning when we could of blown it
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers rookie Paul Konerko started the season sluggishly at the
plate, but recently he has been able to take some of the rust off
his bat. Such was evident when he had his sixth hit in his last 11
at-bats with a two-run home run over the left field fence off
Pittsburgh starter Esteban Loaiza in the second inning to give the
Dodgers a 2-1 advantage. The home run off the 1-0, no-out pitch was
Konerko's fourth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way I hit,'' Konerko said. ``I go up there and
take balls and try to swing at good pitches. I'm just trying to do
my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said: ``Konerko is coming along well. I have all the
confidence in the world in him. People don't remember that he is
still young, too. I'm very pleased with him.''
</P>
<P>
   With the scored tied in the fourth, Dodgers regained the lead
3-2 when Konerko scored on a one-out RBI single by fellow rookie
Adrian Beltre. In the fifth, the Dodgers pushed their advantage to
4-2 when Eric Young scored on a one-out sacrifice fly by Eric
Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman showed confidence in Park by leaving him in to bat in
the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Park retired his first two batters in the seventh. But after
hitting the next batter and allowing a single, Park was lifted for
struggling reliever Scott Radinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Radinsky, who had blown five of his last six save opportunities,
was welcomed with boos and didn't help matters as he loaded the
bases by hitting pinch-hitter Mark Smith. Radinsky, however, struck
out Aramis Ramirez to ruin the Pirates' second chance of
capitalizing on a bases-loaded situation.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, catcher Tom Prince earned just his second RBI of
the season with a two-out RBI single that scored Trenidad Hubbard
and gave the Dodgers a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Antonio Osuna finished the game by striking out Guillen
to earn just his fourth save of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
