<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY HURTS HAMSTRING AFTER HITTING 31ST HOMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Ken Griffey Jr., gave the Mariners a lead in the third
inning Friday night with his 31st home run. And he kept them ahead
in the sixth inning with a sensational catch in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   But the pain Griffey felt in the back of his left leg while
making the highlight-reel grab soon became another giveaway night
by the Mariner bullpen. Minutes after Griffey disappeared into the
dugout, a one-run lead became a four-run deficit and eventually a
13-8 loss to the expansion Arizona Diamondbacks before 47,902 fans
at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White parked a bases-loaded homer off Bob Wells to cap a
five-run sixth inning and send the stumbling, bumbling Mariners to
their 14th loss in the past 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   And that's with Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they have him in the lineup Saturday night depends on
how quickly he recovers from what is believed to be torn scar
tissue near his hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have caught a break,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
``At first, we thought he pulled the hamstring. But that might not
be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Rick Griffin said he believes the scar tissue around the
muscle Griffey pulled last season might have been torn, and that
wouldn't be nearly as troublesome as a hamstring pull. ``But we'll
have to wait and see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey experienced the discomfort when he chased down a
400-foot drive hit by Jay Bell in the Diamondbacks' decisive sixth
inning. Griffey stretched for the ball, grabbing it in the webbing
of his glove in deep left-center. It deprived Bell of an extra-base
hit that would have scored David Dellucci from first base with the
tying run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a heckuva play. I didn't think he had a chance of
catching it,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey made a strong throw back to the infield, but then walked
in, motioning for Griffin to meet him along the way.
</P>
<P>
   That became the focal point on a night Piniella threw a couple
of new wrinkles into the lineup. He moved first baseman David Segui
to left field and inserted designated hitter Edgar Martinez at
first base.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners lost their 10th game this season when scoring
at least seven runs.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Griffey's homer that capped a three-run third inning and
gave Seattle a 3-1 lead, Dan Wilson emerged from a prolonged
hitting slump with three hits, including a three-run homer in the
sixth that put the Mariners in front 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Bill Swift got to the sixth, but not impressively.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed sinkerball specialist, who leads the staff with
seven wins, served up four of the Diamondbacks' team-record five
home runs. Olympia's Travis Lee homered in his first two at-bats,
driving in four runs, White hit the first of his two off Swift and
Andy Fox also knocked a Swift pitch into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was falling behind in the count and trying to throw too
hard,'' said Swift, who had given up just six homers in 722/3
previous innings. ``Pitches that were supposed to be down and away
were up and over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Greg McCarthy, who pitched a scoreless inning, none
of the pitchers Piniella used had much success against the top of
Arizona's lineup. Fox, White, Lee and Matt Williams went a
collective 10-for-17, scored nine runs, hit five home runs and
drove in 12 runs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the lineup changes, Segui had a quiet night in left field
in his first start at the position since May 25, 1995 when he was
with Montreal. He becomes the 56th player to play alongside Griffey
since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had a busy night.
</P>
<P>
   He had six putouts, four assists and started two double plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgar really played a great game at first base,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez didn't have one of his best.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner shortstop twice muffed throws from second baseman
Joey Cora that could have started inning-ending double plays. The
first one was especially costly, prolonging the third inning long
enough for Lee to deliver a three-run homer.
</P>
</TEXT>
