<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND JIANG DEBATE HUMAN RIGHTS, TIBET, TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin
turned a joint news conference Saturday into a dazzling debate
about Tiananmen Square, Taiwan and Tibet that was broadcast to
millions of Chinese TV viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials sought to portray the
cheerfully spirited debate as a historic breakthrough because it
signaled Jiang's willingness to allow his countrymen to hear
conflicting views on human rights and the 1989 Tiananmen Square
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   During their only scheduled working session of Clinton's
nine-day visit, the two leaders agreed to cease aiming long-range
missiles armed with nuclear weapons at each other's cities in a
largely symbolic gesture that could be reversed in a matter of
minutes by U.S. and Chinese military forces.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of China's 18 long-range missiles are aimed at U.S.
cities. U.S. officials declined to specify how many of the nation's
6,000 warheads are aimed at targets in China.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders' 70 minutes of press conference ping pong came after
Clinton participated in the most controversial moment of his visit
thus far _ the welcoming ceremonies at Tiananmen Square where
Chinese authorities crushed a pro-democracy movement nine years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received a thundering 21-gun salute on a plaza
overlooking Tiananmen Square, the 98-acre expanse in the heart of
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public remarks after the ceremony, Clinton urged
Chinese authorities to get ``on the right side of history'' by
apologizing for the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe _ and the American people believe _ that the use of
force and the tragic loss of life was wrong,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang calmly countered: ``Had the Chinese government not taken
the resolute measures then, we could not have enjoyed the stability
that we are enjoying today.''
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders' give-and-take went both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang challenged Clinton to publicly proclaim what has been
promised only by lower-level U.S. officials: The U.S. commitment to
a so-called ``three ~~`No's' policy'' toward Taiwan, an island of
21.8 million people about 100 miles off the Chinese coast.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Three No's'' are: No independence for Taiwan, no U.N.
membership for Taiwan and no diplomatic maneuver that would offer
separate U.S. recognition to China and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing considers Taiwan to be part of China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declined to publicly offer Jiang the reassurances that
he sought. Clinton said that he had ``reaffirmed our long-standing
one-China policy'' during his private discussions. But Clinton left
it to National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger to publicly
restate the U.S. commitment to shun separate recognition for
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is between a rock and a hard place on
the explosive issue. A federal law _ the 1979 Taiwan Relations Act
_ requires the United States to defend Taiwan against any armed
attack by Chinese forces as though Taiwan were an independent
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sent a U.S. Navy armada into the straits between Taiwan
and China in 1996 when Chinese forces aimed intimidating missile
tests toward Taiwan during the province's election.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. support for Taiwan remains a flash point in U.S. domestic
politics. The House voted 411 to 0 in early June for a measure
urging Clinton to call on Beijing to renounce the use of force
against Taiwan. Jiang vowed peaceful negotiations to absorb Taiwan
into China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Jiang treated Chinese viewers to a diplomatic minuet
on the independent-minded province of Tibet and the return of the
region's exiled spiritual leader, Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang said that his government would welcome the return of the
Tibetan leader as long as the saffron robed leader ``can publicly
make the statement and a commitment that Tibet is an inalienable
part of China.'' Clinton endorsed the pre-condition and urged Jiang
to meet with the Tibetan leader.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Jiang seemed to relish their easy ability to
play off each other to make their points to audiences in both
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Citing their nations' ongoing dispute over human rights _
including Chinese authorities' arrest and release of at least three
political dissidents during Clinton's visit _ Clinton told viewers:
``You can see that neither one of us (is) shy about being strong
about how we believe about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiang injected that each leader is ``a strong defender'' of his
nation's interests, ``but despite that, we still can have very
friendly exchanges of views and discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Jiang politely agreed to disagree over the two
nations' conflicting policies on the use of nuclear weapons as they
agreed to detarget their missile arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has long rejected ruling out first use of
nuclear weapons. China pledges only to use its arsenal of nuclear
weapons in retaliation for a nuclear attack that has already taken
place.
</P>
<P>
   Without being asked, Jiang used the free-wheeling format to
reject allegations that the Chinese government funneled campaign
contributions to candidates in the 1996 U.S. federal elections in
an effort to win influence in the United States. The allegations
are ``sheer fabrications,'' Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS - STORY MAY END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Li Zhaoxing, China's ambassador to the United States, told White
House officials that the broadcast on state-run television may have
reached 500 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials surprised Clinton with the decision to
broadcast the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush took part in a nationally televised
question-and-answer session during a visit here in February 1989.
But Chinese authorities declined to translate sensitive remarks
into Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials offered President Ronald Reagan the
opportunity to address the nation in a pre-taped address in 1984.
But the officials then aired only selected portions of Reagan's
address.
</P>
</TEXT>
