<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL: &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SUMMIT (Beijing) _ The U.S.-China summit ended Saturday
night with a formal state dinner after an extraordinary live
televised exchange between President Clinton and Chinese President
Jiang Zemin over human rights, Tibet and China's path to the
future. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TV-BROADCAST (Beijing) _ What is perhaps most remarkable
about Saturday's exchange between President Clinton and President
Jiang Zemin is that the debate, covering sensitive topics from
human rights to Tibet, was broadcast live all over China, via China
Central Television-1, the government's main television station. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ASSESS (Beijing) _ President Bill Clinton handed China's
leaders a gift simply by coming here, giving them global respect
despite the sharp criticism of his China policy back home.
Saturday, with the surprise decision to televise an extended news
conference and debate on human rights, China may have returned the
favor. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-REACT (Beijing) _ As evening fell on Yonganli Street, a
crowded alleyway of small shops on the east side of town, word was
filtering from one doorway to the next about what had been on
television at noon: In a nationally televised news conference,
President Clinton had come out and said that the Chinese
government's use of military force to suppress the 1989 Tiananmen
demonstrations had been tragic and wrong. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HILLARY (Beijing) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton met Saturday
with some of the best and brightest of Beijing's vibrant women's
movement, discussing a wide range of sometimes sensitive issues
from domestic violence to unemployment to China's high rates of
female suicide. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-ASSEMBLY (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ New alliances
emerged Saturday in the aftermath of the election to the Northern
Ireland Assembly, with the British province's largest Catholic and
Protestant parties turning away from old divisions to unite in
support of the fragile peace process. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-U.S.-DUES (United Nations) _ The United States could lose
its vote in the General Assembly unless it comes up with $211
million to $241 million more than it now expects to pay in U.N.
dues and assessments this year, according to a new U.S. government
estimate. By Christopher S. Wren
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-SHARK-ATTACKS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ A spate of
shark attacks, including one that maimed the national body-boarding
champion, has baffled scientists, temporarily closed some beaches
along the South African coast and scared off some surfers. By
Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS (El Bosque, Mexico) _ A recent violent episode in
El Bosque showed both Mexicans and international observers how
volatile the civil conflict in Chiapas has become and how far
President Ernesto Zedillo has moved toward open military
confrontation with the Zapatista rebels, more than four years after
the Indian guerrillas first emerged with a brief New Year's Day
uprising. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-ETHICS-RULES (Geneva, Switzerland) _ Responding to
impassioned pleas from developing countries desperately seeking a
vaccine to fight the AIDS epidemic, an ethics panel convened by the
United Nations is recommending major changes in the way
experimental vaccines are tested in people. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-INVESTIGATION (Paris) _ French investigators looking into
the crash that killed Diana, Princess of Wales, and her companion
here last Aug. 31 have gathered little evidence to bolster initial
police theories that photographers chasing the car caused the
driver to lose control, according to a new book that quotes
extensively from police reports. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL: &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HMOS-DOCTOR-PAY _ Some big health insurers are putting a new
squeeze on doctors, sharply cutting the fees they pay and imposing
strict new rules that physicians say can undermine patient care.
Angry doctors, in turn, are fighting back with lawsuits and
complaints to state regulators. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HARASS _ With the Supreme Court creating a new national
policy on sexual harassment virtually overnight, many companies are
moving quickly to re-examine their rules, expecting to adopt
tougher measures to meet the Court's standards. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   HUD-DRUG-EVICTIONS (Oakland, Calif.) _ According to housing
officials in Oakland, Herman Walker poses a danger to his fellow
tenants in public housing. And if these officials have their way,
he will have to find a new home. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-STREET-CHURCH (Boston) _ When the Rev. Deborah W. Little
holds church, the ground beneath her congregation seems at times to
tremble. But that would be because the service _ a gathering of
people who live on the street together with some who live in the
suburbs _ takes place on a busy corner of Boston Common above a
subway line. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FROG-FUNGUS _ A newly discovered fungus appears to be the
cause of an epidemic among amphibians that is killing off frogs and
toads of a wide variety of declining species in rain forests in
Australia and Central America, according to a new report by an
international team of researchers. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   NYC-BED&AMP;BREAKFAST (New York) _ In a city with a burnished new
image, waves of tourism, and booked-up hotels with the highest
rates in the country, it was bound to happen: bed-and-breakfasts
are springing up all over Manhattan, where landlords are forgoing
the security of long-term leases for the chance to make thousands
more a year putting up tourists for the night. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON: &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ In a striking disagreement over the
Lewinsky matter, the White House and the Justice Department have
taken significantly different legal positions in a Federal appeals
case that will be argued next week over whether President Clinton
can invoke the attorney-client privilege to sharply limit the
questioning of one of his closest aides. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRIPP (Washington) _ They have heard her voice for
months, but on Tuesday morning, the 23 men and women serving on a
federal grand jury here will finally meet Linda Tripp. As the
Pentagon employee explains why she chose to betray a friend, the
grand jurors will have an opportunity to weigh her motives and
credibility by looking in her eyes. By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-INTERNET (Washington) _ The Internet, with its
influence on everything from commerce and national security to
privacy and crime, has become an issue as politically alluring to
many lawmakers as cutting taxes, educating children and locking up
criminals. It seems that not a week goes by on Capitol Hill without
a hearing, a meeting or a gathering about one of a bevy of
Internet-related issues confronting Congress. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ On Linda Tripp's upcoming grand jury appearance.
By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ On Mayor Giuliani's apparent dislike of Public
Advocate Mark Green. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER: &LR;
</P>
