<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9951 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-RIFLE-TOWN-ART-N     06-27 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-RIFLE-TOWN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN CALLED RIFLE STRUGGLES WITH GUN CULTURE GONE AWRY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIFLE, Colo. _ In this gateway to prime elk hunting country, the
motel is called the Remington, the minimall is called the
Winchester, each street sign carries a silhouette of a rifle and
the town history is titled ``Rifle Shots.''
</P>
<P>
   So in a town with a strong gun culture and where people are
keenly aware of the dangers that guns can pose, it was with alarm
and uneasiness that residents watched on their television sets in
recent months as teen-age boys, from rural towns just like Rifle,
showed up at schoolyard after schoolyard in scattered towns around
the nation, and turned their rifles on unsuspecting classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what scares me,'' said Roland Klocker, president of the
local sportsmen's club, as shotguns boomed from a skeet range. ``It
could be here. It could be Rifle.'' Mystified by a gun culture gone
awry, he added, ``I just can't get into the heads of those kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In conversations at the town's firing range, gun shop, high
school and video store, residents revealed that they were wrestling
with the schoolyard shootings, an issue that is gripping rural
America this summer.
</P>
<P>
   At Rifle High School, which has 900 students, teachers have
discussed ways to identify potentially threatening students next
fall. In hunter education classes, instructors are tightening
standards, failing teen-agers who seem immature. Many people here
said they favored childproofing guns, either by locking them in
cabinets or by installing trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   But the schoolyard violence has left the town deeply concerned,
looking for reasons for what has happened and seeking ways to keep
it from happening here.
</P>
<P>
   They offered explanations as diverse as a breakdown of
traditional hunting culture, a modern desensitization to the
consequences of violence and carelessness by adults who store
firearms in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its Western rawhide name, this town of 5,000 people has
a newly suburban overlay. Not far from Rifle, which lies in a
cottonwood valley surrounded by beige mesas dotted with pinyon and
greasewood, an abandoned oil camp has been reincarnated as the
state's largest retirement community.
</P>
<P>
   In the other direction, Aspen beckons with high-paying jobs,
luring migrants here from California. With Rifle's real-estate
values tripling in a decade, the pickup truck tribe shares Railroad
Avenue with families in sport utility vehicles. The hook and bullet
crowd coexists with the Rifle men's play group, an association of
stay-at-home dads.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rifle High School no longer automatically lets students
out for the start of the elk-hunting season, many teen-age boys who
move here feel the pull to go hunting. But hunting-safety
instructors here warn that an adult mentor, either a parent or a
friend, is essential for a teen-ager to learn how to responsibly
handle firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally, we get these kids, where the parents are
divorced, the mother doesn't hunt, but they want to be cool and
hunt because their peer group does this,'' said Sarah McKenney, a
hunter-safety instructor. ``They come in with weird strips shaved
off their heads, earrings, other body parts pierced. They don't
look like real outdoorsmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are going to be smart-mouthed and disrespectful, I'll
let them coast the whole weekend, then I tell them to come back
next year, when they grow up,'' said Ms. McKenney, who has taught
hunter safety to 1,000 students here in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here place much of the fault for schoolyard
shootings on a breakdown in the rural traditions of teaching
children respect for life and responsibility in the handling of
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that the tradition has been broken,'' said David
Ebeler, a 25-year-old who recently passed his hunter-safety course,
a requirement for all hunters in Colorado under 50. ``It's a
respect thing. You keep the guns locked up. It's always been that
way in my household, in my parents' household. You don't point it
at anything you don't want to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   At Timberline Sporting Goods, where wall racks were stocked with
everything from shotguns to muzzle loaders, owner Mike Homan blamed
a lack of discipline, at home and in the schools. ``There's no
punishment for doing something wrong _ it's timeout, Junior, go to
the corner,'' Homan grumbled. ``You can't spank a kid in public
anymore.'' Smacking his fist into his palm, he said, ``My old man
would have said `Time out' _ yeah, when you wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   Homan and others said that exposure to an avalanche of violence,
on television, in videos and in pop music lyrics, had desensitized
young people about the danger of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the kids who come into here are into the violence,''
said Penny Rupp, manager of Sundown Video. ``Definitely violence.
All the blood and guts they can get.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jim Builteman, a hunting-safety instructor, said: ``Today,
if you have a grudge against somebody, death is an alternative.
Fifty years ago, when I was a kid, you got in a fist fight, you got
a bloody nose. And that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Out at the firing range, Klocker, the club president, speculated
that many young people had no understanding of the consequences of
pulling a trigger. ``They see so many movies on TV where the good
guy shoots the bad guy; then, next week, the bad guy is back on TV
again, shooting away,'' he said, as a young marksman shattered an
orange clay skeet with a shotgun blast.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing his round, Carl Day, the 14-year-old marksman,
nodded in agreement. Referring to the high school shooters, Carl
said: ``Those kids were probably frustrated. They didn't know much
about guns, and what they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, 30 years of hunter-safety classes have proved so
successful that state health department statistics indicate that
hunting may be safer than fishing. From 1993 to 1995, three people
were killed in hunting accidents, while nine people died in fishing
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunting teaches young people respect for life,'' said Criss
Payne, a Marine Corps veteran who was shooting at the range with
his young children. ``When they go out and kill an animal, they
have to clean it themselves, they have to drag it out. They know,
without a shadow of a doubt, what a gun does when you pull the
trigger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
