<HEADER>
A9959 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-HARASS-975(2TA     06-27 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HARASS-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES REACT QUICKLY TO COURT'S SEXUAL HARASSMENT RULINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Supreme Court creating a new national policy on sexual
harassment virtually overnight, many companies are moving quickly
to re-examine their rules, expecting to adopt tougher measures to
meet the court's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Most large corporations already have strong harassment policies,
but human resource experts said that if there was a weak link in
those programs it was usually that the companies did not repeatedly
communicate the policy to all employees or did not have effective
mechanisms set up for employees to report harassment without fear
of reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Executives, lawyers and consultants specializing in human
resources predicted that medium-size and smaller companies would
have to do the most to strengthen their anti-harassment policies.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the Supreme Court's two far-reaching decisions on
Friday came quickly. Corporations from Nabisco to Lockheed-Martin
were set to review their policies, corporate executives and
advisers said, to make sure they heed the court's holding that
employers will face broader exposure for sexual harassment by
supervisors, especially if the employers do not have strong
anti-harassment programs.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bernstein, a lawyer in Newark, N.J., who advises RJ
Reynolds and Continental Airlines on employment matters, said: ``In
light of these opinions, I'm telling my clients that the Supreme
Court is saying that if you want to minimize your liability, if you
want to insulate yourself, then establish clear policies,
distribute them among you work force. Make sure you can establish
that your employees have received your policies and your complaint
procedures and that they know precisely who it is they're supposed
to complain to.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't limited to sexual harassment,'' Bernstein said.
``The same general principles apply to claims of homosexual
harassment, racial harassment and national-origin harassment. This
is the perfect opportunity for employers to seize the day and
educate employees to their policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping into a field that had been marked by confusion, the
Supreme Court expanded potential liability for sexual harassment by
ruling that employers could be held liable when a supervisor
threatened to demote or take other action against an employee who
refused the supervisor's sexual demands, even when the threats were
not carried out.
</P>
<P>
   But the court's majority wrote in the pair of 7-2 decisions that
employers could generally avoid liability in such cases by showing
that they had strong anti-harassment programs. In particular, the
rulings suggested that employers make sure they communicate those
policies to all employees and set up effective mechanisms for
receiving and reviewing harassment complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the decisions were issued, corporate counsels
and employment lawyers were reading and rereading the opinions to
figure out exactly how to advise their companies and clients.
</P>
<P>
   With companies eager to avoid the large-scale sexual harassment
settlements agreed to by corporate giants like Smith Barney and
Mitsubishi, several employment experts predicted that the ruling
would drum up a lot of business for consultants who advise
companies on sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi agreed to pay $34 million to settle a sexual
harassment case brought by female workers at a factory in Illinois,
while Smith Barney, in a proposed settlement, agreed to pay several
hundred thousand dollars to female workers who said they had been
harassed and to spend $15 million on anti-discrimination and
anti-harassment training.
</P>
<P>
   Employment experts predicted that tens of thousands of human
resources officials and senior executives would soon begin
reassessing their policies to reduce their employers' chance of
liability in which plaintiffs often win hundreds of thousands and
even millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water-cooler discussions about harassment will now shift to
boardroom discussions about harassment,'' said Susan Meisinger,
senior vice president for the Society for Human Resource
Management, an association of more than 100,000 personnel and
employee relations professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The math has changed a bit,'' she added. ``These two decisions
are the culmination of a public focus on the subject, and employers
have to anticipate the cumulative impact of this will be more
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Conrad, senior vice president for litigation at the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, said: ``After these decisions we'll be telling
people there are things you can do to prevent this from happening
and to protect yourself in the process. Have a policy and
effectively communicate it. Promptly investigate complaints. And
take prompt corrective action.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the two cases decided Friday, a former lifeguard sued
the city of Boca Raton, Fla., complaining that two male supervisors
had created a sexually hostile atmosphere for years through
offensive touching and lewd remarks. Even though the city had a
formal anti-harassment policy, the court found the city liable,
noting that Boca Raton had failed to disseminate the policy to the
beach employees.
</P>
<P>
   The court also faulted Boca Raton for making no effort to keep
track of the supervisors' conduct and for not making clear that
employees could bypass the harassing supervisors if they wanted to
file complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, an employee of Burlington Industries sued the
company, saying she felt compelled to quit after a supervisor had
said he could make life harder or easier for her depending on
whether she did such things as wear shorter skirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most employers should be paying attention to this to be sure
they're not behind on this issue,'' said Angela DeSilva, chief
counsel for Duke Energy Corp. in Houston. ``They should go back and
analyze whether they have a policy and analyze whether they're
effectively disseminating the policy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At some companies, executives voiced confidence that they had
tough anti-harassment policies that would help protect them against
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Sellinger, chief labor and chief litigation counsel at
Nabisco, said: ``You'll probably find that the larger companies are
in really good shape. The medium-sized and smaller companies that
don't have a good human resources staff are not going to be in good
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she said Nabisco executives would certainly review
the court's decisions to make sure the company heeded the criteria
set forth to avoid liability.
</P>
<P>
   In its rulings, the Supreme Court analyzed three situations and
types of sexual harassment. In one, often called quid pro quo
harassment, the supervisor takes an adverse action _ like
dismissal, failing to promote, reducing benefits or reassigning
with significantly reduced responsibilities _ against an employee
who refuses to submit to the supervisor's sexual demands. In such
cases, the court wrote, affirming a long-standing line of cases,
that the employer is automatically liable, even when it has a
strong anti-harassment policy in place.
</P>
<P>
   In the second situation, generally called a hostile work
environment case, there is a sexually hostile environment, marked
by severe or pervasive conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In the third situation, a supervisor threatens a tangible job
detriment, like a demotion, to someone who spurns the supervisor's
advances, but the threat goes unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that in these two situations the employer could
be held liable for the harassment, but could escape liability by
proving that it had ``exercised reasonable care to prevent and
correct promptly any sexually harassing behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled further that employers could also avoid
liability by showing that the employee asserting harassment
``unreasonably failed to take advantage of any preventive or
corrective opportunities provided by the employer.''
</P>
<P>
   Invoking such a defense, employers would argue that it would be
wrong to hold them liable because an employee was unreasonable in
failing to complain to higher-ups and thus did not give the
employer the chance to correct the untoward behavior.
</P>
<P>
   While corporate officials applauded the rulings because they
drew clear lines about what to do to avoid liability, plaintiffs
lawyers and women's groups also praised the decisions for holding
that employers faced liability for harassment by supervisors, even
when there was no tangible adverse job action.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Davis, legal director for the National Organization for
Women Legal Education and Defense Fund, said, ``It does a very
smart thing. It continues to make sure that employers bear the
burden rather than the individual if harm is done. But it creates
very strong incentives for employers to be very vigilant in dealing
with sexual harassment. It makes it clear that it's important for
companies to be very explicit in having a zero-tolerance policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The lifeguard who sued, Beth Ann Faragher, now a lawyer in
Denver, said in an interview, ``This was an argument about
principle and is a victory for working women because it tells their
employers they must take affirmative steps to prevent''
harassment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
