<HEADER>
A9961 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PITFALLS-REVIEW     06-27 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PITFALLS-REVIEW-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIPLOMACY BY OTHER MEANS: GETTING STINKO ON KEROSENE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pitfalls aplenty have lurked around every corner
during President Clinton's visit to China. Political pitfalls: What
to say about Tiananmen Square? Protocol pitfalls: How to overcome
the president's habitual tardiness, which would surely grate on
Chinese ideas of punctuality?
</P>
<P>
   By no means least dangerous were the potential dinner-table
pitfalls, like those that confronted the American guest of honor
Saturday night at the Great Hall of the People in Beijing. The
formal banquet is a Chinese institution, and at its end lies an
inevitable and obligatory round of toasts with the sorghum-based
firewater known as maotai. It smells a lot like JP-4, the stuff
that powers the engines on Air Force One, and it is only slightly
more drinkable.
</P>
<P>
   But drink it visitors must, and it wouldn't do to gag in the
presence of one's host. Richard Nixon knocked maotais back with
Chou En-lai on his historic trip in 1972, and a decade later George
Bush, then vice president, did the same thing with Deng Xiaoping.
``Ganbei,'' the Chinese say _ bottoms up, more or less. They mean
the glass, not you.
</P>
<P>
   No sipping is allowed. An aide who went to Beijing with Nixon
recalls that the president and Zhou looked into each other's maotai
cups at the end of each toast to make sure the other had drained
every drop. A forerunner of the Reaganite doctrine of trust but
verify, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   And all this comes at the end of a multicourse feed where you
are expected to sample every dish. When Bush returned to China as
president in 1989 _ a trip I covered _ his party was served boar's
penis soup, or so the menu translation said. I wondered if it
wasn't a linguistic mishap like ``leg of lamp,'' but boar's penis
soup is what everyone thought it was. We did our duty.
</P>
<P>
   So did the author Theodore H. White, when served suckling pig at
a banquet given by Zhou in Chungking during World War II, when both
were youngsters. White, a correspondent for Time and a Jew,
protested as politely as he could that he did not eat pork. Zhou,
master of every situation even as a junior official, gestured with
his chopsticks and said: ``Teddy, this is China. Look again _ see?
Look. It looks to you like pig. But in China this is not a pig.
This is a duck.'' The writer laughed, shrugged and tucked into his
pork-duck, crackling included.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, they don't care whether you eat all the food, but
they will not tolerate wussing out on vodka. Down the hatch in one
gulp, and once a bottle is opened, it is rude not to finish it
before calling it a night.
</P>
<P>
   I remember more vividly than I would like a dinner on my first
trip to Moscow. I must have been almost 30, with college and the
army behind me, so I should have known better. But I persuaded
myself that I could match some Russian friends glass for rapid
glass, and I very nearly jumped off the balcony of a restaurant
called Praga.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years later, I did a six-month stint in the Soviet
Union, as it was then, and I learned to pace myself. At a farewell
dinner, I paced myself so well, nibbling zakuski between gulps,
that I never even considered a jump.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't. I was out cold, KO'd humiliatingly short of
midnight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   American presidents have displayed a lot more decorum than I
while exchanging many a toast with Russian leaders over the past
few decades. Some may have learned the old Russian trick of dumping
the contents of a vodka glass into a water glass (which works fine,
as long as they don't catch you, and as long as you don't forget
and take a gulp of ``water'').
</P>
<P>
   Only one president I know of, whose name is probably best
suppressed here, publicly displayed vodka's formidable capacity for
undermining politesse, commenting somewhat indecorously after six
or seven belts upon a female aide's physical attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon handled these things well. He coolly exchanged
vodka toasts with Leonid Brezhnev at his swimming pool at San
Clemente in 1973, with Hollywood stars illuminating the evening. A
wine lover, he also developed an effective if stingy method for
conserving his best stock. He instructed the waiter on the
presidential yacht Sequoia, or so it is said, to wrap bottles in a
white towel before pouring. The president got Chateau Margaux, and
so did his special guests; the others got something less grand from
California.
</P>
<P>
   According to his valet in the days when he was a pitchman for
General Electric, Ronald Reagan had a strategy for postspeech
pow-wows with the company's executives and clients: The valet mixed
water and white wine in a thermos, and when it came time to pour
out the martinis, Reagan was given his relatively benign potion
while the others got their loudmouth soup.
</P>
<P>
   What you really want for toasts, of course, is champagne. The
British usually give you Pol Roger Cuvee Winston Churchill on
august occasions, which strikes me as perfect.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it will never give you a head that jerks like a
jackhammer, or cause the distress to the constitution that the
Australians politely call a Technicolor yawn. Lots of other local
specialties will, especially if you're not used to them.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of a long career, I have had disquieting
encounters with Danish aquavit (caraway flavored and drunk with a
beer chaser); French marc (made from the pips and skins of grapes
left in the wine press); Vietnamese wine with a pickled snake in
the bottle; various sugar-cane concoctions in the Caribbean, and
fenny, an Indian bruiser made from cashew nuts. All taste a little
like petroleum distillates. One slug makes your knees knock, two
make you drool and three fell you like a redwood.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Unicum, a bitter, syrupy digestive in an
orb-shaped bottle that is said to cure hangovers. It is
manufactured by Peter Zwack, former Hungarian ambassador to
Washington, former member of Parliament and all-around good guy. It
hurts me to say so, but in my experience it is unmatched for sheer
yuckiness. I call it the dark destroyer, even to my friend's face.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the recent American courtship of Mongolia has proved at
least one thing: Tamer drinks can taste just as bad as stronger
stuff. Nomads there drink fermented mare's milk, and visiting
bigwigs are asked to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip last year, Hillary Rodham Clinton compared the
beverage, called airak, to yogurt. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright didn't compare it to anything, but she sternly instructed
those traveling with her: If you don't want to drink it, ``you must
touch it to your lips as if tasting it.''
</P>
<P>
   And no wincing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
