<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWING TRUST IN CLINTON, CHINESE ALLOWED RARE TELEVISED DEBATE  
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-TV-BROADCAST, CHINA-REACT,
CHINA-HILLARY) 
(nk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton handed China's leaders a gift simply
by coming here, giving them global respect despite the sharp
criticism of his China policy back home.
</P>
<P>
   With Saturday's surprise decision to televise an extended news
conference and debate on human rights, China may have returned the
favor. The live telecast allowed Clinton to make forceful
statements on human rights and Tibet before a Chinese audience,
thereby addressing American criticism that he was appeasing a
repressive government even as he pressed forward with his strategy
of engaging the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Though the basic differences between the United States and China
are no secret here, it was highly unusual for the Chinese to see
anyone on television calling the 1989 killings on Tiananmen Square
wrong, or praising the integrity of the Dalai Lama. Chinese news
reports on touchy debates are invariably one-sided and brief _ as
was the television coverage Saturday night on the day's encounter.
</P>
<P>
   American officials were elated with the televised debate,
convinced it would help justify the president's complex policy of
engaging a country with fundamentally different views on freedom.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Sandy Berger gloated that the event
was a first, allowing open debate on topics censored in China's
official press. It was by no means clear how many Chinese saw the
press conference, since the fact that it would be broadcast live
was not advertised in advance. Word of the debate, however, was
spreading around Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the live broadcast, which must have been approved at the
highest levels, was a testament to the Chinese government's trust
in Clinton, who is viewed here as a great statesman, pursuing
America's long-term interests with China despite backbiting from
his political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   They had to know he might forcefully raise sensitive issues, but
also gambled that he would raise them, as he did, with a nod to
China's historical and cultural differences, and that the two
presidents would end the hour with smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders could turn Saturday's exchange to political
advantage. It provided an example of their largely shared vision of
a partnership in which common interests are pursued while
differences are acknowledged and debated, as they did in Washington
last October when Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited. In this
convenient formulation, the airing of differences becomes a sign of
strength in the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the statements Saturday also foretell discord and
disappointment. For inherent in Clinton's vision, and his ability
to sell it domestically, is the idea that by engaging China,
promoting investment and trade as well as educational and technical
ties, he will cause China to be more like the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Over time he might be right, but in the coming years, at least,
there is no guarantee that China's profound economic and social
changes will lead to Western-style political freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's broadcast signaled the security of Jiang and his
policies of economic reform and deeper ties with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this shows the Chinese leadership is very confident,''
said Liu Xuecheng, an expert on Chinese-American relations at the
China Center for International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Far from shying away from debate, Jiang had clearly prepared for
the pointed exchanges. Though an American reporter first asked
about the detention of dissidents, it was no accident that a
Chinese news reporter asked him to explain China's human rights
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it coincidental that he had prepared detailed notes on
the subject and that he volunteered to expound on China's Tibet
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think President Clinton is a strong defender of the American
interest, and I am a strong defender of the Chinese interest,''
Jiang said. ``But despite that, we still can have very friendly
exchanges of views and discussion. And I think that is democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Along similar lines, Shen Dingli, deputy director of American
Studies at Fudan University in Shanghai, saw the debate as
positive. ``Both countries could uphold their positions on human
rights, but still be friendly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, too, said at the press conference that ``it is
important that whatever our disagreements over past actions, China
and the United States must go forward on the right side of history
for the future sake of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial days of his visit have in fact highlighted these
differences. The day he arrived, a hard-line culture chief in
modern, prosperous Shanghai blocked the travel to New York of a
historical opera, commissioned and paid for by Lincoln Center,
because it did not meet her ideas of cultural correctness.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to Xian was preceded by the temporary detention
of a few local democracy campaigners _ a routine roundup for China,
but one that shocked the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``debate'' Saturday, Jiang gave not an inch. Dissidents
were jailed, he said, because they had violated the law _ and isn't
this what China's vaunted progress toward the ``rule of law'' is
all about? he seemed to ask.
</P>
<P>
   The use of combat troops to end the 1989 student demonstrations
in Tiananmen Square, killing hundreds in the process, could not
have been a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the Chinese government not taken the resolute measures we
did then we could not have enjoyed the stability that we are
enjoying today,'' Jiang said, repeating an oft-used argument.
</P>
<P>
   On Tibet, Jiang sounded more conciliatory than another official
did on Friday when he all but called the Dalai Lama a murderer and
torturer. As Jiang put it, if only the Dalai Lama will acknowledge
that Tibet is part of China and that Taiwan is a province of China,
then ``the door to negotiation is open.''
</P>
<P>
   This formulation has actually been policy for some time.
However, despite the Dalai Lama's recent statements that he is
ready to talk about degrees of autonomy for Tibet, Chinese leaders
insist that his actions still betray a dedication to independence.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon Berger was asked whether China had made any
concessions on rights. He said, referring to the televised debate,
``The very fact that this happened is movement on the part of the
Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   Shen, the Shanghai scholar, made a similar point. ``We need to
view the achievements of this summit through the interactions,'' he
said, ``not what gets written on paper.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
