NYT-06-27-98 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9996 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-RELIGION-$AD     06-27 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-RELIGION-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINA'S CHRISTIANS MUST CHOOSE: RESTRICTED LEGAL WORSHIP OR
UNDERGROUND RISKS
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON; CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV28.
 &HT;    With photo to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, June 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Sunday evening in the candlelit sanctuary of Dong
Tang, a ``patriotic'' Catholic church, a four-year-old Chinese girl
in a frilly dress sang the memorized words of a hymn with as much
gusto as the adults around her.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 worshipers chanted alleluias, partook holy
communion and heard of miraculous events at the Sermon on the
Mount. Elderly men, young couples, three sweaty teens in baggy
pants -- basketball in tow -- filled two-thirds of the pews last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese-language service looked much like a mass in America.
</P>
<P>
   But the priest could not mention Catholicism's most revered
living figure, Pope John Paul II, or even whisper a reference to an
issue central to the church worldwide: the stand against abortion.
</P>
<P>
   And fortunately for the four-year-old's mother, no hard-line
Chinese authorities were in Dong Tang (East Church) that night
looking for violators of government mandates, because it is
forbidden to spread religion to anyone under 18.
</P>
<P>
   China controls all Christian groups by forcing them to register
as social organizations, regulating what they preach and arresting
or detaining those who cross the government-drawn line of
acceptable religious practice. Both Protestants and Catholics must
be part of China's ``patriotic'' religious movement, which means
they cannot align with a foreign-based church.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of restrictions advocates of human rights
hope President Bill Clinton's visit today to a Beijing Protestant
church will spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Dong Peiying, 77, saw her religion outlawed and its
sanctuaries desecrated during the Cultural Revolution from
1966-1976. She welcomes any restoration of open religious practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite free for people to worship. There are many people
who believe in religion now. Usually there are no obstacles,'' said
the diminutive white-haired woman leaving the Dong Tang service,
around the corner from Beijing's Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
   But she sighed when asked about her church's break with the
Vatican, which China's Communist government directed after the 1949
revolution in order to expel foreign influence from a potent social
force.
</P>
<P>
   Will China's Catholics ever return to Rome's fold?
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is possible. We hope it is possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese think tank specialists speak of a possible breakthrough
in informal talks quietly going on between intermediaries for the
Vatican and the Chinese government. To facilitate the reported
compromise, the Vatican would end diplomatic recognition of Taiwan
and take an even trickier step of agreeing Rome would not appoint
archbishops in China.
</P>
<P>
   In back-channel talks in March, a Catholic emissary is said to
have cited as a possible precedent a centuries-old agreement with
French and German monarchs, in which the Vatican reportedly allowed
local authorities to select archbishops.
</P>
<P>
   Even could those conditions be met, the Holy See would face
repeated compromises in reuniting with the Chinese church under
current government controls.
</P>
<P>
   At least four million Chinese Catholics agree with parishioner
Dong that the constraints are not too onerous, and they worship in
the officially-sanctioned church, according to government figures.
Another 10 million Chinese participate in the Protestant churches
registered with the government.
</P>
<P>
   But 30 million or more are estimated to gather in underground
churches in defiance of government regulations, praying in
apartments or caves or fields.
</P>
<P>
   Local enforcement of the national policy is uneven. Some
unregistered churches remain fairly free from harassment, said Nina
Shea, director of the Center for Religious Freedom in Washington,
D.C. Other churches are not.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only underground movement in China. There is no
Solidarity, no samizat press,'' said Shea, referring to the labor
union that brought down Poland's Communist regime and the
underground publications that criticized Soviet life. ``The Chinese
have been terribly efficient in wiping out dissent.''
</P>
<P>
   And dissent, according to Western watchers, is exactly what the
Chinese government fears religion may foster -- especially with
today's increasing unemployment and economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally in China there have been religious sects that have
arisen, especially in the countryside, and gathered a lot of people
and eventually moved to political ends,'' said Brent Fulton,
managing director of the Institute for Chinese Studies at Wheaton
College in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The most infamous example was the 1850-64 Taiping Rebellion, led
by a charismatic Chinese who declared himself a brother to Jesus,
called by God to save China from the oppression of the Qing
Dynasty's Manchu rulers.
</P>
<P>
   His militant evangelism attracted legions of followers who
mounted civil war and took over much of central China. Only with
the aid of French and British forces did the Manchus finally quell
the uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Today, religion with political overtones particularly is
targeted in Tibet, where authorities suspect the exiled Dalai Lama
wants to return to lead Buddhist followers to independence. Muslim
activists in mountainous Xinjiang Province on the western border
are likewise monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Even in mainstream ethnic Chinese areas, however, deviation from
accepted religious lines spells trouble. From across the country
come reports of religious leaders being arrested or detained,
popular shrines shut down and worship sites trashed.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials maintain the charges of religious persecution,
including those made in the latest U.S. State Department Human
Rights Report, are wrong and even fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   Like the previous reports, they simply pieced together hearsay
and distorted information and used this material as the basis for
their report,'' Ye Xiao Wen, director general of China's Religious
Affairs Bureau said at a news conference in Washington this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese citizens' freedom of religious belief is guaranteed
under the constitution of China,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when three prominent American clergymen toured China this
year to assess the status of religion, a key question concerned the
fate of 30 Chinese religious leaders believed detained for reasons
of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton College's Fulton, who was in the delegation, said
authorities did not deny religious figures have been imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   They practiced religion outside the official sphere and that's
why they were arrested. The official version is they were causing
trouble or getting into political affairs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9997 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV     06-27 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RELIGION IN CHINA - TWO MILLENNIA OF COMPETITION
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON; CHINA-RELIGION-$ADV28
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, June 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Here's how China's personality for the last two
millennia has been shaped by religions:
</P>
<P>
   200 B.C.-200 A.D. _ Imperial Confucianism. The human-centered
philosophy of the Chinese thinker Confucius (551-479 BC), who
stressed duty to the state and to ``moral behavior according to
status,'' is adopted by Chinese imperial rulers as a state
religion.
</P>
<P>
   1st Century A.D. _ Buddhism. The teachings of The Buddha, who
probably lived in Nepal in the 7th century B.C., are imported from
India and spread rapidly, eclipsing state Confucianism during the
golden age of Chinese Buddhism in the 5th-9th centuries A.D.
</P>
<P>
   2d-6th Century A.D. _ Daoism. A native mystical philosophy,
rooted in the wise sayings attributed to a Chinese hermit named Lao
Zi, thrives as an alternative to rigid Confucianism. It stresses
contemplation and ``dropping out,'' in contrast to Confucianism's
codes of duty to state and family elders.
</P>
<P>
   8th-9th Centuries A.D. _ Islam. Arabian camel caravans on the
Silk Road introduce the Muslim religion, which takes hold in
present-day Xinjiang province of western China and other ethnic
minority regions.
</P>
<P>
   16th Century A.D. _ Roman Catholicism. Jesuit priests enter
China, reach the imperial Ming Dynasty court and introduce
Christianity among the inner-most elite. Catholic missionaries
begin underground parishes, even though missionary work is
forbidden by the emperors.
</P>
<P>
   1807 _ Protestantism. Nearly 150 years of increasingly open
Christian proselytizing among Chinese begins as the first
Protestant missionary arrives from Britain.
</P>
<P>
   1843 _ Americans arrive. China opens its borders to American
Protestant missionaries, who are allowed to operate churches and
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   1850-64 __ Taiping Rebellion. Firebrand Chinese mystic draws
ethnic minorities and Chinese to his quasi-Christian revolt against
the Qing Dynasty's oppressive domination. British and French forces
help the Qing defeat rebels, who had nearly toppled the empire.
</P>
<P>
   1898-1901 _ Boxer Rebellion. Devotees of folk religion and
martial arts rise up against foreign influences, attacking
Christian missionaries and their converts. A foreign army of 20,000
U.S., British, Russian, Japanese and French troops enters China to
quell the uprising. Western missionary work expands.
</P>
<P>
   1949 _ Communist Suppression. All missionaries are expelled as
Lenin's atheism becomes the state religion. Some Christian churches
are forced to convert into state-controlled ``patriotic'' churches.
The rest are banned.
</P>
<P>
   1950-1960 _ Tibet Shackled. The People's Liberation Army enters
Tibet and gradually suppresses Tibetan nationalist resistance. The
Tibetan Buddhist leader, the Dalai Lama, escapes to exile in India
in March 1959. Chinese troops destroy monasteries and temples.
About one tenth of Tibet's population starve due to failed Chinese
agricultural policies of the ``Great Leap Forward'' (1959-60).
</P>
<P>
   1966-67 _ Cultural Revolution. Mao's Red Guard radicals destroy
Christian churches and arrest Chinese clergymen of the
``patriotic'' churches. Some congregations go underground, others
disband.
</P>
<P>
   1980s-90s _ Christian revival. With restrictions lightened, some
churches re-appear. Others remain underground as China continues to
ban those Roman Catholic churches with ties to the Vatican, as well
as unregistered Protestant parishes.
</P>
<P>
   August 1996 _ New pressure. With international tension
heightened over Taiwan, communist officials warn against foreign
forces using religion as a ``breakthrough point'' to ``westernize''
China. They put younger, more loyal clergymen in charge of the
official ``patriotic'' churches.
</P>
<P>
   1996-97 _ ``Feudal Superstition'' campaign. Worried at the
spread of folk religions in rural provinces, China destroys more
than 15,000 unregistered temples, churches and tombs. The Religious
Affairs Bureau bans building temples and outdoor Buddhas, saying
these flourished in areas ``controlled by sorcerers, witches and
professional superstitionalists.''
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
