<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A ONE-MAN FEUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few years ago Mark Green, the city's public
advocate, said the Police Department could save several million
dollars by redeploying cops who were assigned to auto maintenance
and janitorial duties. Those types of services could be privatized,
Green said.
</P>
<P>
   As Mayor Rudolph Giuliani considers himself more of an expert on
police matters than even his own police commissioners, the
suggestion was not received warmly. The mayor said Green's proposal
was ``idiotic.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1995, an investigation by the public advocate's
office found that homeless women and children were being denied
housing assistance for which they were eligible. When Green issued
a report on those findings, the mayor denounced it as a ``cheap
shot.'' In fact, the report was accurate and the problems
continued.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1995, Giuliani administration officials refused to let
Green hold a press conference at a senior citizens center in an
Upper East Side Housing project.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter for The Daily News wrote: ``That forced dozens of
senior citizens who had invited Green to the Stanley Isaacs Senior
Center to leave their breakfasts and shuffle out to the sidewalk to
hear him and Boston Mayor Tom Menino discuss federal policy.''
</P>
<P>
   For a variety of reasons _ the biggest being the persistent
criticism of the administration _ Giuliani cannot abide Green.
Mention Mark Green to the mayor and you are very likely to get a
snide reply. It's as if his mere existence were irritating, and his
presence as the city's No. 2 officeholder intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been trying to dream up ways to nuke the public
advocate's office, and thus throw Green out of work, since the
beginning of his first term as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 the mayor tried to cripple the office with a draconian
23 percent budget cut. Peter Vallone, the speaker of the City
Council and no fan of the public advocate's office himself, balked.
So did four former mayors, David Dinkins, Ed Koch, Abe Beame and
John Lindsay. They all criticized the attempt. Said Koch: ``It's
unfair to single out one office and to cut it in a huge way when
others were not cut at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The budget reduction eventually was reduced by half. Nothing,
however, could save Green's parking space at City Hall. After 13
parking tickets, he gave up on what he thought was his right to
park there.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mayor is mounting his biggest offensive yet against the
office of the public advocate. He hopes, through his Charter
Revision Commission, to abolish it.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Powers, a former deputy mayor under Giuliani and the
chairman of the commission, mouthed the mayor's sentiments in a
recent television interview. ``A lot of people have suggested that
we don't need a public advocate anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Green had no reason to be surprised, and he wasn't. At the first
mention of charter change he knew his office would be targeted. As
he put it, ``When I saw this train coming down the track, I said,
`OK, Rudy's going to go for it.' I know how this guy operates.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, a candidate in the Democratic U.S. Senate primary, said
he plans an all-out defense of the public advocate's office.
Describing the mayor's actions as ``personal, political and
retaliatory,'' he said, ``I've never heard of a situation where the
No. 1 officeholder tries to eliminate the No. 2 officeholder in
midterm.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick A.O. Schwarz Jr., chairman of the Charter Commission
that led to the current city government structure, explained on
Friday why he and his colleagues established the office of the
public advocate, which was essentially a continuation of the old
City Council president's office.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``With a strong mayor, which the City Charter creates,
it was particularly important to have a number of checks and
balances to that mayoral power. And we thought the public advocate
was and would be an important element of the checks on that
power.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The mayor is extremely strong and the bureaucracy of
the mayoralty is very strong, so you need to have as much sunlight
thrown on that as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, headstrong, belligerent and resentful of any checks on
his power, disagrees. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0004 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-27 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ALL TRIPPED UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A friend of mine who knows Linda Tripp called to
see if I wanted to meet the Iago of Pentagon City.
</P>
<P>
   We could have dinner. Chat. Get to know each other in a relaxed
setting.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, dear readers, the prospect filled me with fear.
</P>
<P>
   Was Linda Tripp shopping for a new best girlfriend? And why me?
</P>
<P>
   When Kenneth Starr's whistleblower has her big moment before the
grand jury this week, she will chronicle her betrayal of her last
best girlfriend, who was horrified to find that Ms. Tripp had
secretly taped those desperate confidences about the Big Creep and
turned them over to the Little Creep.
</P>
<P>
   I imagined a rendezvous with Linda in a nocturnal alley with
cigarettes and fog and zither music. She would bring her wire; I
would bring my tape recorder.
</P>
<P>
   But I declined. The position of being Linda's girlfriend looked
too daunting. I knew she'd always be egging me on to do something
stupid _ sending a lovey-dovey tape to a man who couldn't care less
or treating Vernon Jordan like an employment agency.
</P>
<P>
   I decided it would be more prudent to keep up with her in the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the man who spent the most time proliferating gossip
about Ms. Tripp last week was the Rector of American Journalism,
James Fallows. The editor of U.S. News &AMP; World Report made the
rounds of the same TV talk shows he recently made a career of
deploring. He was flacking his magazine's account of more Monica
tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The noble, puritanical Fallows is now just another groveling,
pandering, sex-addled newsmagazine hack,'' laughed another
newsmagazine editor.
</P>
<P>
   The man who excoriated journalists for sinking into the muck of
scandals, rather than working with the government to solve public
policy problems, was now muck-sodden, hyping a story that featured
such revelations as: ``Tripp and Lewinsky discuss an incident in
which Lewinsky thought the president was becoming sexually aroused
when Lewinsky told him about her Defense Department trip to Bosnia
in July 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   (You know what it does to me when you say Sarajevo ...)
</P>
<P>
   Fallows tried to dignify his descent into tawdriness with some
high-minded fiddle-faddle. The story says its source ``had no
ideological or commercial motivation to favor the president, the
independent counsel, or any other party in the dispute.'' Surely
such a pure, disinterested, even-keeled leaker does not exist in
this city of vipers.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed his account of two hours of tape corrected the
distortions in Newsweek's edited transcript of 90 minutes. But
there are 20 hours of tape. And so there are still more than 16
hours of corrections to be made. Some scoop.
</P>
<P>
   At least Newsweek heard the tape, and gave readers a transcript.
We don't know what the U.S. News reporter was allowed to do. What
does ``reviewing the material'' mean? The reporter could not even
take notes as she ``reviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallows said his story cast doubt on Starr's charge that the
president wanted to buy Monica's silence with a job, because on
these tapes Monica and Linda were talking about asking the
president for help two months before Monica was subpoenaed in the
Paula Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   But The New York Times and Newsweek reported long ago that
Monica had a job interview with then-U.N. delegate Bill Richardson,
arranged by the president's secretary in mid-October, two months
before Monica was subpoenaed in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The big question persists: Where does a young, low-level
Pentagon employee making $30,000 a year get the gumption to demand
that the White House find her a job for $90,000 where she can do
``something easy'' _ as she says in the U.S. News article _ not
hard like media relations?
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. News story tries to support Clinton by suggesting the
press mistakenly characterized the tape Monica messengered to him
as erotic when it was romantic. On that cassette, the story says,
``She suggests that perhaps she and Clinton could have box dinners
and watch a movie, `tawk,' exchange a few hugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the U.S. News material does not improve the
president's image. If anything, Monica seems even more egregiously
used.
</P>
<P>
   Brill. Fallows. On to next week's fetid buzz. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-620&AMP;ADD     06-27 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE AND RENO AT ODDS ON PRIVILEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a striking disagreement over the Lewinsky
matter, the White House and the Justice Department have taken
significantly different legal positions in a federal appeals case
that will be argued next week over whether President Clinton can
invoke the attorney-client privilege to sharply limit the
questioning of one of his closest aides.
</P>
<P>
   Legal briefs unsealed by the appeals court late on Friday
disclosed an unusual rift between Clinton's White House lawyers and
Attorney General Janet Reno over the testimony of one of the
president's closest aides, Bruce Lindsey, the deputy White House
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The briefs disclose that the positions staked out for oral
arguments on Monday present the appeals court with a highly unusual
situation. Three entities _ the office of the president, the
Department of Justice and the independent counsel _ each of which
purport to be the voice of the executive branch in the case, have
put forward three competing views on the law on attorney-client
privilege for all federal agencies and officials.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are seeking to question Lindsey about his
conversations with the president and other witnesses as part of the
five-month inquiry into whether anyone committed perjury or
obstruction of justice concerning Clinton's relationship with
Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, argues that government
lawyers cannot invoke the privilege in criminal inquiries,
particularly because federal employees have an obligation under the
law to report evidence of crimes to the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The president maintains that he enjoys an absolute privilege
that protects all of his conversations with government lawyers from
being disclosed to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   A brief signed by Reno for the Justice Department takes a middle
ground. It contends that in criminal inquiries, the president's
attorney-client privilege is a qualified one that can be pierced by
a federal judge who finds that the evidence being sought is
essential to the inquiry and is not available elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction between the two positions articulated by the
Clinton administration, although subtle, is critical for both the
White House and the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers assert that the president, not the courts,
should be the final arbiter of whether Clinton can keep
conversations he has had with government lawyers confidential.
White House lawyers maintain that a qualified privilege is no real
privilege at all because Clinton would never be certain whether his
consultations with his lawyers would be kept confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very essence of the protection afforded by an absolute
privilege is its predictability _ a quality that is of peculiar
importance in the case now before the court,'' the White House
contended in its brief.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Clinton faced the possibility of an impeachment
proceeding as a result of the Lewinsky inquiry, it added: ``The
president, in his official capacity, must be entitled to consult
with his official counsel on matters bearing on his official
responsibilities _ and on the defense of his constitutional status
as head of the executive branch. If he cannot do so with the
assurance that his conversations will be protected, he will be
disabled from securing the candid, frank legal advice to which he
is entitled _ disabled at the very moment that, under our
constitutional scheme, the president is in the greatest need of
such advice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reno has replied that the courts alone are in the neutral
position to adequately weigh the needs of an investigation and
justice against the president's interest in candid and confidential
advice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In most disputes between two federal agencies about the use of
the attorney-client privilege, the attorney general intervenes and
decides whether the privilege should be invoked or waived.
Typically, the privilege is waived in such situations.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department normally represents the interests of the
president in legal proceedings that involve issues like
attorney-client privilege or executive privilege. But early in the
Lewinsky inquiry, Reno decided to remove the department from
representing the president in those matters, suggesting that it
would be a conflict of interest because she had recommended
referring the Lewinsky matter to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Justice Department ultimately decided to
intervene in the case and file a friend of the court brief because
of the institutional interests it has in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's experience indicates that it would be
rare for the attorney general to strike the balance against
obtaining evidence, ``given the compelling federal interest in the
investigation of criminal inquiry,'' the department's brief said.
</P>
<P>
   But it added that, in inquiries involving independent counsels,
the attorney general and the president were in no position to weigh
the merits of such claims of privilege and that the independent
counsel was in no position to consider the institutional concerns
of the office of the president in keeping certain matters
confidential.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal involves a decision last month by Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson of U.S. District Court that Clinton enjoys only a
qualified privilege that is outweighed by the needs of
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department brief generally supported that ruling,
although it said that Judge Johnson should have applied a
``heightened standard'' before she ultimately ruled against
Clinton. The standard proposed by the Justice Department is that
the material being sought should be found to be ``essential to the
justice of the case'' or ``demonstrably critical'' to the grand
jury's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The brief filed by Starr has not been unsealed, but the Justice
Department and White House criticize each other's position in their
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The White House brief, written by Neil Eggleston, a former White
House lawyer now in private practice, said that the Justice
Department ``confuses two analytically distinct questions, and
arrives at an incorrect result.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The department's proposed approach reaches a result
inconsistent with the unbroken common-law authorities holding the
privilege, once asserted, is absolute and not subject to
balancing,'' the White House brief said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
