<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-ART-87     06-27 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-ART-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO SQUEEZES REBELS, PROVOKING NEW GRIEF
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL BOSQUE, Mexico _ The mayor of this country town in the
southern state of Chiapas should be a happy man. Instead he is in
anguish.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, the state governor ordered hundreds of police and
army troops to storm El Bosque and recapture the town hall from
supporters of the Zapatista rebels who had seized it two years ago,
ousted Mayor Ramon Gonzalez Sanchez and set up their own parallel
administration. The troops arrested the self-appointed Zapatista
officials and reinstated Gonzalez, who is from the government's
party.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 people _ two police officers and eight Indian villagers
who back the Zapatistas _ were killed that day in the military
operations here and in outlying hamlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never wanted this to happen,'' Gonzalez said remorsefully.
``For me it is not right for Indians to fight with other Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Gonzalez, Mexico as a whole is reeling in the aftermath of
the violence in El Bosque. It was the first time that Zapatista
militias had fired back at government troops since a cease-fire
went into effect in Chiapas more than three years ago. In two El
Bosque hamlets there were prolonged gun battles between government
forces and Zapatista militias, even though the rebels were vastly
outnumbered and outgunned.
</P>
<P>
   The episode showed both Mexicans and international observers how
volatile the civil conflict in Chiapas has become and how far
President Ernesto Zedillo has moved toward open military
confrontation with the Zapatista rebels, more than four years after
the Indian guerrillas first emerged with a brief New Year's Day
uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, the former president of Ireland who is now the U.N.
high commissioner for human rights, said there might have been
``serious violations of the rights of indigenous people'' in the El
Bosque episode and called for the peace talks to resume.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also made a rare
reference to Chiapas at a recent Senate hearing, saying the United
States was ``pressing'' Mexico to resolve the situation. The
comment set off a diplomatic tempest as the government hotly
rejected any American pressure in what it regards as a purely
domestic issue.
</P>
<P>
   The violence came only days after the peace negotiations reached
their low point, when the bishop of Chiapas, Samuel Ruiz Garcia,
resigned as mediator.
</P>
<P>
   The operation at El Bosque was the fourth in a series of
government military actions since April to dismantle what the
Zapatistas call their ``autonomous'' town governments and to
reinstate officials belonging to the government's party, the
Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas began two years ago to set up the alternative
governments in Indian towns where they are popular, after they
signed a partial peace agreement with the government. The agreement
laid the groundwork for the Zapatistas to evolve from a clandestine
organization of armed guerrillas into a peaceful political
movement. It also established the foundations for greater legal
autonomy for Indian communities across Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The partial accords were never officially carried out because of
differences between the government and the Zapatistas over how to
put them into effect. Late in 1996 the peace talks collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   But the Zapatistas went ahead and acted on the accords by
asserting their political control and setting up ``autonomous''
governments in communities across the Indian regions of Chiapas
where their followers predominate.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Zapatistas boycotted the national
elections last July, even though Mexico's electoral system
underwent a major reform and Mexicans elsewhere were expressing
their views at the polls with unprecedented enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997 tensions exploded between entrenched
authorities of the government's party and insurgent pro-Zapatista
organizations. In the Indian township of Chenalho, gunmen allied
with the government's party killed 45 unarmed Zapatista
sympathizers in one hillside hamlet. Zedillo concluded from the
massacre that the federal government had lost control in the Indian
communities of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   He and the Chiapas governor, Roberto Albores Guillen, a member
of the president's party, declared the Zapatista towns to be in
violation of the Mexican Constitution and attempted to subdue them
by force.
</P>
<P>
   In El Bosque both factions _ followers of the president's party
and the Zapatistas _ have some weapons. Festering disputes over
land ownership and power have flared into angry rivalries since
1994.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two months Chiapas police reported three ambushes of
government supporters on roads in El Bosque by armed and masked
assailants. The Zapatistas contended that the government supporters
were feuding among themselves, but police said the attackers were
Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   In the third ambush, on June 9, one government supporter was
killed and five were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Albores seized on the episode to send in more than 1,000 police
and army troops. They occupied the town hall in El Bosque and
arrested the Zapatista authorities. They also went to two hamlets,
Chavajeval and Union Progreso, carrying arrest warrants for
Zapatista villagers accused of murder in the earlier ambushes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In El Bosque, Gonzalez said he had been asking the state
government for two years to help him regain his place in the town
hall. But he said he had learned to live with two administrations
in the town, one for the government's followers and one for
Zapatistas. Gonzalez said he was not consulted about the military
operation and felt uneasy about resuming his office in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   In Chavajeval, a village down a rocky road surrounded by steep
promontories, the villagers, still frightened, said local women
went out to block the road to prevent the troops from entering.
Police fired tear gas at them, prompting a small squad of Zapatista
militia members to fire their semiautomatic rifles. The army used
mortars and strafed the village from helicopters during the
firefight, which lasted several hours.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting stopped, the villagers said, they fled and
the soldiers ransacked their homes looking for weapons. Many homes
were destroyed and radios and farm tools were stolen.
</P>
<P>
   In Union Progreso, villagers said the troops fed themselves
after the operation by slaughtering most of the villagers'
chickens.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities returned six bodies to Union Progreso last week.
But they were so disfigured by crude autopsies that they were
unrecognizable, the villagers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't know who died here,'' said Mario Sanchez, a
villager, noting that some Zapatista militia members there on the
day of the fighting were from other villages.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 22 villagers from the two hamlets have been jailed and
indicted on charges of homicide and rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Albores defended the operation, contending that it had averted
greater bloodshed. ``We prevented a conflagration between the
communities in which many more lives would have been lost,'' he
said in a television interview.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo went to Chiapas two days after the violence to promise
that the government was not seeking to renew hostilities with the
Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one of those who are convinced that violence doesn't lead
us to anything good,'' Zedillo said. But he said the government
would try to stem violence on all sides by enforcing ``respect for
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The 33 Zapatista townships responded to Zedillo's calls for
renewed dialogue with a terse communique: ``Zedillo, you are a
murderer. That's all.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
