<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Humidity will be noticeably lower than on recent days east of
the Appalachians from northern Virginia to New England. Sunshine
will be ample in much of the region. However, a stalled front from
the interior Middle Atlantic States to eastern Great Lakes will be
the focus for clusters of clouds and some thundershowers. The
showers will gradually move toward the northeast late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hot and very humid weather will persist over most of the
Southeast and Middle West as high pressure remains strong near the
southern Appalachians. Onshore winds will promote bands of tropical
showers with locally heavy rain from northeastern Texas to the
southernmost Mississippi Valley. Isolated thunderstorms will form
in Florida but no widespread rain is expected in the fire-plagued
areas over the northern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Searing heat and bright sunshine with temperatures at or near
record levels will continue over large parts of the southern and
central Plains. Farther north, a few potent thunderstorms with high
winds and hail will form Sunday evening near a front from eastern
Nebraska to the western Great Lakes. The Northern Plains will be
mainly dry in the wake of the front.
</P>
<P>
   The abnormally cool air that has been over the Northwest will
begin to recede Sunday. A few showers will linger over the hilly
terrain of northern Montana and Idaho. Otherwise, after a cool
dawn, plentiful sunshine will boost afternoon readings to near
seasonal levels. Meanwhile, the Southwest will be sunny and hot as
high pressure expands over the region.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hazy Days
</P>
<P>
   The haze that has reduced visibility during the recent spate of
heat in the Northeast is not just pollution, and it occurs even in
the cleanest environments of the polar regions. Haze is most often
found in the middle latitudes in summer when the winds aloft become
very light. The weak winds allow for considerable vertical mixing
of the lower atmosphere with very little horizontal movement. As a
result, dust, pollen and pollutants are carried higher into the air
than usual. Humid air can contain numerous suspended water droplets
that adhere to the tiny solid particles and thicken the haze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
