A0066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-INVESTIGATION-N     06-27 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-INVESTIGATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOOK TELLS OF FRENZY AT DIANA CRASH SITE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ French investigators looking into the crash that killed
Princess Diana and her companion have gathered little evidence to
bolster initial police theories that photographers chasing the car
caused the driver to lose control, according to a new book that
quotes extensively from police reports.
</P>
<P>
   The chauffeur, who was killed instantly, was far over the legal
driving limit for alcohol, French authorities said a day after the
accident. That fact remains the biggest probable cause of the
tragedy, and witnesses quoted in the book say Diana's Mercedes was
some distance ahead of pursuing photographers when it skidded and
struck a tunnel support pillar at high speed.
</P>
<P>
   But testimony quoted in the new account nevertheless paints a
devastating picture of the behavior of some of the photographers
who had been chasing Diana and her escort, Emad Mohamed al-Fayed,
nicknamed Dodi, for 12 hours before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the 10 photographic agency employees who were among
the first to arrive at the scene tried to call an ambulance,
according to reports of their testimony to police.
</P>
<P>
   Two others spent the first minutes after the crash snapping
pictures of the wreck with Fayed, son of the owner of the Ritz
Hotel, and the driver, Henri Paul, the hotel's acting security
director, lying dead and the princess and a bodyguard gravely
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true, we didn't help the injured,'' one of the two,
Christian Martinez, testified, according to the book. ``I was
paralyzed by the connection between me and the people in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   The other, Romuald Rat, reportedly told police that he opened
the door and tried to take Diana's pulse as she lay moaning in the
wreckage. He also reportedly tried to comfort the bodyguard, the
sole survivor of the crash, but film in Rat's camera later showed
that he had also taken photographs before rescuers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first policemen on the scene, Sebastien Dorzee,
testified, according to the book: ``I was trying to push back the
photographers, who were virulent. In the heat of the action, I was
knocked around several times. At no time did a photographer come to
give me a hand. They kept taking pictures the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   The princess, Dorzee said, had her eyes open and spoke words he
could not understand. ``I think she said `My God,' seeing her
friend was dead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Martinez, the police, nor the investigating judges who
are expected to bring charges in the case by autumn commented on
the extensive excerpts from testimony in the book, ``Investigation
on the Death of Diana,'' published by Editions Stock and written by
Jean-Marie Pontaut and Jerome Dupuis, two investigative reporters
for the weekly newsmagazine L'Express.
</P>
<P>
   The investigating judges could charge some or all of the nine
photographers under investigation in the chase with manslaughter or
failure to come to the aid of the victims in the accident, both
crimes punishable by five years in prison and an $83,000 fine. A
tenth man who is under investigation, a motorcycle driver for Rat,
told police that he was disgusted by the photographers' behavior at
the crash scene.
</P>
<P>
   The judges could also theoretically charge the Ritz Hotel
management with criminal negligence for allowing Paul to take the
wheel drunk and without the chauffeur's license required by French
law.
</P>
<P>
   Police reports quoted in the book contradict assurances by the
Ritz management and by the Fayed family that nobody in the hotel
knew Paul could have been drunk when Fayed asked him to drive as
the couple left the hotel soon after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   According to the book, two bartenders at the hotel, Sebastien
Trote and Philippe Doucin, testified that Paul drank two shots of
Ricard, a licorice-flavored alcoholic drink, diluted with water,
after being summoned back to work unexpectedly at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But it adds that Paul, who had gone to a doctor friend to obtain
drugs to treat a problem with alcoholism, had consumed many more
drinks, probably at home, after being told earlier that he could
have the night off.
</P>
<P>
   After his death, police found a blood alcohol level of between
0.173 and 0.187 percent in his body, more than three times the
legal limit in France. The book says that an even higher level,
0.218 percent, was found in his urine.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the reported testimony confirms accounts of the long
investigation that have been slowly leaking out since the accident.
The French police found nothing, officials say, that would confirm
conspiracy theories voiced by Dodi's father, Mohamed al-Fayed.
</P>
<P>
   He is a London-based Egyptian businessman who has fought
unsuccessfully for British citizenship and has encouraged
speculation that the British Secret Service assassinated the couple
to prevent the embarrassment that would have been caused to the
royal family if they had decided to marry.
</P>
<P>
   But the authorities did find incontrovertible physical evidence,
the book reports, that the Mercedes sideswiped a smaller white Fiat
Uno while passing it just before heading, at over 80 mph, into the
tunnel under Place de l'Alma.
</P>
<P>
   A report by a police crime laboratory quoted in the book matched
Fiat taillight fragments found near the tunnel entrance with a long
white paint scrape and other marks on the right side of the
Mercedes and concluded that the larger car had brushed a Fiat built
between 1983 and 1987 just before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses also told police that they saw a dazed man driving a
battered light-colored Fiat Uno weaving slowly out of the tunnel
just after the accident. Police tracked down tens of thousands of
cars matching the description but have not yet found the vehicle or
the driver present that night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
