<HEADER>
A0069 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERCOMPUTERS-REVIEW     06-27 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERCOMPUTERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVING WINE ON THE MAINFRAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In supercomputing, the time separating the
world's fastest computer from the scrap-metal heap is appallingly
short.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to supercomputers, to become obsolescent isn't
necessarily to become useless. While many of these machines are
mothballed in dank basements, a few are proudly displayed in
private homes as though they were objets d'art. They can also make
dandy space heaters.
</P>
<P>
   The obsolescence of a supercomputer is predictable. The reason,
of course, is Moore's Law. Three decades ago, the co-founder of
Intel Corp., Gordon Moore, observed that every 18 months it is
possible to place about twice the number of transistors on the same
piece of silicon. So now personal computers are nearly as fast as
yesterday's supercomputer _ which cost many thousands of dollars
more.
</P>
<P>
   The life span of a supercomputer, which may cost upwards of $30
million, is typically five years, and sometimes far less. Jack
Dongarra, a computer scientist at the University of Tennessee who
maintains an annual list of the world's 500 fastest computers,
finds that about 250 machines fall off his list yearly.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no pasture to go out to when a supercomputer is
retired. No one reharnesses it to do the billing statements for the
local waterworks. The life of a machine is nasty, brutish and
short.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the connoisseurs.
</P>
<P>
   In a warehouse in suburban Seattle, Nathan Myhrvold, Microsoft's
chief scientist, keeps a growing collection now numbering six
supercomputers _ three early Crays and three Connection Machines
made by Thinking Machines Corp. The Cray 1, designed in 1976 by the
legendary inventor Seymour Cray, was notable in part because it was
a round refrigerator-shaped cabinet encircled by a padded bench,
which was just the thing for technicians who needed to work on the
machine's innards.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the original Crays have less processing power than some
$1,000 personal computers, but as fashion statements, their time
may be here again.
</P>
<P>
   Myhrvold is now planning a new home that will rival that of his
boss, Bill Gates. It will have a living room big enough for a
supercomputer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key aesthetic is that it is the most expensive sofa in the
world,'' said Myhrvold, who bought his machines for their salvage
costs or for a few thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Myhrvold is not the only computer designer who finds the
furniture concept attractive. Not long ago Brewster Kahle, one of
the founders of Thinking Machines Corp., learned that one of the
company's Connection Machines was sitting unplugged in the basement
of the Yale University computer science department.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that old supercomputers are remarkably expensive to
run. Electricity for a Cray 1 would cost $30,000 a month with an
additional $30,000 in electricity costs for the refrigeration
system, according to Dag Spicer, manager of historical collection
at the Computer Museum History Center in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The operating cost didn't bother Kahle, however; he paid Yale
$500 for the Connection Machine and then spent $1,000 for shipping.
It now sits in storage under a staircase in San Francisco, near his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Kahle has big plans for his Connection Machine, which has
thousands of flashing lights and would look right at home on the
flight deck of the starship Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awfully big,'' said Kahle. ``I think I'm going to need a
conference room to display it in, or maybe my next living room.''
</P>
<P>
   A small living room didn't constrain Dan Lynch, an Internet
pioneer who was one of the founders of Cybercash. Lynch, a wine
aficionado, says he has a Cray 1 as an objet d'art in his vineyard
in the Napa Valley along with ``a bunch of tired old '47 Chevys.''
</P>
<P>
   While at Convex, a Texas-based supercomputer company, Steven
Wallach, a computer designer, once used an Alliant supercomputer in
his office as a conversation piece and as partial support for his
desk.
</P>
<P>
   But even Wallach, who was one of the designers featured in Tracy
Kidder's book, ``Soul of a New Machine'' (Atlantic/Little, Brown,
1982), said he was surprised to learn that another Convex employee
had bought a Convex C-1 for its scrap price and was using the
computer to heat his garage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
