<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-SHARK-ATTACKS     06-27 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-SHARK-ATTACKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN SHARK ATTACKS: 8 SO FAR, AND SURF'S STILL UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ A spate of shark attacks, including
one that maimed the national body-boarding champion, has baffled
scientists, temporarily closed some beaches along the South African
coast and scared off some surfers.
</P>
<P>
   The champion, Neal Stephenson, lost his right foot and part of
his left leg in an attack near Plettenberg Bay in mid-May. Since
then there have been seven more attacks, doubling the annual
average of four for the coastline between East London and Saldanha
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday a 20-year-old forestry student became the first
fatality. Mauled by a great white shark on Monday while
body-boarding near Gonubie Point, he died after battling blood loss
and clotting problems. (A body board is smaller than a surfboard.
The rider lies prone on it and uses it to do stunts in the waves.)
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Dudley, a scientist at the Natal Sharks Board in
Umhlanga Rocks, said he could not explain the rash of attacks.
Shark bites usually peak in the vacation rush to the coast at
Christmas, which is summertime here, and again in the midwinter
sardine runs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the notion of a single man-eater roaming the coast pops
up whenever there are several attacks, he said that was impossible
this time. On May 29, two surfers were attacked within 2 hours at
beaches 30 miles apart, and one was probably bitten by a
ragged-tooth, which swims slowly and rarely attacks people. (It is
a close relative of the American sand tiger shark.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That rules out one shark,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary beach closures have followed the attacks, and people
are on the alert. Half an hour before the fatal attack Monday, the
curator of the East London aquarium telephoned the city's chief
lifeguard to say a spear fisherman had told him of spotting a big
shark in the area Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone has been scared from the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes some of the fun out of it,'' said one surfer
interviewed on radio, who said she was still venturing in when she
didn't see diving seabirds or leaping dolphins _ indicators of a
sardine run, and perhaps sharks. ``You definitely think about it.
But you also think you could get killed in a car smash driving to
the beach. The winter swells are up, and we were starved for waves
all summer.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years a new tourist attraction, great white
shark viewing, has been criticized by scientists who say it could
increase attacks. Small boats full of tourists, some of them
dangling underwater in suspended cages, troll through straits where
great whites are known to hunt, while crew members pour blood and
seal fat into the water. But the tours operate from Gans Bay and
Mossel Bay and no attacks have happened near either town.
</P>
<P>
   According to the International Shark Attack File at the
University of Florida, South Africa is usually fourth on the world
list of shark attacks, after the United States, Australia and
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks Board helped develop an effective electric shark
repellent device two years ago, Dudley said, but only a scuba
divers' version is sold. A smaller version, for surfers, has been
stalled for lack of venture capital, he said, as has a plan to
replace the nets protecting whole beaches, like the ones on the
Natal coastline. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
