<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0092 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECOVERED-MEMORY-REVI     06-27 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECOVERED-MEMORY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF WARS NEVER FOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A blockbuster of a story launched a highly touted television
program. But its central allegation was largely based on a disputed
interviewing technique involving recovered memories that the
American Psychiatric Association has condemned.
</P>
<P>
   Recovered memories _ suppressed horrors dredged up under therapy
_ drew attention a few years ago when they became the basis of a
spate of charges of incest, satanic-ritual abuse and sexual abuse
at child-care centers. They were discredited when investigators
determined that many of them had been implanted by zealous
therapists determined to find a cause for a patient's emotional
distress.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, experts have discovered that some Vietnam-era
veterans under psychiatric care in Veterans Administration
Hospitals are especially suggestible. Recovered memories have made
a comeback, and veterans, they say, find themselves ``remembering''
events that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics assert that may be the case in a disputed report
alleging that U.S. soldiers used nerve gas in the Vietnam War.
According to ``Newsstand: CNN &AMP; Time,'' U.S. Special Forces troops
used the gas, sarin, in 1970 while attacking a Laotian village that
was presumed to be harboring U.S. defectors.
</P>
<P>
   By using poison gas in the Vietnam War, U.S. soldiers would have
committed an act regarded internationally as a war crime. And in
covering it up for 28 years, the Pentagon would be seen as damaging
U.S. efforts to expose and eliminate Iraq's suspected caches of
nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
   The report by veteran CNN war correspondent Peter Arnett and
producer April Oliver, who did most of the reporting, was broadcast
June 7 and appeared the next day in Time magazine. As a result of
the report, the Pentagon began an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the air soon began hissing out of the story. Veterans who
had taken part in the mission, called Operation Tailwind, bombarded
the Internet and news media with furious rebuttals. Yes, they had
used gas, they said _ nonlethal tear gas. CNN's own military
analyst, the retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Perry Smith, resigned in
protest when the network wouldn't retract the report.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Newsweek magazine dropped its own bomb. It
revealed that a former Army lieutenant who had participated in the
mission, Robert Van Buskirk, was the primary source for the
nerve-gas allegation, and that he suddenly recalled the use of
sarin only near the end of a five-hour interview with Ms. Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Buskirk had failed to mention sarin in ``Tailwind''
(Word Books), his 1983 book about the mission. He said he had
suppressed the memories when he experienced a religious awakening
in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the program nor the article mentioned that the central
accusation was based on recovered memories.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said last week that several other veterans who had been
interviewed for the report told him Ms. Oliver ``planted'' the
notion that sarin had been used in the commando raid. CNN has
denied that.
</P>
<P>
   CNN said Friday that it had hired Floyd Abrams, the noted First
Amendment lawyer, to review its reporting and declined further
comment.
</P>
<P>
   But experts in the field of false memories say it is not
difficult to manipulate a susceptible subject, given the right
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recovering a false memory as a war atrocity is not as unusual
as you might think,'' said Pamela Freyd, the executive director of
the False Memory Syndrome Foundation, a national organization of
doctors and researchers that has worked to identify false memories.
</P>
<P>
   No one denies that sexual abuse or war atrocities occur, said
Dr. Loren Pankrantz, a psychologist in Portland, Ore., who worked
for 25 years at a Veterans Administration hospital that treated
Vietnam veterans complaining of post-traumatic stress disorder. But
he added, ``I would be extremely reluctant to believe somebody who
told me they had recovered a memory that had been repressed from
the Vietnam War.''
</P>
<P>
   Pankrantz, who wrote ``Patients Who Deceive'' (Charles Thomas
Press, 1998), a book on post-traumatic stress disorder, said that a
long, intense interview with a subject who is troubled, easily led
to conclusions or eager for approval was ``exactly the context in
which false memories occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a subject might repeat a false account that has been
mentioned earlier in the interview, suddenly believing it to be a
true personal experience. ``Given sufficient pressure and
confusion,'' Pankrantz said, ``they'll say, `Oh, yeah, maybe that
DID happen. Yeah, I remember something about nerve gas now,' The
trouble is, he doesn't know whether that memory came from a few
hours earlier in the interview, or 35 years earlier in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   In clinical settings, some subjects are emotionally disturbed,
some are seeking more generous disability payments _ and some even
also have a kind of Homeric impulse. ``They're basically great
raconteurs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Van Buskirk said he was diagnosed with
post-traumatic stress disorder at a VA hospital in 1977 or 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was under treatment for 10 years with lithium and
mind-bending drugs,'' said Van Buskirk. He was classified 60
percent disabled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allan Young, an anthropologist at McGill University in
Montreal who wrote ``The Harmony of Illusions: Inventing
Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder'' (Princeton University Press, 1996)
said he was ``very, very dubious'' about the claims on the CNN
program. Young spent two years at a VA hospital in the United
States studying Vietnam veterans claiming emotional disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   He has been fascinated by new narratives emerging as Vietnam
fades in memory, he said. While many patients obviously had arduous
combat experiences, a growing number of cases ``involve a veteran
who was not in Vietnam _ or if he was in Vietnam, he was not in
combat,'' he said. In group therapy sessions, these patients
assemble shards of others' claims and even snippets of movies into
fantasies of personal combat experiences, usually of heroic actions
or harrowing peril.
</P>
<P>
   But more intriguing, he said, is a small subdivision of that
group _ men who falsely implicate themselves in atrocities. ``They
make up war crimes for themselves,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anybody do that?
</P>
<P>
   Young said that a motive could involve a quest for sympathy, for
bigger disability payments or something far simpler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guaranteed attention,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0093 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-CHINA-TRADE-HNS &LR;      06-27 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE ISSUES UNDERLIE U.S.-CHINA RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``f'' and ``i'' categories)  
 For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All told, critics believe that human rights infractions and an
trade imbalance make a compelling argument for revoking the trade
relationship China enjoys with the United States _ known as Most
Favored Nation, or MFN, status.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this:
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this year, the cumulative U.S. trade deficit with
China during the Clinton administration will be $238 billion. China
imposes what critics say are prohibitively high tariffs _ 100
percent on some automobiles _ and only 1.9 percent of all U.S.
exports are allowed into China while 34.3 percent of Chinese
exports come into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The government expects the year to close with $60 billion in
Chinese goods imported to the United States and $12 billion in U.S.
goods exported to China.
</P>
<P>
   China's record on human rights is little improved since the 1989
Tiananmen Square massacre, and China helped Pakistan develop and
carry out a nuclear test that fuels an arms race in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Still, against a backdrop of U.S. foreign policy of
``constructive engagement,'' China's enormous market potential
gives renewal of MFN status the certainty of a train that has left
the station. Critics are not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration is either in denial or they are
ill-informed,'' said Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-San Francisco, who may be
Congress' most passionate advocate for severing normal trade with
the repressive government.
</P>
<P>
   This was her message to President Clinton on June 11, after he
had called his opponents isolationists: ``If the president doesn't
face up to the realities of his trip to China, to use his own
words, he will be going on a fool's errand.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said she supports engagement that is ``honest, that is
effective and sustainable _ these are pillars of our foreign policy
_ but there is certainly no most favored nation status from China
to the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Every year we hear that the importance of the
Chinese market justifies the current policy, and every year the
current policy fails to remove barriers to access to the Chinese
market. Something is clearly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton approved the annual renewal of MFN earlier this month _
in fact, he said he wants it made permanent _ giving Congress the
opportunity to pass its judgment.
</P>
<P>
   MFN, which Congress is in the process of renaming ``Normal Trade
Relations,'' covers the standard tariff treatment the United States
accords trading partners. Only six nations do not have MFN status:
Afghanistan, Cuba, Laos, North Korea, Vietnam and the former
Yugoslavia _ Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Revoking China's status, says the administration, would raise
tariffs on Chinese products from about 6 percent today to a
trade-weighted average of 44 percent. This increase would make
American consumers pay approximately $590 million more each year
for goods such as shoes, clothing and small appliances.
</P>
<P>
   China would likely retaliate against U.S. exports, said Susan
Esserman, general counsel for U.S. trade representative's office,
by increasing tariffs and other measures and endangering the $12
billion in U.S. exports to China as well as the $15 billion in
exports to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would threaten the jobs of manufacturing workers, the
income of farmers, the employment of young workers in retailing,
software engineers and workers in every other walk of life,'' she
said. ``The jobs and the export opportunities of their employers
would go to Japan, Europe and other competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights issues are a separate matter, in the view of
Americans eager to develop more U.S.-China trade.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ann Veneman, director of the California Department of Food
and Agriculture: ``People involved in trade do not want trade
interrupted for human rights or other political agendas because
that really hurts people in both countries in terms of the trading
relationship. It hurts any export-dependent industry like
agriculture. Trade has to be separated.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the administration policy _ that China's evolution is
profoundly important to the American people, and that U.S. interest
is best served by a secure, stable and open China _ has broad
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done some very stupid things over the years trying to
extend non-economic policies to our trade agreements, and we would
all be better off if we allowed trade to flow freely,'' said Ted
Gibson, chief economist of the state Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Der, a veteran human rights advocate in the San Francisco
Chinese American community and now a deputy superintendent of the
state Department of Education, favors open trade but wants to see
bolder American pressure on China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear the president has turned deaf ears to those who
have made pleas about human rights,'' said Der. ``How hard will
Clinton hit remains the key issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton visit includes an effort by U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky to have China reduce tariffs and
open markets to more products, said a spokeswoman, Helaine Klasky.
``That is part of the reason we think we ought to be engaged with
China, so we can better be in a position to negotiate such
things,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, however, would prefer that Washington use the threat of
revoking MFN status with China as leverage to bring about those
reductions and many other changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the basis of trade alone _ forget the proliferation of
weapons of mass destruction, if you can, and forget human rights
issues _ we have such a bad deal from the Chinese,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1542EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0094 </DOCNO>
