<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0096 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-BED&AMP;BREAKFAST-ART     06-27 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-BED&AMP;BREAKFAST-ART-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TENANTS VS. TOURISTS AT NEW YORK'S ILLEGAL B&AMP;BS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Henry Cohen is a man possessed: He attaches a tiny,
secret-agent-like video camera outside the window of his rental
apartment on West 71st Street and stares at a television showing
his building's front steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got a motion sensor,'' he says, ``so it just records when
somebody's coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   The people Cohen wants to catch coming into his brownstone are
not thieves or drug dealers. They are tourists, like the Chinese
man who kicked Cohen's door one night last month. Or the Paris film
crew that moved in with all its equipment. Or the dozen Dutch
tourists who galloped like gazelles up and down the stairs the
month before.
</P>
<P>
   In a city with a burnished new image, waves of tourism, and
booked-up hotels with the highest rates in the country, it was
bound to happen: Bed-and-breakfasts are springing up all over
Manhattan, where landlords are forgoing the security of long-term
leases for the chance to make thousands more a year putting up
tourists for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the bed-and-breakfasts _ in truth, they usually just
offer a bed _ are in rent-regulated buildings in upscale
neighborhoods, where frustrated landlords have long complained that
they are entitled to more money. They are now making it.
</P>
<P>
   But like a lot of other convenient, money-making endeavors, this
one is illegal in a number of ways. Most operators of transient
rooms in residential buildings violate not only zoning laws and
building codes that require special fire safety measures, but they
also do not have proper licenses and many do not pay sales or hotel
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   And if the apartments are in rent-regulated buildings, the
owners are further prohibited from charging more than the legal
monthly rent, which they easily do when they rent the apartment for
anywhere from $80 to $150 a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're in a residential neighborhood, and they're running
a bed-and-breakfast, they are illegal _ it's that simple,'' said
Ted Birkhahn, a spokesman for the Department of Buildings, which
has no estimate of the number of such operations.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not seem to worry Richard Caine, who will talk
passionately and at length about how he uses two apartments in a
rent-stabilized building he owns on West 70th Street as transient
rooms, for which he sometimes charges $125 a night. ``With the rent
laws,'' he explains simply, ``once you give a lease to a person,
you can never get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   So Caine, a part-time actor who has appeared on ``Murphy Brown''
and ``General Hospital,'' has made a thriving business out of
renting his apartments and helping other landlords and cooperative
owners rent theirs to guests, many of them actors and theatrical
directors in town for short visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any law I'm breaking,'' said Caine,
emphasizing that he is only using his two apartments as short-term
rentals while he prepares to combine them into one apartment to be
used by relatives. He added that because he does not provide meals
or maid service, his building cannot be considered a hotel and
should not be bound by hotel regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a sheet-changer or a floor-cleaner,'' he said. ``What
I'm doing is filling a niche, somewhere between the YMCA and a
hotel, and it's to the advantage of the city. I don't see how
anyone can complain.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the city has shown little interest in exercising its
enforcement power, which mainly consists of shutting the businesses
down, or even in regulating them, perhaps because they provide a
way for many thousands more tourists a year to afford to visit New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Officials could cite only two recent cases of shutting down such
operations after complaints. State and city tax officials also seem
to have turned a blind eye.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the lease-holding tenants in buildings like Caine's have
begun to complain, loudly and with lawyers, describing how their
once-homey apartment buildings have been turned into something like
the jammed stateroom scene from the Marx brothers' ``A Night at the
Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Llewelyn Barton, who has lived in Caine's building for more than
20 years and now shares a floor with one of the transient rooms,
keeps a log of the traffic she spies through her peephole.
``Appeared to be a group of young guys _ couldn't tell how many,''
reads her March 18 entry. ``They were a little noisy. Saw them
several days in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, after dozens more guests came and went, the
diary picks up testily: ``Couple _ 30-something. Chubby woman with
dark curly hair having an argument and slamming the door. He was
complaining to her that she was never satisfied by anything he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It started several years ago,'' said Ms. Barton, a former
backup singer who runs the computer-help desk at a large
entertainment company, ``but in the last few months, it's gotten
pretty heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Levine, a struggling playwright who lives downstairs, said
he was recently followed home at night by two men who suddenly
turned into his doorway and stood behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got really scared,'' he said. ``I thought they were going to
rob me. And then they said, `Richard Caine bed and breakfast?
Richard Caine bed and breakfast?'''
</P>
<P>
   Such operations have been around for years in various guises.
During the recession in the early 1990s, many cooperative owners
stuck with overpriced apartments they could not sell but no longer
lived in began to advertise their places for overnight stays.
</P>
<P>
   Tenants in rental apartments have also earned extra income
illegally while on vacation by letting agencies put up tourists in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   While such accommodations were long publicized mostly by word of
mouth, the Internet is now full of advertisements for nightly or
weekly apartment rentals and for bed-and-breakfast agencies that
offer enticing descriptions of New York. (One describes the East
Village as ``the land of punk and funk,'' adding ``Madonna lived
here before she became a star.'')
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, who has lived in his sunny rent-controlled apartment for
more than 30 years, said he watched with growing anxiety as his
landlord, Veronica Muth, who bought the building and another one
down the street in 1996, began to convert apartments in both places
into hotel-like rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine apartments in his building, Cohen believes five are
being used for tourists and short-term corporate tenants, who are
usually charged about $100 a night, depending on the length of stay
and size of the apartment. (That would mean a monthly income per
apartment of about $3,000 _ much more than the regulated rent _ if
the apartment was booked every night.)
</P>
<P>
   So Cohen has transformed himself into a kind of detective,
keeping not only a video record of tourists coming and going, but
still photos of apartments being renovated and audiotapes of
tourists talking about their accommodations. He wants these records
in case he ever has to show in court how his building is being
used.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Muth did not return telephone messages seeking comment about
the buildings, nor did Alan Kucker, a lawyer who has represented
her.
</P>
<P>
   Like other long-term tenants in the same situation, Cohen says
that while he is bothered by noise and tourists mistaking him for a
concierge, his main concern is safety.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled being startled when a confused tourist from China,
thinking that Cohen's locked apartment was his own, kicked the door
in the middle of night.
</P>
<P>
   When new guests arrive late at night, they pick up keys to
Cohen's building at a restaurant, Pizza Joint Too, down the block.
(A reporter who visited the pizza place last week was shown keys to
the front door and apartment No. 4F on a labeled key chain by a
cashier, who said, shrugging, ``Sometimes the owner comes;
sometimes somebody else comes. We just hold the keys.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be keys to this building floating all over this
city, all over the world for that matter,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Leo MacDougall, an American who now lives in Paris and who came
to New York in May with two other Parisians to make a documentary
for French television, said that as soon as the group paid in cash
for their nine-day stay in Cohen's building, they immediately made
copies of the single set of keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were careful with them, but I can see what he's talking
about,'' MacDougall said, referring to Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies that help tourists find apartments contend that such
safety concerns are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McAulay, who runs Urban Ventures, perhaps the city's
best-known agency, said that in almost 20 years in business, she
has never had a report of a tenant being robbed or assaulted by a
tourist or someone who got hold of a key.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get perps,'' said Ms. McAulay, who represents about
400 bed-and-breakfasts and so-called unhosted apartments, a number
that fluctuates greatly and always shoots up in the summer. ``These
are people who are as concerned about their own security as the
other tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is not convinced. He and his wife Marja keep a heavy stick
with a handle made out of duct tape by the door, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know who's going to be out there,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
