<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-KOSOVO-REBELS-NY     06-27 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-KOSOVO-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MEETS WITH KOSOVO REBEL LEADERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States has held its first extended
discussions with senior political leaders of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, who committed themselves to abiding by a cease-fire in the
southern Serbian province if one can be negotiated, senior American
officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The American special envoy for Kosovo, Robert Gelbard, met two
officials of the political directorate of the rebel Liberation Army
for more than four hours on Friday, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The American officials refused to provide the names of the rebel
leaders or the city in Western Europe where they met, but said
Washington had verified their identity. Gelbard also informed
Ibrahim Rugova, the Kosovo Albanian leader, of the meeting in
advance, said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA leaders agreed to work with Rugova and to ``cooperate
with him on a cease-fire and political negotiations, while
recognizing that for now, at least, they need to support his
leadership to try to provide a common negotiating position,'' one
senior American official said.
</P>
<P>
   But the rebel leaders are enormously skeptical of Rugova and his
advocacy of a nonviolent revolt against the government in Belgrade,
the American officials conceded.
</P>
<P>
   While supporting Rugova and his delegation, the Clinton
administration has come to understand that Rugova cannot speak for
the KLA, which has earned increasing support among ordinary ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo in the last six months as Serbian police and
military units have stepped up their operations in the province,
the American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   So Clinton has decided that a peaceful resolution of the crisis
in Kosovo, where Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is cracking
down on an independence movement among the ethnic Albanian
majority, requires the political participation of the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The group's agreement is also vital, the officials said, to
negotiate and then carry out a cease-fire, since Milosevic
regularly says he cannot stop fighting because he has no guarantees
that the KLA would go along.
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons, the Americans decided they had to make
contact with the group, which Gelbard has criticized sharply in the
past for carrying out ``terrorist actions'' against noncombatant
civilians, mostly Serbs, in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have a dialogue with these political leaders,'' a
senior American official said Saturday, describing the Gelbard
talks. ``The United States regards Dr. Rugova as the leader of a
very disparate group of Kosovar Albanian opinion, and his political
party is the largest in Kosovo. But clearly the KLA has become a
major force, and if we are going to be realistic, they need to be
brought into the process.''
</P>
<P>
   In the regular State Department briefing on Thursday, department
spokesman James Rubin said that he ``would expect there to be
political contact soon'' with the KLA, and that ``Milosevic is just
going to have to deal with that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin was also careful not to refer to the KLA as a terrorist
organization, reflecting the new American view that it is ``an
insurgency,'' a senior official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The group has taken responsibility for attacks on the Serbian
police and on Albanians loyal to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Richard Holbrooke, shuttling in the region, met
with two Kosovo Liberation Army fighters in a village whom he said
he met by chance. In fact, Holbrooke's contacts with the military
wing, even at the village level, were also important in the
American effort to secure the group's cooperation with an
international observer force being set up for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The military men told Holbrooke, news accounts said, that they
would pass his comments on to higher officials in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as Gelbard was meeting the political leaders, Serbian
Information Minister Aleksandar Vucic said in Belgrade that
Holbrooke had made ``a terrible diplomatic gaffe.''
</P>
<P>
   Vucic said Gelbard's meetings with the KLA fighters were
deliberate and represented ``the very proof that the U.S.
intelligence services and even the U.S. government are behind this
gang of Albanian separatists and terrorists.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
