protect its prerogatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also stretched his appointment power. After the
Senate blocked the nomination of Bill Lann Lee to run the civil
rights division of the Justice Department, Clinton defiantly named
him acting assistant attorney general last December.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at the Congressional Research Service say this
designation appears to violate an 1868 law, the Vacancies Act,
which in its current form sets a 120-day limit on such temporary
appointments. The administration disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said the administration was
flouting the law by using temporary appointments to fill 18 percent
of the 320 positions subject to Senate confirmation at various
departments. Without the 120-day limit, Byrd said, ``no president
need ever forward a nomination to the Senate.'' he preside
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's most spectacular unilateral actions came in
1996, on the rim of the Grand Canyon, when he designated 1.7
million acres of Utah's red rock country a national monument. The
step outraged Utah officials and many members of Congress, in part
because it limits development of the land. But Congress failed to
overturn the designation. And the rugged beauty of the area has
become a tourist attraction, as well as a monument to presidential
power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-STREET-CHURCH-     06-27 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-STREET-CHURCH-ART-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHURCH FINDS A HOME AMID A CITY'S HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the Rev. Deborah Little holds a church service,
the ground beneath her congregation seems at times to tremble. But
that would be because the service _ a gathering of people who live
on the street, together with some who live in the suburbs _ takes
place on a busy corner of Boston Common above a subway line.
</P>
<P>
   As tourists pause to gawk, prayers are offered, hymns sung and
hugs exchanged, mainly among men and women on society's fringes.
This is Common Cathedral, a church without stained glass, bell or
roof, founded by Ms. Little, an Episcopal priest whose mission is
attending to the spiritual and physical needs of people who sleep
on park benches and in doorways.
</P>
<P>
   Every Sunday at 1 p.m. for the past two years, she has set up a
cross beside Brewer Fountain, near Tremont and Park streets, and
rolled up a wooden box that does triple duty as altar, kitchen and
clothes closet, providing space for communion at the service, a
counter to make sandwiches afterward and a place from which
clothing can be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian tradition and others say if you want to get
closer to the heart of life, of God, go and be closer to the
poor,'' said Ms. Little, 53. ``I never envisioned myself being in a
traditional parish.''
</P>
<P>
   Tradition does not require a priest to urge people, at each
service, to take the ministry's phone number, in case they wind up
in the hospital or jail. But Ms. Little called out, ``We don't want
you to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   People who come to Common Cathedral seem to appreciate that, as
they do its blend of liturgical structure and informality, evident
in Ms. Little's efforts to bring into the worship circle those
individuals whose battles with addiction or mental illness may
trigger bursts of exuberance or anger, as well as other homeless
people.
</P>
<P>
   For many who attend, the worship service ``is a stabilizing
force,'' said Harold James, 38, who said he began attending when he
was homeless. ``Some of us are proud to say we're domiciled today,
but some of us don't want to cut the connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Adil Hamza, 35, a Sudanese immigrant who came to be baptized,
said, ``They don't care if you have money, they don't care how you
dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before she graduated from General Theological Seminary in
New York, Ms. Little was by turns a reporter, an author and a
businesswoman. Upon her ordination as a deacon in the Diocese of
Massachusetts in 1994, she packed a knapsack with wool socks and
peanut-butter and jelly sandwiches to give away. ``I set out to see
what I could learn from people on the streets about who they are,
and what I could offer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many religious movements, Common Cathedral began with a
moment of inspiration. Two years ago, on Maundy Thursday, the date
on the Christian calendar that marks the anniversary of the Last
Supper, Ms. Little was crossing Boston Common after a foot-washing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about the foot-washing, and about Jesus washing
people's feet,'' she said. ``And then the next thought was Jesus
always went to people. And my next thought was the church was where
people are.'' She decided she would celebrate Easter among the
homeless on the Common.
</P>
<P>
   She invited homeless people she knew, then borrowed a cross from
a church, and for an altar, a wheeled cart from the Episcopal
Cathedral of St. Paul. On the cart, she laid a piece of her
grandmother's table linen.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen people came. Driving away afterward, Ms. Little wondered
whether she might do it again the next Easter. But some of those
who had attended told her, ``See you Sunday.'' So Ms. Little
returned.
</P>
<P>
   These days, attendance typically tops 100, Ms. Little said. But
she is never sure who or how many will show up. Some of her
regulars may disappear for weeks, then turn up to say they had been
hospitalized or had even left the area. She has also picked up
supporters from suburban parishes, who feel inspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jesus himself were with us in the flesh today, this is
where he would be, I feel,'' said Sarah Rossiter, who has been
coming to the services since she heard Ms. Little preach in her
suburban parish 18 months ago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another visitor, on occasion, has been Bishop Thomas Shaw III of
Massachusetts, who last Christmas conducted confirmations of some
of the people who regularly attend Common Cathedral. Ms. Little, he
said, has a better rapport with the homeless ``than anyone I've run
into.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's deeply respectful of the people she ministers to,'' Shaw
said.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cathedral fits under the umbrella of a larger
organization Ms. Little founded, Ecclesia Ministries, which
collects and distributes clothing, trains volunteers in pastoral
care and brings groups of teen-agers into the city to learn about
the ministry. She raises most of the organization's $60,000 budget,
through donations; the diocese contributes $20,000 of the total.
</P>
<P>
   People often ask her what she hopes to accomplish. ``My main
goal is safety,'' she said. ``If somebody's unsafe to themselves or
others, we try to do something about it. We try to provide blankets
if it's cold, or to call an outreach worker or a van.''
</P>
<P>
   But she paused to ask, who is ministering to whom? The people
who come to Common Cathedral are among the poorest of the poor,
often too troubled to seek public aid. ``They're not poor in
spirit,'' Ms. Little said. ``I often ask people who God is, so I
can learn. And the most common response is, God is right out here.
They don't feel let down by God the way middle-class people do.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her regulars is Gary Huber, 44, a part-time carpenter who
lives in a pickup truck. Sitting on the grass after the service,
Huber recalled how Ms. Little brought him food on Christmas Eve
when the stores had closed and he had phoned for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have what you could call a certain affinity for her,'' Huber
said. ``The many times I was cold out here, she brought me clothes,
blankets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
