<HEADER>
A0109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-27 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS IN FLORIDA SEEK RACIAL MEDIATOR  
 SENATOR HIRES HELPERS FOR ELECTION IN 2000  
 WASHINGTON STATE GOP FINED OVER SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The racial rift between white and black Democrats in Florida has
become so serious that some members of the state's congressional
delegation are urging President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
to intervene as peacemakers before the split damages Democratic
chances in both the 1998 governor's race and the 2000 presidential
race.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sen. Bob Graham and Rep. Alcee Hastings of Broward
County warned the White House of the growing political danger of
the simmering months-old split, which traces to an incident in
which white Democrats in the state House of Representatives removed
a black Democrat, Willie Logan of Opa-Locka, from a top leadership
post, asserting that he was ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings, perhaps the most prominent black politician in
Florida, delivered his warning in person at a private meeting with
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some work to do,'' he said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions before the meeting, Hastings warned that if
white legislators did not apologize and make amends for the Logan
incident _ he insisted Logan was an effective legislator _ he and
other black leaders in Florida might urge black voters to cast
their lot with Republicans or stay away from the polls in future
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who is white, did not go to the White House with
Hastings but suggested separately that perhaps the president or
vice president, or both, could somehow ``contribute to bringing
harmony back to the Democratic Party.'' He said that ``looking
toward the year 2000,'' a presidential election year, Gore had a
special stake in seeing that the Logan dispute was resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's office said that Gore told Hastings that
everything possible would be done to help ``bridge that rift.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many Southern states, Florida has been leaning more
Republican in recent years. Without strong support from the state's
large black population, Democrats have little hope of capturing the
governorship _ their candidate this year already trails badly _ or
of making off in 2000 with the state's big basket of 25 Electoral
College votes.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Hires Helpers for Election in 2000
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the dozen or so Republicans and Democrats who are
exploring the possibility of running for president in 2000, Sen.
Bob Kerrey has unpaid volunteers working and scouting for him in
the early caucus and primary states, particularly Iowa and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   And like many of the White House wannabes, Kerrey, D-Neb., also
has a political action committee, Bacpac, that helps promote
favorite causes (not the least being Kerrey) in significant
Election 2000 states, and also helps elect like-thinking state and
local officials in those states (help that presumably would be
repaid in kind should the senator ultimately run for president).
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other presidential ponderers, Kerrey recently began
to sign up professional, paid field workers for his exploration
effort, a sure sign that he is trying to break to the front of the
pack and is ``elevating'' his interest in national politics, as one
of his aides put it.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, he has hired Steve Bouchard, a former state
legislative aide, to be his main political point man and chief
representative of Bacpac, formally known as the Building America's
Conscience Political Action Committee. He also has hired Chris
Sterndale, who worked for him in New Hampshire in 1992 when he
first ran for president.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Kerrey aides say, field workers will be hired in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Washington GOP Fined Over Spending
</P>
<P>
   Going into the 1996 fall election, Republicans in Washington
state, already in control of the state House of Representatives,
figured they had a good shot at also taking over the 49-seat state
Senate, then in Democratic control by only one seat. But it would
take money.
</P>
<P>
   So the GOP poured in the cash. It hired consultants, set up
political action committees and provided major backing to the
Republican candidates who looked in the best positions to defeat
Democrats running for the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The plan worked. The Republican Party came out of the election
in control of the Senate, 26-23 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost two years later, it turns out that some of the
Republican spending was in serious violation of the state's
campaign-finance regulations.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation by the Public Disclosure Commission, the
bipartisan panel that monitors elections in Washington state, the
party has conceded that it spent about $30,000 more than the law
allowed on five Senate races, that it accepted more than $30,000 in
improper contributions to its political action committees and that
it improperly dipped into a restricted fund for about $150,000 to
pay for polls and political consultants.
</P>
<P>
   As reparation, the party has agreed to pay a $5,000 fine and to
reduce its aid to candidates in the 1998 elections by about
$150,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Disclosure Commission also found that the party
``apparently'' violated state campaign law in 1996 by taking
$150,000 from a restricted fund to finance a television
advertisement attacking Gary Locke, the Democratic candidate for
governor who went on to win. That finding, which the GOP disputes,
has been forwarded to the state attorney general for possible
action.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, while pleased with the commission's findings, are
incensed that it imposed a fine of only $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking into the possibility of going to court,'' Paul
Berendt, the Democratic state chairman, said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Would his party also try to have the 1996 elections results
thrown out, given that they cost Democrats control of the Senate?
</P>
<P>
   ``Too late for that,'' Berendt said. ``But the next election is
just a few months away, and we've got high hopes for a comeback.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
