<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ITALY-NORWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY BEATS NORWAY, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLES, France _ It is always excruciating to play against
Norway, which compacts its players in defense as if they are posing
for a team picture. To prevail requires vigilance and patience and
quick precision.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18th minute of their World Cup elimination match
Saturday, Italy unfurled a counterattack through the heart of the
Norway defense, and Christian Vieri sprinted down the middle like
the tight end he resembles. Midfielder Luigi Di Biagio chipped the
ball ahead and Vieri kept bulling forward with the momentum of an
avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Eggen, a sapling of a defender, fell away under this
muscular charge and Vieri stroked a diagonal shot that skidded past
the helpless dive of Norway's goalkeeper, Frode Grodas, and nestled
accurately inside the left post. It was the only goal Italy would
score Saturday in a 1-0 victory, but any goal against Norway
requires hard work and is to be valued. Ask Brazil, which lost by
2-1 to Norway on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vieri now has five goals in this World Cup, more than any other
player, and Saturday he advanced his team toward a likely meeting
with France next Friday in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather play Brazil than France,'' said the Italian
goalie, Gianluca Pagliuca, who avoided the first potential
sudden-death overtime match in World Cup history with a magnificent
save in the 71st minute. ``France has their fans behind them and
they are playing better than Brazil.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an urgent feeling among the Italians, who won in Group
B in the first round, that they will need a rejuvenated Alessandro
Del Piero as Vieri's partner at forward to have any chance of
winning a fourth World Cup. Del Piero finished fourth among Italian
League scorers this season with 21 goals for Juventus, but he
strained a groin muscle before the World Cup and has yet to score
in soccer's world championship.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Roberto Baggio from Saturday's game was seen by
some as an effort by Coach Cesare Maldini to keep Del Piero's
brittle confidence from shattering. Another goal by Baggio, another
rescue, and, the theory goes, Del Piero's self-assurance might be
irretrievably lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play, but I'm not going to make a big deal of
it,'' Baggio said.
</P>
<P>
   Baggio did not score a goal in the first round of the 1994 World
Cup before exploding for two against Nigeria. And Paolo Rossi did
not score until the fifth match of the 1982 World Cup when Italy
won its last title. So there is time to get Del Piero kick-started.
He missed three chances Saturday; perhaps he is thinking too much,
or perhaps he is too concerned with making the goals look pretty
instead of being concerned only with putting them into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that he had chances to score,'' Vieri
said of Del Piero. ``The problems are when he doesn't have
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Vieri, who looks like George Clooney but does not need a Batman
costume for superheroic performances, appears to have all the
confidence that Del Piero lacks. He is mobile and relentless; give
him a chance to score and he does. Perhaps Vieri, 24, is not
feeling the same pressure as Del Piero, because he plays in Spain,
for Atletico Madrid, and he escaped the loud volume of the World
Cup buildup.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a former Torino midfielder, Vieri grew up in
Australia where his father finished his career. He returned to
Italy at 15 and played for runner-up Juventus in the 1997 European
Champions League Cup. But Juventus maintains a ``win-and-sell''
policy, and Vieri was transferred last summer to Atletico Madrid
for $16 million. Still, he scored the vital goal in Italy's playoff
qualifier against Russia, and is now filling the net again in the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hoped there would be more opportunities to score goals
than there were today,'' Vieri said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but it is almost impossible to excavate a goal when Norway,
as is its maddening custom, plays 10 or 11 men behind the ball.
Vieri managed an early puncture and then it was Italy's defense
that became inpenetrable.
</P>
<P>
   Norway, which finished second to Brazil in Group A, insisted on
maintaining Tore Andre Flo as its lone striker, but his teammates
had great difficulty delivering the ball. The Italian defenders,
Fabio Cannavaro and Giuseppe Bergomi, stood on either side of Flo
all day like federal agents guarding a fugitive. Bergomi, a
holdover from Italy's 1982 team, used all his experience to
distract Flo with timely shoves in the back. And Cannavaro, though
a head shorter than the 6-foot-5-inch Norwegian, repeatedly used
his leverage to knock Flo off the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But Flo is as persistent as Vieri, and in the 71st minute, he
shoved through an Italian defender and headed a cross toward
Pagliuca, who instinctively stuck out his right hand and then
trapped the ball against his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't impressed with Italy,'' said Norway Coach Egil Olsen.
</P>
<P>
   No one looks impressive against Norway. Still, Italy beat Norway
four days after Brazil could not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
