<HEADER>
A0119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SOSA-GONZALEZ-NYT     06-27 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SOSA-GONZALEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SOSA SETS A GOAL, WATCH OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Together for the first three years of their professional
careers, they saw their paths diverge for a decade only to merge
again this year. Sammy Sosa and Juan Gonzalez play for different
teams, indeed in different leagues, but they are together again in
the so-far-successful pursuit of the primary goals they set last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has shattered a home run record that not even Mark McGwire
could reach, but the ``3'' at the start of his batting average is
at least as impressive. ``Sammy told me several times, `I want to
hit .300,''' said Jeff Pentland, the Chicago Cubs' hitting coach.
``He said, `I did it once, and I want to do it again.' I've learned
in dealing with the talent I've been lucky to deal with that if
they make a statement, you have to believe in what they say they're
going to do. When these guys set their minds to it, that's what
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez set his mind to a different kind of goal. ``Juan has
set some high personal goals for himself,'' said Doug Melvin, the
Texas Rangers' general manager. ``Staying healthy and playing every
day is probably the No. 1 goal he set out to achieve. He's done
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday, Sosa was hitting .328, and Gonzalez, his
teammate from Sarasota, Gastonia, Charlotte and Tulsa when both
were in the Texas organization, had played in every one of the
Rangers' 79 games.
</P>
<P>
   It was no secret that Gonzalez would produce impressive
statistics if he avoided injury, which had forced him to miss 112
of 469 games the past three seasons. In those years, he drove in a
total of 357 runs in 357 games. This year, he has performed even
more productively.
</P>
<P>
   In his first 79 games, Gonzalez drove in 96 runs, stirring talk
of the pursuit of the record for runs batted in (190) as a subplot
to the chase for the home run record.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa planted himself firmly in the latter race with a torrent of
home runs this month. But the home runs did not detract from his
.300 goal. During a 22-game stretch in which he hit 21 home runs
(May 25 to June 21), Sosa batted .352.
</P>
<P>
   In his first eight seasons in the major leagues, Sosa batted
.300 only once, finishing precisely at that level in 1994. Had it
not been for the players' strike that ended that season
prematurely, Sosa would very likely have fallen below that mark.
His highest average otherwise was .273, which he hit in 1996, and
his career average before this season was .257.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy and I sat down in the winter and put together some
goals,'' said Pentland, who joined the Cubs last July. ``I said 100
walks and 100 runs scored, and Sammy threw in .300. He was vehement
about it. We made out a plan to accomplish that goal. We didn't
talk about home runs, and we didn't talk about RBIs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa ``had a burning desire to be as good as he could be,''
Pentland said. ``That's one of the ingredients you need to reach
greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa also needed to do a better job of reading and recognizing
pitches, shorten his swing ``and try not to hit the ball 700
feet,'' Pentland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Williams did a great job with his swing,'' Pentland
said, referring to the team's dugout coach. ``My job was to make
him aware of how good he could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentland described Sosa as a very emotional person. ``The idea
is to channel that,'' Pentland said. ``Last year he wasn't happy. I
never found out any reasons, but we guessed that the burden he felt
he had to carry was part of it. There were some petty jealousies on
the club. When a team is losing, people tend to point fingers, and
a lot of the time he felt the finger was pointed at him.''
</P>
<P>
   The final element in the evolution of this .300 hitter, Pentland
explained, was the need for Sosa to evaluate himself daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never did it consistently,'' the coach said. ``Now he's
maintaining it. He understands himself better. I've hardly said
five words. I just listen. He's saying all the right things, and
it's showing up on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The self-evaluation, Pentland said, comes when he and Sosa work
in a batting cage for about 10 minutes each day. ``He'll talk about
the game the day before, what he did, how he could have done
better,'' Pentland said. ``His breakdowns are right on the mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez also works daily on achieving his goal of staying
healthy and playing every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in great shape,'' Melvin said. ``When the team is at
home, he works out every morning at the park at 11:30, then goes
home and rests. He comes back to the park later. On the road, he's
always in the health club. His work habits are great.''
</P>
<P>
   The injuries that have undermined Gonzalez's seasons are not
always avoidable through hard work. Last year, for example, he tore
a thumb ligament diving for a ball in a winter league playoff game
and missed the first 24 games of the Rangers' season. But every
time he drives in a run this season, he reminds everyone what a
healthy Gonzalez can do.
</P>
<P>
   In driving in 96, he had nearly lapped the field. The next
highest total in the American League was Ken Griffey Jr.'s 70. Even
McGwire, the National League leader, was 12 behind. But before
those making projections say Gonzalez is on a pace for a
record-breaking 195, it should be recalled that Hack Wilson, en
route to his total of 190 in 1930, drove in 53 runs in the Cubs' 30
games in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that's helped Juan with RBIs is having them as a
goal instead of home runs,'' Melvin said. ``He doesn't go up trying
to hit home runs. Once he got off to a great start with RBIs and
there was that focus, he became a better hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   The general manager cited two recent examples of the kind of
hitter Gonzalez has become.
</P>
<P>
   In a 7-7 game with Colorado, the Rangers had a runner at third
base in the ninth inning, and Gonzalez had two strikes. ``The pitch
was inside, and everybody was thinking he was going to try to hit
the ball over the fence,'' Melvin said. ``But he inside-outed it to
right-center for a single.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Anaheim, the Rangers had the bases loaded with two out
and again two strikes on Gonzalez, and he drove an outside pitch
into the right-center gap. ``If he was chasing the home run title
or trying to hit home runs,'' Melvin said, ``he might try to pull
the outside pitch. He sees those are RBIs, and he gets RBIs by
using the whole field.''
</P>
<P>
   He does it, too, by using the whole schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
