<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDS BY MONTH  
 BUILDING A FLORIDA RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much noise was made last week when Sammy Sosa hit his 19th home
run in June, breaking the record for home runs in a month. So when
did they start playing baseball by calendar months?
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there is nothing sacred about a period running
from the first day of a month to the last. But if one wishes to use
a 30-day period as a barometer for hot home run streaks, how about
the 21 that Sosa hit from May 22 through June 20?
</P>
<P>
   No one in history, the Elias Sports Bureau determined, had ever
hit that many home runs in any 30-day span. The previous high was
20. Ralph Kiner of Pittsburgh hit 20 in 1947, from Aug. 14 through
Sept. 12, and Roger Maris of the Yankees duplicated the feat in his
record-breaking year of 1961, from May 24 through June 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a much more powerful statement than home runs in a
specific month,'' Steve Hirdt of Elias said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more powerfully, Sosa hit 21 home runs in a 28-day period,
from May 25 through June 21. Those were the same 21 home runs he
hit in 22 games, having missed three games during his productive
30- and 27-day periods.
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING A RIVALRY
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Marlins and the Tampa Bay Devil Rays are Florida's
only major league teams, but they apparently do not fit the
definition of a natural rivalry. At least their fans don't think
so.
</P>
<P>
   They played two games in each team's park last week and drew the
fewest fans of the nine four-game home-and-home series that were
played as part of the interleague schedule. The games in St.
Petersburg attracted 53,146; those in Miami drew 36,327. Vincent
Naimoli, the Devil Rays' managing partner, acknowledged that his
team should have promoted the Tampa Bay games more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Can the rivalry be built?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Naimoli said, ``we can do a lot of things from a
marketing standpoint, create a state championship trophy, something
like that. Because of other priorities, we didn't do a real
effective job this time. As time goes on, we'll do better.''
</P>
<P>
   The average attendance for each team's pair of games was below
the average for other games this season. The only other teams that
drew a smaller average than they had for their other games were
Texas and Arizona, who also played each other.
</P>
<P>
   The largest four-game attendance was 206,123 for the Yankees and
the Atlanta Braves. The Montreal Expos had 25,771 for their two
games with their Canadian rival Toronto, but the average was higher
than their previous average of 10,767.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
