<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TIME-STUDY MAN MONITORS WORLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Mr. Blatter is happy. Production is up. Blatter consults
his clipboard and his stopwatch and his computer printouts. More
fouls. Good. More yellow cards. Good. More red cards. Very good.
</P>
<P>
   With the referees under orders to reward the skillful and punish
the wicked, the World Cup of soccer roared into its second round
Saturday. Italy eliminated Norway, 1-0, in Marseilles and Brazil
was playing Chile in Paris in the Round of 16. No more waltzes of
convenience, no more ties.
</P>
<P>
   The clumsy and the inept from soccer's third world _ the earnest
South Koreans and the striving Tunisians and the bickering Yanks _
have been sent packing. Now we were down to 16 survivors who had
learned to live within the rules, to say nothing of the
interpretations and demands of Joseph (Sepp) Blatter, the man who
blows the whistle on the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I call you Mr. Blatter?'' coyly asked Robin Williams
during the goofy showbiz draw for the 1994 World Cup, straight from
the ersatz heart of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   For a few brief moments, Williams and the dignified Swiss Army
officer became a pair, Frick and Frack. But most of the time,
Blatter has serious business at hand, cleaning up soccer's act.
</P>
<P>
   Blatter is the newly elected head of the powerful world soccer
body, known as FIFA. For many years, he has dedicated himself to
making the game less crude, so lively that even the dunk junkies
and home-run addicts in the United States might get it.
</P>
<P>
   More offense. We must have more offense. To accomplish this end,
FIFA pushed through a new rule just in time for the World Cup, an
erratic move worthy of the lords of baseball, with their split
personality over the designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   With only weeks to prepare, players were warned they would be
sent off in abject shame if they did what soccer players have done
for generations _ hack somebody with the ball from behind, to keep
him from advancing. Good grief. If officials had done that, Claudio
Gentile of Italy could not have whacked Diego Armando Maradona into
a bloody stump during the 1982 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The early output did not satisfy Robin Williams' pal. After
watching a few chippy games, Blatter warned the officials to get
tougher, right in the middle of the World Cup, the equivalent of
Paul Tagliabue going into the officials' locker at halftime of the
Super Bowl and saying he was not happy with the holding being
committed by the 'roid-rage linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Blatter got the referees' attention. That very night, one
officious official started pulling yellow and red cards out of his
pocket like a street vendor handing out fliers for a new pizzeria
in Manhattan. Hey, check it out. One ref took the stunned
Cameroonians right out of a game against Italy, but whatever.
Blatter glanced at his flow charts the next morning, and he was
pleased.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first round, the lads are scoring at a clip of
2.63 goals per game, which is slightly down from 1994 but is still
a basketball equivalent of both teams breaking 100 points. There
have been 51.3 fouls called per team, and they seem to reflect the
styles of the teams. Hipper-dipper Brazil has committed the fewest
fouls, 32, and effervescent Nigeria has committed only 33. On the
other foot, so to speak, Iran and Japan, both emerging soccer
nations, have committed the most fouls with 69 each.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously enough, Argentina, no stranger to cynical fouls and
dramatic flopping over enemy affronts, real and imagined _ plus,
the only team to give up zero goals in the first round _ has
suffered the most fouls, a whopping 74. The Yugoslavs, no slouches
themselves, have been fouled 61 times. In a tie for third were
Colombia and the United States with 60 fouls suffered apiece. I
think that means the Yanks can't even get out of the way of a nasty
boot.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have given out 16 red cards and 185 yellow cards. Are
they overreacting? Not always. There was a great deal of wailing
the other day when the American referee, Esse Baharmast, called a
foul on Brazil's Junior Baiano that set up the winning penalty kick
that allowed Norway to qualify ahead of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   African soccer officials are still upset over that call, as well
as the calls that buried Cameroon twice, but a second-day influx of
television replays clearly show Junior Baiano clutching a Norwegian
shirt, the new fashion in fouls this World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   David Will, the FIFA head of officials, made a point of praising
Baharmast, and has assigned him as the fourth referee for a
second-round game, the elimination phase, another world, no more
``playing for a result.'' You either win the game with a goal or go
into the dreaded penalty-kick shootout.
</P>
<P>
   American sports fans can relate to the change in pace, the way
hockey suddenly gets intense during the Stanley Cup playoffs, the
way NBA teams start playing defense in April.
</P>
<P>
   In this phase of the World Cup, if desperate teams should resort
to cynical tactics, let them be warned. The rules will be enforced.
Blatter is watching. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
