<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0137 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-ART-1STL     06-27 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-ART-1STLD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND JIANG DEBATE VIEWS LIVE ON CHINESE TV 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Corrects spelling of ``Khrushchev'' in 11th graf. No other
changes.)  (See also: CHINA-TV-BROADCAST, CHINA-REACT, CHINA-ASSESS,
CHINA-HILLARY) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The U.S.-China summit meeting ended Saturday night
with a formal state dinner after an extraordinary live televised
exchange between President Clinton and Jiang Zemin, the Chinese
president, over human rights, Tibet and China's path to the future.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders announced a number of agreements, including a
pledge to retarget their ballistic missiles quickly so that neither
side is aiming nuclear weapons at the other.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations also announced modest progress toward China's
adherence to an international missile proliferation agreement and
steps toward China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But the drama of the meeting came in a remarkable 70-minute news
conference, carried live on nationwide Chinese television, in which
the two presidents differed sharply on the nature of personal
freedom, the role of the state and the meaning of the Tiananmen
Square demonstrations that were violently suppressed by the Chinese
government in June 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. officials expressed concern after Saturday's exchange
that the Chinese might not permit the broadcast of Clinton's speech
on Monday to students at Beijing University, the rhetorical
centerpiece of the president's nine-day visit to China. But they
said the president had made his point in unvarnished terms before a
potentially huge audience.
</P>
<P>
   However, because few Chinese knew that the news conference would
be televised live, it was not clear how many had actually seen it,
and there was no mention of the debate in later television or print
coverage of the trip in China.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting represented a significant evolution in the often
tense relationship between the two powers and was the first time a
foreign leader had squarely confronted the painful legacy of
Tiananmen Square on Chinese soil _ and on Chinese airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials were jubilant because the news conference allowed
Clinton to speak without filters to the Chinese people of American
concerns about China's human-rights record.
</P>
<P>
   It was also, in their view, a powerful response to critics in
the United States who said that Clinton should not have rewarded
the Chinese government with a high-profile summit meeting even as
its communist leaders continued to suppress political speech and
the free exercise of religion.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said that they did not signal to the Chinese in
advance of the news conference that Clinton planned to speak out
forcefully on the Tiananmen Square tragedy. They said they did not
want to force Jiang into a defensive posture, or, more important,
cause the Chinese to pull the plug on the live broadcast of the
event.
</P>
<P>
   The spirited exchange recalled earlier confrontations between
top U.S. officials and communist leaders, including the ``kitchen
debate'' between Richard Nixon, then vice president, and Nikita
Khrushchev, and the summit meeting between Ronald Reagan and
Mikhail Gorbachev. It also echoed a similar debate on human rights
when Jiang was in Washington last October. But at Saturday's news
conference, the back and forth was more forceful and animated.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flatly told the Chinese leader that his government had
been ``wrong'' to use force to end the peaceful demonstrations of
the spring of 1989 and that broad personal freedom and political
expression were the price of admission to the world community of
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of our agreements, we still disagree about the meaning
of what happened then,'' Clinton said in his opening statement,
referring to the violent crackdown on Tiananmen Square the night of
June 3-4, 1989, that left hundreds of protesters dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, and the American people believe, that the use of
force and the tragic loss of life was wrong,'' the president said
as a stone-faced Jiang looked on. ``I believe, and the American
people believe, that freedom of speech, association and religion
are, as recognized by the U.N. Charter, the right of people
everywhere and should be protected by their governments.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked by a reporter about Clinton's remarks on the lessons
of Tiananmen Square, Jiang appeared ready with an answer. He
defended the use of army tanks and rifles to end what he called the
``disturbances'' of 1989 as essential to maintaining order.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States and China had different social
systems, ideologies, histories and cultures. ``So it's nothing
strange that we may have some difference of views over some
issues,'' Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With regard to the political disturbances in 1989, the Chinese
people have long drawn a historical conclusion,'' he went on,
becoming more emphatic in his expression and his gestures. ``I have
stated our position that with regard to the political disturbances
in 1989, had the Chinese government not taken the resolute
measures, then we could not have enjoyed the stability that we are
enjoying today.''
</P>
<P>
   He then offered Clinton an opportunity to reply, in what U.S.
officials called a generous political gesture that Clinton eagerly
seized.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the U.S. system was based on a delicate
balance between personal liberty and central authority, with
liberty the paramount value.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the question for all societies going forward into the 21st
century is: Which is the better gamble?'' Clinton said. ``If you
have a lot of personal freedom, some people may abuse it. But if
you are so afraid of personal freedom because of the abuse, that
you limit people's freedom too much, then you pay, I believe, an
even greater price.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tibet, Clinton urged Jiang to initiate a direct dialogue with
the Dalai Lama, the mountain region's religious leader, in return
for recognition that Tibet is part of China. He also urged Jiang to
respect the ``unique cultural and religious heritage'' of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang replied that, as a communist and an atheist, he found it
``unfortunate'' that Tibet clung to what he called an anachronistic
theocracy.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that religious freedom was protected in Tibet, as
elsewhere in China, and said that Beijing had invested millions of
dollars in the economic development of Tibet and restoration of
historic shrines.
</P>
<P>
   But he expressed bewilderment that many educated Americans and
Europeans believed in lamaism and blindly supported the Dalai
Lama's calls for greater autonomy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
