<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-LEITER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORST LOSS FOR THE METS: LEITER IS OUT 4-6 WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The loss of their No. 1 pitcher was not what the Mets
wanted to take away from their scintillating series with the
Yankees, but that development is expected to overshadow anything
else that happens for the Mets at Shea Stadium this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter, one of the National League's best starters this
season, went on the disabled list Saturday, lost for what the Mets
said would be four to six weeks with a 50 percent tear of the
patella tendon in his left knee. Leiter's loss is a crippling blow
to the Mets' chances of snatching a spot in the post-season
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, who had possessed the league's lowest earned run average
before he pitched against the Yankees Friday night, was injured in
the seventh inning of the game while trying to tag Derek Jeter in a
play at first base. He was optimistic about an early return but
despondent over the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'm disappointed,'' Leiter said from his Manhattan
apartment in a conference call with reporters. ``To go from having
a career year, putting up great numbers, all sorts of wonderful
things going on, to how many starts am I going to have. It's
upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are faced with replacing the left-handed Leiter, who
lost an almost certain spot on the National League All-Star team,
with someone from their existing staff or organization, most likely
Brian Bohanon, or securing a pitcher in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Harnisch of Cincinnati may be the most available starter,
but a member of the Mets' staff said the club would not pursue him.
Harnisch began last season with the Mets but went on the disabled
list suffering from depression, and his relationship with Manager
Bobby Valentine deteriorated badly.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, was noncommittal on
his plans. Asked how confident the Mets were that Leiter would be
back in four to six weeks, he said that prognosis ``is the hope''
but added, ``I don't know when he's going to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Internally,'' he said, ``we look at four to six weeks and
evaluate from there how we think we fit, who's available on the
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips acknowledged that the Mets' position in the pursuit of
a playoff spot ``makes our motivation more serious or urgent to get
a quick solution to the problem, a quick evaluation how we're going
to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' brain trust plans to spend the next day or two
scouring the market to see which starters might be available. Until
now, they had focused on searching for middle relief pitchers. What
they most likely will find when they seek a starter is that about
half of the teams in the major leagues are looking for the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon, like Leiter a left-hander, has made three starts this
season, two in second games of doubleheaders. Last year he started
14 times, all but one after he was recalled from Norfolk on July
22.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible fill-in starters are Bill Pulsipher, who joined
the Mets from Norfolk last Sunday, and Mark Mimbs, who has won 10
games with Norfolk. There is also Armando Reynoso, who is scheduled
to pitch five innings tomorrow in his comeback from shoulder
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a pretty good track record as a spot starter,''
Bohanon said. ``In my starts last season I threw the ball pretty
well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bohanon was quick to note the significance of Leiter's loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could count on Al going seven, eight, nine innings,''
Bohanon said. ``He made his presence on the mound felt. Hitters
don't like facing him. He has that nasty cutter. He developed a
sinker. He was having a fabulous year.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter has a 9-4 record and a 1.86 ERA, which was second in the
league to Greg Maddux's 1.75 before Saturday night. After Leiter
felt something happen to his left knee on the play Friday night, he
threw one practice pitch, then left the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I threw that one pitch, I knew it was really sore,''
Leiter said. ``But I've been through an awful lot. And a knee is
not as detrimental to a pitcher as for a guy who runs and steals
bases.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Leiter pitched much of last season with an ailing right knee
_ he had surgery after the season _ and it affected his pitching.
He went from a 16-12 record and 2.93 ERA in 1996 to 11-9 and 4.34.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's newly injured left knee will be immobilized, and he
will undergo therapy for it. ``It's not like there's any pain,'' he
said. ``It's more like a real bad, bad case of jumper's knee. But
it's not a weight-bearing injury. I can still walk. It's when I
flex it or bend it that it's sore. It's more sore than anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter said he would miss not being able to go to the All-Star
game. ``I really thoroughly enjoyed my first All-Star game,'' he
said, referring to the 1996 contest. ``It's a downer. It's a
bummer. It's not good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
