A0141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-2T     06-27 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NYC CHAMPIONS PROVIDE HOPE FOR U.S. SOCCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The best high school soccer player in the city, the
sweet, serious Mansour Ndiaye, does not know how many goals he
scored during the last two unbeaten seasons at Martin Luther King
Jr. Nor did he know, until he was introduced at graduation last
Thursday as salutatorian, the precise numbers of his academic
average: 94.5.
</P>
<P>
   But in a thick accent for which he apologized _ without
mentioning that he began speaking English, his fourth language,
only since coming from Senegal two years ago _ the chunky
18-year-old midfielder thanked his coach, Martin Jacobson, and
offered advice to his classmates as precise as his shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' he said, ``you just can't do it by your own.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a fitting ending to a brilliant scholastic career that
also offers a snapshot of inner-city soccer, a world of poor young
immigrants who sneaker companies, amateur federations and
professional teams are just beginning to realize may be America's
only hope of avoiding another century of World Cup wipeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids come to this country at 14, 15, 16 years old, with
games,'' said Jacobson, whose kids won 38 consecutive matches on
the way to two consecutive Public School Athletic League
championships. ``Some of them played on their national high school
teams. America's not going to win anything with upper-middle-class
white suburban kids who play rigid textbook patterns.''
</P>
<P>
   That was underscored last weekend when the United States team
lost to Iran and the core of the King team, playing as a club
called the F.C. Harlem Jakes, easily won the under-19 division of
the 3,000-player, 90-team Nordic Spirit tournament in Middlebury,
Vt.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four games the King boys won was against a team of
Division I collegians from New Hampshire and Massachusetts who grew
increasingly frustrated and physical against the quicksilver
freelancing of the African and West Indian teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   For the Jakes, who live mostly in Brooklyn and upper Manhattan
and attend a high school without a lawn, the culture shock included
the bucolic Middlebury College campus with its 12 lush soccer
fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard not to just stand there and appreciate all
that beauty,'' said Mansour, who is widely known by his first name.
``I was thinking I would be happy to just sleep on this grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansour has been too much of a model citizen and too well
rewarded for his hard work to be offered up as a standard. He is
also luckier than most young immigrants. Between the city's
Senegalese community and its vast ethnic soccer infrastructure, he
has had help finding flexible hours in fast-food jobs and good
weekend and summer-league teams to play on. The uncle he lives with
in Harlem encourages his devotion to schoolwork. Mansour will
attend the University of Connecticut on a full scholarship next
fall.
</P>
<P>
   When Mansour first came from Dakar in 1996, he spoke the dialect
Wolof, French and German. He was steered to King, the largest high
school in Manhattan with 3,200 students. Jacobson uses the school's
excellent English as a Second Language program as a recruiting tool
for talented players.
</P>
<P>
   In Mansour's first year, the team star was Barry Swift from
Trinidad, who is now in a Major League Soccer development program
and is soon expected to be playing for the MetroStars. Mansour was
a wingback that first year, racing downfield from his defensive
position to score.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson thinks that over the two years Mansour has scored at
least 40 goals and made 40 assists, but it has been his policy to
never keep such records because he thinks they are divisive. He
believes that the unselfish love of teammates creates the spirit of
true victory. In Mansour, who switched to midfield this past
season, he may have found one of his most apt disciples, even
though Jacobson is a New Ager who rubs crystals and Mansour is a
Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   ``There cannot be animosity or jealousy,'' Mansour said at lunch
last week, two days before graduation.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks slowly and carefully, as if crafting a pronouncement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a guy who doesn't pass, I give him a good pass to help
him score,'' he said. ``He will realize his errors. You see,
players are not selfish by nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the table, the 52-year-old Jacobson beamed and said:
``Mansour is very sensitive. He is a Pisces.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansour laughed and rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' asked Jacobson, a muscular coiled spring, ``have you
written your speech yet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahhh, Jake,'' said Mansour, smiling, ``I am working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Jacobson, dapper in a jacket and Bugs Bunny tie,
sat on the edge of his chair in the Cathedral of John the Divine as
Mansour thanked everyone who had ``helped a little boy bridge the
gap of language'' and urged his classmates to do their best to
``overcome the handicaps on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not only speaking rhetorically. The students' caps and
gowns did not arrive on time for the ceremony, and the
disappointment was palpable at first in a crowd of families dressed
for an important occasion; many were attending their first
graduation in America. But the spirit prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Mansour had been preceded by the Rev. Alfonso Wyatt, vice
president of the Fund for the City of New York. In his rousing
keynote address, Wyatt implied that the lack of caps and gowns were
a gift from God, giving the students a chance to see themselves
without unnecessary adornment, as they really were, proud
achievers.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the ceremony, Mansour received seven awards,
for leadership and for academic and athletic excellence, including
the plaques for his Parade Magazine all-America team award and for
the Iron Horse, given by the city for the top player in each sport.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional speech, the principal, Stephanie D'Amore, also
gave him a check for $1,000, the Caring and Compassion Scholarship.
She told the audience how Mansour had worked so hard and sent most
of his wages home to Senegal. That brought a long, appreciative
sigh from the families in the cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Mansour tends to make people feel good. Last weekend, he was the
moral star of the Vermont trip, which was put on by Samuel Ravit, a
South Burlington insurance executive and president of the Nordic
Spirit soccer club. Touched by newspaper accounts of the Martin
Luther King Jr. team, he invited the players to the tournament, and
arranged for the IDX Foundation and Paine Webber to defray costs,
including rental for a bus sent down to pick them up on Friday
night and bring them home Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Team members stayed with local families, who were amazed at the
teen-agers' easy courtesy. The players were amazed at the casual
piles of fruits and cereals on the breakfast tables. There were
edgier culture shocks. Many of the tournament teams, who came from
all over the Northeast, were spectacularly well-equipped with
matching gym bags, trainers, soccer moms and even pumps to spray
mist on hot foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the F.C. Harlem Jakes were wearing two-tone whitish
jerseys that Jacobson had bought from a Manhattan soccer supplier,
Doss, for $8.95 each. The jerseys were rejects because the color on
the sleeves did not match the color on the rest of the shirt. When
another coach complained that the Jakes did not have the
tournament's requisite home and away jerseys, Ravit quickly came up
with 11 of the red mesh practice vests called ``pinnies'' and
decreed them proper uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a learning experience,'' his wife, Gail, said dryly.
``Not all the coaches understand that everyone doesn't live in
Shelburne, Vt., and have six of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Such discussions tended to slide over the heads of the Jakes.
Among the issues under discussion that weekend were Mansour's
continuing problems with the Immigration and Naturalization Service
_ documents from Senegal were under review _ and the need to find
work and rooms for three homeless players on the team. Mansour is
the only member of the team accepted to a four-year school.
</P>
<P>
   In such a climate of bucolic affluence and impending reality,
Jacobson managed to get his first yellow card, a technical foul for
calling a referee a ``fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansour was not amused, shaking his head at his coach between
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mad at me?'' Jacobson asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get so hyped up, Jake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologized. I learned from you, Mansour, I did the
diplomatic thing.''
</P>
<P>
   They hugged.
</P>
<P>
   Life without Mansour may be a tad harder for Jacobson _ who else
can translate pep talks into French and rouse a lagging team by
example? _ but the current upsurge of interest in inner-city soccer
may counteract the loss. Nike recently became an MLK Jr. outfitter,
donating uniforms and shoes, and the company asked Jacobson to
consult on its plans to sponsor soccer events in urban
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   That, along with a declaration by Alan Rothenberg, the head of
the U.S. Soccer Federation, that money would be going to inner-city
clubs, has led some to believe that soccer may have learned a
lesson from basketball: new energy for the American game will come
from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Along with that energy will also come the problems that Jacobson
deals with every season _ poor kids without green cards struggling
to stay eligible in overwhelmed public schools.
</P>
<P>
   With all that in mind last Nov. 22, on a Saturday night several
hours after his team had won its second straight city championship,
Jacobson sat at his wooden desk in school, his shaved head in his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Trinidadians were leading the dancing in the halls, the
pizza and soda were on order, but the 52-year-old coach was already
thinking about next year's team. Without the senior captains, Kevon
Isa, Randy Guerra and Mansour, there would be no heart and soul to
the team, he thought.
</P>
<P>
   At Thanksgiving a few days later, Mansour tried to cheer him up.
The world was filled with soccer players, he said. They'll come.
You'll see.
</P>
<P>
   And of course they did. By January, two 17-year-old Nigerians,
Bishop Dike and Henry Iwuchukwu, appeared, steered by the youth
soccer coaches in Brooklyn. They are recent immigrants,
quick-footed, eager, confident.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson supervised their enrollment and made sure they did well
enough His elation was borne out last weekend, when they starred in
the Vermont romp, on and off the field. Bishop made such a big
impression that his host family sent him home with a computer.
</P>
<P>
   At that pregraduation lunch last week, as Jacobson raved on
about Bishop and Henry, someone turned to Mansour and said: ``How
do you feel? Next year people will say, `Mansour who?'''
</P>
<P>
   He was chewing a chicken sandwich and, typically, he seemed to
chew the question for a while before he said: ``It would be too bad
if they forgot me. They should remember what I did so that they can
be better than I was.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
