<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTHOUSE-FACTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lighthouse history
 &HT;    Staff report
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timeline of the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse:
</P>
<P>
   1797: Congress approves construction of a lighthouse at the
Diamond Shoals of Cape Hatteras. It's built a mile inland in 1803,
but at 90 feet is woefully short.
</P>
<P>
   1870: Cape Hatteras Lighthouse built 1,600 feet from sea. At 208
feet, tallest in nation.
</P>
<P>
   1920s: Sea encroaches to within 300 feet of lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   1930s: Civilian Conservation Corps builds up dune line with sand
and dune grass. Still ocean advances to 100 feet of structure.
Coast Guard abandons lighthouse; transfers ownership to National
Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   1950: Coast Guard reactivates lighthouse when erosion appears
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   1970: The Navy builds three concrete and steel sheet pile groins
in front of the naval installation, north of lighthouse, to protect
naval facility. Third groin reaches the lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Early 1980s: Army Corps of Engineers studies alternatives in
wake of beach erosion, including adding fourth groin and relocation
of lighthouse. The third groin is extended, and sandbags and sand
fences are erected. Corps proposes building a seawall.
</P>
<P>
   1987: ``Move the Lighthouse Committee'' presents documents on
relocation techniques. The National Park Service contracts with the
National Academy of Sciences for an independent review of all
protection plans. The academy recommends moving the structure.
</P>
<P>
   1989: Park service decides to move the lighthouse, asks Congress
for funds.
</P>
<P>
   1993: Relocation put on hold so money can be used for emergency
measures. Hurricane Emily damages lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   1994: Hurricane Gordon damages dunes and sandbag revetment.
South groin repaired.
</P>
<P>
   1996: Sandbags added to north and south sides of lighthouse.
Plans go forward for a move.
</P>
<P>
   1997: Park Service asks Congress for $2 million to prepare to
move the lighthouse and $9.8 million for the move. President
Clinton includes it in his budget recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Save the Lighthouse Foundation
</P>
<P>
   Save the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse Committee (opposes relocation)
</P>
<P>
   www.savehatteraslight.org/
</P>
<P>
   Outer Banks Lighthouse Society (supports relocation)
</P>
<P>
   www.outer-banks.com/lighthouse-society/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
