</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIGHTHOUSE28-COX     06-27 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTHOUSE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOS for Cape Hatteras Lighthouse
 &HT;    By Gerrie Ferris Finger
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE HATTERAS, N.C. _ The controversy swirling around the
nation's tallest sentinel of the shore is like the seas beneath it
in a nor'easter, and a U.S. Senate committee's decision last week
to appropriate $9.8 million to move the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse
appears unlikely to stand without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   The combatants all agree that something must be done to save the
128-year-old lighthouse from collapsing on the beach where waves
lap precariously close to its brick and mortar base. The
disagreement is over the method of salvation.
</P>
<P>
   One side says the historic spiral-striped beacon should be moved
back from the advancing ocean. The other side says leave it where
it is and beat back the seas.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service, which owns the lighthouse, wants to
move it. It recently awarded a $1.4 million contract to
International Chimney Co. of Buffalo, N.Y., to prepare plans for a
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locals are going to try to stop the Park Service from
moving it,'' says Irene Nolan, a columnist for the Island Breeze,
who says residents are 10-1 against the move. Even North Carolina's
congressional delegation is divided on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Lauch Faircloth has pushed for funding for the move in the
Senate. Rep. Walter Jones has opposed it in the House and proposed
instead appropriating $4 million to build an 800-foot-long steel
wall south of the lighthouse and pump a half million cubic yards of
sand behind it. A House subcommittee rejected that plan a week ago
but has not voted on funding a move.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Gov. Jim Hunt in March, the U.S. Lighthouse
Society expressed support for relocating the lighthouse. ``It is
time to take action,'' wrote Wayne Wheeler, president of the
society, ``and we believe the proper and only effective course of
action is to move this structure from harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   But local officials oppose relocation. Dare County
commissioners, who rarely vote unanimously on anything, voted
unanimously in November to support building a groin, or jetty, out
from the beach south of the lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Relocation foes, led by businessman and environmentalist Hugh
Morton,have reinvigorated an old campaign to keep the structure
where it is and shore up the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do everything we can to see it protected where
it is,'' Morton says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, the Navy built three groins to protect an installation
that monitored the coast for Soviet submarines, and for 10 years
the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse benefited from them. But the groins
caused a bay to form south of the lighthouse, flattening dunes as
the sea advanced.
</P>
<P>
   To shore up the doomed structure in 1982, Morton's committee
raised a half million dollars and spent $165,000 on Seascape, a
synthetic seaweed designed to trap the sand running toward the
beach and to cause dune buildup. ``It wouldn't be standing today if
we hadn't raised that money,'' Morton says.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody agrees with him, and the arguments range from
the wildly emotional to the highly technical.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the lighthouse means lifting it with hydraulic jacks,
setting it on rails and moving it inland, inch by inch, for 1,600
feet _ about where it was in relationship to the sea when it was
built in 1870. Also moved would be two keepers' quarters, which
have been converted to a gift shop, small museum and historical
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extremely risky maneuver to move it,'' says Morton,
who advocates building a fourth groin south of the lighthouse and
installing erosion stabilizers. ``We've got a lighthouse built in
1870 with a million-and-a-quarter bricks in it. There already are
cracks in the mortar joints. It's 208 feet tall. They propose to
move the equivalent of a 21-story, old building more than half a
mile. There's just no need to take that kind of gamble and risk
losing it.''
</P>
<P>
   A fourth groin would cost $1.7 million to build, and Morton has
pledged his $300,000 in reserves from the 1982 campaign to install
new artificial seaweed to trap sand and create dunes.
</P>
<P>
   But a less expensive solution is not necessarily the better
answer, counters Cheryl Roberts, president of the Outer Banks
Lighthouse Society, a proponent of the move. ``So much history has
been lost in the name of economy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And lighthouses have been successfully moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Structural engineers say there's no problem,'' says Bob Woody
of the National Park Service at the Cape Hatteras National
Seashore. ``It's been done many times, and this lighthouse doesn't
present any unique or unusual problem for them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Danny Couch, a local businessman who backs Morton, likens
the moving of lighthouses to ``Wal-Marting history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they successfully moved the Block Island Light and the
Truro Light,'' Couch says. ``They're cute and they make nice little
postcards, but they're not of the historical significance of this
one. To move it is disrespecting the maritime tradition that this
whole region is about.''
</P>
<P>
   With a somewhat similar view in mind, the Park Service
originally endorsed a project to save the landmark where it stands.
In the mid-1980s, the Army Corps of Engineers developed plans for
construction of a massive stone wall around the lighthouse. But
that would have left the lighthouse on a tiny island with the sea
eventually surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   A group that didn't like the sea wall idea formed the Move the
Lighthouse Committee. It was made up mostly of engineers and
scientists, and its stance was a factor in the Park Service turning
to the National Academy of Sciences for further guidance in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were prepared, based on the best information available, to
build a sea wall around it,'' Woody recalls. ``But at that time we
asked one more organization to take a look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Sciences concluded that the Atlantic
Ocean could not be kept from destroying the Cape Hatteras
Lighthouse unless the structure was moved. The Park Service
abandoned plans to build a sea wall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, state Sen. Marc Basnight asked a panel at North
Carolina State University to review the academy's findings and
scientists there concluded the report was correct.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists do not dispute that a jetty and artificial reefs
could temporarily alleviate the erosion, but nothing can hold back
rising sea levels or nor'easters and hurricanes that pound the
cape. Woody said the Park Service is pursuing a solution that would
last at least a century.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rancor, lighthouse lovers on both sides agree that
the structure is a national treasure _ the most recognized,
photographed and admired lighthouse in North America. It is the
signpost of the Graveyard of the Atlantic casting shadows on the
final resting places of those who died in these moody waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would these ghosts of those old lifesavers do if they
came up on shore?'' Couch says. ``They'd look around and say,
`Where's it at?'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
