<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-OZONE-STATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad air summer
 &HT;    Staff report
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The summer of 1998 is shaping up as the worst season of the
decade for ozone pollution in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Florida: Sea breezes usually keep smog off Florida, but it had a
full week of unhealthy ozone levels in May. Forest fire smoke
continues to contribute to the bad air.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia: Atlanta, with its car-jammed suburbs and interstate
highways, remains the South's major ozone trouble spot. Ozone
alerts have been common this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee: A string of ozone days in the Great Smoky Mountains
National Park was blamed on smog drifting over from Tennessee
cities.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina: In Greenville, the ozone standard for healthy
air has been exceeded by seven days.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina: Charlotte has reported 10 bad ozone days, and
Fayetteville and Raleigh have reported eight each.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama: Birmingham issued its first ozone alert in mid-May,
unusually early for the area. Without significant public transit or
auto inspection laws, that city is being closely monitored by the
EPA for dangerous ozone levels.
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Park Service, various state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The South's bad air
</P>
<P>
   To meet a new Environmental Protection Agency mandate to curb
smog, these Southern states are expected to have to institute more
emission controls on coal power plants within five years:
</P>
<P>
   Alabama
</P>
<P>
   Georgia
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   Virginia
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
