NYT-06-27-98 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-OZONE-COX     06-27 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-OZONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air pollution blowing into problem for all of South
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Triggered by the stifling heat and stagnant weather,
bad air is hanging like a veil over much of the South this summer,
from cities to wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   For ozone, the key ingredient in smog, the summer of 1998 is on
track to be the worst of the decade. States throughout the region
report concentrations of ground-level ozone considered unhealthy in
a number of metro areas in May and June, with Atlanta's air rated
the worst.
</P>
<P>
   A rising tide of ozone is also choking remote areas such as
Alabama's Sipsey Wilderness and Tennessee's Great Smoky Mountains
National Park, as pollutants drift from urban to rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that Atlanta's ozone has an impact on the
region, but there is no doubt that the region has an impact on
Atlanta,'' said Mike Rodgers, an atmospheric scientist and director
of Georgia Tech's Air Quality Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complicated mix of factors, but we now know that
(nitrogen oxide) is a key to the regional ozone problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to curb regional ozone, the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency proposes a crackdown on nitrogen oxide emissions, primarily
from coal-fired power plants, in 22 Eastern states, including
Georgia, and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   As proposed, the states that are considered the prime
contributors of nitrogen oxides _ or ``nox'' _ will have until 2002
to reduce emissions by as much as 70 percent of 1990 levels. The
new rules are expected to be published in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that for most of our region, the nox reductions will
be enough to bring most areas into compliance on ozone standards,''
said Kay Prince, an EPA regional air quality specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Principally emitted by power plants and motor vehicles, nox is a
primary component of ozone. The nitrogen oxide also contributes to
acid rain and the whitish haze that often hangs over the region
during the hot season.
</P>
<P>
   A toxic gas, ground level ozone is harmful to children who play
outdoors, as well as people who have asthma or other respiratory
illnesses. Ozone also damages forests and crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nox emissions have grown, especially in areas of economic
growth,'' said Doug Grano, an EPA scientist who focuses on regional
ozone.
</P>
<P>
   While some 25 years of regulations under the Clean Air Act have
resulted in reductions in most air pollutants, such as lead, sulfur
dioxide and carbon monoxide, regulators have begun only in recent
years to target nox. That's because it was not until the 1990s that
scientists began to understand the role of nox in creating ozone.
</P>
<P>
   There is widespread agreement that cuts in nox will improve the
air throughout the eastern United States, but not everyone agrees
that the EPA plan will solve the ozone problem.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators from 10 states, as well as utility officials,
question the regional approach, saying the evidence is far from
conclusive that ozone is transported over long distances.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that nitrogen oxide reductions should be targeted at
areas of high ozone, but not blanket across the region.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, critics contend, the expense of retrofitting power
plants with additional pollution controls likely will result in
higher power rates that could dampen economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA's approach appears to be a shotgun approach,'' said Barry
Stephens, deputy director of the Tennessee Division of Air
Pollution Control. ``I think we'll spend a lot of money and it
still might not work.''
</P>
<P>
   Governors of six of the 10 states _ including Tennessee, Alabama
and Virginia in the South _ have asked EPA to soften the rule. In a
break from its neighbors, the Georgia Environmental Protection
Division agrees the power plant reductions are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you shut down every power plant in Georgia, our
research shows that you'd still have an ozone problem in Atlanta,''
said Chuck Griffin, a spokesman for the Southern Co., which owns
four electric utilities in four states and is the leading coal
burner in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Even Georgia Tech's Rodgers, a proponent of tougher standards
and of the theory that ozone transport is part of the problem, said
targeting only power plants ``just puts off the day when we tackle
the car problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the controversy is the confusion over EPA standard for
unhealthy ozone. Beginning last year, a new, more stringent
standard, based on ozone measures over eight hours, was enacted,
replacing a standard that was based on calculations of a one-hour
measure of ozone levels.
</P>
<P>
   But while North Carolina, South Carolina and Florida have issued
numerous ozone alerts this season based on the new standard,
Georgia and Alabama have continued to use the old standard for
informing residents of potentially unhealthy ozone.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that Charlotte and Raleigh, and Greenville, S.C.,
have had about as many ozone action days as Atlanta and Birmingham,
despite the fact that Atlanta and Birmingham historically have far
worse air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've decided to bite the bullet and start this program under
the new standard,'' said Tom Mather, a spokesman for the North
Carolina Division of Air Quality. ``This is a public health
concern. And we think it's important to get the word out to the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about air quality standards, see these Web
sites:
</P>
<P>
   www.voap.com
</P>
<P>
   www.epa.gov/airlinks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
