<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHRYSLER-BLDG-REAL     06-27 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHRYSLER-BLDG-REAL-495&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHROME SPIRE BY CHRYSLER TO MEET CRYSTAL BY JOHNSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two of the United States' most durable 20th-century
architectural icons are meeting on East 42nd Street, where Philip
Johnson has designed a modern companion piece to the Chrysler
Building, that giddy but well-loved emblem of Jazz Age abandon and
automotive supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's plans are part of a $100 million renovation of the
entire block between Lexington and Third Avenues owned by Tishman
Speyer Properties and the Travelers Group. The project, to begin
this week, includes the landmark 76-story Chrysler Building, a
32-story annex to the east and a large parcel between them.
</P>
<P>
   The annex, a bland white-brick box, will be enlarged and reclad
with a glass facade designed by Johnson. Five small buildings in
the middle of the block would be replaced by a one-story structure
topped with what Johnson calls an ``explosion of crystals'' _ a
series of glass pyramids 50 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be as dramatic as the top of the building,'' Johnson
said, referring to the chromium-plated spire with its radiant array
of chevron-shaped windows, almost like the spokes of a car wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Architectural features of the Chrysler Building would also be
restored as part of the project. The 1.9 million-square-foot
complex will be known as the Chrysler Center upon completion late
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you bring it all under one roof, figuratively speaking,
you create not only an interesting place but an anchor for 42nd
Street,'' said Jerry Speyer, the president and chief executive of
Tishman Speyer, who has also proposed a controversial renovation of
Rockefeller Center and is bidding to redevelop the site of the New
York Coliseum on Columbus Circle.
</P>
<P>
   The likeliest user of the space under Johnson's ``crystals''
would be a restaurant, Speyer said. Upstairs, only office tenants
need apply: The owners did not consider setting aside part of the
tower as a hotel, a prospect floated last summer before Tishman
Speyer took control.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Speyer said, the building is intended for
``cutting-edge companies of the new millennium,'' in the spirit of
its developer, the automaker Walter Chrysler, who dedicated the
tower in May 1930 as ``a sound contribution to business progress.''
</P>
<P>
   One of countless New Yorkers who have fallen under the Chrysler
Building's spell, Speyer can recall being taken by his father in
the late 1940s to the old Cloud Club on the 67th floor. He was a
boy, and Chrysler was still the second-tallest building in the
world. (It is now the 18th.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so infatuated looking out the windows, because it was an
awesome view,'' Speyer said. ``I remember saying, `I never want to
leave here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Today, he said, he feels like ``the custodian for something
special.'' Tishman Speyer and the Travelers insurance company
bought the buildings last year for about $220 million. They have a
150-year lease from the Cooper Union for the Advancement of Science
and Art, which owns the land under the Chrysler Building.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although it is an aesthetic trophy, the Chrysler Building has
had a checkered economic history, having changed hands six times
since the Chrysler family sold it in 1953. By the end of next year,
the tower and annex will be about 55 percent vacant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been easy to put on a couple of coats of paint
and re-lease it,'' Speyer said. ``But our purpose was to recreate
the monumentality of what we've bought. We want to make it better
without interfering with the greatness of what's there already.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, no significant alterations are planned to the
original building, which was designed by William Van Alen and was
briefly the tallest tower in the world, at 1,046 feet 4} inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in pretty good shape _ it just needs some creative
housekeeping,'' said John Belle, a partner in Beyer Blinder Belle,
the architectural firm responsible for restoring the building, as
well as renovating Grand Central Terminal and Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   The work at Chrysler will include the repair and relighting of
Edward Trumbull's ceiling mural in the lobby, the cleaning of the
surrounding walls (made of a richly veined marble called Moroccan
rouge flame) and the preparation of a master redesign plan for the
storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration proposal and storefront plan are subject to
approval by the city's Landmarks Preservation Commission, as is the
connection between the tower and the new structure designed by
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But the annex on Third Avenue is not a landmark. Constructed in
1952 as the Chrysler Building East, and known recently as the Kent
Building, it is thoroughly undistinguished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only isn't it terribly attractive,'' Speyer said, ``but it
isn't as efficient as it could be.'' The floors of the annex are to
be expanded slightly to the west, thereby placing the elevator core
in the middle of the building rather than against the back wall,
where it is now.
</P>
<P>
   The extension, totaling about 130,000 square feet, will be clad
in glass from floor to ceiling, Johnson said, while the rest of the
building will have smaller windows with glass panels between them,
in a darker color.
</P>
<P>
   Still the enfant terrible of American architecture today at the
age of 92, Johnson set New York abuzz in the late 1970s when he
crowned the AT&AMP;T headquarters on Madison Avenue at 55th Street with
an enormous broken pediment. That building, now known as Sony
Plaza, was instantly likened to a skyscraping Chippendale highboy.
</P>
<P>
   For the Chrysler annex, Johnson made no attempt to echo the
automotive motifs in the landmark, like radiator-cap gargoyles and
hubcap-lined cornices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even like the architecture of it,'' he confessed,
``but it's become sacred now. It's the most loved building in New
York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
