<HEADLINE>
AMONG SENIORS, CRAMPTON KNOWS HE IS UP THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON, N.J. _ He knows he is fighting time and history, but
Bruce Crampton is playing through.
</P>
<P>
   At age 62, Crampton was one stroke behind the leader, Charles
Coody, entering the Cadillac NFL Golf Classic on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Crampton, who won this seniors event last year, is a rarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know only 3 percent of all the senior tournaments have
been won by players 60 years or older,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it is lower than that, about 1.3 percent. Of 532
tournaments, only 7 have gone to golfers older than 60. Only 1 of
the winners was older than 61, and it has been 13 years since that
happened.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to that trivia question? Mike Fetchick, who at age 63
won the Hilton Head Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Crampton is 5 feet 9 inches tall and weighs less than 180
pounds. As he has aged, he has had to change his swing. The style
that helped him win 14 tournaments on the regular PGA Tour was fine
for a younger man, he said. But it does not cut it on the tour for
players 50 and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get older and you swivel this way,'' he said, turning
his body at an extreme angle, ``you start to get back problems. So
I've tried to make it a rounder swing, keeping my back straighter
to save my body.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not merely the yardage that seniors lose that affects
their game, Crampton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of the little things he said. ``The fact you know
what you should be doing, but just can't get the body to do it
exactly that way. Look, when you're driving a car at 60, it's not
the same as driving it at 25. When you try to thread a needle at
60, it's not as easy as it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Trent Dilfer, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers' quarterback and
one of the best golfers among the football players, said: ``I've
learned more with these guys. What I've seen about the seniors is
they're so in control of their game. One thing about football
players is we tend to play golf like we play football.''
</P>
<P>
   Dilfer pointed out that Crampton ``wasn't spectacular'' in the
opening round, ``but he took what the golf course gave him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He made his share of 15- and 20-foot putts,'' Dilfer said.
</P>
<P>
   The age of the players also gives the senior tour its special
profile. Most major sports associations are not concerned about the
prostate cancer among its membership. But the tour has two players,
Arnold Palmer and Jim Colbert, who battled the illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to, but I've become an expert on it,'' Palmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The seniors also travel with two physical therapists and a
chiropractor. Palmer has had back problems going back to the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got it,'' he said, ``we thought it was a hip
problem. But it was a vertebrae problem and it just got worse.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Schueren, one of the physical therapists on the tour, said:
``Think about what a golfer does. They hit the ball 300 times a
day, seven days a week. Add up the years.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds against winning this event does not concern Crampton, a
native Australian.
</P>
<P>
   ``No 60-year-old has won a tournament this year,'' Crampton
said. ``But that adds additional flavor to our events, that a
60-year-old can still compete.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   _ The Professional Caddies Association has signed a seven-figure
deal with BUM equipment to promote its products, and that means the
caddies will be wearing logos on their shirts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quarterbacks don't compete head-to-head, except in tournaments
of this nature. ``I know it sounds immodest,'' TRENT DILFER of the
Buccaneers said, ``but JOHN ELWAY and I are the best golfers among
quarterbacks. If John's not in a tourney, I don't really see myself
competing against another quarterback.'' Dilfer shot a 76 in the
opening round to come into the weekend tied for third among the
football players.
</P>
</TEXT>
