<HEADLINE>
SPRINTER SETS NATIONAL HIGH SCHOOL RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Fla., N.J., Texas, N.Y., La.)   (bl)  
 By JAMES DUNAWAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. _ Angela Williams of Ontario, Calif., set a
national high school record of 11.11 seconds in the final of the
girls' 100-meter dash Friday night at the national junior
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Williams broke one of the longest-standing high school records,
the 11.13 run by Chandra Cheeseborough of Jacksonville, Fla., at
the 1976 U.S. Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   The first two finishers in each event here qualify for the world
junior championships in Annecy, France, July 28-Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Hot and humid weather, with temperatures in the mid-90s, made
times fast in the sprints and slow in the distances.
</P>
<P>
   The Barber twins of Montclair, N.J., Melisa and Mikele, stepped
up in class here Friday, with mixed results. Last weekend in
Raleigh, N.C. the 17-year-old Barber sisters swept the sprints in
the national scholastic track and field championships. Melisa won
the 100 meters in 11.74 seconds and the 200 in 23.94, while Mikele
won the 400 in 52.56, the year's fastest high school time.
</P>
<P>
   Here at the national junior meet, which allow athletes under age
20, the Barbers faced a number of college athletes as well as some
leading high school runners who skipped last week's meet to prepare
for this one.
</P>
<P>
   Mikele ran first and won her qualifying heat of the 400 by six
meters in a swift but easy looking 53.64. Only another heat winner,
Nakia Johnson of Chino Hills, Calif., ran faster, clocking 53.26.
</P>
<P>
   Melisa Barber did not fare as well. She won her heat of the 100
meters in 11.62, but didn't qualify for the final when she finished
sixth in her semifinal in 11.72.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a busy week,'' Mikele said. ``We had the high school
nationals last weekend, then Monday was graduation. The next day we
had to go to our best friend's funeral; she died in an auto
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we had a plane delay coming here and we didn't get into
the hotel until 11 o'clock last night. I think we're both a little
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   In the preliminaries of the men's 110-meter hurdles, Todd
Matthews of Trenton won his heat in a wind-aided 13.83 seconds.
Only one high school boy has run faster: Renaldo Nehemiah of Scotch
Plains, N.J., in 1977. He went on to become a world record-holder.
</P>
<P>
   The men's 100 meters final was won by Tory Mitchell of Big
Spring, Texas, in a wind-aided time of 10.12.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Kutzing, of Port Jefferson, N.Y., won the women's
5,000-meter race walk by more than 150 meters in 24:42.97. She will
be joined on the U.S. national team in France by her fellow Long
Islander Keyon Soley of Uniondale, who finished second in the
girls' long jump at 20 feet 7\ inches, three-quarters of an inch
behind Myra Combs of Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
