<SLUG> BC-RAC-SKIPAWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HINE FAMILY FIRM, SKIP AWAY'S A PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sonny Hine sat in the little office in Barn 1 at Belmont Park in
New York last week and reflected on the impact that Skip Away had
had on his life: winning 15 races, running in the money 30 times in
33 starts and earning $8.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly Hine reflected on the impact that he expected Skip
Away to make during the next four months as he enters the
homestretch of a career with one purpose: to become the richest
horse in racing history.
</P>
<P>
   It is more of a family business than anything else. Hine is the
trainer and his wife, Carolyn, is the nominal owner of Skip Away,
the gray 5-year-old champion. They all started the stretch run
Thursday when they crossed the continent with Skip Away. The colt
is set to confront Gentlemen on Sunday in the $1 million Hollywood
Gold Cup in California. And make no mistake, Hine considers Skip
Away a partner in the family business, not the family pet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's all business,'' Hine said. ``He's a business horse. He's
very sharp. He doesn't want to be petted or hugged. If you're in
his stall working on his legs, he won't attack you. But he doesn't
want you petting him, except for my wife. He listens to her. If
he's eating and she calls, he'll come to her. Otherwise, he's all
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Big business. After some anxious moments last weekend when his
legs showed some swelling, Skip Away headed west with a winning
streak of six races, five of them Grade 1 stakes. They are the $1
million Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park last October, the $4
million Breeders' Cup Classic at Hollywood Park in November, the
$300,000 Donn at Gulfstream Park in February, the $250,000
Gulfstream Park Handicap in March and the $750,000 Pimlico Special
in May.
</P>
<P>
   He took a slight cut in quality but still collected first prize
in the $500,000 Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs in Boston
in late May. Then he came home to Belmont Park to rest for
Gentlemen and Silver Charm and any other challengers waiting in the
second half of his final season at the races.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to surpass Cigar's record haul of $9.9 million and
become racing's first $10 million horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could just go to the Breeders' Cup and go over the top,''
Hine said. ``But he's been in training constantly for four years
now, and he'll race his way up to the Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wins the Hollywood Gold Cup, he'll get first prize of
$600,000 and would reach $8.9 million. In the Pacific Classic in
August, he could reach $9.5 million. The Woodward in New York has a
small purse, but he would reach $9.9 million. And he would pass $10
million in the Jockey Club Gold Cup. Then the Breeders' Cup
Classic, with first prize of $2.5 million, would put him way
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Having charted the final strides for his business horse with
precision and profit, Hine allowed himself to look further ahead,
and said: ``We want him to stay healthy and go to stud. That's
where the real money is. He can make more money standing than
running.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Skip Away is running, Hine will continue to press for
recognition for his star, who has been voted the 3-year-old
champion and the champion older horse but has twice lost the vote
for Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets respect,'' the trainer said, ``from the racing
secretaries when they assign the weights.''
</P>
<P>
   Hine seems determined to make his horse not only the richest but
also the most honored in the business. He cannot understand why
people would object, especially Bob Baffert, the trainer of Silver
Charm and Real Quiet, who won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The two trainers have exchanged volleys in a war of words over
who is ducking whom. The obstacle to a confrontation had seemed
cleared when Silver Charm was booked into the Hollywood Gold Cup
last Friday. But Silver Charm withdrew Wednesday when he developed
a fever.
</P>
<P>
   Hine still reached for respect for Skip Away, and found it. ``He
gets mail every day,'' Hine said. ``One letter made me cry. It was
from a teen-aged girl whose daddy took her to the Jockey Club Gold
Cup the year before last when Skip Away beat Cigar. She bet 10
bucks on Skippy and won. But not long after that day, her father
had a stroke and passed away. Now, every time Skippy runs, she
relates back to her father and how he took her to the track to see
him run for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with sentiment, Sonny Hine lives on strategy. He has
already dug deep into Cigar's experience and concludes that Del Mar
brought an end to that horse's 16-race winning streak in 1996 by
trapping him with a surface that was softer and deeper and more
tiring than usual and with two horses in tandem who made him run
too fast, early and late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skip Away worked very good over a heavy track here last
week,'' Hine said. ``My rider that morning was Angel Cordero. He
also worked him before the Pimlico Special, so this was his second
trip. I wanted him to tell me about the surface. Angel said Skippy
looked like the best horse he'd ridden since Seattle Slew.''
</P>
<P>
   With that attitude and $10 million in sight, let the stretch run
begin. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
