<HEADLINE>
BACK FROM THE DEAD FOR THE U.S.A. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tryout roster for the U.S. team in the world basketball
championships is still at 50 players and may not be whittled down
until practice starts July 8. But in its infancy, Dream Team IV is
already beginning to follow the plot line of other desperate
sequels:
</P>
<P>
   Bring back some character from the dead, prop him up and pray he
can act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, a bunch of CBA guys probably won't catch too many
people's attention, but we might get some people like a Dominique
Wilkins,'' said Rod Thorn, the National Basketball Association's
vice president of operations. ``Or Byron Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Drexler, who retired this season and will coach at the
University of Houston next season, is also contemplating playing in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   USA Basketball's attempt to field a competitive team began in
earnest after NBA players decided to boycott the July 29-Aug. 9
world tournament. Their protest of an expected lockout this week by
the NBA owners left the selection committee digging up careers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the case of Wilkins and Scott, you can cut them,
exile them and tell them they can't play, but they keep coming
back.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler is the player representative on the selection committee,
one of 12 members who chose Gary Payton, Chris Webber, Grant Hill,
Allan Houston and eight other players to represent the United
States in the games this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Although USA Basketball is independent of the NBA, the players'
association believes the marketing of NBA players overseas is
directly tied to the league's image and merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   As for foreign citizens who play in the NBA, they may go to
Greece no matter what. Steve Nash is expected to play with Canada,
Detlef Schrempf with Germany, Vlade Divac with Yugoslavia and Toni
Kukoc with Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday is Witching Hour
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, NBA business will come to a standstill
Wednesday. A telephone conference call scheduled for Monday or
Tuesday is expected to end with the owners unanimously in favor of
suspending all trades and free-agent acquisitions until a new
collective bargaining agreement with the players is signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never say never, but all signs point to a lockout at this
time,'' said Russ Granik, the league's deputy commissioner.``We
haven't made much progress since we began and there are no meetings
currently scheduled.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's negotiation broke off after only 30 minutes, with
the players' association's president, Patrick Ewing, and its
executive director, Billy Hunter, leaving the bargaining table
without ever hearing a new proposal.
</P>
<P>
   With the union scheduling a golf outing in Hawaii from July
3-12, it does not appear much headway will be made next month
either.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell and Riley?
</P>
<P>
   It is probably nothing but talk-radio speculation, but when Pat
Riley and Latrell Sprewell pop up in the same sentence, you start
to wonder. Would Riley take the biggest gamble of his career and
trade for Image Problem?
</P>
<P>
   With a strong desire to move Voshon Lenard and perhaps either
Jamal Mashburn or P.J. Brown, Riley is considering every possible
option, a Western Conference team official said. The only problem
is, the Golden State Warriors are probably stuck with Sprewell _
whose choking of P.J. Carlesimo set off a national debate and the
longest suspension in league history _ until at least the end of
July.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the manner in which Sprewell's contract is
structured, the Warriors will not receive equal value on his $8
million annual salary in a trade until the two-year anniversary of
his contract signing at the end of next month. With the lockout
pending, Sprewell will probably be a Warrior for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But what a teary reunion it would be for Sprewell and Tim
Hardaway in Miami. They had one of the biggest running feuds in the
league when they played together, giving each other death stares on
the court and warring on the bench during timeouts. Something about
passing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Another sappy scene: Mashburn's possibly going to Golden State
and playing alongside his old Dallas teammate, Jim Jackson. They
didn't get along, either.
</P>
<P>
   Camby's Doubters
</P>
<P>
   Toronto coach Butch Carter was so ecstatic over obtaining
Charles Oakley that he pleaded with a confidant the day before the
deal was made not to say anything to anyone about it. The reason:
</P>
<P>
   ``If Patrick Ewing ever gets wind of this, he'll veto the whole
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, who has often let Knicks management know his strong
feelings about keeping Oakley in the past, actually signed off on
the trade that brought Marcus Camby to New York last Thursday. But
many more in the organization were not convinced that getting Camby
automatically made the Knicks a stronger contender in the Eastern
Conference. Privately, two high-ranking team employees questioned
the wisdom of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   However tough it might be, parting with Oakley was not the
problem, they said under condition of anonymity. The general belief
among the Knicks was that Oakley was wearing down. But acquiring
Camby caused the most consternation. Wingspan and blocked shots
aside, the thinking was that the injury-prone Camby, 24, is not
much better at this stage of his career than John Wallace, the 1996
first-round draft pick whom the Knicks moved to Toronto last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   As for Oakley, he is planning a news conference in New York next
week and has said he will not bite his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Often critical of spin-control management types and teammates he
did not think were totally committed to the cause of winning a
title, Oakley may get a tad nasty.
</P>
<P>
   He was in Richmond when the Knicks' president, Ernie Grunfeld,
caught up with him and broke the news. His sister said he was in
North Carolina on Thursday. Like his prospects for a championship,
he is going South.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps finding out he will soon be a resident of Ontario and a
Raptor employee made him run for another border.
</P>
<P>
   Tough Trip for Van Exel
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy Camper, Part II.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Van Exel also went from the showroom to the clearance rack
on draft night, moving from the glare and promise of the Los
Angeles Lakers to the dim and dilapidated Denver Nuggets. Van
Exel's agent, James Bryant, told the both The Los Angeles Times and
The Rocky Mountain News last week that his client would consider
not reporting to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Though Nuggets general manager Dan Issel finally had his first
telephone conversation with Van Exel on Friday, and tried to
promise good things, the mercurial point guard was not scheduled on
a flight to Denver over the weekend, a team official said.
</P>
<P>
   He has until 4 p.m. Monday to report to the club under the
collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side for Van Exel, he is a shoot-first,
pass-and-ask-questions-later point guard and no longer has to worry
about such menial tasks as, say, giving up the ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GINGRICH-NYT &LR;      06-27 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GINGRICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STANDING UP TO THE HOUSE BULLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times said in an editorial, Sunday, June 28:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Panic has gripped the House leadership. One sure sign is the way
Speaker Newt Gingrich and his team try scheme after scheme to block
campaign-finance reform. In the latest maneuver, Gingrich has
signed on to a move to threaten removal of independent-minded
Republicans from their House leadership positions if they continue
to support legislation opposed by the Speaker _ in this case the
bill to ban soft-money contributions to the national parties.
</P>
<P>
   The threat runs counter to Gingrich's own stated vision for
cleaning up the House. The man who arrived in Congress as a
reformer has become the guardian of its debased, influence-peddling
status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the speaker's wrath is the petition signed by
several Republicans this spring demanding a vote on the
Shays-Meehan legislation to outlaw unlimited special-interest
donations to the Republican and Democratic national committees.
Only when it became clear that the petition was going to get a
majority did Gingrich relent and promise a vote. Now a dozen
diehard Republicans are circulating their own petition to the GOP
Steering Committee, suggesting that it think twice about handing
out top committee posts to anyone defying the leadership on
important issues. In an unusual step, Gingrich signed the petition
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox is, of course, that Republicans were themselves all
too happy to get Democrats to sign discharge petitions when the
Democrats controlled the House. Gingrich led such a move some years
ago to get a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced budget
out of committee. As a rebel, he stood for independent thinking by
lawmakers and repeatedly condemned the Democrats' financial
shenanigans. Now he has changed his tune, and is said to be
especially irritated at the actions of Christopher Shays of
Connecticut, Republican co-sponsor of the campaign reform bill, and
also of Jim Leach, the banking committee chairman who signed the
campaign reform petition and has one of the GOP's best records for
curbing campaign donations from groups affected by his committee.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of responding to Gingrich's threats, House members
should listen to a growing number of business leaders who also
favor cleaning up the system. Last week, about 20 Republican
members met in the Capitol basement with Warren Buffett, Jerome
Kohlberg and influential investors who said that the integrity of
American democracy was jeopardized by the unlimited corporate
contributions that the Shays-Meehan bill would end. Buffett warned
pointedly that if change is not made now, it will be harder to
bring about in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Last week The Wall Street Journal also reported that House
Republicans were assured they need not worry about killing off
comprehensive tobacco legislation because the industry would pay
for television ad campaigns to support those who stood by it. Were
reform to pass, such ads would be subject to strict fund-raising
limitations that govern direct donations to candidates, as they
should be.
</P>
<P>
   With each revelation of naked congressional greed, Americans
grow more disgusted by a legislature that puts its conscience out
for bids. When Congress returns from its recess in mid-July, it has
no higher priority than listening to the public's demand for change
and, perforce, finding the spine to stand up to the bully from
Georgia. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
