u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-625(2TA     06-27 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKE, RAIN AND RAINBOWS: JUST ANOTHER DAY AT WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Some say this place is doomed. Some say it
should be domed.
</P>
<P>
   Even though hail was in the forecast, fire and rain, along with
a redemptive evening rainbow, were the main players Saturday at
Wimbledon. While weather intrusions are the tiresome norm around
here, there was also the novel disruption of an afternoon fire at
an adjacent high-rise apartment building. The blaze required the
evacuation of Court 18 because of billowing black smoke that posed
a potential health hazard; The Associated Press reported that one
woman from the building was treated for smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Martin, the two-time Wimbledon semifinalist who along with
defending champion, Pete Sampras, represents the last of the
American men still in contention, was ahead, 6-4, 4-6, 7-6 (7-1),
2-2 in his third-round encounter with Australia's Todd Woodbridge
when police and fire officials closed down the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who says we have to play in front of people?'' pleaded Martin,
who felt it better to continue playing than risk getting rained
out, which is exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Over on Court 1, where the smoke was less dense but still an
annoyance, sixth-seeded Monica Seles and Indonesia's Yayuk Basuki
were commanded to play on even though both suspected the air was
contaminated from the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just so strange with the fire, I was hoping it's OK to
breathe this air in, and both Yayuk and I felt we should stop,''
Seles said after the 6-2, 6-3 victory, ``but in the end, it was
probably better to just go on. We've seen everything today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Round of 16, Seles faces 14th-seeded Sandrine Testud, the
player who ambushed her here last year in the third round and ended
her Italian Open run this year. But Seles said she's a far more
focused player now. In the last two losses to Testud, Seles was
wracked with guilt about playing at all instead of being at home in
Florida to comfort her father, Karolj, who succumbed to cancer last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I don't have doubts and I don't feel guilt,'' Seles
said, ``so that makes it easier, gives me peace of mind, and I
think that translates on the court, too.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the supporting cast tried in vain to play
catch-up in the brief sunny spells, the defending champion Martina
Hingis, her Cheshire cat grin back in place after pouting through a
lackluster second-round outing, played cat-and-mouse with Yelena
Likhovseva.
</P>
<P>
   Had it been permissible to tear her opponent into tiny pieces
and toss her into the center court breeze, the 17-year-old Hingis
probably would have chosen that mischievous option. Instead of
inflicting actual bodily harm on the flustered Likhovseva, Hingis,
undefeated in 10 consecutive Wimbledon matches, merely toyed with
the Russian and advanced by a comfortable 6-2, 6-1 margin into the
Round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis has already won four Grand Slam titles in her career, and
she won't stop collecting until she has tallied 28 Grand Slam
victims in a calendar year, the feat Steffi Graf performed in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more matches you play, the more confident you are,'' said
Hingis, who has the kind of confidence that Graf had before
injuries reduced her from tenacious to tentative. ``She was on the
other side,'' Hingis said, referring to Graf, a seven-time
Wimbledon champion, ``and we would only meet in the final, so I
don't really care if she is in or out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her breezy words, Hingis doubtless prefers that Graf,
the only top player with a winning record against her, is out, a
third-round victim of Natasha Zvereva on Friday. Now four rounds
away from defending the title that last year made her the youngest
Wimbledon champion since Lottie Dodd in 1887, Hingis remains on
target to become the youngest champion since Dodd to successfully
defend the championship.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It seems a lifetime ago that Conchita Martinez prevented Martina
Navratilova from attaining a record-breaking 10th Wimbledon title
when she dealt her a surprise defeat in their 1994 final. Since
then, Martinez, of Spain, has managed no more Slam titles, and
Saturday she was thumped from contention, 2-6, 6-3, 7-5, by
Britain's own Samantha Smith. The 94th-ranked Smith had never
before managed to pass Wimbledon's first round and was trounced,
6-1, 6-0, by Martinez when they met last year at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's the most disappointing loss ever,'' said
Martinez, who led, 4-1, when the match was suspended by rain Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   This morning when they reconvened, the pixieish Smith, who
prefers to be called Sam, stuck to the classic serve-volley,
chip-charge style that England seems to cultivate in its tennis
hopefuls. But Martinez, who normally wields a sniper's passing
shot, apparently never woke up in time for the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was there, I think I am much more superior, but today I
felt that I was not there,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   The 55th-ranked Chanda Rubin kept her mind on the immediate
problem of a 7-7 third-set deadlock with Tara Snyder. Rubin emerged
the victor, 3-6, 7-5, 11-9.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two of the seeded men with games replete with the stylish
strokes required to win on grass, third-seeded Petr Korda and the
local hero, the 12th-seeded Tim Henman, moved into the Round of 16.
Korda eliminated Jerome Golmard, 4-6, 7-5, 7-5, 7-5. And Henman,
who next faces the reigning U.S. Open champion, Patrick Rafter,
gratified the center court crowd by picking up where he left off on
Friday night and downing Zimbabwe's Byron Black, 6-4, 6-4, 3-6,
7-5. . . . ... Once the unseeded Dutchman Jan Siemerink disposed of
11th-seeded Jonas Bjorkman, 7-6 (8-6), 5-7, 2-6, 6-4, 7-5,
out-acing him 15-2, there were just two seeds left on the bottom
half of the men's draw, including Siemerink's compatriot,
ninth-seeded Richard Krajicek, whose third-round match with
Germany's Nicolas Kiefer was rained out after three games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
