<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-SALMON-NYT &LR;      06-27 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-SALMON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: GOOD BOOK MAKES WAITING FOR SALMON PALATABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, N.H.)  (duplication warning: also sent with `s' code) 
 (bl)  
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UPTON, Maine _ Ruth Kirchmeier and I caught few landlocked
salmon on a recent trip to Lake Umbagog and the Rapid River, but we
did get hooked on Alain de Botton's ``How Proust Can Change Your
Life.'' The book didn't alter our lives, but it brightened our
wind-buffeted camp as we sat out one gale after another, waiting
for a lull of sufficient duration to allow us to go fishing.
</P>
<P>
   A stiff breeze had greeted us at the trip's start when we
launched our canoe on the Androscoggin River in Errol, N.H., and
went three miles upstream to where the river flows out of the lake
on the New Hampshire side. From there, it is about two and a half
miles across the lake to where the Rapid River enters from the
Maine shore. Whitecaps were forming when we went out on the lake,
but pushed along at four or five knots by our two-horsepower
outboard, we were more than halfway across when the wind picked up
and we began to take water over the port bow, requiring Ruth to
bail continuously.
</P>
<P>
   I altered our course, even though this made the trip longer, in
order to take the waves head on, and when I was directly upwind of
the camp, I turned and ran with them. By that time, the long,
shallow lake was a froth of white with three-foot swells. Our
venerable 20-foot Grumman aluminum canoe was heavily laden and
would often tend to bury her bow as we slid down the face of a
swell, forcing me to throttle back time and again.
</P>
<P>
   We rent the camp, which is on the south shore of the Rapid River
at the juncture of river and lake, from Dick and Liz Celli of
Lenox, Mass. They awaited us at their dock, having come over the
day before in their pontoon boat to ready the place for our
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Dick's first words were, ``I never thought you'd bring Ruth
across on a day like this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I share your incredulity,'' I responded.
</P>
<P>
   While I sorted out my gear, Ruth boated upriver to Cedar Stump
and the river's outlet pool with the Cellis. From there they hiked
up the Carry Road to visit with Aldro French. French and his
partner, Joan Magrauth, have launched a guiding service on the
Rapid River for trout and salmon anglers. (Their address is P.O.
Box 404, Middle Dam, Andover, Maine 04216.) Their base on the Rapid
River is French's Forest Lodge and Winter House, formerly owned by
Louise Dickinson Rich, whose 1942 best seller, ``We Took to the
Woods,'' described her life in the Rapid River wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   The Cellis left camp the next day and, I learned later, got to
the opposite shore just ahead of a torrential rain squall and a
short-lived gale out of the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   During a period of calm that evening, Ruth and I went to the
outlet pool. I made fewer than six casts before a fierce electrical
storm sent us scuttling back to camp. I had no wish to be sitting
in an aluminum canoe waving a graphite rod under such conditions.
As we headed back with lightning all about us, Ruth observed, ``It
might not be a bad way to go: quick and in a spot we love.''
</P>
<P>
   I responded, ``I have promises to keep and miles to go before I
sleep.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The following afternoon we spent a few hours at the outlet pool.
The river was high and the fishing was slow. I caught, all on a
Muddler Minnow, one 11-inch brook trout, four 12-inch salmon and
two big white suckers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rapid River is fly-fishing only, all brook trout must be
released, and only one salmon a day 14 or more inches long may be
kept. After Aug. 15, no salmon may be kept.
</P>
<P>
   The Rapid River, particularly upstream at Pond in the River, has
some huge brook trout. The salmon, at least the ones I've caught
over the past decade, are not unusually large. A three-pounder is
something to brag about. The river's attraction is its remoteness
and its tumultuous descent to Lake Umbagog, which is now the heart
of a national wildlife refuge.
</P>
<P>
   In the five days that followed, I fished for less than a total
of eight hours, and it was impossible to go out on three of them.
We sat in camp reading, or watching storm clouds build over the
mountains to the northwest and torrents of wind, sometimes gusting
to 50 miles an hour, rip across the lake, lifting sheets of spray
from the whitecaps. That week, a record June wind howled across the
top of Mount Washington: 137 miles an hour. Rain drummed on the
aluminum roof every day but one, and most of the nights. The
temperature was in the low 40s by midnight, sometimes rising to 50
at noon.
</P>
<P>
   We fired up the wood stove _ Celli keeps a good supply of dry,
split hardwood logs on hand _ and took turns reading the Proust
book. I encountered a Proust I had not known, and de Botton's
approach to his subject was varied, humorous and brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   That done, we savored Jill Ker Conway's ``The Road from
Coorain,'' a shining, stirring account of her early years in
Australia. I was much less enchanted by a college poetry textbook
that I had mistaken _ when hastily packing for the trip _ for an
equally battered Thomas Hardy collection of poems. Ruth turned to
Mary Gordon's latest novel ``Spending.''
</P>
<P>
   On the penultimate day, the wind slackened off in the late
afternoon and we went to the outlet pool, where, after flailing
away with a Muddler and assorted dry flies for two hours with no
success, I switched to a Black Ghost and caught a 15-inch salmon on
my first cast. On my second cast with the same fly, I was fast to a
heavy fish. I knew that it wasn't a salmon because it fought deep
and doggedly with no acrobatics. Ten minutes later, it was in the
canoe, a six-pound female largemouth bass. This was a surprise.
Largemouths are devotees of still waters and I was fishing at the
foot of a rapids.
</P>
<P>
   We bore the two fish _ the only ones we killed on the entire
trip _ back to camp. I baked the bass, Ruth made an almond and
butter sauce for it, and we served it with white rice, freeze-dried
green peas and a salad. The salmon was eaten raw in thin slices
with pickled ginger, wasabi mustard and crackers and the last of
our wine, a triumphant repast, albeit no banquet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0167 &Cx1f; taf-z
