A0168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDPORN-TIPS-COX     06-27 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDPORN-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET SAFETY TIPS FOR PARENTS
 &HT;    Staff Report
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tips for parents:
</P>
<P>
   _ Never allow children to have computers in their rooms or any
part of the house where they could have unsupervised access to the
Internet. Keep the computer in a public area of the home and make
unannounced checks to see what your children are doing on-line.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use services provided by your Internet Service Provider or
commercially available software to block access to chat rooms or
inappropriate sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Instruct your children to never give out identifying
information such as name, address, telephone number or school name
in a public message forum such as a chat room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage your children not to respond to any messages or
bulletin boards that are suggestive, obscene, belligerent,
threatening, or that make them feel uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stress to your children that the 12- or 13-year-old girl or
boy they think they may be chatting with on-line may actually be an
adult. Pedophiles often compile profiles of children before
recruiting them to become victims.
</P>
<P>
   _ Advise your children not to upload photographs of themselves
to anyone they do not know personally. They may be providing those
photographs to a pedophile.
</P>
<P>
   _ Your children should be instructed to never download
photographs from anyone they do not personally know. They could be
receiving pornography.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stress to your children the dangers of arranging face-to-face
meetings with someone they have met on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sources: FBI; the National Center for Missing and Exploited
Children
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
