<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDPORN28-COX     06-27 1664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDPORN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet spreading child porn, investigators say
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Federal investigators say it was not unusual for
25-year-old Stephen Parrish of Atlanta to spend six hours a day in
front of his computer, cruising the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike most people who use the Internet for research or
legitimate entertainment, Parrish had a more sinister motive,
searching for child pornography and stalking young boys in teen
chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Last month in U.S. District Court in Atlanta, Parrish had his
probation revoked for a previous child pornography conviction in
Florida and was sentenced to eight years and a month in federal
prison. Prosecutors said the sentence was one of the longest in
memory for probation revocation but was justified because of
Parrish's obssession with child pornography and young boys.
</P>
<P>
   That type of on-line obssession is not unusual for pedophiles
and some child molesters, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen people who spend 12 to 18 hours a day on their
computers doing this. They hardly have time to eat or sleep,'' said
Gene Weinschenk, director of the Cyberspace Smuggling Center for
the U.S. Customs Service in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish is among what federal officials believe is a growing
number of people, mostly male, who are using their computers to
collect and distribute child pornography and to cruise numerous
unmonitored chat rooms in search of potential underage sex
partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of a dirty old man in a trenchcoat hanging out by the
school yard, now you have dirty old men on the computer,'' said Pat
Johnson, supervisory special agent in charge of Crimes Against
Children investigations in the FBI's Atlanta office.
</P>
<P>
   The ``dirty old men'' have turned out to be pillars of the
community in some instances.
</P>
<P>
   _ The former city manager of Camilla, Ga., and his wife were
sentenced to 50 years in prison earlier this month after pleading
guilty to molesting the woman's two children. Investigators say the
couple had sex with the two teenage boys, photographed the acts and
distributed the photos and videos on the Internet while collecting
thousands of other images of child pornography on their computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ An Alpharetta father of five and youth-league baseball coach
pleaded guilty in May to transporting, distributing and possessing
child pornography. He was arrested on his way to St. Louis to meet
who he believed was a 13-year-old girl he had courted on the
Internet. The girl turned out to be an adult police officer who was
part of a sting operation.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Lafayette, La., a former Boy Scout leader and his one-time
roommate were each sentenced to 19 years and seven months in prison
for sexually exploiting children and producing child pornography.
Investigators found more than 1,800 images of child pornography on
computer equipment used by the men.
</P>
<P>
   _ Since January, customs officials say, they have arrested a
minister, a church choir leader, a pediatrician and the former head
of the child abuse unit of the New Orleans Police Dept., all on
child pornography charges and all involving use of computers.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent Kenneth Lanning, who specializes in cases involving
the sexual victimization of children for the bureau's Behavioral
Science Unit in Quantico, Va., said customs had virtually wiped out
importation of child pornography by the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the advent of high-speed modems and computers made child
porn easily accessible from anywhere in the world,'' Lanning said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also has enabled pedophiles and child molesters to
more easily communicate with others like themselves, Lanning said.
``They spend a lot of time on-line with people who are like them in
an effort to validate their own behavior and feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials say the surge in use of personal computers is
directly linked to a marked increase in their arrests for kiddie
smut. In fiscal year 1995 Customs recorded 48 arrests for child
pornography. The following year that number doubled to 96 and in
1997 it jumped again to 136. As of April 1, 1998, Customs had
recorded 104 child porn arrests.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the problem, the FBI set up an anti-child porn
unit called ``Innocent Images'' that Johnson says is ``the most
overt undercover operation in the country.'' Originally started in
1993 as an investigation into a missing 10-year-old Baltimore boy,
agents soon learned that a number of children in their area had
been sexually exploited over a period of time and that computers
were routinely being used to transmit images of child pornography
involving them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (investigation) gave rise to the fact that this was a
national problem. Until that time we had no idea about the scope
and magnitude of the problem,'' said FBI agent Pete Gulotta, a
former member of the Innocent Images squad.
</P>
<P>
   Innocent Images is now a nationwide undercover operation that
attempts to identify individuals who use computers to recruit
underage sex partners and those who distribute child pornography on
a large scale. The operation has become something of a
clearinghouse and repository for the FBI on child pornography and
child molesters who cross state lines to find their victims, known
to investigators as travellers.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception Innocent Images has obtained 181 arrests,
176 indictments, and 201 convictions (some individuals were
convicted of multiple offenses).
</P>
<P>
   Convicting pedophiles and child pornographers is usually not
difficult because many keep large collections and meticulous
records, according to Janice Jenkins, an assistant U.S. attorney
who prosecutes child porn cases in the Northern District of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the cases plead out because usually there is just so
much evidence,'' said Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   In one case prosecuted by Jenkins she said a doctor was caught
when he inadvertently left his computer on with a screen-saver that
showed two young boys having sex. His maid saw it and called
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``For these people it's not a matter of thinking; it's a matter
of need,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   What investigators and sex therapists are still trying to
determine is whether the Internet is prompting the seeming
explosion of child pornography or merely making it easier to get to
the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``This problem became more apparent as the Internet grew,'' said
Larry Faust, spokesman for the FBI's Baltimore office and Innocent
Images. ``It isn't necessarily growing. It's always been there.
We're just discovering the magnitude of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Strickland, a psychotherapist at the Highland Institutue
for Behavioral Change in Atlanta who treats pedophiles and other
sex offenders, said ``we're definitely seeing more people in
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   She attributes part of that to the FBI's interest and ability in
tracking down pedophiles who use their computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people they are going to catch are the obsessive
pedophiles who spend a lot of time on the Internet looking for
pictures or in chat rooms. That's their interest. That's their
arousal,'' Strickland said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Strickland said child molesters usually do not spend
as much time on the Internet as those who collect porn, there are
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more horrific cases on record, FBI officials say
that in 1996 they broke up the U.S. portion of a child porn ring in
which members linked their computers so they could watch children
being molested on-line. What was known as the Orchid Club allegedly
had members in nine states and four countries. The members
exchanged still pictures and videos of child pornography that
included real-time molestation of several children 10 and younger.
Sixteen people were indicted and three men are now serving federal
terms ranging from 30 to 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more insidious aspects of computer technology and its
relation to child pornography is a technique called morphing. Those
familiar with the technique can download photographs of innocent
children from an individual's home page about his family and morph
them into sexually explicit photographs that are then widely
distributed on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials and investigators believe they are
only seeing a small portion of the problem with the Internet and
the computer age.
</P>
<P>
   Beryl Hedrick, an inspector who specializes in child pornography
for the U.S. Postal Service said that he has ``600 active cases
available for investigation at any one time'' in the region he
covers, which is Alabama, Georgia and the Panhandle of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am buried with investigations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hedrick estimates there are ``3,000-4,000 targets for potential
investigations of child pornography principally through the mail''
in his southeast region. ``It would be much, much higher if you
added computer cases. It's phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   In March the Atlanta FBI office put one agent full-time on cases
involving crimes against children, which includes sexual
exploitation and pornography. There have already been three
convictions with 13 cases still being investigated as a result of
increased emphasis on the problem, according to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a week goes by that I don't get several tips,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is now considering legislation that would toughen
penalties for those who use their computers to lure kids into
having sex. Passed earlier this month in the House 416-0, the bill
would make it a federal crime to send obscene materials to minors,
possess even a single image of child pornography or to simply make
contact with anyone under 18 for the purpose of engaging in sexual
activity.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators and sex therapists are not sure it will be
enough for a situation that seems to be perilously close to
spinning out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely a lot more of it out there than anybody
thought,'' Weinschenk said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
