<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KATZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOB KATZ, 93, SOCIAL HISTORIAN OF THE JEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Professor Jacob Katz, an internationally known authority on the
history of the Jewish people, died May 20 in Hadassah Hospital in
Jerusalem. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, who was born in Hungary, joined the faculty of Hebrew
University, in Jerusalem, in 1950 and went on to hold its Bella and
Israel Unterberg Memorial Chair of Jewish Social and Educational
History. From 1969 to 1972, when he retired from the university, he
was its chief academic officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of this century's greatest and most influential
historians of the Jews,'' said Yosef Hayim Yerushalmi, a professor
of Jewish history, culture and society at Columbia University.
Yerushalmi, who is also the director of Columbia's Center for
Israel and Jewish Studies, said: ``His work, always innovative, was
of incredibly wide scope, ranging freely through medieval and
modern times. No one working in Jewish history or interested in it
can ignore what he achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz, an Orthodox Jew, has been called a pioneer in applying
social science methods to the writing of Jewish history. As a
social historian, he drew on his command of Talmudic and rabbinic
sources and also used what has been called a critical openness.
</P>
<P>
   His book ``Exclusiveness and Tolerance: Studies in
Jewish-Gentile Relations in Medieval and Modern Times'' (1961,
Behrman) has been applauded for its openness in speaking of all
aspects of that relationship, including tolerance and intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   He has also been called an innovator in writing about the
history of the traditional Jewish law in terms of the relationship
between social realities, including political and economic
developments, and the development of the law.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and 1970s he was a visiting professor at Harvard,
Columbia and Brandeis Universities. He was also a member of the
American Academy of Arts and Sciences. Several of his books remain
in print in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, who was born in Magyargencs, Hungary, pursued religious
studies and was ordained a rabbi. He went to Germany and received a
doctorate in social history from the University of Frankfurt in
1934. He settled in Palestine in 1936 and was a secondary school
teacher and administrator before he began teaching at Hebrew
University.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 62 years, the former Gerti
Birnbaum; three sons, David of Ashkelon, Israel, and Chanan and
Uriel, both of Jerusalem, and 11 grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
