<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0173 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRES-VACATIONERS-COX     06-27 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-VACATIONERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida officials fear smoke will choke tourism
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The headlines and television pictures tell
the story: Thousands of acres of Florida woodlands are ablaze,
blanketing huge areas with choking smoke and sending walls of fire
sometimes to the outskirts of developed areas.
</P>
<P>
   But with the lucrative July Fourth weekend approaching, Florida
tourism officials worry that the news coverage isn't telling the
complete story: Much of the state, including beaches, theme parks
and other attractions, has been largely untouched by the crisis,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drivers may experience temporary closures along some Florida
roadways due to limited visibility from forest fires,'' said Bud
Nocera, chief of Visit Florida, the state's tourism promotion
agency. ``But area attractions, beaches, golf courses and hotels
are still open for visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   While visitors won't have to run for their lives to escape a
fire, the smoke could inconvenience their vacation. And if they
plan to bring elderly family members, children or people with heart
or respiratory problems on their trip, they should call ahead to
see if visiting areas are affected by the fires.
</P>
<P>
   The brush fires have occurred primarily in the state's northeast
corner from Jacksonville to Daytona Beach. In places, including
some of Florida's most popular beaches, the smoke has been thick
enough at times to burn throats and eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Atlantans is that one of their favorite
stretches of Florida beach, the Panhandle, has escaped the worst of
the fires and smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news, especially for stock-car racing fans, is that
Volusia County, home of Daytona Beach International Speedway and
the Pepsi 400 race scheduled for July 4, has been one of the
hardest-hit places.
</P>
<P>
   However, the popular race is still on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race fans should come on down,'' said John Story, the
speedway's chief spokesman. ``We haven't considered changing the
schedule in any way, shape or form. It has been smoky every
morning, but the winds shift in the afternoon and it blows away.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Panhandle, the nearest fire to Panama City was in Gulf
County, 40 miles to the east. That fire doesn't threaten the
beaches of Cape San Blas or St. George Island, both popular with
Atlanta residents, although it has sent some smoke over the beaches
at times, returning visitors have reported.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, Florida's most popular vacation destination _
Walt Disney World_ has also been largely unaffected by the fires.
Orlando has been hit by smoke at times in the past week, however,
with a thick haze blown over from the Volusia County fires, about
50 miles to the northeast. The city has also had elevated ozone
levels due largely to the heat and smog from cars.
</P>
<P>
   What Florida visitors may miss is getting to shoot off their own
fireworks for July Fourth. Gov. Lawton Chiles has banned all
personal fireworks because of the high fire danger. But July Fourth
revelers may still be able to see public displays; the ban exempts
licensed, organized exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Daytona Beach, the speedway, St. George Island and
Panama City Beach all plan to have their fireworks displays. At
least one meteorologist believes fire-dousing rain is on its
way.``We are seeing the end of the dry cycle,'' Eric Swartz, a
forecaster for the South Florida Water Management District, told
The Orlando Sentinel. ``For the past week, we have been seeing
thunderstorms over the southern two-thirds of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   By then end of the week, more than 160,000 acres had burned and
every Florida county but one _ Monroe, home of the Keys _ had been
hit by at least one fire. Some 100 structures have burned, one
person has died and 30 people have been injured.
</P>
<P>
   The fires have been limited mostly to rural areas. Flames neared
the small town of Waldo near Gainesville and licked the outskirts
of Jacksonville, but haven't directly threatened any major urban
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Sections of I-10 and I-95, along with numerous state and county
highways, have been closed at times, mostly because of smoke
obscuring the roadways.
</P>
<P>
   However, motorists needn't worry they will suddenly drive into a
wall of fire: Fires near roadways have been reported almost
instantly, and troopers are usually on the scene within minutes,
redirecting traffic if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the fires are not frightening walls of flame.
Most are knee-high lines of burning brush. Sometimes the flames
reach into the canopies of trees, but more often they stay low,
spreading along the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem for most visitors and residents has been
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Three Florida counties _ Duval, St. Johns and Volusia _ have
issued warnings advising the elderly, children and people with
heart or respiratory problems to stay indoors, said Bill Parizek of
the state health department.
</P>
<P>
   The smoke has been bad enough to send some tourists packing,
some for health reasons, others out of exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awful,'' said Lily Ruegger, of Spartanburg, S.C., who
left Daytona Beach after one night and headed for Hilton Head,
S.C., to complete her family's vacation. ``It's a beautiful beach
but this smoke is so bad I couldn't sleep last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Sewell of Demorest, Ga., had the same experience. Her two
grandchildren have asthma, and 4-year-old Macy was awakened in
their motel room with a deep hacking cough after smoke crept
through the air-conditioning unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame anybody, it's just happenstance,'' Sewell
said. ``We're going to drive up the coast to Savannah or Myrtle
Beach. We have to get these girls near the ocean. They want to
swim.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, weren't bothered by the smoke enough to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be much nicer without it, but it will clear out this
afternoon and it will be just like there's no smoke around,'' said
Jim Overstreet of Lilburn, who was vacationing at Daytona Beach
with his family. ``It blows away and it's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach hoteliers rely on the July Fourth weekend as one
of their biggest summer events, and most report they are completely
booked. A few, though, have started getting some cancellations, and
some have noticed a drop-off in walk-in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not getting any walk-ins,'' said Chelsea Kim, whose
family owns the Bermuda Villas. ``We've also had a few guests leave
early, but most stay once they see the smoke usually blows away in
the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean Baxter, manager of the nine-unit Sierra Suites on Daytona
Beach, had one family leave early because of the smoke, and has had
two cancellations. ``It's definitely going to have an impact on our
business unless we get some rain,'' she said. ``But I believe the
die-hard race fans will come anyway, whether they can breathe or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
