<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LEGISLATION-3TAKES     06-27 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGISLATION-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR ACTIONS OF NEW YORK LEGISLATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA and RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The 221st session of the New York state
Legislature ground to a close at 6:02 p.m. on June 19, not with the
usual lofty declarations of achievement and unity, but with a
general acknowledgment by lawmakers that in an election year of
partisan attacks and personal animus, many important issues were
left unaddressed.
</P>
<P>
   There were, in essence, two sessions. The first began with
modest agendas but fairly high hopes, and culminated in April along
with the Legislature's budget negotiations, conducted in public for
the first time, and the earliest passage of a budget in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Gov. George Pataki's broad budget vetoes, which kicked
off the second session, one of anger, recrimination and inaction.
</P>
<P>
   Irate lawmakers, primarily Democrats, denied Pataki, a
Republican, nearly all of his agenda for the year, including
restructuring of the court system, tougher criminal-justice laws,
and charter schools. But the Democrats, too, were denied in their
quest for more money for school construction and child care, and
control over changes in the electric power industry.
</P>
<P>
   After a bitter internal fight, the Democrats who control the
Assembly agreed to mandatory reporting of people infected by the
virus that causes AIDS and notification of their partners,
something the Republicans had long sought and the Democrats had
long resisted. And for the second year in a row, a constitutional
amendment to allow casino gambling, supported by Pataki, died in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In the last days of the session, several bills of broad
importance were agreed on, including inspection of commercial
trucks to reduce air pollution and the creation of an independent
panel to arbitrate policyholders' disputes with health insurers
when they are denied coverage for certain treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In the Assembly, 2,245 bills were introduced, the fewest since
1944, and 1,574 were passed. In the Senate, 1,938 bills were
introduced, also the fewest since 1944, and 1,394 were passed.
</P>
<P>
   Just 671 bills passed both houses, the fewest in at least 88
years. Of those, the governor has signed 111 into law and vetoed
one, and the remaining 559 await his action.
</P>
<P>
   The following were the major actions of the session:
</P>
<P>
   The Budget
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in history, the Senate and Assembly
negotiated much of the state budget publicly, in conference
committees involving dozens of legislators, rather than in secret
meetings among the two legislative leaders and the governor.
</P>
<P>
   A $2 billion surplus, and the relative simplicity of having two
sides to the negotiations rather than three, resulted in passage of
a budget by both houses on April 14, just two weeks after the start
of the fiscal year. Legislators said they were generally pleased by
the process, and hoped it would become the norm.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki gave lawmakers a rude surprise, vetoing 1,300 items
in the budget, eliminating $760 million in 1998-99 spending and
cutting $840 million in borrowing for projects, many of them in
future years.
</P>
<P>
   He did not veto any of the $743 million a year in tax cuts the
Legislature passed, many of them for business.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in particular took the vetoes as a declaration of war.
One of the items the governor cut, a $500 million increase in
spending on school construction and repair, was their top priority
for the year. Another program he eliminated, $77 million to raise
the salaries of teachers in urban areas, was a favorite of the
teachers' unions, which are among the Democrats' leading allies. In
the last days of the session, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver sued
the governor, challenging the legality of many of the vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   But even after the vetoes, the budget, at $71.4 billion, was 8.2
percent larger than the previous year's, reflecting the surge in
tax revenue driven by the stock-market boom.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most generous increases were for education, as Pataki
reversed his earlier attempts to cut school spending. The budget
included an $850 million increase in basic school aid, the largest
ever, to more than $11 billion, and a $100 million increase in
school construction spending, to $858 million.
</P>
<P>
   It also included the first year of a $3 billion capital program
for the State University and City University of New York, increases
in operating aid for the two systems, and tuition aid to low-income
college students.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since he took office, Pataki did not try to
make serious cuts in Medicaid, the biggest portion of the budget,
at more than $28 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Government and Ethics
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would provide $87 million to help Yonkers comply with federal
court orders to desegregate housing and schools.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have required computerization of city and county
campaign-finance records statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Lowers the top corporate income tax rate to 7.5 percent from 9
percent. Savings: $230 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Lowers several taxes on small businesses. Savings: $131 million.
</P>
<P>
   Expands tax credits for securities industry investments in
technology, like computers. Savings: $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Accelerates scheduled property tax reductions for the low-income
elderly. Savings: $1.1 billion over three years.
</P>
<P>
   Raises the income limit for the child-care tax credit to $50,000
per family, from $35,000. Savings: $50 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Establishes two weeks free of sales taxes on clothes and shoes
costing up to $500 per item, in September and January, and broadens
a permanent sales tax exemption for clothes, scheduled to take
effect Dec. 1, 1999. Savings: $105 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Lowers auto-registration fees by 25 percent, to an average of
$40 every two years. Savings: $66 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Accelerates a scheduled reduction intaxes on health-care
services. Savings: $193 million over three years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would adjust New York City property-tax formulas to prevent an
automatic increase of up to 5 percent for 700,000 homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Would protect people from liability for the tax debts of their
former spouses.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have provided a state tax credit for family medical
savings accounts that qualify for a federal exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Crime and Justice
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have taken the first step toward amending the state
Constitution to streamline the state's court system by merging
several courts.
</P>
<P>
   Would have abolished discretionary parole for all violent
felons, requiring them to serve at least 85 percent of their
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed people convicted of drug crimes to be
sentenced to residential drug treatment centers, rather than
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required prison inmates to take part in educational
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Would have increased penalties for juveniles who commit violent
crimes, and lowered the age at which they could be tried as adults
for certain crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Would have broadened the definition of rape to make it easier to
prosecute cases of date rape and instances when physical force was
not used. Would also have given prosecutors the power to appeal
rulings in sexual assault cases, and allowed prosecutors in such
cases to introduce evidence of prior sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Would have lowered the blood alcohol threshold for drunken
driving to 0.08 percent from 0.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Would have outlawed discrimination on the basis of sexual
orientation in employment, housing, credit and other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Would have imposed longer prison terms for crimes motivated in
part by the victim's race, ethnicity, religion, age, sex or sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Would have imposed criminal penalties for operating a train
under the influence of alcohol or drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed someone who obtained a license to carry a
concealed weapon in another part of the state to carry the weapon
in New York City as well, rather than requiring that a separate
license be obtained from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Education
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would change New York City community school board elections from
paper ballots to electronic voting, and would eliminate the complex
``weighted'' voting system.
</P>
<P>
   Would eliminate the right of New York City community school
boards to override district superintendents' disciplinary actions
against employees.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have permitted the formation of charter schools, public
schools that operate largely outside the control of the usual local
school authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Banking and Insurance
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would extend the law allowing state-chartered banks to enjoy the
same powers as federally chartered banks, like the ability to sell
stock and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Would encourage insurance companies to cooperate with an
international commission on resolving claims of Holocaust
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Would extend the law allowing companies to raise or lower auto
insurance premiums up to 7 percent without prior approval of the
Insurance Department.
</P>
<P>
   Would extend the law allowing companies to drop up to 2 percent
of their auto-insurance customers each year.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed mutual insurance companies to sell stock
without turning over most of it to policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   Would have extended the law allowing companies to offer
auto-insurance policies under which covered injuries would have to
be treated through a managed-care company.
</P>
<P>
   Would have put restrictions on auto insurers' profits, and
created a position of consumer advocate, who would argue against
rate increases before the state Insurance Department.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare and Families
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Establishes the third Sunday in June as Children's Day.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would provide $45.7 million to build 500 to 600 apartments for
mentally ill homeless people in the coming year in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Would extend a landmark program that requires the state to close
costly and outdated psychiatric hospitals and to use the savings to
expand a broad range of community mental health programs.
</P>
<P>
   Would require state officials to track the number of adults
accompanied by children who are denied access to domestic violence
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have disqualified entire families from receiving welfare
benefits if the head of the household refused to accept a job
assignment or comply with other welfare requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed state welfare officials to match the
fingerprints of welfare recipients against those of criminals to
insure that certain felons do not receive any welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed children to testify via closed-circuit
television, rather than in court, in trials involving murder and
attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   Would have expanded the availability of child care for
low-income families and welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Would have increased penalties for noncustodial parents who
kidnap a child from the custodial parent.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed welfare recipients to own a car worth up to
$18,000, rather than $4,000, without losing benefits. Environment
and Energy
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Allows five towns on the East End of Long Island to levy a 2
percent tax on real estate sales, with the proceeds to be used to
preserve open space.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would provide additional time for public review and comment
before a utility enacts a minor rate change.
</P>
<P>
   Would require that an environmental impact statement be
developed before a waste transfer station is built at the Eastern
District terminal station in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Would require diesel-powered trucks to undergo an annual
emissions inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Would extend a program that provides low-interest loans to
localities that improve their water supply systems.
</P>
<P>
   Would provide $40,000 for the reintroduction of otters to rivers
in western New York State.
</P>
<P>
   Would create a park along the Hudson River in Manhattan from
Battery Park to 59th Street.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have required a statewide 25 percent reduction in electric
rates within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required that consumers be given a choice of electric
energy providers.
</P>
<P>
   Would have begun the process of changing the state Constitution
to establish elections for the state Public Service Commission,
which regulates utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Would have restructured the state's electric utility industry.
</P>
<P>
   Would have prohibited the New York State Power Authority from
acquiring nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Would have established a map to track cancer clusters across the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Would have prohibited burning household waste in the open.
</P>
<P>
   Would have prohibited the sale of any product that contained
more than 30 percent of the pesticide DEET.
</P>
<P>
   Would have imposed stricter penalties for removing trees or
disposing of waste on state-owned lands.
</P>
<P>
   Would have established lower utility rates for low-income people
and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Would have authorized local governments to regulate the
commercial application of pesticides on lawns.
</P>
<P>
   Health Care
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Accelerates the elimination of a gross receipts tax on hospitals
and other health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would expand a program that provides health care for poor
children up to age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Would establish a system for having independent review boards
resolve disputes between health-maintenance organizations and their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Would require the reporting of the names of people with HIV to
the state, and the notification of their sexual partners.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have held health-maintenance organizations liable for the
injuries or deaths of their clients as a result of the insurers'
refusal to provide necessary medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Would have increased penalties for selling cigarettes and
tobacco products to minors.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed a person whose employer is changing medical
insurers to continue seeing his primary doctor for up to a year,
even if that doctor is not a member of the new insurer's network.
</P>
<P>
   Would have given people who are victims of medical malpractice
one year from the date of the discovery of the problem to take
legal action against their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required insurers to cover the cost of
contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required health-maintenance organizations serving
Medicaid recipients to provide family-planning services.
</P>
<P>
   Would have made it more difficult for hospitals that merge to
eliminate their family planning services.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required children to be immunized for chickenpox
before being permitted to enroll in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Would have expanded a program that provides hearing, speech and
physical therapy for children up to 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Affairs
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Extends to June 1999 a state law that bars ticket scalping
within 1,000 feet of the event.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would prohibit retailers who provide discounts to elderly people
from discontinuing those discounts during a sale day unless advance
notice is provided in an advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Would prohibit sweepstakes operators from attempting to get
authorization from entrants to change their long-distance telephone
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Would prohibit telemarketers from blocking caller-identification
information.
</P>
<P>
   Would require retailers of swimming pools to inform customers of
the additional costs they might face to comply with state safety
requirements, such as erecting a fence.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have imposed a $1,000 fine on car-rental companies that
refuse to rent a car to people because of the neighborhood they
live in.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required sellers of weight-loss products to inform
customers of the medical risks that may result from losing weight
too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required store owners to post a sign warning
consumers of the dangers of not washing bagged salads and other
produce.
</P>
<P>
   Would have given new members of a health club seven days to
cancel their membership.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed anyone to obtain free, from a credit
reporting agency, a copy of their own credit report, once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Compensates dairy farmers in upstate New York for any losses
they suffered during January's ice storm.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would require the state Urban Development Corporation to provide
financial assistance to homeowners, business owners and farmers who
suffered financial losses during severe storms in six upstate
counties this year.
</P>
<P>
   Would extend the period in which farmers must repay loans under
the Farmworker Housing Project Loan Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Would increase fines for the illegal transportation of horses.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have imposed penalties on retailers who sell perishable
foods with altered expiration dates.
</P>
<P>
   Would have increased fines for merchants found guilty of food
safety violations.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed inspection of trains, cars, planes and buses
used to transport food.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed New York dairy farmers to join a regional
dairy group that is permitted to set milk prices higher than those
normally permitted under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Business and Labor
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would provide the largest increase ever in pension benefits for
more than 300,000 current and retired state employees.
</P>
<P>
   Would require the state to keep confidential any information it
collects from people for the purposes of providing unemployment
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have provided a cost-of-living increase for mental health
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Would have moved jurisdiction for labor disputes between New
York City and the police union from a city office to a state agency
that could be expected to offer more generous settlements than the
city does.
</P>
<P>
   Would have increased the state's minimum wage to $5.15 an hour
from $4.25.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required employers to allow workers to take time off
to attend school-related conferences when such conferences cannot
be scheduled around their regular work hours.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed employees to use their sick days to attend to
sick children or parents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
