</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ROLLERCOASTER-MISHAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLER COASTER MISHAP AT NEW JERSEY AMUSEMENT PARK INJURES 13 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ANDREA KANNAPELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILDWOOD, N.J. _ A roller coaster at a Jersey Shore amusement
park broke an axle Friday night, injuring 13 people who were jarred
when the ride came to an abrupt halt.
</P>
<P>
   The ride's owner, the Morey Organization, said it had called in
outside experts to try to determine what happened. The State
Department of Community Affairs, which is responsible for
inspecting rides, is also investigating the incident, which
occurred at Mariner's Landing, a cluster of rides on a pier along
the boardwalk in the Wildwoods.
</P>
<P>
   The roller coaster, known as the Sea Serpent, backs a chain of
cars up a steep incline and then releases them. The cars zoom down
and then whip around two vertical loops, running out of momentum on
an incline that parallels the first. The cars inch up the remainder
of the incline and are then released to run the course in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first serious amusement park incident in the region
this year. Safety concerns have grown following a scattering of
incidents, including a drowning at a New Jersey water park and
injuries to two children riding roller coasters at Jersey Shore
parks last summer.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey altered its inspection system earlier this year,
giving responsibility to the Department of Community Affairs. The
state also raised fines for amusement park operators and
established fines for patrons who do not follow operators'
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred about 9 p.m. Friday after a brief
thunderstorm. The ride was halfway through, with the cars beginning
their reverse run, when the axle broke and the ride screeched to a
halt. Patrons were sitting upright in the cars at the time.
</P>
<P>
   One witness, Louann Zinsmeister of Harrisburg, Pa., said she was
on the pier with her two children. ``There was a loud, loud noise,
like thunder,'' she said. A chunk of the last car flew off, and Ms.
Zinsmeister saw sparks flying as the last car scraped along the
metal track.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven patrons were treated for bumps and bruises at Burdette
Tomlin Memorial Hospital and released; two others were held
overnight for observation. The hospital identified them only as a
19-year-old man in good condition and a 17-year-old girl in fair
condition. Will Morey, the head of the Morey Organization, said
finding out what happened and why was a priority. ``We all put our
families on these rides,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
