A0181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-AMATEUR-DRAFT-467     06-27 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AMATEUR-DRAFT-467(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PICK WELL-ROUNDED ATHLETE FIRST IN NHL DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The Rangers' first-round pick Saturday in the
NHL's entry draft, Manny Malhotra, is a 6-foot-1-inch, 210-pound
center who scouts say has skating speed, puckhandling skills and
leadership potential and who can play defense as well as offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to be a leader; I never really try to take
a back seat to anybody,'' Malhotra said. ``It was always a dream to
play in the National Hockey League, just like the big guys on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Right after being named the seventh overall pick in the draft at
Marine Midland Arena here, Malhotra, 18, talked to Ranger fans at
Madison Square Garden by conference call. ``A few thousand fans
there,'' Malhotra said, referring to the Garden. ``I already like
the sound of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra's background may be as interesting as his hockey
skills. His father is a former table tennis champion from India,
while his mother, a French-Canadian from Quebec, runs a Roman
Catholic prayer ministry from the family home in suburban Toronto.
Both hold doctoral degrees in chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Their son, who plays for the Guelph Storm of the Ontario Hockey
League, was voted the league's scholastic player of the year last
season. He is bilingual, biracial and seems to exude charisma.
Malhotra's agent is Bobby Orr. Dave Branch, commissioner of junior
hockey in Canada, is one of several hockey authorities who gushed
about Malhotra Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the finest young men I've ever been around,''
Branch said. ``This is a very special young person. Manny is just
an unbelievable kid. He is sensitive and humble. And he is a
big-time hockey player.''
</P>
<P>
   In 57 games with the Storm, Malhotra scored 16 goals and had 35
assists. According to the NHL's Central Scouting Bureau report,
Malhotra ``is not an established scorer'' but is ``always an
offensive force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An excellent two-way player,'' the report concludes, ``with
excellent work ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra's mother, Lise Malhotra, standing at the back of the
news conference where her son was introduced, said she was proud of
the scholastic honors of the youngest of her four children. ``He
always did his studies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, choosing ninth on the first round, took Michael
Rupp, a 6-5 left wing from Erie of the Ontario League. Born in
Cleveland, Rupp, 18, is said to be ``a strong skater with good,
straight-ahead speed,'' the central scouting report said. Rupp is
listed as weighing 218 pounds, but he said today: ``I'm pushing
230. I don't think I'm going to get any taller, but I'm going to be
getting bigger. I do have a long way to go, but no reason I can't
handle it. I plan on being a power forward in the NHL someday.'' In
64 games last season, he had 16 goals and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were scheduled to chose 26th overall later Saturday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had hoped to trade up in the draft for a higher
selection, but were unable to make a deal. After Tampa Bay took
Vincent Lecavalier from Rimouski of the Quebec League with the
first pick, the expansion Nashville Predators traded picks with San
Jose, moving up from third to second.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville took David Legwand, an American-born center from the
Plymouth, Mich., team of the Ontario League. The Sharks took
defenseman David Stuart from Regina of the Western League with the
third pick. After Vancouver, picking fourth, chose defenseman Bryan
Allen of Oshawa in the Ontario League, the Anaheim Mighty Ducks
surprised the gathering by choosing Vitaly Vishnevsky, a defenseman
from Ukraine who played in Russia for Yaroslavl. He was the first
European chosen and was not rated that highly by most North
American observers. When Calgary, picking sixth, took Rico Fata of
the London Knights in the Ontario League, the Rangers had the next
pick and activity suddenly picked up around their table. Neil
Smith, the president and general manager, got on the telephone.
John Muckler, the coach, stood up and began speaking assertively.
While the fans booed, Commissioner Gary Bettman first warned the
Rangers that they were running out of time, then announced a
timeout and charged it to them.
</P>
<P>
   When Smith approached the stage to announce the decision, he
appeared to exchange a few words with Bettman. Rangers spokesman
John Rosasco said that Colorado general manager Pierre Lacroix
tried to get the Rangers to trade their pick but the Rangers
refused. Rosasco said the Rangers wanted to trade with Anaheim and
get the fifth pick because they rated Malhotra that highly and
feared he would be taken before they got their chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
