</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBIA-UNIV-GIFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATION TO SCHOOL AT COLUMBIA SETS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Columbia University's School of Public Health will
announce this week that the Mailman Foundation is giving it $33
million, the largest donation ever to a school of public health.
</P>
<P>
   The school will be named in honor of Joseph L. Mailman, a
founder of Mailman Corp., one of the earliest conglomerates in
North America. He died in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The school, one of 27 schools of public health in the United
States and the only one in New York City, has about 600 students in
master's and doctoral programs, an annual budget of about $50
million and an endowment of about $24 million. It plans to use the
money for faculty salaries, financial aid for students, and
research into areas like AIDS, cancer, women's reproductive health
and health care for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, a relatively small organization consisting of
four family members and no staff, has assets of less than $50
million. The family _ Mailman's widow, Phyllis, and their son,
daughter and grandson _ had been planning to spend $5 million to $6
million, and ended up committing so much because the school seemed
to be a perfect solution after they had considered so many
different projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an extraordinary organization,'' Jody Wolfe, their
daughter, said. ``All these pieces we liked seemed to lead back to
the same School of Public Health.''
</P>
<P>
   The gift is unusual in that neither Mailman nor any member of
his family attended Columbia. Relatives said it was the result of
an unusual search.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Mailman described it, the search began about four years
ago when the family members decided that they wanted something that
would help disadvantaged people in New York, where Mailman had
spent his life. They found that they disagreed about how to focus
their interest _ their ideas were ranging from health care and
clinics to women's issues and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   She finally called the family's lawyer, Bill Josephson at Fried,
Frank, Harris, Shriver &AMP; Jacobson. ``I'm getting older and time is
flying,'' she told him. ``If I don't do this now, it might not
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He helped put her in touch with Lionel Pincus, a venture
capitalist and vice chairman of Columbia's board of trustees, and
Columbia's vice president for health services, Herbert Pardes.
There was ``immediate rapport,'' Mrs. Mailman recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, however, the right project proved elusive. For a
year, Pardes and his staff suggested various projects, both in the
university and outside it. They all seemed attractive, but nothing
seemed quite right. ``We were about to settle on something,'' Mrs.
Mailman said, ``but we were still not really excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one day last fall, Josephson called. ``Are you sitting
down?'' he asked. During a casual conversation, Allan Rosenfield,
the dean of the School of Public Health, had suggested that the
family make a sizable gift to the school itself.
</P>
<P>
   The family was especially pleased that the school combined
public policy with hands-on treatment of people, that it was aimed
at preventing disease across whole communities, and that it
operated family health clinics in Harlem, a breast-cancer study on
Long Island, and efforts to prevent pregnancy and smoking among
teen-agers and to study health problems of refugees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
