<SLUG> BC-LA-DEM-CONVEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. COURTING DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION FOR 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- When 54 high-level Democrats come to Los Angeles
next month, they will be given a bird's-eye view of what local
officials say is the metropolis of the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter ride is just part of a celebrity-studded,
whirlwind trip around Los Angeles -- a critical step in the city's
high-stakes bid to host the Democratic National Convention in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential nomination party is politics' biggest prize, a
windfall that will give the host city unparalleled hype with the
invasion of 15,000 journalists and pump more than $137 million into
the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is facing stiff competition from six other cities,
including Boston, which hosted the convention's Site Selection
Committee for three days last week.
</P>
<P>
   Boston pulled out all the stops: Mayor Thomas Menino served a
lobster dinner, arranged an indoor fireworks show and took
committee members to a Red Sox game -- where hockey great Bobby Orr
served the drinks.
</P>
<P>
   So how is Los Angeles going to top that?
</P>
<P>
   Cocktails at Mayor Richard Riordan's private Brentwood home,
followed by dinner at the Getty Center. Hollywood limo tours. A
virtual visit to the $300 million Staples Center, which is set to
open in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And if that's not enough, a reminder that California represents
54 electoral votes. That's more than any other state and a bloc
that all but ensures that whoever wins California goes to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shouldn't be ruled out,'' said Roz Wyman, a member of the
Site Selection Committee since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Riordan pulled the city from consideration for
the party conventions because Los Angeles was consumed with
rebuilding itself from the Northridge Earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Riordan said, the city is ready, adding, ``Los Angeles has
turned around and we have a lot to be proud of and a lot to show
off.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Staples Center, the new downtown cathedral
will be near completion and work is expected to be under way on the
Disney Center performance hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic delegation's three-day visit will begin with VIP
treatment at Los Angeles International Airport. Members will be
whisked to luxurious rooms at the Biltmore Hotel downtown, where
they will find summer survival kits -- sunglasses, suntan lotion,
caps and other gear to help them manage their Los Angeles stay.
</P>
<P>
   Top city, county, state and federal officials will bend their
ears, and the host committee is trying to lure some big-name
Hollywood stars to help sell the city's assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have the glitz,'' Wyman said. ``You have to sell
your city. And you have to realize a lot of the Democratic
delegates aren't rich and many have to use their vacation time to
come, so they are looking for other attractions.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wyman, a former Los Angeles councilwoman, serves as a
member of the Site Selection Committee, she has made no secret of
her desire to see the next convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' host committee -- chaired by businessman Eli Broad
with help from David Geffen of DreamWorks SKG and a laundry list of
the city's movers and shakers -- will promote the city's major
attractions, including Olvera Street and Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said his appeal to Democratic leaders has been a practical
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last nine elections, Republicans have won six times,''
Broad said. ``The three won by Democrats were when Democrats
carried California. Fifty-four electoral votes mean a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   His second argument is equally basic: money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles and New York are the two most important cities for
donations to the party,'' Broad said. ``But a lot of us are getting
older. If the party wants to attract new donors, they have to come
out to meet with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Broad said a convention in Los Angeles would draw
more viewers in Southern California because local television
stations would be focusing on the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Broad's committee will coordinate all the activities, with the
pledge to raise $27 million for the various costs involved in
preparing and submitting a bid.
</P>
<P>
   That money is viewed as an investment designed to bring in $137
million for the city and help set its image for the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   When the delegation arrives next month, the city built on
make-believe will be asking representatives to use their
imaginations to picture Los Angeles as the city of the millennium,
the metropolis that should serve as host of the party's national
convention in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Host committee members will be talking up what will be one of
the nation's newest convention halls, the Staples Center. The
center, being built as the new home of the Los Angeles Lakers,
Kings and Clippers, is scheduled to open for the 1999 season, and
officials are confident it will meet its time line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is we have to show them we can put on a
convention in a building that isn't built,'' Wyman said. ``Staples
Center will be built, but it's not so easy showing them a model
rather than the building.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Boston, competing cities include Houston,
Philadelphia, Miami, New Orleans and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
