<HEADLINE>
HOTEL PROPOSAL LIFTS OCEANSIDE'S SAGGING IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By KEVIN BRASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEANSIDE, Calif. _ A proposal to build a 475-room hotel and
conference center on the waterfront is generating new interest in
this city's long-dormant hotel market.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 miles north of San Diego Bay, Oceanside is home to a
1,900-foot wooden pier, wide sandy beaches and a manmade harbor. It
is also neighbor to the country's largest Marine base, Camp
Pendleton.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 1,078 guest rooms here are motor courts catering to
military families and travelers on Route 101, which intersects
Interstate 5, the main artery between San Diego and Los Angeles, at
the northern boundary of the city and the Marine base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the perception of being a rough town,'' said Robert
Miller, a lodging industry specialist with Grubb &AMP; Ellis, the
national commercial brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Oceanside entered into an exclusive development
deal with the San Diego-based Manchester Resorts to build the hotel
and conference complex on 11.44 acres next to the city's pier. The
city owns about half the land, and Manchester is already in escrow
to buy most of the rest, contingent on the project's going forward.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for twin 12-story towers. A third tower would contain
100 apartments to be sold as time shares, which allow people to buy
a small share of a unit to be used on specific dates. The
developers have until Sept. 4 to negotiate final details with the
city, which is offering incentives such as street closures and help
in developing parking spaces and is working out special financing
inducements. The developers also want to use land the city owns to
build a new golf course a few miles from the pier site.
</P>
<P>
   Although some residents are protesting several issues, including
plans to move a city amphitheater to accommodate the new resort's
swimming pool, negotiations are moving forward in a ``positive and
expeditious manner,'' said Thomas Wilson, Oceanside's City Manager.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, a group of investors proposed 300 time-share units for
the property. The concept was approved by the California Coastal
Commission in 1992, but the units were never built.
</P>
<P>
   Later efforts to build a hotel also failed, and a portion of the
land fell into a bankruptcy proceeding. ``Financing just dried up
in the early 90s for hotels in southern California,'' said James
Watkins, one of the original partners in the unsuccessful
time-share project. ``Hotels were in real trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of San Diego County has rebounded, Oceanside has
seen little hotel activity in the coastal downtown area. Average
room rates hover in the $55-a-night range, while other coastal
areas are getting more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   The lone hotel property directly on the city's 1,000-foot
marina, the 64-unit Oceanside Marina Inn, fell into disrepair and
bankruptcy in the 80s. In 1994, the city, which owns the land, paid
$1.1 million to buy back the lease, which was due to run out in
2036.
</P>
<P>
   The city hired a management company to operate the hotel while
it spent more than $100,000 to put a new roof on the building and
repair and renovate rooms. In 1997, it signed a 10-year lease with
Radelow, Gittens Real Estate Management, a private company, to
operate the property.
</P>
<P>
   According to Larry Gittens, a partner in the management company,
the Marina Inn's occupancy rate has risen to 77 percent from 58
percent in 1994, thanks in part to a marketing campaign targeting
vacationers from inland California and Arizona. Room rates are now
about $95 a night after years in the $50 range, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To counter its image problem, Oceanside has begun a
redevelopment effort. Several buildings have been remodeled, the
pier was restored and the California Surf Museum moved into new
quarters there. The city also moved a railroad switchyard that
adjacent to the proposed hotel site. ``There was little interest in
a hotel site next to a rail switching yard,'' said Eli Sanchez, the
city's redevelopment director.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite the improvements and an overall drop in crime, the value
of lodging properties in the downtown area continues to lag the
rest of the county.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a group of local investors paid $2.25 million
for the 82-room Bridge Motor Inn, with a restaurant, overlooking
the harbor. The property had been in bankruptcy and badly in need
of renovation. The price translates to about $27,000 a room,
compared with the $75,000 often paid for properties near San
Diego's waterfront. ``Once we have more quality rooms, people will
stay in Oceanside,'' said Dr. Shantu Patel, one of the partners.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Patel and his wife, Mona, bought another 82-room inn
near the water for $1.6 million. They renovated the facility and
affiliated it with the Days Inn chain. ``Oceanside has changed for
the positive,'' Patel said. ``At one time, Oceanside was recognized
as a Marine town, but now more people are recognizing it as a beach
town.''
</P>
<P>
   To many investors, Oceanside still suffers from a stigma, said
Robert Rauch, managing director of Interbank Brener Hospitality, a
New York-based consulting company. Last year, Rauch paid $2 million
for a 50-room motel with few amenities away from the waterfront in
Leucadia, a few minutes' drive south of Oceanside.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the proposed hotel and conference center, Rauch
said: ``The Manchester property is going to have to be the driver
of change in Oceanside. I don't know who else would want to take
the risk, given the high quality of the other submarkets in the
county.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manchester project would face competition from several new
resort properties in the county, including new hotels operated by
Four Seasons and Hyatt in Carlsbad and La Jolla, respectively, both
within a 20-minute drive of this city.
</P>
<P>
   The number of hotels in the county almost doubled in the 80s.
Although occupancy rates plummeted to 63 percent in 1993, overall
occupancy now averages a healthy 76 percent, according to PKF
Consulting of Los Angeles, a lodging specialist.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern part of San Diego, hotels have been able to
build a strong corporate business, fueled by the growth in the
biotechnology and communications industries. The average occupancy
rate in the north coast area of San Diego County last year was 87
percent, and the average room rate rose more than 10 percent,
according to PKF Consulting's research.
</P>
<P>
   To survive in southern California outside the major tourist
areas hotels ``have to be within three or five miles of a
significant corporate demand generator,'' said Richard Swig,
president of RSBA &AMP; Associates, a hotel consulting concern in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Oceanside has neither a strong corporate base nor ``distinctive
shopping or a cute factor,'' Swig said.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester Resorts believe it can attract conference business to
Oceanside. Its project includes 26,000 square feet of meeting
space. The off-site golf course is part of the plan to attract
business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident we can reach that group market,'' said Richard
Gibbons, chief executive officer of Manchester Resorts. The company
developed the Hyatt Regency and the San Diego Marriott Hotel and
Marina on San Diego Bay. If the project is built correctly, it will
be able to attract steady business by inserting itself into the
rotation of annual events from hotel to hotel, Gibbons said.
</P>
<P>
   Official releases for the pier project refer to a
``Hyatt-quality'' hotel and news reports often suggest Hyatt's
involvement, but Hyatt is still not committed to the project. A
spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to lure bigger chains, the city is launching a new
marketing program targeting hotel operators and investment groups.
``If Manchester is able to build the hotel, I think Oceanside will
change,'' said Miller, the lodging specialist. ``They need
something to improve what people think of Oceanside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
