u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NEW-DEATHROW-790(2     06-27 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEW-DEATHROW-790(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRISON GUARD IS GOING BACK AS INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANNEMORA, N.Y. _ The rules that will govern Darrel Harris' life
on death row are dizzying in their detail. Awaiting his execution
at Clinton Correctional Facility here, Harris will be allowed to
read the Bible, smoke cigars and wash his hands with a 1-ounce bar
of soap. He will not be allowed to wear his own clothes, chew gum
or play a musical instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' death sentence, which jurors in his murder trial voted
for earlier this month, sent prison officials scurrying to dust off
dozens of regulations drawn up three years ago, shortly after Gov.
George Pataki reinstated the death penalty in New York.
</P>
<P>
   With Harris scheduled to arrive at Clinton after his official
sentencing on July 21, they are also putting the finishing touches
on death row itself, a block of 12 cells in a building that houses
criminals with the most severe disciplinary problems.
</P>
<P>
   As they bring death row back to life, prison officials admit
that they are feeling their way. New York has not had a condemned
inmate since 1984, when the state's highest court declared the
remaining provision of the death penalty law in effect at the time
unconstitutional. It has not put a prisoner to death since 1963,
when Eddie Lee Mays went to the electric chair in Sing Sing for
killing a woman as he robbed a bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a learning experience for everybody,'' said
William Burke, an assistant deputy superintendent who is helping
prepare for Harris' arrival. ``A lot of things will have to be
decided after we get under way.''
</P>
<P>
   New York prison officials visited Texas and several other states
to study their systems of capital punishment soon after Pataki
signed the new death penalty law, which specified execution by
lethal injection. The research helped them develop disciplinary
policies for condemned prisoners and a step-by-step instruction
manual for executions, outlining everything from the number of
witnesses to the exact mix of drugs required.
</P>
<P>
   They chose Clinton, a maximum-security prison in the
northernmost corner of the state, as the site of death row because
it has a separate building for the most troublesome inmates. There,
each of the 12 cells on death row is divided into two rooms. Three
of the cells have been renovated so that the rear room has a
shower, a visiting area and a door that opens onto a small
recreation yard, so condemned prisoners have almost no reason to
leave their cells.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials have decided that Harris will have no contact
with the nearly 2,000 other inmates at Clinton, most of whom have
been convicted of drug offenses or violent crimes. Troublesome
inmates will still be housed in the remaining 36 cells in the
separate building, but on death row, Harris will be unable to see
them.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 40, is a former prison guard in a New York City jail who
won a medal in 1987 for showing heroism during a 1986 inmate
uprising. Jim Flateau, a spokesman for the State Department of
Correctional Services, said Harris' knowledge of the prison system
made him especially dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a former corrections officer who is very well aware of
procedures, operations and the kinds of scams that inmates will try
to accomplish,'' Flateau said. ``He knows the system far better
than 99.9 percent of the offenders anywhere in the country. And
remember, you're talking about someone who has nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals process will almost certainly delay Harris'
execution for years, and could even reduce his sentence. But the
execution chamber, 200 miles south of Clinton at Green Haven
Correctional Facility in Dutchess County, is ready at a moment's
notice. Prison officials decided not to put the chamber at Clinton
because ``to have the death house and the actual execution occur
elsewhere helps to keep stress levels down,'' Flateau said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials spelled out how they would put inmates to death
in an 11-page memorandum in 1995. It lists the drugs to be injected
into the prisoner's arms: sodium pentothal, which causes
unconsciousness; Pavulon, which stops respiration, and potassium
chloride, which stops the heart. But Flateau said prison officials
would not choose or train technicians for the ``injection team''
until an execution is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It serves no purpose to do it right now,'' he said, ``because
we all know that realistically, it's going to be awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris was convicted May 19 of first-degree murder for killing
three people as he robbed a Brooklyn social club in 1996. He
remains in jail at Rikers Island until he is transported upstate.
His lawyers, some of whom work for a state agency created to defend
death row inmates, are already preparing his appeals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn district attorney's office in New York City would
challenge an appeal of the conviction, but the state attorney
general's office would handle any appeal challenging the
constitutionality of the death sentence. That office has assigned
an assistant attorney general, Diane LaVallee, a former prosecutor
in Erie County, to fight Harris' appeals full time.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dennis Vacco hired Ms. LaVallee two years ago
to lead the Capital Assistance for Prosecutors Team, which helps
county prosecutors try death penalty cases. But she has never
handled an appeal from a condemned prisoner, said Chris McKenna, a
spokesman for Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has that kind of experience here, really,'' McKenna
said. ``But we have spoken to other states about it.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenna said Vacco chose not to hire lawyers with expertise in
death penalty appeals because it would be costly, and because New
York's law was intended to prevent lengthy appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academia claims that you're going to have all these high
expenses from death penalty cases,'' McKenna said. ``But it's never
been shown. I don't know where these bloated $2 (million) or $3
million figures always come from. We have these people on staff who
are being paid whether they are doing death penalty cases or
parking-ticket cases.''
</P>
<P>
   But with three new capital cases coming to trial around the
state this summer, the costs for such cases could soon rise, as
they require more preparation than noncapital cases. The trial of
Dalkeith Williams, accused of fatally shooting his estranged wife
and her daughter in 1996 as they sat in a parked car, began this
month in Poughkeepsie. And two other capital trials are expected to
begin soon in Brooklyn and on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Correctional Services has spent $25,000 to
outfit three of the 12 cells on death row with showers and visiting
areas, and $2,500 to remove the electric chair from Green Haven and
replace it with lethal-injection equipment. The state will
eventually spend $350,000 to renovate all 48 of the cells in the
building that houses death row, improve the ventilation system and
install security cameras to monitor inmates, Flateau said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has spent $190,000 renovating the third floor of the
old hospital building at Bedford Hills Correctional Facility in
Westchester County to serve as death row for women. Three cells are
ready for use.
</P>
<P>
   Five prison guards will be assigned to watch Harris, one at a
time, in eight-hour shifts at a desk near his cell. If more than
five guards apply for the job, it will go to the men with the most
seniority. If none apply, the most recently hired guards will be
tapped, Flateau said.
</P>
<P>
   A guard supervising a cell block at Clinton this week, who would
not give his name, said nobody wanted to spend his days watching
the only condemned man in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a high-profile job, with cameras all over the place,'' he
said. ``Those guys are going to be scrutinized like crazy. No
thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a day, a guard will escort Harris to the courtyard outside
his cell, where he can exercise for an hour unless it is snowing or
raining hard. He can take a small television set for his cell, but
it must be black and white. There is a window across from his cell;
it looks out on a fence topped with razor wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he can see a patch of sky,'' said Burke, the deputy
superintendent. ``Nothing more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
