<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES 7, METS 2
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The event known as the Subway Series is becoming
something of a bust, like so many Super Bowls. It was supposed to
be competitive, it was supposed to be rollicking, it was supposed
to be something to remember. Instead, the Yankees are routing their
crosstown rivals, and the Mets are presenting little resistance.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Mets aided and abetted the Yankees on Saturday,
committing numerous defensive mistakes in an embarrassing 7-2 loss
before 53,587 fans at Shea Stadium. The Yankees will go for a
three-game sweep Sunday night, with Orlando Hernandez pitching
against Masato Yoshii, the Mets pitcher who has an 8.04 earned run
average in his last four starts.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, held out of the starting lineup in Friday's
come-from-behind win, hit a three-run homer and started another
Yankee rally with a double, helping pitcher Andy Pettitte improve
his record to 9-5. The Yankees are 9 for 16 with runners in scoring
position in this series, the Mets 2 for 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' record is now 55-19, the second-best record after
74 games in their storied history; the 1928 Yankees started 56-18.
</P>
<P>
   With their anemic offense, the Mets must pitch and catch well to
win. They do not often generate enough runs to overcome mistakes,
and they cannot afford to give away runs.
</P>
<P>
   They did that in the second inning when, with one out and the
left-handed-hitting Paul O'Neill coming to bat, the infield
shifted, with Rey Ordonez moving toward second so that he was
playing almost directly up the middle. When O'Neill hit a roller a
few feet to the first base side of second, Ordonez was perfectly
positioned, scooping the ball and throwing to first, head high.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud, his hands as good as anyone's in the league,
reached up to take the throw _ and the ball hit the webbing of his
glove and bounced away. Quite simply, he dropped the throw.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill took a lead off first, with Olerud holding him there and
Darryl Strawberry at the plate. For weeks, Strawberry had looked
forward to this series, to playing in his former kingdom, and this
was his first chance. Trying to send a ball into orbit, Strawberry
swung twice with malicious intent. After the second big swing,
Strawberry held a palm down, a warning meant only for himself: calm
down.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusting to a curveball, he slowed down his swing and pulled a
grounder through the right side, past Olerud, with O'Neill turning
at second and rambling into third. Even if you believe that Mets'
starter Bobby Jones would have pitched Strawberry the same way
whether there were runners on base or not, there is this: If Olerud
had not dropped the throw, putting O'Neill on first, he would have
been in position to field Strawberry's grounder and the inning
would have been over.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Yankees had two runners on and Martinez at the
plate. Jones threw a curveball to the Yankees' first baseman, it
hung, and Martinez lifted a line drive that barely cleared the
eight-foot fence in right field and landed in the Mets' bullpen.
Whether Yankees fans made up 20 percent of the crowd or 50 percent,
they made 100 percent of the noise at that moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets played listlessly and without much energy the rest of
the way. And adding to their misery was the news that Al Leiter,
the team's best pitcher, will miss at least six weeks and perhaps
more with a knee injury suffered in Friday night's loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
