<HEADER>
A0194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT &LR;      06-27 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURE INTO NEW YORK REAL ESTATE MARKET WITH CAUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is hardly news that the real estate market in the
New York City area is about as hot as it has been in quite a while.
And since the heat seems to be generated by the friction from
buyers bumping into one another chasing sellers, there has hardly
been a more appropriate time to apply the first rule of the open
market: ``Let the buyer beware.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People do strange things when they're under pressure,'' said
William Selsberg, a real estate lawyer in Stamford, Conn., noting
that buyers who are anxious about losing the house of their dreams
had a tendency to become careless with what might be the most
significant investment of a lifetime. ``And if you're careless,
you're probably going to get kicked.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Selsberg said, some clients have suggested in
recent months that they would be willing to waive one or more of
the common contingencies inserted into a contract of sale _ things
like home inspections, and requirements that a mortgage must be
obtained and that an existing home must be sold before the buyer is
required to complete the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them that waiving things like that can end up costing
them a fortune,'' Selsberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Waiving a home-sale contingency, for example, might seem safe
when a person buying a new home already has a signed contract to
sell the current one. Many people reason, Selsberg said, that if
the sale of their existing home falls through, they will be able to
safely exit from the contract for the purchase of the new one
because mortgage commitments themselves are generally contingent
upon the sale of an existing home.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not necessarily the case, Selsberg said, because it
can be argued quite convincingly that the mortgage contingency
clause in the buyer's contract to purchase the new home was fully
satisfied when the mortgage commitment was issued, even though the
commitment was contingent upon the sale of the buyer's existing
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That contingency is between the buyer and his lender,''
Selsberg said. ``As far as the seller is concerned, the mortgage
contingency has been met and the buyer has to go through with the
deal or lose his deposit.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Selsberg said, he has a stock answer for clients
who suggest waiving a standard contingency: ``Don't you dare do
that,'' he tells them. ``You can never skip a step.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the more common steps that buyers seem willing
to skip is the home inspection. And that can have costly
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think that if they insist on a home inspection, someone
will come and steal the house out from under them,'' said Maryann
Murphy, director of Housemaster, a nationwide home inspection
company based in Bound Brook, N.J. But an inspection by a qualified
inspector, Ms. Murphy said, can uncover problems that even
knowledgeable buyers might miss, things like water seepage, the
presence of asbestos, radon gas or lead paint or a leaking
underground oil storage tank.
</P>
<P>
   And while such problems cost a buyer money only when they are
successful in purchasing the house, there are some risks that can
occur when they are unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of available apartments decreases, particularly in
Manhattan, ``the waiving of mortgage contingencies by apartment
buyers has suddenly emerged as a widespread practice in New York
City,'' said Gordon Shanks, managing director of Home Mortgage
Acceptance Corporation, a Manhattan-based mortgage broker. ``They
know that if they don't win the bidding the first time, it might be
months before they find another apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   But waiving the mortgage contingency is generally considered
risky because the deposit can be lost if a mortgage cannot be
obtained and the buyer can't go through with the deal. But it is
possible to eliminate that risk, Shanks said, if a buyer can get a
mortgage commitment before entering into a contract of sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``These buyers apply for a mortgage and get a commitment letter
before they actually find the apartment they want to buy,'' Shanks
said. ``When they find an apartment, they can bid on it immediately
and waive the mortgage contingency.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Bader, president of Skyscraper Mortgage in Manhattan, said
that while a buyer with a commitment in hand might safely waive a
mortgage contingency, those who have only been ``prequalified'' or
``pre-approved'' should proceed with caution.
</P>
<P>
   Prequalification, Bader said, is merely an indication that a
lender is likely to grant a mortgage. That, however, is based only
upon the information provided by the prospective borrower.
Generally, he said, prequalifications do not take into
consideration significant factors like credit history, employment
history, and the special scrutiny given to income generated by
self-employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prequalification certainly isn't enough for a buyer to safely
waive a mortgage contingency,'' Bader said.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-approval, on the other hand, does provide some measure of
assurance because most factors are accounted for. But the problem
with pre-approval is that it doesn't take into consideration one
factor of great significance to a lender _ the appraised value of
the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the appraisal comes in too low, the mortgage will probably
not be approved,'' said Bader, noting that the buyer would be
paying more than the lender believed the property was worth. And
that, he said, can result in the loss of the buyer's deposit if
there is no mortgage contingency clause to provide an escape route.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Saatchi, an agent with Dayton-Halstead Real Estate in East
Hampton, N.Y., said that property owners there were addressing that
issue by agreeing to share the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers are waiving the mortgage contingency only if sellers
will guarantee the appraisal value,'' said Ms. Saatchi. ``If the
appraisal comes in too low, the buyer's lack of a mortgage
contingency doesn't matter because the seller's guarantee gives him
another out.''
</P>
<P>
   But how likely is a low appraisal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Very likely,'' said Peter Bell, chief executive of Balch
Buyers Realty, an exclusive buyer-broker in Mamaroneck, N.Y.
``There's such tremendous competition for listings now that if a
seller wants to list his house for $50,000 more than it's worth, a
broker might take the listing anyway because he knows that if he
doesn't take it, another broker will.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, Bell said, coupled with low interest rates, high
salaries, dual incomes and generous bonuses can result in purchase
prices being driven upward by what buyers can afford to pay today,
rather than what the real value of the property would be in a less
robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Davis, a Manhattan real estate lawyer, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the late 80s, people buying real estate believed that the
good times would last forever and that the market would never stop
expanding,'' he said. ``But the market contracted, and people lost
their jobs or had to move, and some of them couldn't even sell
their apartments for the outstanding balance on their mortgage.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Davis said, buyers whose dream home is appraised
for less than what they are about to pay for it should take a deep
breath and contemplate whether the low appraisal is a blessing in
disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get intoxicated with a particular piece of real
estate, you tend to make decisions that are emotional rather than
reasonable,'' he said. ``And buying real estate should always be a
function of sobriety.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
