<HEADER>
A0195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SECURITY-REAL-2TAK     06-27 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SECURITY-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDINGS WITHOUT DOORMEN UPGRADING SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOYCE COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First there were homeless people sleeping in the
vestibule. Then there was a mugging. And so the residents at 309 W.
104th St., a co-op without doormen, decided to beef up security.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago they locked the outside vestibule door as well as
the inside door, installing a buzzer on each so that visitors must
ring twice to get in. And they removed residents' names from the
outside directory, making it impossible to tell who lives in what
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sarah Conly has to explain to visitors that they must buzz
again to get through the inside door. She has to make sure they
know her apartment number. Sometimes she just sends her children
down to the lobby to wait for guests. ``I feel it has made the
building safer,'' she said. ``It makes it twice as hard to get
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the city, nondoorman buildings are upgrading their
security. No one keeps statistics, but security experts say that
changes have become increasingly common, especially over the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
   The most widespread measures are relatively simple, like the
ones taken at 309 W. 104th St. _ locking the outer door and
eliminating names from the directory or using numbers instead of
apartment designations.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a rise in the use of video surveillance systems,
especially those connected to residents' television sets.
</P>
<P>
   Doorman buildings, many of which already have monitors at the
entrance, are upgrading, too. But the most recent change for those
buildings is decidedly low-tech: locking the front door at night.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the city's lower crime rates, people are more
security-conscious than ever. Improvements have ``gone on and on
for the 35 years I've lived in New York,'' said Robert McCrie, head
of the security management program at John Jay College of Criminal
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   In nondoorman rental buildings, good security is important as a
selling point, he said. What's more, said McCrie, ``there is a
long-term trend of growing liability on the part of the building
owner, operator and manager; landlords know they have a legal
obligation to make the building secure.''
</P>
<P>
   As for co-ops and condominiums, ``there's a greater sense of
propriety,'' he continued. ``They make decisions on their own
well-being, and security is invariably a topic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes improvements are made when a building converts, he
said, but often the buildings ``take care of the cosmetic work
first and turn to security sometime later.''
</P>
<P>
   For many buildings that went co-op in the late '70s and early
'80s, later is now. ``These people have gotten their co-ops in very
good financial shape,'' said Matthew Arnold, president of Academy
Mailbox &AMP; Intercom Co. in College Point, Queens. ``Their bills are
paid and they're spending money for upgrades. What they're doing
today is above and beyond the minimum.'' (The minimum, according to
the state's Multiple Dwelling Law, is a locked door and, in
buildings with eight units or more, an intercom with a door
release.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, Arnold said, requests to relocate
locks and intercoms have risen from one or two a month to one or
two a week.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the domino effect: ``They see other buildings
(heightening security) and think it's a good idea,'' said Al Simon,
president of Nortronics, a security company in Palisades Park, N.J.
``Or they need to fix something and they say, `Let's put in a new
one while we're at it, better than before.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, of course, there's a catalyst. The man they call the
``East Side rapist,'' on the loose since 1994, may have much to do
with security upgrades on the Upper East Side. In most of his 16
attacks, the rapist has sneaked up on his victims after they had
gone through an unlocked outer door. In the wake of these attacks,
the 19th Police Precinct recommends locking the building's outer
door, which prevents people from lurking in the vestibule and keeps
tenants more visible from the street.
</P>
<P>
   Following the recommendation seems to be working. ``We have had
almost no incidents'' in buildings where outside locks have been
added, said Ira Meister, chief operating officer of Elm Management
Associates, which manages more than a dozen nondoorman buildings in
Manhattan. ``We have had no claims in the past two years.'' Before
that, he said, ``there were break-in-type situations.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also found that, in big buildings, video surveillance has
reduced thefts by employees. (Security experts note that signs
announcing a building is under video surveillance, even when it
isn't, are effective.)
</P>
<P>
   And residents at 309 W. 104th St. report an unexpected side
effect of their two locked doors _ far fewer take-out menus under
their apartment doors. Still, the need to ring twice confuses
people, said Ms. Conly.
</P>
<P>
   It confuses them so much, in fact, that some security companies
post instructional signs on their outside intercom panels. ``Ring
apartment from inside panel after admittance,'' reads the sign from
Gorilla Security Systems in Mineola, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of variations on the locked-outer-door system.
Some buildings add a wrought-iron gate and perch the buzzer there.
Others simply move the lock from the inside to the outside, keeping
only one door locked. Sometimes visitors have to ring just once to
get through two locked doors: Residents can buzz them in through
the outer door, wait a few seconds, and buzz again to release the
inner door.
</P>
<P>
   Other systems have a time delay, where one buzz unlocks an outer
door and then, some seconds later, unlocks an inner door. Simon, of
Nortronics, disapproves of those. ``What's the point of having two
locks,'' he said, ``if someone comes through the outer door and can
breeze right through the inner door?''
</P>
<P>
   Another danger, of course, is that an intruder will buzz at
random until a resident lets him in.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the small rectangular plate that's near almost
every intercom panel? That's the key keeper, and it's there for
postal purposes. The letter carrier has a master key that opens the
key keeper for every building in the ZIP code; inside is the
building's front-door key, usually on a retractable cord. The
master key also opens the bank of mailboxes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Relocating hardware to an outer door requires new wiring for
each apartment, which costs about $30 a unit, though prices vary
according to the building's size and the hardware. In a new
building, installing the hardware from scratch costs $100 to $150
per unit.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, higher-tech security systems, such as those that use
video cameras, are much more costly. But one big advantage is they
can record what they see, so there is a log of who has come and
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Closed-circuit television allows a building have a kind of
in-house security channel. With a camera aimed at the front door
and sometimes other places like the elevator and the laundry room,
residents can tune in and see what's going on. Such a system would
cost a total of $1,000 to $1,500 in a 12-unit brownstone _ more if
some residents of the building don't have cable, according to Kevin
Cogan of Alert 1 Alarm Systems in Manhattan, which installs the
equipment for Time Warner Cable.
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa McCarthy, who lives in the West 70s, appreciates the
in-house channel because packages from her husband's office are
often delivered late at night. ``If I'm expecting a messenger I
turn on Channel 77 and see who it is,'' she said. ``If something
were to happen, you get a picture of who it is.''
</P>
<P>
   An in-house channel also lets people spy on their neighbors.
This is a plus, said Cogan, who said business has doubled every
year in the past several years. ``There's always someone in the
building who has nothing better to do than sit there and monitor
the lobby,'' he said. ``So they'll keep it on the TV and this gives
you an extra set of eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one small inconvenience: People must go over to the
television set and turn it on before they can see who is ringing.
The solution to that is a video intercom, a screen-and-telephone
combination mounted on the wall. Because this requires equipment
plus rewiring, it is relatively costly _ perhaps $6,000 or $7,000
to retrofit that 12-unit brownstone.
</P>
<P>
   Video intercoms have been around for about two dozen years but
fell out of favor because of problems with repairs, maintenance and
spare parts, security experts say. Still, as technology improves
and costs drop, they expect these units will become more widely
used.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies tout keyless entry systems, with cards that can
be swiped like a Metrocard or poked in a slot, ATM style. But these
are still uncommon on outside doors in New York, and are used more
against problem tenants than intruders. Because the cards can be
programmed or deprogrammed, departing tenants can't walk off with
usable keys and current tenants can't pass out duplicates.
</P>
<P>
   John Jay's McCrie, for one, speculated that such high-tech
security systems would eventually become more widespread. ``Perhaps
in the future there will be a biometric system or the use of a
transistor that will allow people to enter,'' he said _ a kind of
EZ Pass for pedestrians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
