u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ADIRONDACK-NYT &LR;      06-27 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ADIRONDACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL NOTEBOOK: UPROAR OVER QUIET IN THE ADIRONDACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times said in an editorial, Sunday, June 28:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ADIRONDACK STATE PARK, N.Y. _ The lake, like thousands of others
created by New York's ancient glaciers, is small and remote, a
narrow valley of water less than two miles, end to end. At one
time, its underground springs nurtured brook trout, and to hear the
old fishermen talk, these glistening creatures tasted like no
modern food, certainly not like the experimental, acid-resistant
species now grown, ``neutered'' and dumped from state helicopters
into the lakes below.
</P>
<P>
   Acid rain from the Midwest is the plague that we often use to
explain our ghostly fish, as well as our forests singed orange by
thunderstorms and the neighboring ponds turning as tart as lemon
juice. It is an all-purpose peril, this cloud-borne pollution, and
it can even be adapted to explain seasonal aberrations in the
nature of things. This year, for example, there are no mice and no
chipmunks. Our basement and the balsam trees outside the windows
are uncommonly silent.
</P>
<P>
   We can blame distant industries for the silence, but the noise
we bring on ourselves. And it is one of the reasons that some
neighbors no longer wave automatically to each other as their boats
or cars pass within eyeing distance. Our lake, which of course does
not belong to any of us who borrow it for a few months each summer,
has become a tense battleground in the national recreation wars
between those who yearn for nature's quiet and those who thrill to
man-made sound _ in our case, the big-throated roar of a high-speed
motorboat.
</P>
<P>
   The split between the big boaters and the small boaters has
hardened people on both sides of our tiny summer community. When we
tried a do-it-yourself solution a few years ago, the majority did
not rule because there was no real way to enforce our communal law
on the minority. ``Un-American,'' the angry few grumbled, as we
worked to stop the high horsepower motors from churning our small
lake into a thick brown stew. ``Nobody can tell me what to do in
the Adirondacks,'' they said, thereby muscling their freedom into
position as the only freedom allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Like other lakeside communities, we then moved our petitions for
relief to local and state governments. This season we are fighting
over something called ``no-wake zones.'' Ever since 1942, New York
State law has decreed that most boats, but not those launching
skiers or barges in canals, must move slowly within 100 feet of the
shore. Now the idea is to expand the slow zone to 200 feet from
shore to stop erosion and turbidity, and improve safety for humans
and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   John Miller, president of the New York State Federation of
Lakes, tends the lakes in our area like a shepherd worrying over
his flock. He has been pushing the 200-foot zone because he argues
that although the number of motorboats in the state is growing,
from 100,000 or so in 1942 to almost 500,000 today, ``the number of
lakes stays the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who watch the gasoline scum on the water surface and
hear the loons screaming at boats several hundred yards away know
that 200 feet is a very short distance between a waterway and a
wilderness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
