<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON0628 _ BEIJING _ Clinton heading Chinese official
church in country where unofficial churches are banned. Begin
updates when Clinton actually goes to church, scheduled for 9 p.m.
EDT Saturday. (Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Both early and later versions will include a wrap of
previous day's developments, including detargeting pact, human
rights statements, Tibet, etc. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   With CHINA-RELIGION-$ADV28 _ BEIJING _ Sunday evening in the
candlelit sanctuary of Dong Tang, a ``patriotic'' Catholic church,
a four-year-old Chinese girl in a frilly dress sang the memorized
words of a hymn with as much gusto as the adults around her. More
than 200 worshipers chanted alleluias, partook holy communion and
heard of miraculous events at the Sermon on the Mount. Elderly men,
young couples, three sweaty teens in baggy pants -- basketball in
tow -- filled two-thirds of the pews last week. The
Chinese-language service looked much like a mass in America. But
the priest could not mention Catholicism's most revered living
figure, Pope John Paul II, or even whisper a reference to an issue
central to the church worldwide: the stand against abortion. And
fortunately for the four-year-old's mother, no hard-line Chinese
authorities were in Dong Tang (East Church) that night looking for
violators of government mandates, because it is forbidden to spread
religion to anyone under 18. These are the kinds of restrictions
advocates of human rights hope President Bill Clinton's visit today
to a Beijing Protestant church will spotlight. (Kunstel, Cox News
Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   (LIVE). With CHINA-ACCOMPLISH _ BEIJING _ What did Clinton
accomplish in his big day of talks with the Chinese on Saturday?
(Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   With CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV28 _ Religion in China, through the ages.
(Albright, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ Another recess begins for Congress Monday, and once
again Newt Gingrich is taking to the road. But the itinerary of
this trip seems more geared to helping vulnerable GOP candidates
than to furthering presidential ambitions, perhaps reflecting that
the fall races are tighter than the Republicans had expected.
(Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AUS-JASPER _ Members of the Ku Klux Klan demonstrate in this
East Texas town Saturday as it seeks to heal wounds from the
nationally publicized racially motivated killing of a black man who
was dragged two miles behind a pickup. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA: 6:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-OZONE _ From Miami to Nashville, ozone alerts have been
more frequent this year, as the South appears headed for a bad air
summer. And with new, more stringent ozone rules now being enforced
by the EPA, a number of metro areas in the Southeast could face the
same sort of restrictions on highway construction and smoke-stack
industries that Atlanta has felt for several years. But EPA also
has a plan to fight ozone in the South and the target is dirty
coal-fired power plants. (Harmon, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI _ More low levels of chlorine are reported at White Water,
the park where kids contracted the potentially deadly E. coli
bacteria. (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-STOP _ After Mary Heersink's 11-year-old son barely
survived the onslaught of a deadly food-borne bacterium, she could
have returned home after a seven-week hospital vigil and gratefully
resumed her stay-at-homemom duties. But she couldn't. Not with what
she had just learned: A killer lurked in restaurants, meat counters
and cookouts in the form of the all-American burger. She formed
STOP, a network of parents to stop the spread of the deadly
pathogen. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-DOOLEY _ Dan and Melissa Dooley are low-key people. Only a
small yellow ribbon tied in a bow and attached to a tall green
shrub near their driveway hinted at their ordeal. The Dooleys
brought their two daughters, Mary Beth, 6, and Anna, 2, back home
Friday from a long brush with death. The two girls fell gravely ill
with E. coli 0157:H7 in early June and spent three harrowing weeks
in the hospital. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY-ANALYSIS _ Analysis piece, hopefully with some news, on
what's going on in the JonBenet case. Ramseys were interviewed by
DA this week and 30-days period that DA said it would take to
determine whether to seek indictments is quickly approaching.
(Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   KIDPORN _ A growing number of people, mostly male, are using
computers to collect and distribute child pornography and to cruise
numerous unregulated chat rooms in search of potential underage sex
partners. FBI agent Kenneth Lanning, who specializes in cases
involving the sexual victimization of children for the bureau's
Behavioral Science Unit in Quantico, Va., said customs had
virtually wiped out importation of child pornography by the late
1980s and early 1990s. (Martz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-FIRES _ For decades Southerners have weathered the
Fourth of July heat in Florida to take the kids to the beach while
school is out and the Firecracker 500 is being held at Daytona. But
there will be no firecrackers this Fourth in bone-dry,
wildfire-burned Florida, and in some places smoke is drifting out
across the beaches and blinding motorists traveling the interstate.
What can visitors expect when they head south in the next few days,
and is the tourist industry worried that travelers might stay home?
(Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA-VOTE _ Preview of Tuesday's runoff election between Fob
James and Winton Blount. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTHOUSE _ CAPE HATTERAS, N. C. - Controversy is swirling
around the nation's tallest sentinel of the shore like the seas
beneath it in a nor'easter. The combatants all agree that something
must be done to save the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse from collapsing
on the beach where encroaching waves lap precariously close to its
brick and mortar base. It's the method of its salvation that has
tempers roiling. One side says the historic spiral-striped beacon
should be moved back from the advancing ocean. The other side says
leave it where it belongs and beat back the seas. (Finger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
