<SLUG> BC-NY-HUDSON-OUTRIGGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWAII ON THE HUDSON? OUTRIGGER RACERS HOPE SO 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a spectacle of endurance and speed more commonly
seen on the turquoise waters of Polynesia, dozens of paddling teams
raced outrigger canoes through the steely gray swells of New York
Harbor Saturday in the second-annual Liberty World Challenge, a
15-mile paddling sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Racing outriggers is increasing in popularity as a competitive
sport across the country and around the world, and organizers of
Saturday's event said they hoped to bring mana, the ancient
Polynesian life spirit, to New York City. After all, they said,
Manhattan is an island, just like Oahu.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hawaii, it's a little different,'' said Todd Bradley, an
all-star paddler and one of seven members of Team Hawaii, who are
serving this weekend as outrigging's ambassadors to New York. ``We
have beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, incongruities abounded. Instead of laying their
45-foot-long boats on soft sand and gently dragging them into the
surf, the paddlers cushioned the boats on old tires to keep them
off the asphalt at Pier 25 just north of Battery Park City. To get
to the water, the boats had to be carried over a fence and down a
metal ramp to a small wooden dock.
</P>
<P>
   And the canoe teams, who came from the Northeast and as far away
as California, Hawaii and the South Pacific, were framed against
the staggering skyline of lower Manhattan. ``We're getting whiplash
looking around,'' Bradley said. ``Wow, there's the Statue of
Liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the spirit of the ancient sport prevailed. Before the
women's teams sped off in the first race Saturday morning, several
of the teams huddled together to offer a group puli, or prayer.
``Please make us No. 1,'' they pleaded in Hawaiian.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's race Saturday, the No. 1 designation went to the
Wicked Wahines, a team of powerful paddlers who were gathered for
this event by Sheila Conover-Doyle, a three-time Olympic kayaker
from San Diego. She was joined by Chance Adair, also from San
Diego; two Hawaiians, Laurie Antonellis of Kauai and Elizabeth
Dolezai of Maui; and two New Englanders, Karen Levitt of Keene,
N.H., and Sue Slowick of Westhampton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   As the race began, and the long boats shot forward like arrows
from a bow, the Wicked Wahines _ ``wahine'' (pronounced wa-hee-nay)
is Hawaiian for ``woman'' _ quickly took a commanding lead. Racing
in a sharp yellow boat borrowed from the Kent Island Outrigger
Canoe Club from Maryland, the Wahines raced past Battery Park City,
past the glittering World Financial Center, and past a crowd of
dumbfounded tourists waiting to depart aboard the ferry to the
Statue of Liberty and Ellis Island.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-mile course took them south from Pier 25 around the tip
of Manhattan to the Brooklyn Bridge where they turned and headed
back, looping twice around Governor's Island and the Statue of
Liberty before heading back north to Pier 25. The Wahines came in
first, , finishing the course in 2 hours, 14 minutes and 5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in the first Liberty World Challenge only eight men's
teams and six women's teams participated. This year, there were 21
men's teams and 14 women's teams. And paddlers said they expected
the event to continue to grow in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outrigger has exploded on the East Coast,'' Ms. Conover-Doyle
said, explaining why she had flown from California to race in New
York for the first time this year. ``Last year we were home in
California watching CNN and we're like, `Oh my God, look at this,
there's an outrigger race around the Statue of Liberty.'''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's race, she said after climbing out of the winning
boat, was everything she expected. ``You go and you race in Hawaii
and there are the trade winds and the beautiful Hawaiian waters but
there's just something about paddling past the World Trade
building, Wall Street and you're on your way to the Statue of
Liberty. It's like wow, you're at the heart of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The sport has a history tracing back thousands of years to the
Pacific regions of Melanesia, Micronesia and Polynesia where
warlords often wagered on canoe races. Losers in those early
regattas sometimes paid with their lives. Canoeing, of course, also
has an even longer history in the Pacific as a peaceable mode of
transportation and important tool of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Modern outrigging seems to combine all of these elements with
heated competition, a fun-loving enthusiasm among racers and
increasing sponsorship of teams by corporations to help with the
costs of boats, other equipment and travel to competitions around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see two different atmospheres,'' said Penelope Hunter,
44, a member of the Mountain Home Canoe Club in Portland, Ore., one
of the teams that competed Saturday. ``People are really friendly
up until the start of the race. And they'll be really friendly
after the race. But they'll just as soon cut your throat during the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Classic outrigger canoes hold six paddlers including a steerer
at the rear.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional paddles are made of wood, which many racers believe
can catch the wind in its blade and translate it into power in the
water. Modern, ultralight paddles are made of carbon graphite.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-foot-long outrigger boats weigh approximately 400 pounds
and each one is equipped with an ama, or stabilizing bar, that is
attached to the side of the boat by wooden beams called iako. Even
with the ama, there is always a danger that a canoe will flip over.
</P>
<P>
   To race at optimum speed requires precise synchronization
between the six paddlers at a pace of about 68 strokes per minute.
</P>
<P>
   The boat captain calls out commands telling the paddlers when to
switch sides, usually after every 12 strokes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
