<HEADER>
A0200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATE-ATTORNEYS-GENER     06-27 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-ATTORNEYS-GENERAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUITS SHINE SPOTLIGHT ON STATE ATTORNEYS GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Conn.)   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The job of state attorney general has sometimes been ridiculed
as attracting ambitious officeholders and then stranding them in
political oblivion. According to one old political maxim, ``AG''
stands not for attorney general, but for aspiring governor.
</P>
<P>
   But over the last couple of years, a new activism by the chief
legal officers in many states has made their job more
consequential. It began with the state lawsuits against tobacco
companies, which accelerated the national battle over smoking. It
expanded when 20 states, including New York and Connecticut, joined
the Justice Department in filing antitrust charges against
Microsoft in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``These actions and the attention the media gave them have put
attorneys general, for the first time in history, front and center
all across the country,'' said Robert Abrams, a former New York
state attorney general who was the unsuccessful Democratic U.S.
Senate nominee in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   It would be an exaggeration to say the new attention is turning
the region's attorneys general into celebrities. ``If you stop 10
people on the street, 9 of them wouldn't know who I am,'' said New
Jersey Attorney General Peter Verniero.
</P>
<P>
   Still, attorneys general are in the news more than ever before,
including Verniero (whose post is filled by the governor under New
Jersey law), Richard Blumenthal of Connecticut and Dennis Vacco of
New York, who are both seeking re-election this year.
</P>
<P>
   The attention is likely only to grow now, with last week's court
victory by Microsoft in a separate case in which an appeals court
approved the way the company sells its software for navigating the
Internet. That could strengthen the company's hand in the broad
antitrust case brought by the government and the 20 states.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the failure of federal tobacco legislation has
returned a national focus to the states' tobacco suits, including
suits pending by New York, Connecticut and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Although joint suits by states are not new, the widespread
public attention and strong feelings surrounding the Microsoft and
tobacco cases have made the politics of the attorney general jobs
more convoluted. And that, some legal and political analysts say,
has only increased public confusion over what it is, exactly, that
attorneys general do.
</P>
<P>
   That confusion, some experts say, comes partly because the
responsibilities of attorneys general are defined differently in
different states and partly because the politics of the job often
make the job itself seem more perplexing than may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there is an absence of a firm understanding of what
the job is, it permits you to be a chameleon in the race,'' said
Eliot Spitzer, one of four Democrats competing to challenge Vacco,
the Republican incumbent in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For years, state attorneys general were known mostly for the
routine work that is the heart of their responsibilities. They
defend their states from thousands of suits each year dealing with
such subjects as claims against government officials and accidents
on state land. In recent decades, they have also filed scores of
suits annually on such usually undramatic causes as charities
fraud, price fixing and consumer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Such work created some political stars, like Joseph Lieberman,
the U.S. senator from Connecticut, and Jacob Javits, the former
U.S. senator from New York, both of whom were their state's
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   But many more attorneys general have failed than succeeded in
their bids for higher office, including Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams reeled off an informal tally on the subject. The ratio,
he said, was something like 35 attorneys general failing in bids
for higher office to 5 who made it to such positions as governor or
U.S. senator in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say even the tobacco and Microsoft cases are little
more than new efforts to turn the attorney general offices into
political stepping stones. But some of the attorneys general note
that their tobacco cases are playing a pivotal role in an issue
that the federal government has been struggling with for a
generation. And some legal experts say it is impossible to assess
whether the presence of the aggressive state attorneys general
stiffened the Justice Department's resolve to move against
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in their offices in Trenton, Hartford and New
York, the three incumbent attorneys general described themselves
as, essentially, apolitical lawyers who view legal issues with
clinical detachment. Vacco, 45, who is often described as a
conservative Republican and who won four years ago ardently
supporting the death penalty, for example, described himself as ``a
balanced, practical problem solver.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, 52, a Democrat, said, ``I'm certainly a practicing
lawyer in this job, and I pride myself on it.'' He is often
described as liberal and was a protege of the archetypal
Connecticut liberal Senator, the late Abraham A. Ribicoff. But he
said he does not describe himself as liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Among attorneys general, at least, it is not considered shrewd
to appear partisan. ``You check politics at the door in this
position,'' said Verniero, 39, a Republican, who admits he has been
a political ``junkie'' since he was a teen-ager. Before becoming
attorney general, he was chief counsel and chief of staff to New
Jersey's Republican governor, Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Verniero insisted on an apolitical point of
view. But he happened to mention various points on which he agreed
with Whitman, and none on which he disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, who is running for a third term in November, is in
the ticklish position of insisting he is nothing more than a
visionary lawyer for his state, while hinting that his politics do
make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   He did manage to note that, in his opinion, he had been out
front in battling the tobacco companies without any help from
Connecticut's Republican governor, John G. Rowland, until the
political winds shifted against the tobacco industry. A spokesman
for Rowland, however, insisted that the Governor ``was supportive
of the attorney general right from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big political tent in New York, of course, Vacco's race
for re-election has already been marked by intense politics. He has
reveled in an active role in both the tobacco and Microsoft suits,
which could appeal to Democratic and downstate voters. But critics
contend that both cases suggest blatant politicking, since Vacco's
stance appears philosophically inconsistent with a conservative
viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Before he filed a tobacco suit, Vacco was quoted as describing
such suits as silly enough to be compared to suing dairy companies
for causing cholesterol damage. In the interview, he seemed to back
away from that position. But his early lack of enthusiasm has led
some Democratic opponents to call him a ``Dennis come lately'' to
the anti-tobacco cause.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Vacco's involvement in the Microsoft antitrust case
has brought the wrong sort of attention from people who might be
considered natural supporters.
</P>
<P>
   In a column expressing consternation about the new activism of
state attorneys general and their role in the Microsoft suit, Paul
Gigot, The Wall Street Journal's conservative columnist, recently
accused Vacco of ``a political transformation worthy of the
accolade `Clintonian,''' which Gigot did not seem to mean as a
compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco, a former U.S. attorney in Buffalo, won his position four
years ago with a razor-thin margin over Karen Burstein, his
Democratic opponent. He is widely considered politically vulnerable
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, he explained the attacks on him. ``Politics,''
he said, was the explanation. Sounding misunderstood and a bit
hurt, he said people like Gigot were confused about the Microsoft
suit, which he described as probusiness because it is aimed at
encouraging competition.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of the tobacco and Microsoft cases often put Vacco
at odds with traditional Republican ideology. He said, for example,
that Gov. George Pataki, has told him of concerns about the
Microsoft suit.
</P>
<P>
   But Vacco made it clear that he is a long way from courting any
quarrel with the politically strong governor who is at the head of
his ticket. ``George Pataki calls me,'' Vacco said, snapping his
fingers, ``and I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the would-be opponents and lawyers who watch attorneys
general say it is a job that attracts ambitious politicians because
it regularly allows the incumbent to work his way into news
accounts with worthy battles.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, worthiness is sometimes in the eye of the beholder.
Blumenthal speaks passionately about fighting polluters, protecting
consumers and going to war for children. But Santa Mendoza, a
41-year old West Hartford lawyer who is the likely Republican
candidate for Connecticut attorney general, took issue with
Blumenthal's description of his accomplishments. ``Being
immortalized during the 6 o'clock news, has been, during his eight
years in office, his top priority,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in New Jersey, where the attorneys general have seldom run
for election to anything, the political bug seems to bite occupants
of the office. John Degnan, the attorney general for Gov. Brendan
Byrne, and W. Carey Edwards, the attorney general for Gov. Thomas
H. Kean, are among the former attorneys general who have failed in
quests for gubernatorial election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they get the idea that they are more prominent than they
really are,'' said Ronald Chen, an associate dean of Rutgers Law
School.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the lure, there is always a list of lawyers who would
love to have the job at almost any cost. By the time the election
rolls around in November in New York, Vacco and the four Democratic
candidates who are battling each other in a primary are, by some
estimates, expected to have spent a total of about $10 million
trying to win the position.
</P>
<P>
   And after all that, it seems clear that most citizens will not
know much more about the job than they do right now. G. Oliver
Koppell, a Democrat who succeeded Abrams as attorney general in New
York and then lost his job in a primary four years ago, is
competing to win the Democratic nomination with Spitzer, state Sen.
Catherine Abate, and Evan Davis, a former counsel to Gov. Mario
Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   From his experience not only occupying the job, but running for
it as well, Koppell offered a timeless observation: ``The public,
in general,'' he said, ``is completely uninformed about the
attorney general's office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
