<HEADER>
A0205 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALABAMA-VOTE-COX     06-27 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-VOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama GOP in holy war: Candidates clash, use religion as
weapon
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Alabama Republicans are waging holy war for
the gubernatorial nomination as they head into Tuesday's runoff
election, and appear to be trying to out-Christian each other.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent Gov. Fob James employs former Christian Coalition
director Ralph Reed as a consultant and reminds voters of his firm
support of school prayer. Challenger businessman Winton Blount
quotes Proverbs in radio commercials and professes his belief in
Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder popular analysis of the race frames this as a
window to the GOP's national soul. But the deciding factor simply
may come down to style.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people misunderstand this election as a clash between
the religious right and fiscal conservatives,'' said Wayne Flynt,
an Auburn University history professor and critic of James.
``Certainly there's that matchup, but this is more about a
bumbling, inept politician making one mistake after another.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican voters Tuesday _ as well as an undetermined number of
Democratic crossovers _ will consider who has the best tax pledge
and whether James has crystallized the stereotype of a backwoods
state or prevailed as a champion for religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   James, 63, has threatened to call out the National Guard to
protect the Ten Commandments hung on a county courtroom wall, told
Alabamians to ignore a federal judge's order limiting school prayer
and once imitated a monkey's walk during a meeting to illustrate a
textbook's characterization of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Blount, 55, casts those images as embarrassing to a state trying
to economically keep pace with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does image mean?'' James said. ``When you can't talk
about reality, you talk about imagery. I'm not much of an imagery
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Dewberry, a 46-year-old Birmingham coal miner, crossed
over from the Democratic Party in 1994 to vote for James. ``He has
a down-to-earth ability to communicate with people,'' Dewberry
said.
</P>
<P>
   James has hitched his re-election to a ``No New Taxes'' bus
tour, promising efficient spending of state revenue with no
additional levies while deriding Blount for not making the same
promise. Blount counters with a plan to trim the state tax on
groceries.
</P>
<P>
   But the substantive differences between the candidates have been
blurred by backbiting so harsh that Republicans worry the wounds
may be too damaged to heal by the November general election against
Democrat Don Siegelman, the lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Anonymously circulated fliers refer to a 1969 wreck that killed
Blount's first wife and imply she may have been dead before the
``trajic (sic) accident'' with Blount behind the wheel of his
Jaguar. James disavows responsibility for the ``smear sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   And the difference is?
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, a Blount radio ad intimates the governor lied
about a family-owned landfill that has benefited from business with
the state and that he may have committed perjury in the trial of a
former agency leader James had fired for theft.
</P>
<P>
   Roger McConnell, chairman of Alabama's Republican Party, has
``encouraged both candidates to stay focused on issues,'' but he's
certain the summer rancor will make his job tougher this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be easy for us,'' McConnell said. ``If Don Siegelman
positions himself as a conservative and there's no difference
between our two candidates, then we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   James won 48 percent of the vote in the five-man GOP primary
June 2. Blount took 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Alabama Republican Party, unlike the Democratic
party, has an open primary, a wild card Tuesday will be two brands
of Democratic crossover. One is the long-standing white-flight
version that once supported George Wallace and later Hunt. The
other is a new entry: urban blacks encouraged by Birmingham Mayor
Richard Arrington to vote for Blount. During the candidates' final
debate in Birmingham, James said his vision is for the state to
become No. 1 in the nation in SAT scores. Blount urged voters to
``throw off the shackles of low expectations.'' Playing on a
campaign trip to Huntsville's space center, Blount said, ``We went
to the moon from Alabama, we're going to Mars from Alabama and a
change is going to happen on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, James was asked to rebut Blount's charges that the
image of the state has suffered under his administration. James
responded with a question _ and an image of his own, of Blount as
liberal spender:
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear the debate? Did you hear his closing remarks?
Have you ever heard such grandiose, pie-in-the-sky, Hubert
Humphrey-sounding nonsense in your life?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
