<HEADER>
A0206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-COX     06-27 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich pulls out all stops in support of candidates
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- In 1996, Speaker Newt Gingrich starred in campaign
ads in Republican Anne Northup's Louisville, Ky., district.
</P>
<P>
   They were Democratic ads, of course, similar to ones running on
television stations around the country. Their aim was clear: Tie
Northup to Gingrich and beat her by pounding him.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker never set foot in the district during the campaign.
Northup eked out a victory and Gingrich held on to his job, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   As the Republican Party gears up once again to try to retain its
House majority in November, the Gingrich travel ban has been
relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   With the House on an extended vacation until the middle of July,
Gingrich will raise money for nine Republican incumbents, including
Northup and other freshmen, two statewide candidates in California
and state legislative hopefuls in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The stops will include a Salt Lake City fund-raiser for freshman
Rep. Merrill Cook (R-Utah) in an anti-tobacco stronghold. ``Many
Mormons would like to see Republicans take a stronger stand on
tobacco,'' Cook said. But he predicted the speaker would be warmly
received.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Gingrich will be with Northup in Louisville,
home of Brown &AMP; Williamson tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the speaker will dine with the Republican Party's
biggest contributors in the Napa Valley wine country in California,
part of a three-day swing through the most populous state.
</P>
<P>
   Among his more intriguing appearances will be a speech in Dallas
on Wednesday to the League of United Latin American Citizens'
annual meeting. Some LULAC chapters had considered boycotting the
event because they view the GOP agenda as anti-immigrant, spokesman
Larry Trejo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've come to realize that we have to understand what
these people are saying,'' Trejo said.
</P>
<P>
   That this busy travel schedule also would serve Gingrich if he
decides to run for president has been lost on no one, said Gingrich
campaign spokesman Mike Shields.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of it is geared toward any kind of presidential politics.
But would it hurt, the fact that we're a national figure and get to
meet with all these people? No,'' Shields said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that Gingrich already has visited 35 states this
year, exclusive of his publicity tour for ``Lessons Learned the
Hard Way,'' his recent book on the trials and tribulations of
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   And when Gingrich speaks on behalf of California Secretary of
State Bill Jones and U.S. Senate candidate Matt Fong, he will be
collecting IOUs that could come in handy in a presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But a more important purpose to his travels over the next two
weeks will be to gauge the reaction to a rush of Republican
proposals that emerged last week on health care, tobacco and taxes
_ three crucial topics for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On health care, House Republicans are proposing some expansion
of the rights of patients in managed care plans and other changes
that are more modest than Democrats would like.
</P>
<P>
   Their anti-teen-smoking bill will, at most, contain a small
price increase on cigarettes and will punish teen smokers, but not
the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also proposed a further cut in the capital gains tax _
from 20 percent to 15 percent, and from 15 percent to 7.5 percent
for low income taxpayers _ and asserted that it would not cost the
government. More people will sell their assets because of the lower
tax rate and actually bring in more tax revenues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The House Democratic leader, Dick Gephardt of Missouri, said
Republicans are continuing their ``long march against the interest
of working families and children'' with last week's announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Republican tobacco bill, only the outlines of which
emerged last week, Gephardt said, ``To put it in a word, this is
Big Tobacco's dream. ... It really should be the RJR Republican
Party. They are fully aligned with the interests of Big Tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt also included criticism of the House's approach to
campaign finance reform in his tirade against the GOP, saying it
``languishes on the floor'' of the House because of Republican
efforts to drag out the debate until August.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is by no means clear that tobacco or health care or
campaign reform legislation will become law in 1998. (The tax cut
is another matter.)
</P>
<P>
   Legislative inaction on most topics might suit Republicans fine.
They would prefer to run on the budget surplus and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   They are a confident bunch in the wake of their victory in a
special congressional election in New Mexico last week that
Democrats had hoped would create momentum for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for being sanguine, said Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.),
chairman of the National Republican Congressional Committee, is
that the well-funded Democrat in New Mexico never tried to use
tobacco as an issue, an indication that Democrats do not have the
magic bullet in tobacco that they have claimed.
</P>
<P>
   And, Republicans wonder happily, if Democrats can't capitalize
on close links between the Republicans and an industry that has
made lawyers, politicians and journalists seem popular, what
weapons will Democrats have to oust Gingrich as speaker?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
