<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 6/27/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) EL BOSQUE, Mexico -- June 27, 1998 -- MEXICO-CHIAPAS,
6-27 -- A policeman stands guard in the main plaza of El Bosque,
Chiapas, after government forces recaptured the town hall from
Zapatista supporters. The operation at El Bosque was the fourth in
a series of government military actions since April to dismantle
what the Zapatistas call their ``autonomous'' town governments. The
incident showed how volatile the conflict in Chiapas has become.
(Keith Dannemiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 27, 1998 -- NYC-BED&AMP;BREAKFAST, 6-27 --
Henry Cohen outside his West 71st Street apartment building, where
he believes five of the nine units are being used for short-term
rentals. In a city with a burnished new image, waves of tourism,
and booked-up hotels, it was bound to happen: bed-and-breakfasts
are springing up all over Manhattan. Most operators of transient
rooms in residential buildings violate not only zoning laws and
building codes, but also do not have proper licenses and many do
not pay sales or hotel taxes. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) OAKLAND, Calif. -- June 27, 1998 -- HUD-DRUG-EVICTIONS,
6-27 --Herman Walker, who lives in public housing in Oakland, is
fighting an eviction stemming from accusations that a caretaker and
a visitor had illegal narcotics or paraphernalia in his apartment.
The resulting lawsuit filed by Walker and three others illustrates
a growing conflict between Federal officials, who have urged local
housing agencies to crack down on illegal drug use, and some
advocates for the poor, who say that innocent people are falling
victim to a Draconian offensive in the war on drugs. (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- June 27, 1998 -- BOSTON-STREET-CHURCH, 6-27 --
The Rev. Deborah Little has conducted church services at Boston
Common for two years, reaching out to people like Paul Kirouac.
Every Sunday at 1 p.m. for the past two years, she has set up a
cross beside Brewer Fountain, near Tremont and Park Streets, and
rolled up a wooden box that does triple duty as altar, kitchen and
clothes closet. ``The Christian tradition and others say if you
want to get closer to the heart of life, of God, go and be closer
to the poor,'' says Ms. Little, 53. (Evan Richman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) RIFLE, Colo. -- June 27, 1998 -- COLO-RIFLE-TOWN-2, 6-27
-- Penny Gagliano, 14, of Grand Junction, Colo., fires during a
shooting tournament. In Rifle, shooting competitions are a way of
life. So in a town with a strong gun culture, it was with alarm and
uneasiness that residents watched as teen-age boys, from rural
towns just like Rifle, showed up at schoolyard after schoolyard
around the nation, and turned their rifles on unsuspecting
classmates. Residents are seeking ways to keep it from happening
here. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) RIFLE, Colo. -- June 27, 1998 -- COLO-RIFLE-TOWN-1, 6-27
-- Guns are as much a part of growing up in Rifle, as teddy bears
and crayons. But with reports of schoolyard shootings in similiar
rural towns, Rifle residents worry that the same thing could happen
there. Pat Payne, 10, recently took part in a shooting match as his
father, Criss watches. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
