A0215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PELOSI-NYT &LR;      06-27 0234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PELOSI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSWOMAN FAULTS CLINTON'S REMARKS ON RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-TV-BROADCAST, CHINA-REACT,
CHINA-ASSESS, CHINA-HILLARY, CHINA-PITFALLS-REVIEW,
U.S.-CHINA-REVIEW)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congresswoman known as a particularly harsh
critic of the Clinton administration's China policy said Saturday
that President Clinton's comments on human rights were intended for
his detractors in the United States, but did little to assist
reform in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said what was needed for American consumption without
assisting the cause of democratic reform in China,'' said Rep.
Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the exchange between Clinton and President Jiang
Zemin ``may end up being harmful to the cause of dissidents in
China,'' and that the Clinton administration was ``buying into the
Chinese view that the Tiananmen era is in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, she said, ``keeps mentioning personal freedom, but what
is important is political expression.'' She said the Chinese
``can't speak out about political or religious matters without
being punished.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the president's visit to Beijing ``falls short of what
we would generally call a summit'' because ``the Chinese didn't
make any concessions; we accepted their terms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The product is not worthy of a summit,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
