<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0231 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-HARASS-(2TAKES     06-27 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HARASS-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES REACT QUICKLY TO COURT'S SEXUAL HARASSMENT RULINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs for editorial fine-tuning throughout, and addition of Kilberg
quote)  (nk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the U.S. Supreme Court creating a new national policy on
sexual harassment virtually overnight, many companies are moving
quickly to re-examine their rules, expecting to adopt tougher
measures to meet the court's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Most large corporations have strong harassment policies, but
human resource experts said that a weak link in those programs was
usually the companies' failure to repeatedly communicate the policy
to all employees or to have effective mechanisms set up for
employees to report harassment without fear of reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Executives, lawyers and consultants specializing in human
resources predicted that medium-size and smaller companies with
inadequate human resources staffs would have to do the most to
strengthen their anti-harassment policies.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the court's two far-reaching decisions Friday came
quickly. Corporations from Nabisco to Lockheed-Martin were set to
review their policies, corporate executives and advisers said, in
view of the court's holding that employers will face broader
exposure for sexual harassment by supervisors, especially if the
employers do not have strong anti-harassment programs.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bernstein, a lawyer in Newark, N.J., who advises RJ
Reynolds and Continental Airlines on employment matters, said: ``In
light of these opinions, I'm telling my clients that the Supreme
Court is saying that if you want to minimize your liability, if you
want to insulate yourself, then establish clear policies,
distribute them among you work force. Make sure you can establish
that your employees have received your policies and your complaint
procedures and that they know precisely who it is they're supposed
to complain to.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't limited to sexual harassment,'' Bernstein said.
``The same general principles apply to claims of homosexual
harassment, racial harassment and national-origin harassment. This
is the perfect opportunity for employers to seize the day and
educate employees to their policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping into a field that had been marked by confusion, the
Supreme Court expanded potential liability for harassment by ruling
that employers could be held liable when a supervisor threatened to
demote or take other action against an employee who refused the
supervisor's sexual demands, even when the threats were not carried
out.
</P>
<P>
   But the court's majority wrote in the pair of 7-2 decisions that
employers could generally avoid liability in such cases by showing
that they had strong anti-harassment programs. In particular, the
rulings suggested that employers make sure they communicate those
policies to all employees and establish systems for receiving and
reviewing harassment complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the decisions were issued, corporate counsels
and employment lawyers were poring over the opinions to figure out
exactly how to advise their companies and clients, against the
backdrop of the large-scale sexual harassment settlements agreed to
by corporate giants like Smith Barney and Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   In Mitsubishi's case, the corporation agreed to pay $34 million
to settle a sexual harassment case brought by women working at a
factory in Illinois. Smith Barney, in a proposed settlement, agreed
to pay hundreds of thousands of dollars to women who said they had
been harassed and to spend $15 million on anti-discrimination and
anti-harassment training.
</P>
<P>
   Employment experts predicted that the ruling would drum up a lot
of business for consultants who advise companies on sexual
harassment. They said they also expected that tens of thousands of
human resources officials and senior executives would soon begin
fashioning their policies to reduce the chance of liability in
which plaintiffs often win hundreds of thousands and even millions
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water cooler discussions about harassment will now shift to
boardroom discussions about harassment,'' said Susan Meisinger,
senior vice president for the Society for Human Resource
Management, an association of more than 100,000 personnel and
employee relations professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law of sexual harassment is an area of shifting sands,''
she added. ``Each time that there's this evolution, employers have
to go back and check their practices to make sure they're not going
to get themselves in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the decisions were issued, corporate counsels
and employment lawyers were reading and re-reading the opinions to
figure out exactly how to advise their companies and clients. With
companies eager to avoid the large-scale sexual harassment
settlements agreed to by corporate giants like Smith Barney and
Mitsubishi, several employment experts predicted that the ruling
would drum up a lot of business for consultants who advise
companies on sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Conrad, senior vice president for litigation at the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, said the group would soon advise the Chamber's
200,000 members, 90 percent of which have fewer than 100 employees,
on the effect of the ruling. ``After these decisions, we'll be
telling people there are things you can do to prevent this from
happening and to protect yourself in the process, '' she said.
``Have a policy and effectively communicate it. Promptly
investigate complaints. And take prompt corrective action.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In one of the two Supreme Court cases, a former lifeguard sued
the City of Boca Raton, Fla., complaining that two male supervisors
had created a sexually hostile atmosphere for years through
offensive touching and lewd remarks. Even though the city had a
formal anti-harassment policy, the court found the city liable,
noting that Boca Raton had failed to disseminate the policy to the
beach employees.
</P>
<P>
   The court also faulted Boca Raton for making no effort to keep
track of the supervisors' conduct and for not making clear that
employees could bypass the harassing supervisors if they wanted to
file complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, an employee of Burlington Industries sued the
company, saying she felt compelled to quit after a supervisor had
said he could make life harder or easier for her depending on
whether she did such things as wear shorter skirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers are going to pay attention to these decisions,''
said Angela DeSilva, chief counsel for the Duke Energy Corp. in
Houston. ``Most employers should be paying attention to this to be
sure they're not behind on this issue. They should go back and
analyze whether they have a policy and analyze whether they're
effectively disseminating the policy. If you have an employer who
has a policy that's kept in the HR department and that's not
disseminated to employees, it's not going to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Several human resource experts interviewed after the Supreme
Court issued its ruling said most large corporations have strong
sexual harassment policies. These experts said that if there is any
weak link in those programs, it is usually that the companies do
not repeatedly communicate the policy to all employees or do not
have a effective mechanism set up for employees to report
harassment without fear of reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   At some companies, executives voiced confidence that they had
tough harassment policies that would help protect them against
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nabisco already has a strong sexual harassment policy in
place,'' said Barbara Sellinger, the company's chief labor and
chief litigation counsel. ``You'll probably find that the larger
companies are in really good shape. The medium-sized and smaller
companies that don't have a good human resources staff are not
going to be in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she said Nabisco executives would certainly review
the court's decisions to make sure the company heeded the criteria
set forth to avoid liability.
</P>
<P>
   In its rulings, the Supreme Court analyzed three situations and
types of sexual harassment. In one, often called quid pro quo
harassment, the supervisor takes an adverse action _ like
dismissal, failing to promote, reducing benefits or reassigning
with significantly reduced responsibilities _ against an employee
who refuses to submit to the supervisor's sexual demands. In such
cases, the court wrote, affirming a long-standing line of cases,
that the employer was automatically liable, even when it had a
strong anti-harassment policy in place.
</P>
<P>
   In the second situation, generally called a hostile work
environment case, there is a sexually hostile environment, marked
by severe or pervasive conduct. In the third situation, a
supervisor threatens a tangible job detriment, like a demotion, to
someone who spurns the supervisor's advances, but the threat goes
unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that in these two situations the employer could
be held liable for the harassment, but could escape liability by
proving that it had ``exercised reasonable care to prevent and
correct promptly any sexually harassing behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled further that employers could also avoid
liability by showing that the employee asserting harassment
``unreasonably failed to take advantage of any preventive or
corrective opportunities provided by the employer.''
</P>
<P>
   Invoking such a defense, employers would argue that it would be
wrong to hold them liable because an employee was unreasonable in
failing to complain to higher-ups and thus did not give the
employer the chance to correct the behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``These decisions give employers a road map,'' said William
Kilberg, a lawyer in Washington who wrote a brief in the case for
the National Association of Manufacturers. ``You have to have a
policy and then regularly remind people of its existence. And you
should create some easy mechanism, like a hot line, for employees
to file complaints. Arguably, if Boca Raton had a hot line that
went to City Hall or to someone in the human resources department
and if they had then investigated, then the city would not have
been held liable.''
</P>
<P>
   While corporate officials applauded the rulings because they
drew clear lines about what to do to avoid liability, plaintiffs'
lawyers and women's groups also praised the decisions for holding
that employers faced liability for harassment by supervisors, even
when there was no tangible adverse job action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does a very smart thing,'' said Martha Davis, legal
director for the National Organization for Women Legal Education
and Defense Fund. ``It continues to make sure that employers bear
the burden rather than the individual if harm is done.
</P>
<P>
   The lifeguard who sued, Beth Ann Faragher, who is now a lawyer
in Denver, said in an interview, ``This was an argument about
principle and is a victory for working women because it tells their
employers they must take affirmative steps to prevent'' harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meisinger of the Society for Human Resource Management,
recommended that employers consider buying insurance against sexual
harassment cases. She said: ``The math has changed a bit. These two
decisions are the culmination of a public focus on the subject, and
employers have to anticipate the cumulative impact of this will be
more litigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
