<HEADER>
A0235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-DOOLEY-COX     06-27 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-DOOLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ailing sisters home from hospital
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Dan and Melissa Dooley are low-key people. Only a
small yellow ribbon tied in a bow and attached to a tall green
shrub near their driveway hints at their ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Dooleys brought their two daughters, Mary Beth, 6, and Anna,
2, back home Friday from a long brush with death.
</P>
<P>
   The two girls fell gravely ill with E. coli 0157:H7 in early
June and spent three harrowing weeks in Egleston Children's
Hospital. Their kidneys failed and they underwent dialysis; doctors
gave them so many blood transfusions their parents lost track.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday evening, as family and friends gathered at the
Dooleys'home in the Hull community of Madison County, both girls
were darting around as though they had never been ill. They played
with dozens of balloons and stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley said the girls' physician at Egleston had planned to
release them Thursday but decided to wait until Friday so both
could have one more blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   The girls suffered complete kidney failure at the height of the
infection and had to be placed on kidney dialysis machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had good days and bad days,'' said Melissa Dooley, 35,
who stayed at the hospital almost full time and took turns visiting
one daughter's room or the other's. Dooley, 39, split time between
the hospital and his CPA business in Hull. And the Dooleys'
parents, sisters and friends also took turns at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls knew something was wrong,'' Mrs. Dooley said, ``but
they were too young to know how terribly wrong. We gave them a lot
of love. That's all you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   She knew her daughters had finally turned a corner only a few
days ago, when doctors removed them from dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart goes out to all those parents whose children have E.
coli,'' she said, ``because it is so scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley said that physicians told him that his daughters' cases
were evidently isolated, unrelated to an earlier case of E. coli in
a Danielsville Elementary School student, who apparently contracted
it from a contaminated beef patty in the school cafeteria. That
child was released from a hospital May 9, and the Dooley children
did not fall ill until June.
</P>
<P>
   Nor had either girl been to White Water Park, as had the other
children who've become ill, Dooley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dooleys said the love and support of family and friends
helped get them through the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got more friends than we knew we had,'' Dooley said.
``They sent a lot of love and said a lot of prayers for our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
