<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-STOP-COX     06-27 2200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-STOP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mothers against microbes
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They shared a similar boyhood dream.
</P>
<P>
   One wanted to be a doctor, tending to critically ill children.
The other wanted to deliver the sick and wounded to the emergency
room door.
</P>
<P>
   But they also shared a nightmare named E. coli O157:H7.
</P>
<P>
   Today, one boy steps purposefully toward college. The other
blazes through the playground, red hair flying, running through
recess forever.
</P>
<P>
   Damion Heersink carries himself with the reserved enthusiasm of
an eldest son and big brother who's finally breaking free from
parents and little brothers and a sister. Visiting Atlanta, he
lunges at the opportunity to navigate his mom around his
soon-to-be-adopted big city, more than four hours from his Dothan,
Ala., home. Yet he admits to missing his toddler twin brothers when
a baby's shriek rings out in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   This August, at Atlanta's Emory University, Damion hopes his
doctor dreams take flight. He wants pre-med courses, then the long
haul of medical school, to lead him back to the hospital. Back to
where doctors and nurses and the constant vigil of his parents kept
him alive as his body battled the ravages of a toxin picked up
during a Boy Scout cookout.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to be like Dr. Daniel Plasencia, a pediatric specialist
who guided Damion's 1992 roller-coaster ride through E. coli hell
at Tampa's St. Joseph's Children's Hospital. Plasencia led the
crisis management of kidney, heart and lung experts who battled the
constant complications of the killer microbe: E. coli O157:H7.
</P>
<P>
   Damion suffered from hemolytic uremic syndrome, or HUS, the same
kidney and blood disruption affecting seriously ill children in
Georgia's rush of E. coli cases. Because of his age, 11, he also
battled an adult version of the kidney and blood malfunction. This
bacteria has proved to be unlike any other in its tenacity and
toxicity. All doctors can do is keep patients alive until their
bodies fight off the poison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was when I was in the hospital that I decided I wanted to
be a doctor, to help kids get through what I almost didn't get
through,'' says Damion, now 18.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times in seven weeks as he was wheeled into surgery,
through March and April 1992, his mom, Mary Heersink, told her
first born good-bye.
</P>
<P>
   His kidneys failed, his lungs turned to soup, his intestine
ruptured, his own blood turned against him. Tubes in his mouth,
nose, chest and bladder linked to breathing machines and nutrition
and drainage devices kept him alive. Doctors repeatedly drained the
fluids around Damion's heart that threatened to suffocate him. But
it had to be done without anesthesia because his compromised body
couldn't handle the sedative.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to talk because of a respirator in place for four weeks,
Damion frantically scribbled notes to his mom. ``Please, Stop Them
From Stabbing Me'' read one when the long needle plunged into his
heart. ``Please, today?'' read another, which had become shorthand
for his eternal request for any liquid, preferably a taste, a sip,
of his favorite drink: a strawberry Slurpee.
</P>
<P>
   Though doctors had forbidden liquids, Mary Heersink finally gave
in. Damion took one sip. Instantly, he writhed in pain. Nurses
rushed Damion to the operating room, where doctors sliced him open
from throat to groin to remove 26-feet of looping and coiling
intestinal tract to search for holes.
</P>
<P>
   Damion suffered the most serious complications of E. coli
O157:H7, a bacteria that has sickened nine Georgia children and
four others from out of state. Two of those children are in
critical condition. The bacteria lives in the intestines of cattle,
and is released in cattle feces. It sometimes hitchhikes its way
into the food supply, primarily on ground beef, but E. coli
outbreaks also have been associated with unpasteurized apple juice
and milk, fruits and vegetables. According to the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, this particular E. coli strain
sickens 20,000 Americans, killing about 500 yearly.
</P>
<P>
   Although the strange name is now become part of the lexicon of
potential deadly poisons lurking in our food supply, in 1992, the
Heersinks _ like most Americans _ had never heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   When doctors surmised Damion had contracted the tiny, invisible
bacteria from eating beef _ his mother was dumbstruck.
</P>
<P>
   ``How on earth could this have happened?'' she remembers
thinking. ``The meat industry and the Department of Agriculture
knew very well about this bug back then. But no one ever told us
the rules had changed about how you approach eating beef.''
</P>
<P>
   One year later, Nancy Donley asked the same question.
</P>
<P>
   Her 6-year-old boy was dead from eating a grilled hamburger
patty.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted a simple answer to a simple question: Why?
</P>
<P>
   In four days, E. coli: O157 had coursed through her only child's
tiny body with a voracity that shocked even the doctors at
Chicago's Children's Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to donate Alex's organs, but we couldn't,'' Nancy
Donley says. ``E. coli destroyed every single organ. The autopsy
showed it even liquefied portions of his brain.''
</P>
<P>
   When the two mothers united in 1993 to demand safer meat, they
discovered the answers to the why, how and whens of their sons'
illnesses were anything but simple. The query led everywhere and
nowhere: to consumers blamed for not thoroughly cooking their beef;
to public health officials doing at poor job at communicating risk;
and to the historically weak federal regulation of the nation's
slaughterhouses and meat-packing plants.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Jack in the Box outbreak of E. coli, which killed
four children and sickened hundreds in the Northwest in 1993, for
the rest of America to get this same crash course on microbes,
meat, public policy and the power of private industry.
</P>
<P>
   Like Heersink and Donley, more mothers, fathers and E. coli
survivors met and instantly bonded. They formed Safe Tables Our
Priority, or S.T.O. P. It's now a national group with 5,000
members, a victim hotline, and a tiny Brooklyn-based office headed
by a diligent researcher and spokesperson named Heather Klinkhamer.
When clusters of cases occur, S.T.O.P. members contact victims'
families, offering support and information, as Heersink did this
week in the Georgia cases.
</P>
<P>
   The group has been praised by President Clinton and his wife,
Hillary, and has been invited to international summits on food
safety. It sits on national meat-safety advisory boards, and swoops
onto the information-networking scene during every E. coli
outbreak, from Tokyo to Tennessee. S.T.O.P. is the the citizens'
force credited to last year's recall of 25 million pounds of Hudson
beef that had been traced to 17 serious illnesses in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made it a personal issue,'' says Dr. Robert Tauxe, chief
of the CDC's foodborne disease branch. ``The activities of Ms.
Heersink and the S.T.O.P. group began a pivotal transformation of
the Department of Agriculture and the safety of meat.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the documentation and epidemiological reports
proving the threat of this invisible food microbe didn't exist, the
word just hadn't gotten beyond the often insular office walls of
researchers and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   According to a former USDA assistant secretary, S.T.O.P. has
been one of the most successful grass-roots groups to ever get the
ear _ and action _ of Congress. Through old-fashioned lobbying and
committee hearing testimonials, S.T.O.P. shook loose the meat
industry that had been immune to government intervention for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   It's biggest accomplishment: Getting federal testing, safety and
recall regulations imposed upon E. coli O157:H7. Previously, a
discovery of contaminated meat was met with ``be sure to cook your
meat'' refrains from meat distributors, who claimed the
contamination of this new, lethal bacteria was inevitable and
unavoidable in the farm-to-table chain.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if the bacteria is discovered in meat after it's
distributed, the batch of beef receives a federal government
warning and most often is voluntarily recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been constantly and emotionally moved by the way
they've worked together and what they've accomplished,'' said Carol
Tucker Foreman, assistant USDA secretary from 1977 to 1981, who now
heads the advocacy group, Safe Food Coalition, in Washington, D.C.
``They have been extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Heersink, Donley and other S.T.O.P. members are also credited
with demanding a better public health tracking of E. coli-related
infections, and a computerized tracking system for foodborne
outbreaks. Those systems, monitored by the CDC and state public
health departments, have helped pinpoint the extent of the Georgia
outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, while pregnant with twin boys, Mary Heersink wrote the
personal account of her son's illness, a 300-page book she gladly
gives away to families entering E. coli hell. It's been translated
into several languages, including Japanese, where it became a
best-seller following that country's E. coli O157 outbreak that
killed 11 people and sickened nearly 10,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The book is simply called ``E. Coli O157: The True Story of a
Mother's Battle With A Killer Microbe.'' She dedicated it to 13
children _ none of them older than 7 years old _ all of them dead
from E. coli O157.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a group that promotes vegetarianism, though Heersink
and Donley don't eat ground beef. They also do not mince words over
the mincing and mixing practices of the beef industry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when a small meat processor told the Secretary of
Agriculture that new proposed USDA safety regulations were costly
and seemed excessive, Mary Donley shot back: ``You're really just
saying that it is inconvenient for you to make the change to assure
your product isn't contaminated. Well, let me tell you. It wasn't
convenient for me to have my son die.''
</P>
<P>
   USDA Secretary Dan Glickman refers to Heersink and Donley as
modern-day Upton Sinclairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``S.T.O.P. has turned the tide on food safety,'' Glickman said
on Jan. 18, 1998, the fifth anniversary of the Jack in the Box
outbreak. ``You have become a powerful, morally unstoppable force
for change. . . . Never, ever stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The meat industry, however, is a less complimentary. ``They're
very well-meaning, but it's a little bit like asking MADD to write
laws to make sure people don't go drinking and driving,'' said
Rosemary Mucklow, executive director of the National Meat
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Heersink and Nancy Donley share a sense of mission that
takes them from tough-as-nails testimonial rhetoric to a mother's
empathetic ``I've been in that ICU-waiting room'' tears.
</P>
<P>
   In the trenches for six years now, Heersink, 43, admits to
wanting to devote more time to her six children, particularly
Damion's younger siblings, ages 2 1/2 to 16. She needs to return to
her suburban ``mom'' things in her 65,000-population town:
attending basketball and soccer games, tending to tree houses,
gathering every night over dinner and the family prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to gracefully back out,'' she says one minute while
untangling her twin boys' fingers from her long hair. But the next
minute, she is fielding reporters' calls on her cellular phone,
revving up the fax machine, packaging material to send to worried
parents sitting in Atlanta ICU waiting rooms.
</P>
<P>
   She always makes it a point to express the gratitude of the good
fortune of her outcome, one she says was aided by her physician
husband, Marnix Heersink, knowing how to navigate hospital protocol
and treatment therapies, and a plasma-transfer procedure that
cleansed Damion's blood.
</P>
<P>
   It is a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   It is a burden.
</P>
<P>
   One her lanky 6-foot-4 adolescent son is just realizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he senses a huge responsibility to these kids who have
died,'' she says. ``He's a voice for children that have been
silenced.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Donley will never know where the
``what-I-want-to-be-when-I-grow-up'' jabber of her little redhead
would have led.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him my little monkey-boy. I don't know know why. I
guess he was always climbing around being a typical little boy,''
she says. ``He wanted to be a paramedic. He was always there to
help people, even asking how they were doing when he came into a
room. He was very unusual in that way, how he didn't just think of
himself. And he was only 6, just graduated kindergarten.''
</P>
<P>
   If Alex were alive today, he'd be 11 years old, the same age as
Damion Heersink when he suddenly developed a bad case of diarrhea
on his way to a Florida space camp.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy, 43, a real estate agent, says she and her husband, Tom,
only wanted one child, and they haven't changed their mind in the
years since losing sparkly-eyed Alexander Thomas on July 18, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Alex and he was perfection and we decided to stop at
perfection,'' she says quietly yet forcefully. ``He was everything
we wanted in a child. It just doesn't seem right to have another.''
</P>
<P>
   To contact S.T.O.P., call 1-718-246-2739; the victim hotline is
1-800-350-STOP
</P>
<P>
   Web site: http://www.stop-usa.org/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
