<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEMS WARNED: PARTY FACES EXTINCTION IF LOSES STATE ELECTIONS &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    (Eds: optional trim)
 &HT;    By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Democratic attorney general nominee Jim Mattox,
who resurrected his political career this year, sternly warned the
Texas Democratic Convention Saturday that the party will be near
extinction if it loses this year's statewide elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important convention in modern times because
if we do not leave here united ... we will lose these statewide
elections and will become irrelevant for the next 20 years,''
Mattox said. ``We can't allow that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention ended Saturday with the Democrats vowing to turn
the tide that led to major election defeats in 1994 and 1996. As
the Democrats organized for the fall elections, they elected their
first woman as party leader, former Republican Molly Beth Malcolm
of Texarkana.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the convention's speakers served as cheerleaders at a
pep rally, playing down their party's uphill battle against the
popularity of Republican Gov. George W. Bush and the apathy of
voters caused by the state's good economy. But Mattox gave the
convention a stiff slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox said Republican U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm was right two weeks
ago when he predicted that if Republicans sweep statewide this year
that dinosaurs will walk the earth before a Democrat wins the
governor's office again. Mattox said only 43 percent of the state's
voters identify themselves as Democrats and that is not enough to
win an election.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're to have a new majority for this Democratic Party, we
must reach out and find practical, pragmatic individuals who are
not looking just at ideology,'' Mattox said. ``They are looking for
creative ways to solve the problems we face.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattox, who has been considered one of Texas' most liberal
politicians over the past three decades, told the convention that
Democrats ``cannot worship at the altar of the New Deal any longer
... . We must look to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattox said he finds it ``gratifying'' to once again be in a
party leadership role just four years after many observers declared
him politically dead.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox was attorney general from 1983-90, but after his loss to
Ann Richards in the brutal 1990 gubernatorial primary many
Democrats were intent on driving Mattox out of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Richards pressured party leaders to keep Mattox out of the 1993
U.S. Senate special election, and the following year Mattox lost
the Democratic primary for the Senate nomination to millionaire
Richard Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, before the primary, some party leaders tried to find
a major opponent for Mattox in the attorney general's race but gave
up when then-Houston Mayor Bob Lanier turned them down. In the
latest Texas Poll, Mattox was the Democrat with the highest level
of voter support for the November general election, leading
Republican John Cornyn 44 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While Mattox emphasized the need for party unity, gubernatorial
candidate Garry Mauro tried to dissipate a perception that
Democratic elected officials are shunning his campaign. About 150
Democratic elected officials and candidates joined Mauro on the
convention's main stage in a display of support.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Texas Poll showed Mauro trailing Bush by more than 50
percentage points. Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock and dozens of
other Democratic office holders have endorsed Bush in the past
year. And Democratic lieutenant governor candidate John Sharp and
comptroller candidate Paul Hobby have distanced themselves from
Mauro's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm 30 points down, they're not going to be real gung ho
about campaigning with me,'' Mauro said. ``But when I'm three
points up, they'll all be there.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention adopted a party platform that largely reflected
Mauro's campaign agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The platform called for adoption of a constitutional amendment
to ban the sales tax from being extended to groceries and medicine.
It also demanded a Patient's bill of rights to require that health
maintenance organizations give their customers total freedom to
choose their own doctors.
</P>
<P>
   While the platform supported abortion rights in general, it did
not address the issue of whether to notify parents before giving a
minor an abortion. Outgoing party Chairman Bill White said that was
left out because Democrats were not united on the issue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the Republican convention earlier this month, Bush promised
to make passage of a parental notification law a ``key'' priority
of his next administration if he is re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   The convention also heard speeches Saturday from land
commissioner nominee Richard Raymond, agriculture commissioner
nominee Pete Patterson and Railroad Commission nominee Joe
Henderson, as well as Houston Mayor Lee Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating the themes of his own campaign last year, Brown
emphasized cultural diversity and government programs aimed at
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best and most effective government is the one that puts
people first,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his statement last week that he would address the
convention in a nonpartisan role, Brown joined the partisan
cheerleading by urging the delegates to go home and organize their
party's voters. ``We must get our voters to the polls,'' he said,
after asserting that nation is on an upswing because of President
Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
