<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-GERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOWITZKI WILL VISIT DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Mavericks have persuaded first-round draft pick Dirk
Nowitzki of Germany to come to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   How long he stays, however, is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Though Nowitzki said yesterday that he is leaning toward staying
in Germany for two years before coming to the NBA, the Mavericks
are flying him to Dallas today for a red-carpet tour of the city
aimed at persuading him to play here next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm ready for the NBA yet, but they are trying
to convince me,'' said the 20-year-old Nowitzki, who was measured
at 7 feet tall during a private workout for Mavericks coach/general
manager Don Nelson, assistant coach Donnie Nelson and owner Ross
Perot Jr. on Friday in Wurzburg. ``I think I want to stay here for
a year or maybe two, but it's still up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks, who engineered a three-team trade to acquire
Nowitzki and point guard Steve Nash in the NBA draft Wednesday, are
encouraged that he will visit Dallas and that his father, Jorg,
told his son yesterday to ``seize the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have agreed to let Nowitzki pursue his dream of
playing for Germany in the 2000 Olympics, allowing him to leave the
team for four-day periods in November and February 1999 to play in
qualification games. Nowitzki, who said he is ``too weak'' to play
on the world's ultimate playground, must believe that he will
receive significant playing time in Dallas and that the NBA's
probable lockout Wednesday will not severely stunt his basketball
development.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mavericks can't offer as much money as the four
European teams competing for his services, Nowitzki said yesterday
money will not be the deciding factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not important,'' said Nowitzki, who has offers of $2
million tax-free from teams in Spain and Italy, while the Mavericks
are limited to offering $1.3 million for next season. ``I've been
surprised by the Mavericks' visit and them wanting me to return
with them. I am very interested.''
</P>
<P>
   In what Donnie Nelson called ``the biggest recruiting trip in
team history,'' the Mavericks will introduce Nowitzki to Nash and
Mavericks star Michael Finley tomorrow morning, take him to one of
the team's basketball clinics for children and escort him on a tour
of Fort Worth-Dallas, including the site for the new arena.
Nowitzki, who can't sign a contract before Wednesday but could
agree in principle to play in Dallas next season, is scheduled to
leave Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson called Nowitzki ``one of the best players I've ever
seen,'' and Donnie Nelson echoed that praise yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got special, special skills for a guy his size,'' said
Donnie, who coached Nowitzki during his 33-point, 14-rebound
performance in a game against U.S. high school players in March in
San Antonio. ``I'm not saying he'll be an All-Star because a lot of
different factors go into that. But when he comes into his own,
he'll be one of best, most versatile players in the league.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
