<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-NAACP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP GATHERING DENOUNCES KLAN AND PANTHERS IN JASPER 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds: This story is a side to Jasper-KKK) 
 
 
By T.J. MILLING 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER _ While protesters hurled racial epithets across the town
square Saturday, a small group of black officials and area
residents gathered in a funeral home chapel and sang the old civil
rights hymn We Shall Overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Swaying to the music in the very room of Robinson's Funeral Home
where James Byrd Jr.'s torn body once lay, they sang the words,
``Black and white together, we shall overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The gathering of about 30 locals and officials of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People was at times
emotional but free of the divisive rhetoric in front of the county
courthouse, where a Ku Klux Klan rally had drawn about 50 black
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Diggles, an African-American who heads an East Texas
economic development council, denounced both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are wrong,'' he said, ``the Klan and the Panthers.'' He
lauded the Byrd family for its public plea for racial
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing over there at the courthouse is the worst in
people, and what we're seeing here is the best in people,'' added
Mike Bradford, the U.S. attorney from Beaumont, who came to inform
the group and hear complaints. ``This is what we need to be
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, mostly with blacks but including a few whites, was
one of a series the NAACP plans to hold here to gather information
and monitor the prosecution of the three white men accused of
dragging Byrd to death behind a pickup, dismembering him in the
process. Bradford said the investigation is nearing completion and
either state capital murder charges or federal civil rights charges
could be filed within a month.
</P>
<P>
   At present, Shawn Berry, Bill King and Russell Brewer Jr. are
charged in the case. Officials have said they will pursue the death
penalty against at least two of the men.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bledsoe, president of the state conference of NAACP
branches, called for a task force to investigate hate groups in
prison. King and Brewer have possible links to white supremacist
prison gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned about what's going on in prison, people
becoming more hardened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, who said he updates U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno
daily on the case, pledged to spare no expense to conclude the
investigation quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening over at the courthouse today,'' he explained,
``is reason why we don't want this lingering.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
