<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0244 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     06-27 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Column: England's passion is a national curse
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Wimbledon is a local institution, the mother church of
tennis. It is venerated by the Brits, whose circadian clocks are
set by the arrival of the fortnight.
</P>
<P>
   If the strawberries and cream are being served up on Church
Road, SW 19, then it must be summer. Even if it feels like the dead
of winter, which it did early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But soccer, nonetheless, is the English religion. And, head up
against the World Cup, lawn tennis takes a dusting.
</P>
<P>
   When England beat Colombia on Friday night to advance to the
World Cup's Sweet 16, Steffi Graf's loss to Natasha Zvereva became
a minor event. You had to dig through nine pages of World Cup
coverage in the Times and the Sun _ two newspapers at opposite ends
of the taste and sophistication spectrum _ to find a word about the
seven-time champion being ousted in the third round by a woman she
had defeated 17 times in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But had England's on-the-brink lads succumbed, oh boy. There
wouldn't have been enough ink to properly dissect the depth and
breadth of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits' last _ and only _ World Cup title came 32 years ago,
on the sacred sod at Wembley. It remains unlikely the current team
will stage a repeat on French soil, but that doesn't deter a doting
populace from daring to dream on. England gave soccer to the world
_ as well as the word ``soccer,'' from ASSOCiation Football _ and
hope springs eternal England will reclaim its birthright.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer team, economy booming
</P>
<P>
   The Lions' failures on the pitch long have been a symbol of the
national malaise. Now, with the country's economy in the midst of a
solid recovery, with London booming like never before in modern
times, it's hoped the footballers can find it within them to follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
   The TV audience for the Colombia game was estimated at 20
million. Friday evening, the usually snarled West End traffic had
thinned appreciably. Only mad dogs and American tourists wandered
about.
</P>
<P>
   Next up are the Argentines, in Saint-Etienne on Tuesday. The
Falklands War was a minor skirmish compared to the consequences of
this rematch.
</P>
<P>
   How seriously do the Brits take soccer? Kasey Keller, the
American-born U.S. team goalkeeper who plays in England's Premier
League, has at least a dozen documented namesakes in South London.
Such was his popularity when he starred for Millwall, possibly the
most rabid and rowdy of all soccer neighborhoods, that babies were
being christened Kasey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys and girls,'' Keller's wife said.
</P>
<P>
   At Arsenal's home stadium, in East London, there hangs a sign:
``Welcome to Highbury, The Home of Football.'' And it is. The
Gunners _ pronounced Gooners _ have a global following after 77
unbroken years of Premier League play. With a high percentage of
fans who really are fans, not beer-swilling cretins with tattoos
and shaved heads pretending to be fans, Arsenal long has stood as a
symbol of what's good about English soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, England always can be counted on to show a
different side, its ugly side, on the World Cup platform. France's
easy access has left it vulnerable to invasion by the drunken louts
known locally as ``yobs.'' Despite a virtual garrison of French
security police, the English ``supporters'' outdid themselves in
and around Lens before the Colombia match. As the Times' banner
headline noted: ``England win marred by 489 arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   With team comes hooligans
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the notorious hooligans _ including one guy
with 27 convictions for violent behavior _ were turned back at
Calais and Le Havre, and a ban on liquor sales was enforced over
much of the area, chaos resulted.
</P>
<P>
   Some 500 Brits went on a rampage outside the stadium before the
game, pelting police and passers-by with beer bottles. In the
Belgian port of Ostend, shops and bars were looted by Brits, and
skirmishes between the gendarmes and hooligans erupted in Lille, 30
miles from Lens.
</P>
<P>
   A possibly worse situation is feared for Saint-Etienne, in
central France near Lyon, for the Argentina match. There would be
bad blood between the two teams without the Falklands squabble for
a backdrop because of Diego Maradona's questionable ``Hand of God''
goal that eliminated the English 2-1 in the 1986 quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Revenge is being vowed by the morons who believe England's
``honor'' can be avenged with criminal behavior. It's a mystifying,
and terrifying phenomenon, for which there appears only one option:
Ban the Brits from the World Cup until the nonsense abates.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly fair to the players and their legions of
legitimate backers, but it seems a logical response to ridiculous
behavior. Something must be done, and I suppose shooting the
rowdies on sight is a bit extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Then again
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
