<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waltrip is not done yet
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Just when many people in the racing world looked at
Darrell Waltrip and saw his Winston Cup career permanently a lap
down, he caught a caution.
</P>
<P>
   With an impressive sixth-place finish at Pocono, Waltrip
reminded us _ again _ that he wasn't done, wasn't gone.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip led 10 laps late in the race. No fluke. Just a solid
outing when he needed it the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of years, I have struggled with a lot of
things,'' the 51-year-old Waltrip said. ``I know my career is
running short. I'm not trying to live off my past. I think I bring
an awful lot to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The man has a point. He has 84 Winston Cup victories, tied for
third with Bobby Allison on the all-time list; 59 poles, fourth
all-time; and three Winston Cup champonships. And he's the only
driver to win $500,000 or more in a season 18 times.
</P>
<P>
   But when Walthip's sponsorship evaporated, he did what most
honorable men do. He tried to keep his team together. Tried to keep
the people who were paying the bills happy. Tried to race. He
couldn't do any of them well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My racing was terrrible and I knew it was terrible,'' he said.
``I was down. I felt defeated. I felt like a loser. It was just the
worst of times. I came to the conclusion that the only way out was
to sell my team.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, to Tim Beverly, who loaned him to Dale Earnhardt, who
needed somebody to drive the No. 1 Pennzoil car while Steve Park
rehabiliated his broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly needed the time to get his new team up and running in
time for Walrtip to return for the Aug. 1 Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   Everything's on schedule. Waltrip begins testing his old No. 17
car soon, putting his heart and soul into that endeavor, just as he
did in working with Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   And his performace at Pocono has gone far in restoring in him
what most believed was gone. Anyone who saw his postrace interview
had to be moved by his passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big; this is big,'' Waltrip said, choking back tears.
``It has been so much fun, and I enjoy every minute of it. This is
my little oasis. The Lord was good to me. He saved me (when Beverly
came along) and gave me a little oasis, gave me time to catch my
breath and get my act back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's going to pay off in the long run. It won't be
too far away. I can win in this car (No.1). I knew I could a few
weeks ago. We ran hard. We raced 'em. They didn't drive by us. We
ran the best laps of the day when it counted, and that's all I care
about.''
</P>
<P>
   It was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
