<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shepherd McCall Pepsi 400 pick
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   Winston cup
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Shepherd, who has served as fill-in driver for several
teams this year, will be behind the wheel of the No. 96 Caterpillar
Chevrolet for the Pepsi 400 night race at Daytona International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd wasn't Buzz McCall's first choice. Hut Stricklin was.
But Stricklin, who was fired from the No. 8 Stavola Brothers, is
under a one-race contract to drive a second Andy Petree entry in
the 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's excting to have the opportunity Buzz has given me,'' the
56-year-old Shepherd. ``I really didn't want to miss the first
night race at Daytona. It's such a big event. The Cat car tested
well here, so I'm looking forward to a good ride under the
lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Childress team?
</P>
<P>
   After making changes to his two NASCAR teams, Richard Childress
is considering adding a third Winston Cup team next year. He's put
the thought on hold until he straightens out his two other teams,
which underwent major changes two weeks ago in Michigan. ``Right
now, our goal is to get these two cars _ Dale Earnhardt and Mike
Skinner _ back to running and getting our guys healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Partner for Spencer
</P>
<P>
   Add team owner Travis Carter to the list of possible multiple
teams in 1999. He's considering a second team, joining Jimmy
Spencer. ``It's the way to go these days,'' Carter said. ``Sharing
information has been beneficial, but the future is multiple-car
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch series
</P>
<P>
   Craven on mend
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, Ricky Craven will return to action this
weekend at Watkins Glen for the first time since suffering
post-concussion syndrome after the March Atlanta race. Craven
tested at the Glen last week and pronounced himself fit. He hopes
to return to the Winston Cup circuit at Daytona, if all goes well
in today's Lysol 200.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for redemption
</P>
<P>
   Having slumped to fourth in points, three-time Busch champion
Randy LaJoie sees Watkins Glen as the Redemption 200. He finished a
lap down in 21st place last year and comes to the Glen with recent
results a third at Pikes Peak and two 11ths at Dover and Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   LaJoie: ``It's time to turn up the wick.''
</P>
<P>
   Craftsman trucks
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's top 10
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top 10 things Mike Wallace and his crew have
planned before the July 4 Sears DieHard 200 in Milwaukee. 10)
Attend autograph-signing party at Solid Gold NASCAR Night; 9)
Sample the beer at Summerfest brew tents; 8) Visit five continents
in one day at the Milwaukee County Zoo; 7) Attend a Brewers game;
6) Spend a day on The Grand Avenue shopping at more than 130
specialty stores; 5) Take a ride on the Harley-Davidson Milwaukee
Iron Motorcycle Tour; 4) Try luck at the Potawatomi Bingo Casino;
take money; 3) Spend evening listening to Shania Twain at
Summerfest; 2) Take in the Firstar Fireworks display; 1) Watch
Wallace win the Sears DieHard 200.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Randy Tolsma had one of the worst records in the
Craftsman series after nine races: did not qualify four times,
didn't attempt two others and one top 10. He was 32nd in points.
Today, he's made every race, is seventh in points with five top
10s, qualifying out of the top 20 once. What's the difference?
``Simple,'' Tolsma said. ``We have better people, better trucks and
a better attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
