</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-LABOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reality of a lockout looming ever closer
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When the clock strikes midnight Tuesday, NBA business
will be shut down for the summer. The owners' threat of a lockout
will become a reality, and so the league that has never had a
stoppage in play faces perhaps its biggest challenge to keep that
streak intact.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations since April have wrought very little progress. The
talks were so bad last week they abruptly broke off without another
session scheduled before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The games next season are threatened because the sides likely
will not begin schedulingserious talks until late in the summer,
around September 1. And if talks do not progress rather rapidly
then, the owners' lockout could extend into the first week of
November, which would halt games.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the lockout prevents any player movement or
negotiation of contracts. So, players like the Hawks' Alan
Henderson, Chicago's Scottie Pippen, Phoenix's Antonio McDyess _
and more than 120 other free agents who anticipated the excitement
of free agency _ cannot negotiate a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Also, teams cannot discuss or make trades until a new collective
bargaining agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   The old agreement was deemed passe by the owners, basically,
when players salaries totaled nearly 57 percent of generated
income. As per a stipulation in the pact, the owners voted 27-2 to
reopen the agreement and hammer out a new one.
</P>
<P>
   There are fundamental problems with the obsolete deal that have
to be negotiated. For one, there is no middle class in the NBA. The
top players and highly drafted rookies get substantial money, while
the quality veterans are left, at times, to play for the $1 million
exception.
</P>
<P>
   The owners believe simply that player salaries are terribly out
of whack. They are unhappy that Minnesota's Kevin Garnett, a talent
that has not won a playoff series, can command a $121 million
contract extension after just two years.
</P>
<P>
   So, to remedy that, they want to eliminate the so-called Larry
Bird Exception, where a team may go to any lengths over the salary
cap to re-sign one of it's own players. It is something the Players
Association is hell-bent on keeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they start talking about eliminating the Bird
Exception,'' said New York's Buck Williams, the former union
president, ``they are talking about something sacred. That's
something that cannot be touched.''
</P>
<P>
   The other area the owners want touched up is the rookie salary
scale. In the old agreement, first-round draft picks got a
guaranteed three-year deal, with the top choice guaranteed about
$10 million. But those players _ many times unproven _ hold teams
hostage after two years because of the threat of signing elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Players Association's proposal of a five-year rookie scale
was rejected by the owners, who want a six-year deal with an option
(the team's) after the third season.
</P>
<P>
   Street and Smith's Sports Business reported that four NBA teams
lost money in 1996-97 and received as much as $3 million of
financial relief from the league. Those teams reportedly are the
Hawks, Los Angeles Clippers, Indiana Pacers and Golden State
Warriors. The league claims as many as 14 teams might need similar
help after last season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
