<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-KLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLAN RALLIES IN TOWN WHERE BLACK MAN WAS SAVAGELY SLAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The anguished peace of a small town reeling from
a brutal slaying was fractured Saturday by a spectacle of hate.
</P>
<P>
   As two dozen hooded Ku Klux Klansmen spewed racist rhetoric in
Jasper's historic courthouse square, police struggled to repel
nearly 30 black militants, including members of the New Black
Panthers and black Muslims, who repeatedly rushed at the white
supremacists, challenging them to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Wielding shotguns and strapped with ammunition, nearly two dozen
additional members of the Houston-based New Black Panthers were
barred from the square by the FBI, Texas Rangers, and local police.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous skirmishes erupted between sympathizers for the
factions, but only two arrests were made, for disorderly conduct,
and no one was seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hate versus hate, right in the town square,'' said Willie
Rhodes, a local logger. ``It's like a high-noon, country
shootout.''
</P>
<P>
   The backdrop to the showdown was the gruesome slaying of James
Byrd Jr., a disabled musician, on June 7 in what police have called
one of the most brutal hate crimes in the South in many years.
Three white supremacists were charged with beating Byrd, chaining
him to the back of a truck, and dragging him nearly 3 miles on a
country road, tearing his body to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The atrocity ignited national outrage and prompted many black
residents of Jasper to protest what they say is their second-class
status in a community controlled by whites.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Byrd's family had urged Jasper residents to boycott the
rally. Saturday
</P>
<P>
   ``Let this horrendous violation of the sanctity of life not be a
spark that ignites more hatred and retribution,'' Byrd's family
said. ``Rather, let this be a wake-up call for America _ for all
Americans. May it spark a new cleansing fire of self-examination
and reflection.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the vast majority of Jasper's 8,000 residents heeded
the appeal, several hundred spectators turned out, including scores
who heckled the white supremacists as they declared Jasper ``Klan
country.''
</P>
<P>
   KKK leaders, who disavowed any association with Byrd's alleged
killers, said they requested a permit to rally in Jasper because
the ``liberal media'' unfairly linked them to Byrd's murder and
because they wanted to restore the ``white pride'' that may have
been damaged in the fallout from the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jasper residents hailed members of the New Black Panthers
and black Muslims as they tried to break through police barriers
and confront the Klan groups from Texas and Louisiana. Several Klan
sympathizers said they had weapons ready in case of a
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to say to the Klan that you will no longer
intimidate and harass people, and if you get out of line today,
wishing to drag a black man behind a truck, we have brought our God
and our guns, and we will blast you to hell and back,'' said
Minister Quanell X, of the black Muslim movement in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Klan members declined the challenge. Many of them
recoiled as the black groups charged their cars as they drove away
from the courthouse after the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper officials, who said they had prayed for rain to wash out
the event, watched in vain in the steamy, 95-degree heat as the
street drama unfolded. For nearly two hours, a force of 200 law
enforcement offices struggled to maintain peace in the small,
usually quiet town center.
</P>
<P>
   A similar number of journalists, some of them from as far as
Japan and Sweden, scurried to record the scene, as the New Black
Panthers and black Muslims circled the courthouse, searching for a
gap in the police line around the Klan members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like this in my life,'' said Jasper
County Judge Joe Folk, ``and I hope I never do again.''
</P>
<P>
   On a weekend when the community traditionally prepares for its
annual Jasper Jamboree Fourth of July festival, a Klan sympathizer
waving a Confederate flag and carrying a knife was arrested outside
the local thrift shop. An ally of the Black Panthers was arrested
as he tried to lunge at a Lincoln Continental carrying away Klan
leaders after the rally. And supporters of the factions toted
placards with such messages as ``White Power'' and ``The Only Good
Fascist Is A Dead One.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not happy for any groups to come in and try to divide
our county,'' said Jasper Police Chief Homer Alexander. ``But we
made sure nobody's civil rights were violated, everybody got to say
what they wanted to say, and nobody got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Jasper residents said they were drawn to the showdown by
curiosity and a reluctance to miss one of the largest news events
in city history. Others said they turned out to denounce hatred,
and some said they attended as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   A few said they wanted to know if the KKK hoods covered faces
they knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know who these people are,'' Eddie Williams said.
``I got a family and I'm going to protect them any way I can. I
need to know if one of these guys is my friend, my banker,
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Byrd's slaying, many blacks have raised new questions
about the deaths of several Jasper residents in recent years,
including the 1989 hanging of Rodney Williams, whose family
believes he was killed for dating a white woman.
</P>
<P>
   Police ruled the case a suicide. But Abert Williams Jr.,
Rodney's father, said he believes authorities covered up evidence
to protect his son's killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was no suicide,'' Williams said. ``He loved himself and
God too much'' to kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   Other black leaders complained about the town's lingering
segregation, from the churches to neighborhoods to the public
cemetery, where Byrd was buried in a back section traditionally
reserved for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' said Reverend Ray Charles Lewis, a local
church pastor. ``From now on, we should take any steps necessary to
make clear that the KKK or anyone else are not safe violating our
rights. We will not live in fear.''
</P>
<P>
   On the road where Byrd died, more than 80 fading orange rings
mark the spots were police found parts of his body and his effects.
There is also a memorial to Byrd, a white cross inscribed with his
name and a biblical passage that condemns evil and promises that
``the meek shall inherit the Earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
