<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE TV BROADCAST OF CLINTON-ZEMIN EXCHANGE IS A FIRST FOR CHINA 
 
 

</HEADLINE>
 TV-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese expecting to see the news on government-run
television at noon Saturday tuned in to history instead.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that stunned but gratified President Clinton and his
delegation, the Chinese government let the freewheeling news
conference between the U.S. leader and President Jiang Zemin pour
live over the airwaves to a potential audience of 1.2 billion
people.
</P>
<P>
   There were none of the cuts and suspect translations that marked
earlier government-sanctioned broadcasts by U.S. presidents during
visits to China. The whole 70-minute exchange _ including Clinton's
comments about the Tiananmen massacre nine years ago and the two
leaders' pointed debate on their nations' differing views of human
rights _ was on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a live event quite like it,'' said a U.S.
diplomat with long experience in China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger,
said the show was probably the first live broadcast in China of
press conference by a visiting foreign leader ``and certainly was
the most extensive public discussion by far between a Chinese
leader and an American leader on human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese government spokesman Zhu Bangzao refused to say when and
by whom the decision was made to air the leaders' joint appearance.
But he relished the attention generated by the decision to permit
the telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has shown that China has adopted an open attitude and
would like people to know the different attitudes of different
sides,'' Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
   White House planners had urged Chinese officials to give the
American president's public comments as much air time as possible,
but as recently as Friday senior Clinton aides were uncertain how
much coverage to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping they'd do it, and they just threw the switch,''
said a White House official who participated in planning Clinton's
nine-day visit to China.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said he got an indication
from the Chinese side shortly before the news conference that it
would be broadcast live. But he was uncertain why.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're maybe reaching a point where they desire a more open
debate on human rights and want to present their position more
clearer to their own people,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry and Zhu said the live broadcast was not negotiated
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this was a question of concession or
compromise,'' Zhu said. ``It was a decision solely made by the
Chinese side.''
</P>
<P>
   Experienced Chinese observers, however, saw in the broadcast a
decision by Jiang to accommodate Clinton and repay his dedication
to the trip and the welcoming ceremony in Tiananmen Square in the
face of vocal criticism back home.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the broadcast ``must have been Jiang's decision at the
last minute,'' said Jasper Becker, Beijing correspondent of Hong
Kong's respected South China Morning Post. ``Clinton put his neck
on the line coming to Tiananmen and he was owed something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jiang had to know that Clinton would probably say something
about Tiananmen, and it would have been very embarrassing if
Clinton had said those things and then all the reports had been
about how they not were not broadcast in China,'' Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   Live broadcasts of any kind are rare in China, a U.S. diplomat
said, recalling only two recently: the 1997 ceremony in Hong Kong
marking the reversion of the British colony to Chinese control and
the session in which Zhu Rongji was elevated to the premiership
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   For earlier U.S. presidential visits, Chinese government
broadcasters have promised full coverage, but not delivered.
</P>
<P>
   During President Reagan's 1984 trip, after promising to
rebroadcast a key speech by the American leader during prime
viewing time, the Chinese edited the tape to delete references to
the Soviet Union and what White House spokesman Larry Speakes
called at the time ``values that Americans cherish.''
</P>
<P>
   When President Bush was in Beijing in 1989, a brief question and
answer session with Chinese television reporters was shown, but
accompanied by what U.S. diplomats called a ``doctored''
translation that toned down some of the president's comments on
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. television networks used the Bush trip in February 1989 and
the historic visit of Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev in May that
year as an excuse to bring their own satellite dishes into China _
and leave them in the country. That meant that the equipment was
still there less than four months later and could be used to beam
pictures of the Tiananmen demonstration around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The satellites were ordered shut down, with at least one U.S.
network broadcasting live as Chinese officials demanded that the
plug be pulled _ and the screen then going blank.
</P>
<P>
   Networks were not allowed to bring in new dishes for Clinton's
trip. All television transmissions for foreign broadcasters,
including those used by U.S. networks to send home reports on the
Clinton trip, are being handled through Chinese government
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
