<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0252 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-?-?-BOS &LR;      06-27 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-?-?-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton delivered a pointed lecture on human
rights to Chinese leader Jiang Zemin Saturday _ an extraordinary
reprimand because it was televised live across China to a citizenry
unaccustomed to such a bald critique of its government.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before the gathered media in the vast Great Hall of the
People, Clinton and Jiang traded accusations and explanations over
human rights and other issues for more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening moments, Clinton, fresh from a welcoming ceremony
in Tiananmen Square, condemned the Chinese government's actions in
the killing of hundreds of democracy protesters on the historic
plaza on June 4, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, and the American people believe, that the use of
force and the tragic loss of life was wrong,'' Clinton said. ``I
believe, and the American people believe, that freedom of speech,
association, and religion are the right of people everywhere and
should be protected by their governments.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Jiang thrice referred to the massacre as a ``political
disturbance,'' once saying, ``Had the Chinese government not taken
the resolute measures, then we could not have enjoyed the stability
that we are enjoying today.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the roundup of several dissidents last week at the
outset of the summit, Jiang replied, ``Any law-breaking activities
must be dealt with according to law.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials appeared excited with the session and
placed far more emphasis on its live broadcast than the relatively
modest policy accomplishments that came out of private meetings
between the leaders earlier in the day. White House spokesman
Michael D. McCurry described the news conference as ``remarkable,''
and Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger, called
it ``truly historic.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the barbs were softened by a flurry of compliments between
the two, in contrast to a similarly free-wheeling news conference
when Jiang arrived in Washington for a summit last October and the
pair tangled over human rights with nary a good word between them.
This time, the leaders seemed to develop a rapport that saw them
constantly laughing and joking with each other in private.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the exchanges, Jiang, animated and often smiling,
seemed to invite the debate, even prompting an exchange on Chinese
rule of Tibet, though no question had been asked about it.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Saturday, Clinton said, ``Our friendship may never
be perfect. No friendship is. But I hope it will last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly and privately, Clinton advisers expressed a belief that
the president's performance Saturday helped salvage a summit that
had increasingly seemed destined to fail. They also used the news
conference as vindication for the administration's policy of
engagement, in which Clinton and senior aides involve Chinese
leaders in high-level talks in hopes of affecting change in such
areas as human rights and trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reached Chinese people,'' said Winston Lord, a former
ambassador to Beijing and Clinton administration State Department
official. ``He shored up his domestic support for his trip and
policy, and he gained the respect of the Chinese leaders by being
firm. You don't deal with the Chinese by being restrained.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton extolled the virtues of his policy, saying at the news
conference, ``You should at least appreciate the fact that we now
have an atmosphere in which it is possible for us to be open and
honest and in great detail about this.''
</P>
<P>
   The day began with an arrival ceremony replete with a military
review on Tiananmen Square. The People's Liberation Army rifled a
21-gun salute.
</P>
<P>
   The event had raised the ire of human rights activists and
congressional Republicans, who said Clinton's appearance on
Tiananmen Square would demean the memories of the slain protesters
and help Chinese government officials put the massacre behind them.
The White House was so sensitive to the issue that officials had
wrongly told reporters in prior days that the ceremony was near the
square, not on it.
</P>
<P>
   The night ended with a festive state dinner at the Maoist-era
Great Hall of the People, where the military band played ``Chelsea
Morning'' and ``Home on the Range.'' The latter was played for
President Nixon when he came to Peking in 1972. Clinton even
conducted the band as it played ``Hands Across the Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your people are leading lives inconceivable just a generation
ago,'' Clinton told Jiang in a toast.
</P>
<P>
   In Jiang's toast, he said, ``China and the US differ in social
system, ideology, cultural tradition, and historical background and
are at different stages of economic development. It is nothing
strange that they should have some differences of views on certain
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Jiang, and their aides, met in the Great Hall for
over two hours and hashed out a series of modest agreements.
</P>
<P>
   First was a so-called detargeting agreement, in which China and
the United States will no longer aim nuclear missiles at each
other. Because the weapons can be retargeted in a matter of
minutes, the move was considered largely symbolic, but would at
least serve to lessen the chances of an accidental launch.
</P>
<P>
   In a breakthrough, China agreed to allow the United States to
inspect US high technology imports to be assured that they were
being used for the approved purpose.
</P>
<P>
   China vowed to ``actively study'' the formal adoption of the
Missile Technology Control Regime, and agreed, along with the
United States not to export medium- and long-range missiles to
Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
   On the economic front, the United States again declined to offer
China full support for admission to the World Trade Organization.
US officials expressed disappointment that China had not taken
greater steps to lower tariffs on American goods to help chip away
at the $50 billion annual trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area where progress was made was in new tariff cuts across
a wide range of products, though not enough, particularly in some
of the key export areas that are important to American workers and
producers,'' said Gene Sperling, Clinton's national economics
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   On the sensitive issue of Taiwan, Clinton told Jiang he
continues to support a ``one China'' policy and would not advocate
Taiwan for any international organizations that require independent
statehood. But Clinton also said it was crucial to the United
States that China resolve Taiwan's status peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Clinton urged Jiang to preserve the cultural and
religious identity of Tibet, which is under Chinese rule, and to
meet with Tibet's religious leader, the Dalai Lama, who fled Tibet
in 1959 after a failed uprising against China rule. The Dalai Lama
has said he has abandoned his goal of an independent Tibet, and is
now pushing for autonomous rule by Tibet as a part of China.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the Dalai Lama can publicly make the statement and
a commitment that Tibet is an inalienable part of China and he must
also recognize Taiwan as a province of China, then the door to
dialogue and negoiation is open,'' said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in the final words of the news conference, replied: ``I
have spent time with the Dalai Lama. I believe him to be an honest
man, and I believe if he had a conversation with President Jiang,
they would like each other very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to attend church in Beijing on Sunday and speak on
religious liberty, before embarking with his family on a day of
sightseeing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
