<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHOPRITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORENSTAM SHOOTS RECORD 65 AND LEADS INKSTER BY 2 STROKES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABSECON, N.J. _ Annika Sorenstam plays golf with such precision
and consistency that no one questioned her dominance here Saturday
when she made a bogey after 30 holes in the ShopRite LPGA Classic.
The premier player in women's golf responded with three birdies on
the last four holes and will have a two-shot lead over Julie
Inkster going into Sunday's final day of the $1-million tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After firing a 66 on opening day, Sorenstam shot a six-under-par
65 Saturday afternoon to match the best round by an LPGA player on
the 6,024-yard Bay Course at the Seaview Marriott Resort, where the
tournament returned after 11 years at Somers Point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very comfortable about my game,'' Sorenstam said after
her round of seven birdies and a bogey. ``The last month or so, my
game has come together, and I hope I stay calm and play a shot at a
time for another day. I like to be in contention and play in the
last group on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam will play in the last group with Inkster, a two-time
winner of this event, who shot a 66 Saturday and is alone at 133.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster started the day a shot behind Sorenstam and four others,
and she was the only player to threaten Sorenstam seriously at the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Barrett, who also shared the first-day lead, shot a 69 and
was alone in third at 135, a shot ahead of Rosie Jones (68), Donna
Andrews (68), Lorie Kane (67), Kelly Robbins (67), and Dawn
Coe-Jones, who shot a 65 to match Saturday's effort by Sorenstam
and Sherri Turner in 1987 as the best round on this course by an
LPGA player.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, Jones, Coe-Jones, Andrews, and Robbins never got to the
top of the leaderboard on an ideal day for golf after severe
thunderstoms suspended play twice on Friday. Rather, it was an
unknown who took the spotlight away from Sorenstam, but only for a
few holes.
</P>
<P>
   Smriti Mehra of India, who started the day a shot behind the
leaders, vaulted ahead with three birdies on the first four holes,
but she fell behind with bogeys on the sixth and ninth. Mehra is at
137 after shooting a 70 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam regained the lead from Mehra with birdies of her own
at the third and fifth holds, but found herself tied at the turn
tied at seven under par with Barrett and Inkster, the winner of
this tournament in 1986 and 1988. Inkster had three birdies on the
front nine.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam took the lead again with a birdie 2 on the 11th hole
but bogeyed the 371-yard 12th when she three-putted, falling into a
tie with Barrett. But Sorenstam regained the lead with a birdie on
the par-3 15th and extended it with another birdie on the last
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course fit my game pretty well the last two days,''
Sorenstam said. ``It's a course that makes you think and I like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Dibos of Peru (72), Caroline McMillan of England (72),
and Moira Dunn (71), who started the day tied for the lead with
Sorenstam and Barrett, faded early.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lopez was among those who missed the cut, which was at
one-over 143. Lopez shot a 71 Saturday with birdies on her last two
holes for a two-day total of 145.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the third time this season that she failed to make the
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle McGann, who with rounds of 65 and 64 edged Sorenstam to
win the tournament last year, also missed the cut. She shot a 75
Saturday to go with a 73 on Friday when her round included a
quadruple-bogey 8 on the 12th hole.
</P>
</TEXT>
