<HEADER>
A0258 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LABOR-HNS &LR;      06-27 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NBA lockout appears certain
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The labor landscape in the NBA is a lot like a typical Houston lawn
these days. If you don't water it, growth will be slow and, in some
cases, imperceptible.
</P>
<P>
   So it is in the Great NBA Labor Fight of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Because neither the owners nor the players have been willing to
water down their headstrong emotions the past few times they have
met at the bargaining table, the NBA expects to impose its second
work stoppage in four summers by locking out the players Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That is the beginning of the fiscal year in the NBA and the
league wants to freeze player movement until the sides can hammer
out a collective-bargaining agreement. What amounts to the owners
asking for give-backs because of botched bargaining negotiations in
the past will lead them to suspend all operations with players.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the league's standpoint, representing the owners, it's
really very simple under the current system _ too much money is
being paid out in salaries,'' said NBA deputy commissioner Russ
Granik, the league's point man in the negotiations. ``And we need a
new system that will bring salary growth in line with revenue
growth. And we anticipate very strong revenue growth over the next
four years. That's the big issue from a management standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem, from what we've been told from the
players' standpoint, is that they don't want any controls on
salaries for high-end players. And it's kind of difficult to get
those two positions to mesh. And it may be impossible. So we have
to find some other ground if we're going to make a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have been going on for more than two months.
Movement has been microscopic on both sides. Progress has been
nonexistent. A lockout is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Some issues are not so staggering. The players have agreed the
three-year rookie wage scale needs to be longer, as the owners
want. A new five-year rookie contract is likely to be in place in
the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But other problems figure to be bitter, hard-fought battles. In
particular, the owners want to do away with or limit severely the
so-called Larry Bird exception that allows teams to sign their own
free agents to any amount, regardless of how far over the league's
soft cap the contract might put a team.
</P>
<P>
   The players, meanwhile, are standing firm, saying they never
will give up the right to total free agency nor the idea of
re-signing with their own team at any amount. In addition, the
issue of random marijuana testing figures to be a sticking point.
</P>
<P>
   The players point to the fact owners never have volunteered to
open their books and let the bottom lines for all 29 teams be made
a public record. The NBA has become a global industry with billions
of dollars in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the players, along with a souped-up marketing machine,
that generate the incredible revenues, not only from ticket sales,
but merchandising sales and other money-making streams.
</P>
<P>
   The players believe the owners are balking at an agreement that
was reached in 1995 and originally was scheduled for six years. The
owners retained the option of reopening the collective-bargaining
agreement if, after three years, the money paid to players rose
above 52 percent of the defined gross revenues. This money also is
called basketball-related income.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1997-98 season, the players received more than $950
million in salaries. This represented approximately 57 percent of
all basketball-related income.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the owners voted 27-2 on March 23 to reopen
negotiations, effectively nullifying the final three years of the
'95 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners agreed that 52 percent was a point at which the
agreement would not be working,'' commissioner David Stern said.
``The owners could easily have not reopened the agreement. But at
that point, losses would have become certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a serious economic issue. The fact is that we will have
paid out almost a billion dollars in compensation (this season)
and, under any scenario I can imagine, we will continue to pay out
more than that each year so that overall compensation will continue
to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not running away from the payment. But we need to slow
the growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The players see it differently. Patrick Ewing, president of the
players' union, and NBA Players Association executive director
Billy Hunter believe the owners want a built-in mechanism to
protect them from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the players' responsibility, the union heads say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider it to be the players being asked to protect
the owners from themselves,'' Stern said. ``I think of it more as,
we have a lot of money to pay out. Why don't we find a way to make
sure that this system is intelligent, that it maintains competitive
balance and that it reduces pressure on teams to continually raise
ticket prices in a double-digit way, because that's a spiral that
doesn't seem to be yielding an intelligent business result.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said as many as nine teams this year will receive some
sort of subsidy _ a profit-sharing boost, if you will _ from the
NBA to make up for shortfalls on the bottom line. Only four teams
received such subsidies last year.
</P>
<P>
   The way the current agreement has been going, Stern claims half
the teams in the NBA would be losing money by the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   So the owners are ready to do whatever is necessary to batten
down the financial hatches. They saw what a work stoppage did to
baseball, which lost the World Series in '94 because of a players
strike and never has fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the owners claim they have solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners voted 27-2 to open up the collective-bargaining
agreement, and they did so knowing what the risks are,'' Stern
said. ``They did not receive a sugar-coated presentation about what
the risks are that are associated with reopening a
collective-bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it fair to say that this situation reflects mistakes at the
bargaining table in the past? Yes. We've managed to keep the wolf
from the door over the years by virtue of a system that has more or
less worked and by the infusion of new dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not working now.''
</P>
<P>
   The lockout comes at a time when the NBA faces crossroads in
other areas as well, Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had by NBA standards a very successful year,'' he
said. ``That said, we know we're in the midst of collective
bargaining and we know that eventually, if not sooner, Michael
Jordan will be retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we also know that we've had sort of an interesting year
with respect to Latrell Sprewell. But that's life in the NBA. On
balance, we're very happy about where the NBA is and we think its
growth is going to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   But how that growth is distributed appears to be leading to the
sort of infighting that could have a long-term impact if a
settlement isn't reached during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA never has lost any games to a work stoppage. But the
clock is about to start ticking. And if they don't come up with a
workable agreement for both sides in the next three months, those
October training camps could be in danger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
