<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four children with E. coli remain in area hospitals
 &HT;    By David Pendered
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Four children with confirmed E. coli infections
remained hospitalized Saturday in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials, acting on requests from the parents, have
not identified the children.
</P>
<P>
   At Egleston Children's Hospital, a 3-year-old boy, admitted June
20, remained in good condition. At Scottish Rite Children's Medical
Center, a 3-year-old boy, admitted June 20, remained in serious
condition. A 2-year-old girl, admitted June 15, was in critical
condition. And a 4-year-old girl, admitted June 18, was also in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Two little sisters and a 5-year-old boy from Georgia who
survived a bout of the E. coli bacteria were discharged Friday from
these hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Two sisters, age 6 and 2, were sent home from Egleston, where
they had been hospitalized since June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center sent home a 5-year-old
boy who was hospitalized June 23.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a fourth child, admitted June 23 and suspected of
having the disease, was discharged Friday from Scottish Rite. The
youngster's age and gender were not made public. Lab tests were not
complete on whether the child had E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
