<HEADLINE>
CHINA SUMMIT CALLED A SUCCESS, DESPITE A FEW THORNY ISSUES 
 
 
 
BY CRAGG HINES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The Clinton administration, painting the summit with
China as a success, praised progress on nuclear nonproliferation
issues Saturday but conceded key decisions still lay ahead for the
Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, U.S. national security adviser, said
the nuclear control agreements approved by Presidents Clinton and
Jiang Zemin came ``as China increasingly becomes part of the global
nonproliferation regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger acknowledged, however, the incremental nature of some of
the steps announced after Clinton and Jiang met for about two hours
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Most elusive was concrete action on defusing the nuclear
confrontation in southern Asia, where regional rivals India and
Pakistan each recently tested nuclear devices. The gist of a
three-page joint statement on the troubling development was that
Washington and Beijing would continue to consult closely.
</P>
<P>
   Given China's edgy relations with India and historic military
support for Pakistan, little more of substance was expected on the
thorny issue.
</P>
<P>
   The American side was heartened by the Chinese decision to agree
to actively study joining the Missile Technology Control Regime, an
international pact that limits export of nuclear know-how and
equipment for warhead delivery systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, what does that mean?'' Berger asked, anticipating
questions about the nebulous nature of the Chinese promise. He
called it ``an important step'' toward Beijing fully subscribing to
the control agreement. Actual agreement to the MTCR, he said, would
be ``a very significant development in terms of the sales of
missile technology worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the interim step followed a pattern of China's
inching up to finally signing international accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese often jump across the river in two or three
steps,'' Berger said. In the case of the MTCR, the Chinese began
several years ago by saying they would observe the regime's
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that ``general commitment'' did not necessarily mean
China was observing MTCR's detailed list of prohibited sales, ``and
it's not binding in any kind of international way.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House was also encouraged by what it saw as
flexibility in China's ultimate decision to agree that each nation
would drop the other as a target of intercontinental nuclear
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the deal, Beijing had to drop its demand that
Washington adopt a ``no-first-use'' policy for its nuclear arsenal
_ a step the Clinton administration, following long-established
U.S. policy, refused to take. Non-nuclear U.S. allies, including
Japan and NATO nations, have depended on U.S. nuclear weapons as a
last resort should they face defeat from conventional forces.
</P>
<P>
   China, which was the first country to make a ``no-first-use''
pledge, viewed its demand that the United States follow suit as a
way of cutting into the Pentagon's clear nuclear advantage. Beijing
also worried that the promise of the U.S. ``nuclear umbrella'' for
Japan constituted what Li Zhaoxing, Chinese ambassador in
Washington, called ``a sort of nuclear threat to China.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidents also approved agreements to:
</P>
<P>
   Strengthen controls on export of ``dual-use'' chemicals, those
that have legitimate commercial uses but also could be weapons
components.
</P>
<P>
   Allow U.S. inspections to make certain that high-technology
exports to China are not diverted into unauthorized military uses
and are not passed on to another country.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the issue of U.S. export waivers for additional
Chinese launch of American satellites did not come up in the
presidents' talks.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is controversial because of allegations that a U.S.
company aided China in making its missiles more accurate, which
could be a security breach. The company, Loral Space and
Communications, is headed by Bernard Schwartz, the leading
individual contributor to the Democratic National Committee during
the 1996 election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our view is that while there are some instances of
private companies being investigated, that our policy with respect
to satellite launches on Chinese missiles is one that serves the
national interest and has not compromised our security,'' Berger
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
