<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DRAFT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS GO FOR SIZE, ATTITUDE IN DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not since 1992 have the Stars' selections been so sparse in an
NHL entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   But if 1992 is any indication _ Jere Lehtinen was tabbed at 88th
and Juha Lind at 178th _ the Stars are hoping yesterday's entry
draft in Buffalo, N.Y., will yield at least a couple of NHL
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do in any draft is take the ones you think can
make it and hope for the best,'' said Craig Button, Stars director
of scouting. ``We think we were able to get some quality
prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman John Erskine will have the best chance of making it,
although all of the players taken are expected to play at least two
more seasons of junior hockey before even getting a chance to move
to the Stars' affiliate in Kalamazoo, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The 39th pick overall, Erskine has size (6-foot-4, 200 pounds)
and attitude (205 penalty minutes in 55 games played). NHL Central
Scouting said of Erskine, who plays with London of the Ontario
Hockey League: ``has good size and uses it to play an aggressive
and intimidating style of game ... a hard hitter who punishes
opponents in front of the net ... a lot of desire, eager to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection, a day after Erskine's 18th birthday on Friday,
was quite a gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great, it's the next steppingstone,'' Erskine said.
``I've always wanted to play in the NHL, and to be drafted by a
great organization like Dallas makes it well worth the wait.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who had the last pick (27th) in the first round as a
result of having the best regular-season record in the NHL, decided
to hedge their bet by picking up an extra pick. They traded the
27th pick to the New Jersey Devils in exchange for the 39th and
57th picks _ passing up the highly rated Ramzi Abid (50 goals, 266
penalty minutes in 68 games), who went to Colorado at 28th. The
Stars previously had traded away their second-round selection in
this year's draft, their fourth-, fifth- and eighth-round picks,
and Button said getting two quality players was better than taking
someone like Abid.
</P>
<P>
   With the 57th selection, the Stars took speedy winger Tyler
Bouck (pronounced Bowk) from Prince George of the Western Hockey
League. Bouck has two years of junior experience and is a teammate
of 1996 Stars draft pick Joel Kwiatkowski. Bouck had 11 goals and
26 assists in 65 games. He is projected as a hard-working,
third-line winger.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars chose center Gabriel Karlsson with their 86th overall
pick. Karlsson had 11 goals and 15 assists in 27 games last season
with Sweden's HV '71.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
