<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-KKK-HNS &LR;      06-27 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-KKK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JASPER, POLICE KEEP KKK AND BLACK PROTESTERS APART BUT NOT
QUIET  
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
and   T.J. MILLING 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, TEXAS _ Ignoring pleas from the community to stay away,
25 Ku Klux Klan members and about twice that many black protesters
from Houston and Dallas converged Saturday on Jasper, scene of a
racially motivated slaying three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Police were largely successful in keeping the groups apart, with
only occasional skirmishes and two arrests for disturbing the
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are relieved that no one was injured, there was no property
destroyed and there were only two minor arrests,'' Jasper County
Sheriff Billy Rowles said after the hour-and-a-half rally.
</P>
<P>
   There were times, however, when flaring tempers appeared to
match the 96-degree temperature on Jasper's courthouse square.
</P>
<P>
   Groups of eight or 10 black militants marched several times up
to the red plastic fence barricades that surrounded the area where
18 robed and hooded and seven unrobed Klansmen held Confederate and
other flags and shouted racist slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Before the noon rally got under way, about 50 African-Americans,
mostly members of the New Black Panther Party from Dallas, gathered
at a staging area across the street from the police station, well
east of the courthouse square. About 10 of the men were armed with
rifles and shotguns, which they assured reporters were loaded. They
said they wanted to protect Jasper's black residents from the KKK.
</P>
<P>
   A contingent of leaders went, unarmed, to confront the KKK,
after which the whole entourage marched down some Jasper streets
shouting, ``Black power!''
</P>
<P>
   When several of the armed men attempted to cross the barricades
onto the square, police threw back their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black people, we can take these bastards. We can run over the
damn police and take their ass,'' yelled former Nation of Islam
spokesman Khallid Muhammad in an unsuccessful charge.
</P>
<P>
   Klan leaders said they were there to denounce the slaying of
James Byrd Jr., a 49-year-old black man who was beaten and dragged
behind a pickup for almost three miles on June 7, and to counter
reports that at least two of the three suspects in the case may
have ties to white supremacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the Klansmen also took the opportunity to air their racial
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hell with the negroes and their special programs,'' shouted
one.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Flinn, imperial wizard of the Vidor-based Knights of the
White Kamellia, complained that a white man had been killed by a
black man a week earlier than Byrd's death ``and nobody claimed
that was a racial crime.''
</P>
<P>
   He said most white men sent to Texas prisons have to join gangs
such as the Aryan Brotherhood to protect themselves from blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In prison you're not going to call a block meeting to work out
racial problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jasper is part of the invisible empire,'' said Rick Anderson,
grand titan of the Knights of the White Kamellia. ``Make no mistake
about it, this is Klan country.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments were not reflected by most people in the racially
mixed crowd of perhaps 100 spectators. Many chanted, ``KKK, go
away!''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper officials had asked residents to stay away, and many said
beforehand they were praying for rain not only to ease a two-month
drought but also to dampen the rally.
</P>
<P>
   There were no showers, but the stay-at-home message apparently
worked for most people in this East Texas timber town of 8,000.
Most of the locals who did attend appeared angry at the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Resident John Handy, 73, marched along the streets around the
square during the rally with a sign proclaiming ``Jesus is the
answer.'' He said the Klan and black militant groups were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-towners listed a variety of reasons for coming. Some had
marched in civil rights protests of the past, others simply were
curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see a sad day in Texas history,'' said Sandra
Kanak of Rosenberg, whose family owns a vacation home on nearby Sam
Rayburn Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Curry, a 39-year-old bicycle mechanic from Hitchcock,
said he came to Jasper with his video camera to record ``the real
truth'' of the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The liberal media don't show it all,'' said Curry, who is
white.
</P>
<P>
   Two college students from Jasper, Joe Hailey, who attends
Abilene Christian University, and Sterling Popejoy, who attends
Texas A&AMP;M, set up a camera on the second floor of a building
Popejoy's father owns on the square. The camera was hooked to a
computer and instantly projected images of the rally onto the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just thought it might be something interesting to see,''
said Hailey.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Butler of Houston, who grew up in Jasper and said she was a
distant cousin of Byrd, held aloft a large American flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to show them (the Klan) that we are not
intimidated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Rowles said about 150 officers from at least 10 or 15
different departments _ mainly Texas Rangers and Department of
Public Safety troopers _ were on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The only arrests came at the end of the rally when two men _ one
white and one black _ were arrested in separate incidents on
disturbing the peace charges. Both quickly bonded out, Rowles said.
</P>
<P>
   The platoons of officers and the crowd were matched in size by
the media. News reporters from as far away as Europe converged on
the square.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the KKK that stirred most Jasper residents to anger.
Pauline Leach, 47, screamed threats at Klansmen as they loaded into
cars behind the courthouse to drive out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cops and them are all the same,'' she said, ``they wear
blue in the daytime and white at night.''
</P>
<P>
   When the rally was over, Rowles commented that he'd ``ruined a
new $65 hat'' with sweat, but said he was glad to have the day
over.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't quite, however. About that time, officers got a radio
report of black militants being along Huff Creek road, where Byrd
was dragged to his death. An officer at the scene requested 20
officers to help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep a low profile,'' Rowles advised the officers to responded
to the call.
</P>
<P>
   He later said the group's appearance on the road resulted in
nothing more than a traffic jam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
