<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-JASPER-COX     06-27 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-JASPER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Racial drama plays out in Jasper with two arrests, none hurt
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino and Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A surreal drama of racial hostility played out
on the tree-shaded courthouse square Saturday as white-robed Ku
Klux Klan members rallied and black militants repeatedly tried to
storm the fence protecting the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   State troopers with riot gear repelled the New Black Panther
Party members several times as they tried to reach the 25 Ku Klux
Klan members, who made speeches about white power and ``violent
Negroes.''
</P>
<P>
   The day ended without any injuries but two people were arrested
for disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom-line is no one was hurt, no property was destroyed,
and no one's civil rights were violated,'' said Jasper County
Sheriff Billy Rowles.
</P>
<P>
   The Klan members cut short their two-hour rally by a half-hour,
only to be rushed by black militants who tried to confront them as
they were getting into their cars. Law officers wrestled a black
man against the trunk of a car, arresting him for disorderly
conduct. During the incident, officers screamed at by-standers and
reporters to stay back .
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle _ which was prompted by the gruesome June 2 murder
of James Byrd Jr. _ drew about 200 onlookers and an equal number of
journalists. One hundred and fifty officers from 15 local, state
and federal agencies were in the Jasper County Courthouse area.
City officials had asked Jasper residents to stay home and ignore
the Klan rally. But some African American residents said they came
to show the Klan they are not intimidated by their tactics and to
tell them to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not scared,'' said Mandy West, a Jasper resident, who
taunted the Klan members to take off their masks. ``It's not
Halloween,'' she yelled.
</P>
<P>
   One of the robed Klansmen was Rick Anderson, a property manager
from Austin who is the grand titan of the western province of the
Knights of the White Kamellia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drunken act of violence that took the life of James Byrd
was indeed a disaster,'' he told the crowd. ``What on God's earth
could causes someone to do such a thing?''
</P>
<P>
   The Klan called the rally in Jasper to denounce Byrd's murder
and to make it clear the three white suspects accused of killing
him by dragging him behind a pickup truck were not Klansmen. But
the Klan also had another message: ``White power!'' they shouted
again and again.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 members of the New Black Panther Party came with
rifles, but they were not allowed to bring them near the
courthouse. Police had barricaded a nine-block area around the
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to the courthouse, the New Black Panthers
distributed fliers to local residents that said, ``Load your
shotguns. Load your rifles. Load your guns!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sit on your porches, stand in your yards and protect
yourselves and your homes from behind closed doors.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Black Panther party was created in Dallas in the early
1990s, but members of the original Black Panther party of the 1960s
have distanced themselves from the new group because it preaches
anti-white messages and violence. The Black Panther party sued the
New Black Panther Party in 1996 to protect its trademark name and
won a court order to prevent the new group from using the Panther
name or symbol.
</P>
<P>
   At Saturday's rally, the Klan members said they are the
guardians of white rights, which they fear are being diminished by
affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blacks have the NAACP looking after them. The Hispanics
have the LULACs looking after them. And the homosexuals have AIDS
taking care of them,'' said Michael Lowe of Waco, a Texas leader of
the Knights of the KKK.
</P>
<P>
   While about 50 Klan supporters in the courthouse crowd applauded
the Klan speeches and occasionally shouted out for ``White Power,''
most of the onlookers were African Americans heckling the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey hey, go home. The KKK has got to go,'' many yelled in
unison trying to drown out the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Klan claimed they were already home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Klan country, has been Klan country and will be Klan
country from now on,'' said Darrell Flinn, imperial wizard of
Knights of the White Kamellia.
</P>
<P>
   While city officials deny there is a racial problem in Jasper,
civil rights experts and some black Jasper residents say
discrimination is prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism is alive and well in East Texas,'' said Mark Potok,
editor the Alabama-based Southern Poverty Law Center's quarterly
journal that tracks white supremacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the deep South,'' he said of Japer, which is
55 percent white and 42 percent black. ``It's not a part of the
West. This was slave-holding Texas. That's why the region is much
blacker than most of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
