r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     06-27 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-U.S. INFLUENCE UP NORTH HURTS HITCHCOCK AT AWARD TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
The award is supposed to go to ``the head NHL coach adjudged to
have contributed the most to his team's success.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which makes it a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock contributed mightily to whatever success the Stars
attained this season. He was the glue that held the team together
through thick, thin and Bryan Marchment. He was the anchor that
kept the team playing at a high level for seven months, amid an
epidemic of sprains, strains and arthroscopic surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   The Jack Adams Award is supposed to be based on accomplishments
during the regular season. And who accomplished more during the
1997-98 season than the team that was 49-22-11 and won the
Presidents' Trophy with 109 points?
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the balloting for the Adams Award was announced at the
NHL's annual gala last week, Hitchcock finished neither first nor
second.
</P>
<P>
   Good ol' boy Pat Burns of Boston was named the winner, with that
icon of Montreal's past glories, Larry Robinson of the Los Angeles
Kings, coming in second.
</P>
<P>
   Hitch finished third. Somebody, therefore, needs to help with
the math here. Team finishes first equals coach finishing third?
</P>
<P>
   What next _ a glowing puck?
</P>
<P>
   This is not to disparage Burns, whose Bruins made a 30-point
leap in the standings. Nor is it to imply that Robinson, one of my
old heroes, didn't do marvelous things in resuscitating the Forum's
Other Team.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns inherited a Boston team that should have won 40 games
the season before. He is like the service man summoned in the
middle of the winter night, who pokes around the family furnace and
announces, ``Your pilot light was out. That'll be $250.''
</P>
<P>
   For this, you get named coach of the year?
</P>
<P>
   No, because the reasons for snubbing Hitchcock go deeper than
that.
</P>
<P>
   To the average Canadian, hockey is more than seven months of
headlines and Don Cherry's sport coats. Canadians adore hockey with
a passion unequaled in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we have Cubs fans. Packers fans. Bulls fans. Red Wings fans.
</P>
<P>
   But Canadians are hockey fans, and when one Canadian team is
ousted from the NHL playoffs _ as they invariably do lately _
Canadians pull for another.
</P>
<P>
   And Canadians worry. They have seen teams in Quebec City and
Winnipeg move south to warmer and wealthier climes and nearly saw
the Edmonton Oilers follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians worry that their six teams have to compete for their
most critical commodity _ players _ in U.S. dollars while earning
revenues in Canadian dollars. They worry that most of the 20 U.S.
teams are in larger markets. And they worry that the average club
payroll of the cost-conscious Canadian teams is $8.4 million less
than the U.S. teams' average.
</P>
<P>
   What's this have to do with Hitchcock?
</P>
<P>
   His owner, Tom Hicks. And all that Hicks, the Stars and the city
of Dallas represent.
</P>
<P>
   To the part of the league that looks at things through maple
leaf-clouded glasses, Hitchcock coached a rich, store-bought team
that represents all that is ``wrong'' with today's NHL. Free agents
want to play for the Stars. A new arena is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   It might be silly to think that a voter would cast a ballot
against Hitchcock for all these symbolic reasons. But let me
suggest that those reasons have contributed to the mind-set that
some have about the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Hitch can't win. He works for the league's Steinbrenner. More
poignantly, the NHL's Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The Adams Award is selected by the NHL Broadcasters Association.
Hmm _ does Dale Hansen belong to the NHL Broadcasters Association?
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock actually had seven more first-place votes than
Robinson in the balloting. But Burns was a runaway winner with 306
points to Robinson's 149 and Hitchcock's 123. Outrageously, 52 of
the 87 ballots did not name Hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not blame Canadians. Let's blame the mind-set that compels
the league to think that all Hitchcock has to do is ring up the
cash register and make up the lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   It will be curious to see what happens when Team Canada has to
pick its next coach for the World Championships and 2002 Winter
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious choice is a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock has played a huge role in turning around this
franchise. He has earned the respect of his players, and his record
speaks volumes. He is a great story.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the NHL broadcasters keep missing it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 2126EDT &QL; 
