<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0279 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RODEO-STAR-PARALYSIS-     06-27 2494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-STAR-PARALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATFUL OF HOPE FOR FORMER CHAMPION BULL RIDER JEROME DAVIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ On a steamy Saturday night, approximately
8,000 rodeo fans screamed a welcome loud enough to shatter glass
when legendary bull rider Tuff Hedeman pushed wheelchair-bound
Jerome Davis across the dirt arena floor.
</P>
<P>
   After Davis was introduced under a spotlight in the darkened
coliseum arena, the injured former world champion slowly raised his
hand over his western hat and formed a fist.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture symbolized Davis' rodeo life of defying the odds.
Three years ago, he became the first bull rider with a residence
east of the Mississippi to win a world title. But three months ago,
he began facing the challenge of his life when the bull, Knock 'Em
Out John, broke Davis' neck during a show in Fort Worth, leaving
the 25-year-old paralyzed from the chest down and with soaring
medical bills that could pile up to $1 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy may have shortened Davis' career by 10 years, what
would be comparable to permanently sidelining a running back like
the Cowboys' Emmitt Smith after five 1,000-yard seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as just another injury,'' said Davis, who firmly
believes that he will walk again. ``During the years that I
competed, I had my share of injuries that sidelined me from bull
riding for a period of time. So I look at this one the same way. I
don't sit back and mope about it. But unlike the other injuries,
this one is just going to take a little longer to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic energy from last weekend's Jerome Davis Championship
Challenge IV in Charlotte might have been part of the healing
process. It was Davis' first appearance at a rodeo show since the
crippling injury.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is a founding father of Professional Bull Riders, an
organization that conducts a lucrative national tour of shows
devoted solely to bull riding. The association has sanctioned the
annual bull riding event in Charlotte since 1995 in honor of Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, Davis attended as a spectator and provided color
commentary from the announcer's stand as each competitor prepared
to ride. Then, Knock 'Em Out John appeared in a chute. It was his
time to buck.
</P>
<P>
   After the bull exploded out of the gate and unceremoniously
dumped its rider in a few seconds, Davis informed the crowd that
this was the animal that crippled him. But that revelation came
only after the ride had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to build the bull up by saying that this was
the bull that hurt me while the cowboy was getting ready to ride,''
Davis said. ``All that would have done was put negative thoughts in
the rider's mind. With me, it was just a deal that happened by
accident. I've had a lot of bulls hit me in the face and I've been
knocked out several times, so it was something that could have
happened on any other bull.''
A rodeo camp Davis was reared in the small North Carolina town of
Archdale, a suburb of Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he lives in a two-story white house on a hill in a
sparsely populated area. The house is surrounded by large trees
that hang over decorative wooden furniture and wagon wheels. From
the back of the house, a wooden deck overlooks a meadow with a
rodeo arena and lush grassland for livestock.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Davis has purchased rodeo livestock and
conducted weekly bull-riding jackpots at the small ranch. The
house, which now is equipped with a wooden walkway for wheelchairs,
has been in Davis' family for more than four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the house, the living room table is a glass-covered wagon
wheel with gold-and-silver belt buckles embedded between the
spokes. Atop another coffee table, there's a classic photo of the
late, legendary bull rider Freckles Brown, who stunned the rodeo
world when he won the world title in 1962 while in his early 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The walls are decorated with rodeo posters and back numbers from
high-profile rodeo shows. But the memento that stands out is a
framed collection of color photos, one of each of the 10 rides and
the scorecard from the 1995 National Finals Rodeo when Davis
secured the world title.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are bull horns and deer horns mounted on the
walls, and a ``Welcome Home Jerome'' banner hangs from a staircase.
As Davis sits in his wheelchair and watches TV on a large screen,
there's a sense that he hasn't forsaken rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I did,'' Davis said of bull riding. ``Everything
revolved around rodeo. That will be with me until I die.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the rodeo memorabilia, the house is stocked with
medical equipment, such as wheelchairs, a specially designed bed
and pill bottles.
</P>
<P>
   It takes Davis' fiancee, Tiffany Brady, 23, up to three hours to
prepare Davis for a public appearance. The daily routine includes
taking Davis' blood pressure, giving him about 20 pills, helping
him with range-of-motion exercises and bathing him. Each night, she
rolls Davis over in bed every two or three hours to prevent him
from getting bed sores.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I did was jump in and began helping him the first night he
was sick,'' Brady said. ``I've been like a nurse ever since. When
someone becomes paralyzed, it's a 24-hour-a-day job. It's not like
you can just jump up and go somewhere. And when you put clothes on
him, it's like picking up 140 pounds of dead weight, but I've
learned how to manage.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady, the daughter of a rodeo livestock contractor, has kept an
upbeat attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many girls who are 23 have only gone and hung out in bars,''
she said. ``But I've gone all over the country to rodeos with
Jerome. I just think of what most girls haven't gotten to do and
how fortunate I am to have done all of the things that we've
done.''
A crushing blow Brady was in Fort Worth on March 14 when Davis was
injured at the Tuff Hedeman Championship Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had to face Knock 'Em Out John in the first round. About
five seconds into the ride, Davis lost control of the bull and
tumbled over the front of the animal. His head collided with the
bull's horns, knocking Davis unconscious. Then, he was thrown head
first into the arena dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had no feeling in his legs when he was examined by the
Justin Sportsmedicine team at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum. He was
taken out of the arena on a stretcher and rushed to Fort Worth's
John Peter Smith Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit of it I can remember,'' Davis said. ``I can
remember Tiffany talking with me. I said, `I can't feel my legs'
and she said, `You're just numb.' I said, `I really can't feel
anything.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Davis had fractured the sixth and seventh vertebrae at the base
of his neck. After he underwent surgery the next day to stabilize
the spine and neck, medical officials said he was not expected to
walk again.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Davis has limited use of his arms and fingers. He cannot
feed himself, but he can adjust his cowboy hat. Brady signs Davis'
name for autograph seekers.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' father, Carson, said his son always has been aware of the
potential danger of climbing on 2,000-pound bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood that this could happen when he started riding,''
the elder Davis said. ``Sometimes you have to sacrifice _ you don't
think this type of thing is going to happen, but it did to
Jerome.''
</P>
<P>
   But these types of injuries do happen, and rodeo cowboys think
about them all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who rides knows it's very dangerous,'' said K.J.
Pletcher, a bull rider who was Davis' traveling partner. ``I'm just
glad that it didn't kill Jerome.''
The wonder boy During Davis' childhood years in North Carolina, the
thought of gaining a spot on the high-profile rodeo circuit was
like conquering the unrivaled bull.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis overcame the low expectations that may have deterred
many Eastern rodeo cowboys from rising to stardom. There are few
big-time rodeos along the Eastern seaboard, few opportunities to
see the best in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I've opened some doors where they could see the
light,'' Davis said of every aspiring bull rider in the East. ``I
hope to get them knowledgeable so they can go on. There are a lot
of guys who can.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis began competing in rodeos at age 11. He developed his bull
riding skills as a teen-ager; his father produced amateur weekly
bull riding shows at the family ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Davis, who operates a feed store and announces rodeos,
said North Carolina offers an abundance of amateur and minor-league
rodeos. But he encouraged his son to dream bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tons of guys who come to our bull riding on Thursdays
that have some girl on their mind that they want to impress,''
Carson Davis said. ``Around here, rodeo promoters make local heroes
out of these boys, and they end up staying here. But that wasn't
Jerome's goal. He had to move on. He had the National Finals and a
world championship on his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   During his high school years, the younger Davis competed in the
International Professional Rodeo Association, billed as the sport's
most prominent minor league. When Davis was a senior, he gained
respect and attention at the IPRA's finals in Oklahoma City by
winning the average _ posting the highest aggregate score on five
rides.
</P>
<P>
   That helped him earn a rodeo scholarship at Odessa College, a
two-year school in the West Texas city known for its rodeo team. He
won the national collegiate bull riding title as a freshman in
1992, and that year he moved on to the Professional Rodeo Cowboys
Association tour to rub shoulders with world champions such as
Hedeman, Ty Murray and Jim Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closest that I'd ever seen them ride was on TV,'' Davis
said. ``The first time I actually saw them, I was riding against
them. It almost didn't seem real.''
</P>
<P>
   During his first year on the PRCA circuit, Davis was sidelined
for several months with broken ribs and failed to qualify for the
1992 National Finals Rodeo in Las Vegas. But he finished in the top
five each of the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Davis won the world title in a race that was not
decided until the last bull had bucked, edging out Terry Don West.
Today, Davis has more than $1 million in earnings in the PBR and
PRCA, five National Finals Rodeo berths and four qualifications to
the PBR championships, also in Las Vegas.
Overwhelming support Though he is confined to a wheelchair and has
to endure hours of rehabilitation and medical treatment each day,
Davis says he's very fortunate to have received overwhelming
support from his family and fans.
</P>
<P>
   The fan appeal is apparent just by clicking onto the
Professional Bull Riders Web site on the Internet; it has listed
updates since Davis was injured and contains a form to send e-mail
messages to him. Davis has received more than 40,000 messages via
the Web site, PBR media officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very encouraging,'' Davis said. ``The responses just keep
coming from all over. When I see so many, I don't know what to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Bull riding officials also are carefully helping Davis. Randy
Bernard, the PBR's chief executive officer, said PBR is planning to
hire Davis to help anchor a planned feature program about bull
riding on The Nashville Network and to help announce bull riding
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerome will have a lot of friends the next two years because
of all of the hype about his injury,'' Bernard said. ``But after
that, the PBR needs to step to the plate and strongly support him
for the rest of his life. He will stay very connected with the
PBR.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pack and Hedeman, who co-produce the Tuff Hedeman
Championship Challenge in Fort Worth each March, said they plan to
show Davis the ropes of managing bull riding shows for the PBR. For
the past two years, the Hedeman event has been voted by competitors
as the association's top regular-season show.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also plans to continue raising rodeo livestock. Last
weekend, long-time stock Texas stock producer Fred Cordell of
Childress hauled a small bull all the way to North Carolina for
Davis. The small bull was fathered by Grasshopper, the top bull in
the PRCA in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Davis will focus on raising this bull to be a top challenger and
a breeder of top-caliber bulls, another way of making an impact in
professional rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jerome rode bulls, he had a never-give-up attitude, and
he will keep that same attitude as a rancher or a stock
contractor,'' said Hedeman, the association's president from Morgan
Mill. ``He's the type of guy who will be successful. If he never
rides again, it won't keep him from being successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of guys who ride great, but Jerome is a guy
who has brought the sport to where it is today. He's the type of
guy who would do the little things like sign autographs or get up
at 6 in the morning to do a TV show. As bull riders, we were able
to live our dreams, and now that Jerome is sidelined, we want him
to stay involved and be able to provide a livelihood for his
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who had only $20,000 worth of insurance from the bull
riding association, also has benefited from many fund-raisers since
the accident. Last weekend, more than $65,000 was raised at an
auction in Charlotte that included memorabilia from world-class
rodeo riders. In Fort Worth in April, more than $130,000 was raised
at an auction that included memorabilia from NASCAR drivers. And
Davis received a $26,000 check from Winston Cup star Bobby Labonte
after Labonte won a race in Darlington, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Davis has received more than $300,000 in contributions,
his mother, Pam Simmons, said. And other fund-raisers are planned,
including a benefit at the PBR's Nov. 6-8 World Finals in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Davis receives assistance from his mother and father,
and his stepmother, Vicki. Even before the accident, the three were
the best of friends and traveled to rodeos together to watch Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``'We've always been very close,'' Vicki Davis said. ``The first
time that Jerome got seriously hurt \Rin Reno, Nev., in 1992\S, I
drove Pam and Carson to catch the plane. When he got hurt last
March, I kept things going out here, took all of the phone calls
and handled TV interviews while Carson and Pam traveled to Fort
Worth to be with Jerome.''
</P>
<P>
   All that support has helped Davis remain optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very fortunate that I've gotten good people behind me,''
Davis said. ``It's easy for me not to be bitter about what happened
because there are many people who are injured like I have been who
don't really have anyone to take care of them. It's a whole
different ordeal for them. So it's easy for me to say that I'm
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the odds of recovering his mobility are considered very
slim by medical officials, Davis said his Christian faith has
spurred his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray every night that I can come out of this,'' Davis said
``I have faith that I can walk again through medical help or
through the Lord's healing power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
