<HEADER>
A0281 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLAN-RALLY-COX     06-27 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLAN-RALLY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police maintain order at Klan rally
 &HT;    By Mitch Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The 25 robed individuals standing on the Jasper
County Courthouse lawn where many in this town had prayed for
healing two weeks earlier looked almost like extras in a scene from
a B-movie.
</P>
<P>
   They called each other names like Grand Wizard, Grand Titan,
Dragon and Knight.
</P>
<P>
   What many of the residents here feared actually happened. The Ku
Klux Klan had come to town and its opposite number, The New Black
Panthers, were also here vowing to protect the town's black
residents from Klan intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake about it,'' Rick Anderson, Grand Titan of the
Knights of the White Kamellia, said. ``This is Klan country.''
</P>
<P>
   Klan members were there to disavow any connection with those
involved in the slaying of James Byrd Jr., a 49-year-old black man
who was chained behind a pickup and dragged for three miles early
June 7.
</P>
<P>
   During the dragging, Byrd's head and right shoulder were torn
from his body. Three white men have been arrested in connection
with what authorities have said is a racially motivated killing.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, of Sulphur Springs, and Jasper
residents Shawn Allen Berry and John William King, both 23, have
been charged with murder and are being held in Jasper County jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fellows that did this were not a part of any Klan group
that we know of,'' a Klansman called Nathan told a crowd of more
than 200 media spectators and 200 onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Klan and approximately 20 Panthers decried the crime as
brutal. Mutual agreement between the two groups ended there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Black Panthers are arming the violent black youth in
the area,'' Anderson said. ``Now the good white people of Jasper
are in jeopardy. ... Now if one of you ends up dead for the crime
of being white, will the nation grieve and mourn over your mangled
corpse? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will even notice you're gone. No one noticed when our
white neighbor Mr. McQueen was murdered at the hand of a Negro just
one week prior to Mr. Byrd's death. You can bet that no one will
remember your name either. One thing we can draw from that is the
life of a Negro has far more value than the life of a white.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Jerry McQueen, 37, a Jasper white man, was beat
to death with a blunt instrument. Donald Kinnebrew, 34, a Jasper
black man, has been arrested and charged with murder in connection
with the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Klan is a coward organization,'' Minister Khallid Abdul
Muhammad said before the confrontation between the two groups.
``They hide their faces behind sheets. They used to be called night
riders, because that is when they attacked people. They attacked
when they outnumbered their victims 100-to-1. They ambushed people,
tied them up with chains and lynched them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or they hide behind the badges of sheriff's officers and wear
the black robes of judges. They don't want to fight with us. It's
no fun when the black men have guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Black Panthers tried several times to penetrate the
barricades set up by authorities but were rebuffed each time. About
one hour into the Klan rally, Quanell X, leader of the
Houston-based Black Muslim Movement, gathered the black people
around him and asked if they were ready to fight.
</P>
<P>
   A cheer went up and a voice whispered softly from the inner
circle:'' Let's go get the guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Black Panthers, followed by dozens of media and
onlookers marched down the street while Texas Department of Public
Safety troopers formed a skirmish line about a block away from the
rally.
</P>
<P>
   The New Black Panthers were prohibited from bringing their guns
into the area where the Klansmen rallied, and meanwhile authorities
were escorting the white and black robed men and women into their
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Several times the New Black Panthers ran at the cars, with
people throwing ice and at least one man throwing rocks at a car
carrying the Klansmen away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran those suckers out of here,'' Muhammad shouted
victoriously along with others. Then the New Black Panthers marched
down the street, followed again by media and bystanders, fists
raised in the air, cursing the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   Not a shot was fired; not a blow was landed. Law enforcement
rarely raised a hand except to make an arrest of a man carrying a
knife and to restrain a man throwing rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the local people were at some other location during the
Klan rally. Local government officials and ministers cautioned
people to stay away from the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   But not all stayed away. Ray Lewis, pastor of Faith Temple
Church of God In Christ, told those who stayed behind after the
rally that Jasper officials were being hypocritical about the
town's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all say pray at the courthouse and let the healing begin,''
Lewis said. ``In short, words coming from the officials are saying
go home and go to sleep. ... I'm not trying to tell them what to
say. They're our elected officials, they should know what to say.
But what they should stop saying is there is no problem here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
