A0282 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMENS-OPEN-COX     06-27 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENS-OPEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Renewed Sorenstam primed for '98 Open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wisc. -- This week's U.S. Women's Open at the Blackwolf
Run Golf Course in Kohler, Wis., has a stiff challenge ahead. If it
wishes to match last year's tournament for engaging story lines, it
better get started with the subplots early in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Ridge in 1997, in this order, was:
</P>
<P>
   Annika Sorenstam's attempt to win an unprecedented third
straight U.S Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   The resurgence of Nancy Lopez, who turned the corner after
turning the big Four-Oh, won in Atlanta, and seemed prepared to
capture the one championship that has eluded her.
</P>
<P>
   The shocking development that saw Sorenstam not only fail to win
again, but even fail to make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-foot putt that slid by the cup on the 72nd hole,
thwarting Lopez once again.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of England's tiny Alison Nicholas, who, while
unfamiliar to American golf audiences, experienced the week of her
life, winning the U.S. Women's Open with a tournament-record score
of 10-under par.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, much has changed. The Swedes were dominant at the
beginning of the LPGA year _ without Sorenstam to assist them.
Liselotte Neumann and Helen Alfredsson each won twice, with
Sorenstam needing five months to secure a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam is fourth on the LPGA money list with $387,765,
significantly behind leader Donna Andrews ($525,944), but she
enters this Women's Open ($1.5 million purse, $267,500 to the
champion) with significantly less pressure on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Open (in 1995) was the first time I won in the U.S., so
it's very special to me,'' Sorenstam said during this week's
ShopRite Classic in advance of Blackwolf Run. ``You need to play
the best you can at the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a little difficult,'' she said. ``The only thing
on my mind was three-peat, three-peat, three-peat, and it got me
away from my thinking and my game. I missed the cut, and I hadn't
done that in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   She feels renewed from her win at the Michelob Light Classic in
St. Louis on June 7 as she enters the most significant tournament
in women's golf.
</P>
<P>
   Missing a cut should be her most distant thought. Since winning
the 1995 Open, she has missed only two cuts in 48 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot last year, and I'll be ready to play next
week,'' said Sorenstam, who is third in LPGA scoring at 70.11,
behind Andrews (70.04) and Karrie Webb (69.69). ``I just have to
remember to play shot by shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, 41, promises to be the fan favorite once again at
Blackwolf Run, a venue unfamiliar to most of the 140 players.
</P>
<P>
   A former regional site of the Andersen Consulting World
Championship of Golf, it is, by Pete Dye standards, a relatively
benign property.
</P>
<P>
   Typically quick USGA greens might help Lopez, who has struggled
with her putting much of the year. Lately, she has been drawing a
line on her ball to help with alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to get your golf game just right for the Open,'' Lopez
said, getting a jump on some visualization. ``I'd like to walk down
the 18th fairway Sunday with a two- or three-shot lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The U.S. Women's Open received a record 925 entries this
year, with 79 qualifiers joining 61 exempt players. ... Savannah's
Hollis Stacy, a three-time champion, was among the qualifiers,
shooting a 72 at the Broadmoor in Colorado Springs, a former Open
site.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
