<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE FOR ME OR STAY HOME, MAURO TELLS TEXAS DEMOCRATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Shunned by members of his own party and trailing
in the polls, Democrat Garry Mauro urged like-minded candidates to
get behind his campaign for governor Saturday and gave this blunt
message to the non-believers: ``Stay home.''
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by about 150 candidates and activists on the stage at
the Texas Democratic Convention, Mauro invited all Democratic
candidates to ``walk with me and carry the Democratic ticket to
victory in 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you're not for a $5,000 pay raise (for teachers), don't
walk with me,'' Mauro said. ``And if you're not for reducing class
sizes, stay home, don't walk with me. And if you're not for the
right to choose your own doctor, I don't want you to walk with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's feisty speech underscored the uphill challenge he faces
in unseating popular Republican Gov. George W. Bush, a challenge
made even more difficult by Mauro's lack of overt support from his
Democratic colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not only Mauro who faces a steep challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats frankly acknowledged as their convention wrapped
up that the party is at a crossroads and must change and recruit
new blood to regain prominence in a state that has seen a shift to
the Republican Party in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   One such change came Saturday, when Democrats _ by voice vote _
selected former Republican Molly Beth Malcolm as party chairwoman.
Malcolm, the first woman to head the state party, replaces Houston
lawyer and businessman Bill White, who is retiring after 21/2
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to expand our grassroots,'' said Malcolm, of
Texarkana. ``That means we're going to attract more young people to
the party. That means we need to reach out to independents and,
yes, Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mattox, running to get his old job back as attorney general,
was more explicit about the need to rejuvenate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Democrats, despite all the pretty speeches, have to learn a
few things. We do not win with 43 percent,'' Mattox said, referring
to the percentage of people who call themselves Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't worship at the altar of the New Deal any longer.
That's something from the past. We must move forward to the future
is what we must do.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mauro, moving forward means knocking on lots of doors. He
vowed to ``knock on 1 million doors by Labor Day,'' and said that,
with help from activists, he could knock on a million more.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' land commissioner since 1983, Mauro was swept into office
the same year Ann Richards was elected state treasurer, Jim
Hightower became agriculture commissioner and Mattox was elected
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost 16 years later, Mauro is the only one who holds
elective office in Texas. Polls show he will have a tough time
avoiding the fate of his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent Texas Poll, Mauro is trailing Bush by 53
percentage points. Mauro disputed the poll, saying he is probably
closer to 30 percentage points behind, but he acknowledged that the
survey ``hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are discouraged,'' he said. ``It's a demoralizing
poll.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, which Mauro began after delegates heard the theme
song from the film ``Rocky,'' the veteran Democrat pointed to
come-from-behind victories by his political idol and longtime
friend, President Clinton, as proof that he can pull off an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also touted his signature program at the Land Office, the
acclaimed beach clean-up efforts. And the Democratic nominee
harshly criticized Bush for supporting a voluntary program to
reduce emissions at ``grandfathered'' industrial plants, his veto
of the Patient Protection Act in 1995 and his support of a
low-level radioactive waste dump in West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out of touch with ordinary Texas families,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said Mauro's showing in
the polls shows ``who's out of touch.''
</P>
<P>
   While scores of candidates joined Mauro on stage, including
Mattox and Richard Raymond, the Democratic nominee for land
commissioner, two were notable for their absence.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hobby, the Democratic comptroller candidate, and John
Sharp, running for lieutenant governor, left the convention after
delivering speeches a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Hobby was with his family yesterday, but ``would have been on
that stage,'' had he still been in San Antonio, said campaign
spokeswoman Margaret Justus. Still, neither Hobby nor Sharp has
openly endorsed Mauro by name.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Hobby was specifically endorsing Mauro, Justus said,
``Paul Hobby has said he is endorsing the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp spokesman Kelly Fero said Sharp, the state comptroller, is
making no endorsements in statewide offices. Fero said Sharp agrees
with Mauro's call for a teachers' pay raise, although he couldn't
commit to Mauro's specific figure of $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Sharp supports reduced class sizes and doctor
choice, though they could differ on significant details. Fero said
Mauro's challenge to fellow Democrats is not important.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many important issues facing Texas today,'' Fero
said. ``This isn't one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said the lack of explicit support for candidates who
challenge popular incumbents is nothing new, and he predicted that
Democrats will support him as the November election draws near.
</P>
<P>
   He said his message to Sharp and Hobby is that ``everyone has
their own race to run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to knock on a million doors, and they are welcome to
join me,'' Mauro said. ``They will. It's just a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
