r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-COLUMN-LADN     06-27 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS OF U.S. SOCCER'S FAILURE AND FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It was a shame, Tab Ramos was saying, that nowhere in
the United States' performance in France was there evidence of the
strides American soccer has taken since the last World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sampson might not agree he seemed to have seen signs of
growth everywhere he looked but Tab, in this instance, appears to
have gotten to the heart of what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   What was so disappointing wasn't that the Americans failed to
win nobody in his right mind expected them to reach the second
round, although triumph over Iran would have been nice it was how
they failed.
</P>
<P>
   Miserably.
</P>
<P>
   At no point during the past two weeks OK, at one point, the
first 20 minutes of the second half against Germany did Sampson's
Army appear the least bit capable of the magic it employed to knock
off Argentina in 1995 or Brazil back in February. There was no
cohesion, no creativity, no spark, and for once the stats tell the
whole story: One goal, no wins, 32nd place.
</P>
<P>
   Disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, it appears an honest appraisal of where we stand within
world soccer.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface and this, perhaps, is where Sampson focused the
Americans didn't do as badly as it seemed. They threw a small scare
at the Germans (if only Frankie Hejduk's header had found its way
past Andreas Koepke), were robbed by the post against Iran, and
might have gone 0-0 with Yugoslavia if not for that unfortunate bit
at the start. No matter that they appeared unable to penetrate the
opposing defenses, that their attack stalled in the final third of
the field, or that Claudio Reyna wasn't ready for the
responsibility hoisted upon his shoulders, had the ball bounced
just a little bit differently, the Yanks might have been playing
for a chance to lose to Holland in the second round when they took
on the Yugoslavs on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, that's just a fantasy. The Americans were far weaker
than the Germans and Yugoslavs no surprise, and no disgrace and
they weren't as good as Iran, either. We had no one with the skills
of Khodadad Azizi; Reyna was no Karim Bagheri; Hejduk probably the
best U.S. player in the Cup was no match for Mehdi Mahdavikia; and
our tactics, while assuring us most of the possession and plenty of
chances, weren't as well-crafted, as successful as the Iranians'
sit-back-and-counterattack mentality.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Soccer officials might publicly pretend otherwise, but they
realize we're still light years away from competing with the
Germans and the Yugoslavs and the Brazilians and the French and the
(fill in your favorite soccer power here).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to have a world championship-caliber team for
some time to come ...,'' admitted Alan Rothenberg, U.S. Soccer's
president, after the final defeat. ``We are inching forward as a
world soccer power we're not leaping forward, but we never expected
to leap forward. It's a long, hard road to get to the top. We are
committed to getting there, we are applying resources to get there,
we have a plan to get there. We've seen glimpses of it ... it's
just going to take time.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's going to take talent, some of which we are starting to
see. Eddie Pope, probably, is bound for a top European club Major
League Soccer is fielding seven-figure offers and there is
continental interest in Hejduk, Brian Maisonneuve, Brian McBride
and Cobi Jones, too. And a crop of even more promising young talent
Clint Mathis and John O'Brien and Jovan Kirovski and Leo Cullen and
Nick Garcia and Carlos Bocanegra and Ben Olsen and Jamar Beasley
could be playing key roles when the Americans head off for Japan
and South Korea, as they surely will, for the 2002 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   That team won't be good enough to win, nor good enough to
contend, either. To do that, soccer needs to attract the best U.S.
athletes, the Michael Jordans and the Ken Griffey Jrs.; at the very
least, America's top players need to head elsewhere, to Europe, to
Italy and Germany and Spain and England, like the last generation
of U.S. stars did. It's a different world over there the
competition is more fierce, the level of play far higher, than what
can be found in MLS.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson recognizes that. ``If (players) have the opportunity,
they should grasp it and take advantage of it,'' he says. ``In the
rest of the world, you live, you eat, you breathe soccer, and
that's the only way to be able to compete with the rest of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   America will never eat, breathe or live soccer. But we have a
plan nonetheless for winning the World Cup for ``competing
realistically to have a chance to win the World Cup,'' Rothenberg
prefers within 12 years. It's Project 2010, and its aim is to
locate talent and prepare it for soccer's wars. Somewhere out
there, maybe in L.A., is a 5-year-old Ronaldo. He is the future of
American soccer.
</P>
<P>
   It may soon be Sampson's job to find that child, to develop his
skills. When he is fired as U.S. coach and he will be fired, with
Bruce Arena, perhaps, or some high-profile foreigner stepping in
figure he'll take charge of Project 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Given America's aspirations, it might be a promotion.
</P>
<P>
