<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-FEMALE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEMOCRATS ELECT FIRST WOMAN TO LEAD STATE PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 CHIEF-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GINGER D. RICHARDSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The state Democratic party elected its first
female chief Saturday, former Republican Molly Beth Malcolm.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm, a Republican activist until 1992, will take over for
Houston businessman Bill White, who has been state party chairman
for the past two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for your encouragement and your dedication; thank
you for believing in me. Most of all, thank you for giving me this
incredible opportunity,'' Malcolm said during her acceptance
speech. ``Because of you, I can say today that, yes, I am proud to
be a Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm, 43, of Texarkana, has been active in the Democratic
party since 1993, and has served on the State Democratic Executive
Committee. She was endorsed by the Texas AFL-CIO after Cecile
Richards, daughter of former Gov. Ann Richards, decided not to run.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm, the president of Texas Democratic Women, made it clear
Saturday that she will endorse all the Democratic candidates _
including Garry Mauro, who has had some trouble drumming up support
among members of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the ticket from the top to bottom; we have wonderful
candidates,'' Malcolm said. ``We have people who have the right
issues running for the positions on our ballots, and I think you're
going to hear a lot about health care and education, two major
concerns for the people in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said she will be one of the foot soldiers spreading the
Democratic message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to be out there talking on a daily basis, I intend
to get our message out,'' Malcolm said. ``We're the party of real
Texas family values _ not corporate family values.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her former allegiance to the GOP, Malcolm had few
positive things to say about Republicans after her election
Saturday. The Texas GOP also has a chairwoman, Susan Weddington.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference in that woman who is leading that
other party,'' she said. ``This party has always supported women;
women have always been in positions of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican party, yes, they have a woman in charge, but I
think they did it as a token gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
