<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0298 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     06-27 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' SUCCESS OVERSHADOWED BY DODGERS' MESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ever a season the Anaheim Angels should be easily upstaging
the Los Angeles Dodgers, it is this zany one in which the two
franchises have reversed traditional roles.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Angels (a) have a remodeled state-of-the-art
stadium, (b) have a robust hitting team with an emerging superstar
in Darin Erstad, (c) are winning on a consistent basis and (d) have
a manager, Terry Collins, and (e) a general manager, Bill Bavasi,
who haven't even been (f) fired.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Dodgers have become baseball's equivalent
to the Titanic, with the team and many of its employees sinking
tragically into a sea of comedic chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the impressive record of the Angels and the
embarrassing failings of the Dodgers, one gets the unmistakable
feeling that there still is far more interest in the Dodgers in
Southern California than the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Before a game the other night between the Dodgers and Angels,
there was a most revealing scene on the Dodger Stadium field.
</P>
<P>
   As the two teams went through their fielding, batting and
calisthenics drills, you noted a swarm of reporters gathered near
the Dodgers' dugout while only one news person was encamped by the
Angels' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Why such a disparity?
</P>
<P>
   Why so much more media attention to the Dodgers in these parts
even during a season when the Angels, clearly, are the stronger and
more entertaining team?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the stunning departures of Mike Piazza and Hideo Noma
and sackings of Fred Claire and Bill Russell are contributing
factors.
</P>
<P>
   But even had these men not not suffered such fates the Dodgers
would have commanded more press space than the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Why do the Dodgers, even when they're haplessly
floundering, even when the team has more firings than home runs and
complete games, even when the Angels are in first place in their
division, still remain a greater public fixture?
</P>
<P>
   It long has been the belief here that those sporting types who
live within the confines of Los Angeles County simply are too
provincial to warmly embrace an entity from Orange County, which
might only be a few miles away in distance but might as well be
Fresno or San Diego to those, say, in the San Fernado Valley who
never even traverse the Sepulveda Pass.
</P>
<P>
   Look what happened to the Rams when Carroll Rosenbloom moved
them 35 miles down the Santa Ana Freeway to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Almost overnight, they became strictly an Orange County
proposition, with the Valley and West L.A. fans shedding their Ram
allegiances and eventually lending their support to the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for such a phenomenon is the lengthy history of
success that the Dodgers have enjoyed since moving here from
Brooklyn in 1958. During this period, they have won eight pennants
and five World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have been an ill-starred franchise that still is
seeking its first American League pennant in its 38th year.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to causing their loyalists frustrations, the
Angels exceed even the Clippers, if for no other reason than
they've been bumbling around here a lot longer.
</P>
<P>
   For too many seasons, the Angels were the the laughingstocks of
their sport, enduring the agonizing disappointments and bitter
turmoil that now are cursing the Dodgers, this summer's
laughingstocks.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Angels did have some joyful times under the ownership of
Gene Autry, even coming within a strike of finally making it to the
World Series in 1986 when their manager, Gene Mauch, alas, made a
most notorious decision.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the ninth inning and the Angels in front by a
run, Mauch pulled his best pitcher, Mike Witt, setting in motion a
disastrous series of events that wound up with Dave Henderson's
hitting a dramatic home run off Donnie Moore that would propel the
Boston Red Sox to a stirring comeback and shatter Gene Autry's
World Series dream.
</P>
<P>
   For most of their existence, the Angels have struggled and
gotten rid of people the caliber of Nolan Ryan, while the Dodgers
have triumphed and sent people like Sandy Koufax and Don Drysdale
and Tom Lasorda to the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's the Dodgers foolishly peddling away future Hall of
Famers, but their indiscretions haven't changed anything.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels still can't emerge from the massive Dodger shadow,
even failing to stir the passions of a segment of residents in
their own backyard.
</P>
<P>
   You must understand that there are those in Orange County who
simply won't root for a team with a nickname linked inextricably to
Los Angeles, long known as the City of Angels.
</P>
<P>
   One does idly wonder why a team ensconced in Anaheim still
refers to itself as the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   I realize the Angels began life at old Wrigley Field in L.A.,
and assumed the name of the stadium's former PCL tenants.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm surprised the Angels didn't change their name when they
shifted to Anaheim in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Why would the Anaheim-based team blindly cling to its L.A. roots
when that city still pays only scant attention to it, even during a
season when the Angels are shining?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
