<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-CLINTONO628-     06-27 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-CLINTONO628-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: updates with Clinton arriving at the church; services
beginning
 &HT;    CLINTON HEADS TO A STATE-REGULATED CHURCH IN CHINA
 &HT;    With CHINA-RELIGION-$ADV28; CHINA-ACCOMPLISH-0628;
CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV28.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Bill Clinton worshipped at a
government-regulated Protestant church Sunday, preparing talk about
the free practice of religion, in what may be the most personal
remarks he will deliver during his sweep across China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The come for one purpose, to honor God,'' said the pastor, in
opening the service at 2,300-member Chongwenmen church, not far
from the seat of state authority in the heart of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   After addressing the largest Protestant church in China's
capital, Clinton planned to talk to a group of clergy, who in China
face the prospect of being replaced if they displease the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Churchgoers sang ``Golden Break the Dawn,'' heard the scripture
and repeated the Lord's Prayer, before Clinton had his turn at the
pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton already made blunt comments about China's human rights
practices on Saturday, during an exceptional televised news
conference in which he and China's President Jiang Zemin announced
their summit a success. Then they went on to engage in a polite
debate over the 1989 violent crushing of the Tiananmen Square
protests and other sensitive subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Restriction of religious freedom has loosened in some Chinese
localities, but it remains one of the practices most criticized by
human rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   The week before Clinton left on this China visit, he met with
three American religious leaders who investigated religious
practices in China, including Tibet, last winter. The report they
released upon returning said conditions had improved in some
places, but that repression still existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Clinton) is going to reflect about what they told him,''
White House spokesman Michael McCurry said Saturday. ``He's going
to talk about the importance we attach in the United States to the
freedom to worship.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself said last week that this speech is ``most likely
to be one that I will do virtually by myself and close to the
time'' of the event.
</P>
<P>
   The summit talks Saturday produced no breakthroughs on either
trade or limits on missile sales, which had been considered the two
most important issues to be addressed, but the leaders pronounced
the summit a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talks were positive, constructive and productive,'' Jiang
said at the summit's close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our friendship may never be perfect -- no friendship is,''
Clinton said. ``But I hope it will last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides agreeing to stop targeting missiles at each other's
territory, the presidents agreed to tighten controls on the export
of chemicals that can be used for weapons, called for establishing
a new compliance mechanism for the biological weapons convention
and committed their countries to ending the export and
``indiscriminate use'' of anti-personnel land mines.
</P>
<P>
   They also set up a number of exchange programs and cooperative
projects on the environment, health improvements and legal
training.
</P>
<P>
   The most remarkable development was that the news conference
televised live to an estimated half-billion Chinese at the close of
the formal talks.
</P>
<P>
   It not only showed Jiang discussing the ``extensive and in-depth
exchange of views'' between the two, but Clinton relating that he
reaffirmed America's ``one-China'' policy during the summit.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger called it ``a
truly historic press conference'' showing for the first time ``the
leader of the United States and the leader of China discussing and
debating a range of issues, but most particularly human rights, to
a live audience across China and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Americans disagree with the use of force at
Tiananmen Square and suggested that China release some of the
prisoners arrested ``for offenses no longer on the books in
China.'' He referred to the sweeping law against
counter-revolutionary activities under which thousands of Chinese
were arrested over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang reiterated the Chinese stand that the aim of maintaining
order and stability was paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the arrests of dissidents just prior to Clinton's
arrival -- acts that drew critical comments from Clinton and other
White House officials -- Jiang said an investigation ``shows that
there was never such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The American side deemed that very response ``unacceptable'' on
Friday, but by Saturday was trying to paint the summit in a golden
glow, so simply ignored the fact that Chinese authorities still
appeared to be stonewalling the question.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese president also himself raised the charges in America
that the Chinese government had made illegal campaign contributions
to the Democratic National Committee, calling them ``absurd and
ridiculous'' and ``sheer fabrications.''
</P>
<P>
   ``China can never do such a thing,'' he said, ``and China never
interferes in other country's internal affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being televised live, excerpts of the news conference
were shown on the main Chinese evening news show, which was mostly
devoted to the Clinton visit. The excerpts, however, did not
include the sensitive comments on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The extensive state news coverage began with China's formal
welcoming of Clinton at the Great Hall of the People on the western
edge of Tiananmen Square, a ceremony some American members of
Congress had urged Clinton to skip. There followed a biographical
sketch of Clinton, then the news show ran through highlights of the
day. It even included interviews in the United States with
political and academic figures.
</P>
<P>
   A late-breaking addition to the news was a report on the state
banquet Jiang held for the Clintons in the cavernous hall that can
hold 5,000 diners.
</P>
<P>
   In one unexplained incident, a bus of journalists leaving the
dinner was suddenly stopped by a woman who had lain down in the
road. She appeared to be holding a piece of paper that she extended
up in the direction of the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists on the bus said a man appeared next to her, and
immediately two green-shirted policemen roughly grabbed the pair
and dragged them out of the road and onto the sidewalk. The bus
driver refused requests to stop so the journalists could find out
what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
