<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y'ALL DON'T COME BACK NOW, HEAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Me and some fellers was sitting around the campfire the other
nite, chawing tabacci and waiting for Cookie to commence ranging
the dinner bell soes we could head over to the chuck wagon for a
plate of beans, when Buck (or was it Duke?) says, ``Is any of you
boys riled?''
</P>
<P>
   We all looked at him, puzzled-like.
</P>
<P>
   Soes he says, ``Honest, I ain't a-foolin'. I was reading this
here newspaper out of Boston, that has a article in it by a feller
name of David Nyhan, and he says weez supposed to be riled.''
</P>
<P>
   Riled over what? I was fixin' to ask, least ways 'til I sinks my
spurs into a more imporant question.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you doin' lookin' at a paper from Boston?'' I asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, beggin' yer pardon,'' says Buck (or was it Duke?), ``but
all of us ain't ignernt. Some of us figure we can learn a thang or
two from peoples living in furren countries, like Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Out here in Arizona, when a feller gets to expressin' hisself in
such a fashion, showing signs of book learnin' and other
highfalutin notions, it gits the rest of us excited. &QL; 
`We cud be smart' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Me and the boys started won derin' outloud if maybe we should
commence to readin'. Maybe stu dyin' up on what fellers from Boston
have to say. Maybe even learnin' a furren language that ain't
American, like what they talk in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cud be smart,'' I says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And cultured,'' says another.
</P>
<P>
   I tell ya, it was a rite nice momemt.
</P>
<P>
   Then we come to our senses and hauled ole Buck to the nearest
tree and hung 'im.
</P>
<P>
   Or was it Duke?
</P>
<P>
   I don't reckon it matters much no more. We did look at that
paper outta Boston, though. That feller Nyhan wrote up an article
supposed to be about Arizona's U.S. Senator John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The write-up is about how the tabacci companies is taking off
after the senator in uncomplimentary ways, ``riling the ranchers
and rodeo hands of Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers and rodeo hands?
</P>
<P>
   Yeeeeee-hah! Ain't that just like an Easterner?
</P>
<P>
   I 'member a few months back, when the mayor of New York come to
town. A reporter from back East wrote how the mayor ``arrived in
the land of cactus flowers and six-shooters.''
</P>
<P>
   And they say WE is ignernt? &QL; 
GUN-TOTIN' MANIACS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every time one of them Eastern dandies does a report on us, they
make it out like we is all ``ranchers and rodeo hands.''
</P>
<P>
   And a course, we ain't.
</P>
<P>
   We's also rustlers and gunsling ers, desperadoes and cutthroats,
thieves, cattle rustlers, and all perti nent forms of toothless,
gun-totin' maniacs.
</P>
<P>
   They's even a Democrat or two, though they's as jittery as
prairie dogs and just as likely to stay in they holes.
</P>
<P>
   We got rattlers, scorpions, black widder spiders and more vermin
and varmints than all the East combined, providin' you leave out
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And, still, settlers keeps a comin'.
</P>
<P>
   We changed the state motto to ``It's too durn hot!''
</P>
<P>
   Still, new peoples arrive. Home steaders. Bringin' with them
houses and cars and green grass. Puttin' in cement ponds. Buildin'
schools and picture shows and ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a regular stampede.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't no use trying to cut 'em off at the pass, neither. I hear
tell they's machines now called air-o-planes that carry folks right
over top.
</P>
<P>
   Dang.
</P>
<P>
   What's a cowpoke to do? No matter how much we say, ``Can't all
you little dogies just git along?'' they don't listen.
</P>
<P>
   Our only chance may be to call in the law. 'Round here, that'd
be Joe Arpaio, who calls hisself the ``toughest sheriff in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd be one Arizona lawman who knows how to track down outside
agitators like this Nyhan feller from Boston. See, turns out Joe
was born in a town name a Springfield. In the country of
Massachusetts. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or
 &UR; at ed.montini &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
