<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0416 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LAD     06-27 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASORDA COVETS HIS METS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The New York Mets are in a pennant race. The
Dodgers are in denial.
</P>
<P>
   New general manager Tom Lasorda was working his old shtick in
his first week on the job, even though the Dodgers dropped 13{
games behind San Diego. And through several well-placed hints,
suddenly Mike Piazza was coming back to L.A. next year and bringing
Mets manager Bobby Valentine along.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mets are in a heated wild-card race. They dropped
the first two games of a weekend series with the cross-town
Yankees, but Shea Stadium is hopping for the first time since the
Darryl Strawberry era.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Piazza and Valentine aren't coming here next year.
Piazza's seven-year, $105 million contract demand was too much for
Fox (not just Fred Claire and Peter O'Malley). Why would it be
better with Piazza a year older and probably another year without a
championship?
</P>
<P>
   Adding the Dodgers to the free-agent shopping list is great
leverage for Piazza and his agent Dan Lozano, but Mets owner Nelson
Doubleday has seen his ballpark empty for too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Mike, we are going to get that thing done one way or
another,'' Doubleday said this past week. ``We are definitely going
to get that done.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Valentine can't get out of his three-year,
$2.1-million contract that has two years to run after this season.
He has a way of grading on management and players, the way he did
in Texas, but he is not at that point yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Valentine is our manager and he will remain our
manager,'' Doubleday said. ``Sure, he is a protege of Tommy
Lasorda. But Bobby Valentine is our manager, and he is a hell of a
manager. We would resist anyone coming after him, hard, strong and
heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the Mets, Valentine has made attempts to forge a
non-Lasorda identity. But the two have known each other for 30
years, and Valentine was a close friend of Lasorda's late son, Tom
Jr. Valentine played in Los Angeles and is married to the daughter
of former Brooklyn Dodgers right-hander Ralph Branca.
</P>
<P>
   Three times, Valentine has come close to working on a
major-league staff with Lasorda. Shortly after Lasorda retired as
Dodgers manager in 1996, Valentine considered bringing him to the
Mets as a coach. In 1982, Valentine would have become Lasorda's
third-base coach, but the Mets didn't allow him to leave the
organization. George Bamberger, then the Mets' manager, took him as
a major-league coach, instead.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing possibility, though, came in 1992, during
the Dodgers 99-loss season.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was set to join Lasorda in Tampa Bay. Vince Naimoli,
the current Devil Rays owner, and Vince Piazza, Mike's father, had
reached a tentative agreement to buy the Giants and move them to
Tampa Bay for the 1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, unsure that the Dodgers were going to retain him after
the last-place showing, agreed to take the job as Tampa Bay manager
for one year before being promoted to GM. His third-base coach that
first year was going to be Valentine, who would then take over as
manager the next season. His pitching coach was going to be Charlie
Hough, who took the Dodgers job Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball owners would not approve Piazza as an owner, and
the Giants never moved. Lasorda was given a new contract by
O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, when Lasorda was inducted into the Hall of Fame, he
was asked which manager he would hire if he were a GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would take Bobby Valentine,'' Lasorda said. ``I think he's
an outstanding manager. I've seen what he's done with that Mets
team. The guy's taken a team that no one even thought had a chance
and he's about 14 or 15 games over .500. I think that's quite a
remarkable job.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda already had alienated long-time friend Bill Russell,
Dodgers manager until last Sunday. But O'Malley also was incensed.
He chewed Lasorda out just a day before Lasorda's number was
retired in ceremonies at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Mike Piazza say he is intrigued by the
possibility of returning to the Dodgers _ much the way Kenny Lofton
returned to Cleveland one year after he was traded by the Indians.
One of Piazza's confidants said recently the catcher is now
considering signing a long-term contract with either the Mets,
Yankees, Dodgers or Orioles. He would give the Mets the first
chance if he thought they would maintain a strong team around him.
</P>
<P>
   For Piazza, one of the pluses of playing with the Mets is he
does not have to be a leader. Closer John Franco likes that job,
although he is eligible for free agency. The Dodgers forced the
leadership role on Piazza simply because he was their best player.
It was a bad fit.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza also has been given assurances that he will be catcher
when incumbent Todd Hundley returns from reconstructive elbow
surgery next month. Hundley was given a no-trade clause to assure
him that he will have time to make the transition to left field
without pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only concern is helping the Mets win, and hopefully,
getting them into the playoffs,'' Piazza said. ``I can't answer
about the past. I can't answer about the future. I'm dealing with
the present.''
</P>
<P>
   ABBOTT'S RETURN?
</P>
<P>
   Jim Abbott, who returned to baseball this season with the
Chicago White Sox after retiring from the Angels two years ago, was
promoted this past week to Double-A Birmingham after five starts at
Single A.
</P>
<P>
   In his last start at Winston-Salem, Abbott gave up one hit and
no runs in six innings. This is the same pitcher who had a
significant drop in velocity on his fastball in his final year with
the Angels, but there is some hope that he could be ready to make a
big-league comeback after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting more and more comfortable every time out,''' said
Abbott, who lost 18 games for the Angels in 1996. ``I knew coming
down here, it was going to take some work. I feel like I've got my
feet back underneath me.''
</P>
<P>
   White Sox instructor Jerry Terrell was at the game in
Winston-Salem and was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a chance to scout him in the big leagues, and that was
vintage Abbott tonight,'' Terrell said. ``Not only was he in
command of his pitches, but he fielded his position.''
</P>
<P>
   GABE RUTH
</P>
<P>
   Tigers rookie third baseman Gabe Alvarez homered twice Tuesday
in Detroit's victory against St. Louis, one day after getting a
single in his first major-league at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, 24, was acquired from Arizona in November in an
expansion deal for Travis Fryman. He was tied for the lead among
all minor-league players with 20 home runs. In addition, he had 58
RBI and was batting .273 at Triple-A Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited about this I didn't sleep at all last night,''
said the former USC player after his first game. ``I couldn't. So I
watched cartoons, then caught a flight here.''
</P>
<P>
   After his first hit, Alvarez got a little advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always remember Mark McGwire saying when I got to first
base, `See, all you have to do is work the count to 3-1 and you get
a nice fastball,''' said Alvarez, who was surprised McGwire even
spoke to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous, and I think he knew I was nervous,'' Alvarez
said. ``He loosened things up a little''
</P>
<P>
   GOING DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Josh Booty, the first pick of the 1994 draft, began this season
as Florida's starting third baseman in place of the injured Bobby
Bonilla. But last Sunday he was hitting only .142 with 44
strikeouts and just seven walks in 37 games for Triple-A Charlotte
before the Marlins demoted him to Double-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a point where you've got to put up numbers, and it
wasn't getting done for Josh in Triple-A,'' said John Boles, the
Marlins' vice president of player development. ``There's no way to
sugar-coat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Booty is a career .198 hitter in the minor leagues and has yet
to make the adjustments he needs to make to become a major-league
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josh has to continue working on hitting the breaking ball and
the change-up, and he wasn't having success with it in Charlotte,''
Boles said. ``You want the guy to build on some positive things,
and he didn't have too many positives going for him in Triple-A.''
</P>
<P>
   WONDER DOG GROUNDED
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a surprise Wednesday when the Phillies released former
Angel Rex Hudler and his .122 average.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hudler's release was like no other in the history of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   First, he performed his own interview on the all-sports
television station that carries Phillies games. Then, he broke down
in tears talking about what a pleasure it was to hear fans thank
him for signing autographs along the first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   He also thanked the Phillies for all they had done for him.
Then, after saying his good-byes to teammates, Hudler, 37, walked
across the Phillies' clubhouse and hugged Jon Zuber, the man who
had just taken his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more than a stats player,'' said Hudler, whose
ultra-positive clubhouse influence got him the nickname Wonder Dog.
``I'm not the same player I was when I was 25, 26, 27 years old,
but I still have some physical skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, no one saw them this year. The Phillies signed him to a
two-year, $2.6-million deal before last season, and he contributed
12 RBI. In 1996, Hudler hit .311 with 16 homers and 40 RBI for the
Angels. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
