A0418 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-KKK-TEX     06-27 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-KKK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KKK, BLACK PANTHERS TRADE INSULTS IN JASPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
.MDNM/ JASPER, Texas _ Members of the Ku Klux Klan and the New
Black Panthers postured and exchanged bellicose words Saturday in
this tense East Texas community, but the confrontations were minor
and only two people were arrested.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only 16 Klansmen and two Klanswomen showed up in robes and
hoods, despite two weeks of media coverage before the rally. The
white-supremacist group called the gathering to dissociate itself
from the June 7 torture-slaying of a disabled black Jasper man by
three whites.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 New Black Panthers, marching a few blocks away with
rifles and shotguns, were not permitted to come near the Klan rally
on the courthouse square. Several of their leaders tried to rush a
cordon of state troopers in riot gear who surrounded the Klansmen,
but they were pushed back each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only takes one,'' Darrell Flinn of the Vidor-based Knights
of the White Kamellia replied when asked why the Klan turnout was
so poor, despite his assertion that Jasper is in the middle of
``Klan country.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute Klan rally began, curiously, with a recorded black
Gospel rendition of the ``Battle Hymn of the Republic,'' theme of
the Union forces in the Civil War. ``It's on the tape,'' explained
a chagrined grand dragon, Michael D. Lowe of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   All Klan speakers decried the slaying of James R. Byrd Jr.,
which they called ``unnecessary.'' They said the killing was
wrongly blamed on white supremacists because two of the three men
arrested had joined the Aryan Nation in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Three white men _ Shawn Berry and John William King, both 23,
and Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., 31 _ are charged with Byrd's
slaying. All three have prison records and authorities have said at
least two have tattoos associated with white racist prison gangs.
Racist literature was seized from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Klan accused the ``liberal'' media of playing down the
killing of a local white man, Jerry McQueen, by a black man a week
before Byrd's murder. Flinn called it a hate crime; authorities
said the assailant fatally beat McQueen during a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Stores and banks within several blocks of the courthouse square
closed down at the city's request.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper's black mayor, R.C. Horn, said all but a few dozen local
residents heeded his advice to stay clear of the area, where 200
Texas Rangers, state troopers, game wardens, local police and
sheriff's deputies provided tight security. Many chose to follow
the afternoon's events at home through folksy, live reports by Mike
Lout, owner of Jasper's only rock 'n' roll station, KJAS-FM.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, in San Antonio to speak at the
Democratic State Convention, said he is not going to Jasper this
weekend and urged others to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Klan is there marching to recruit,'' said Jackson, a civil
rights leader and former presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're there to put salt in the wounds. They're there to
convince whites that the three whites who killed Mr. Byrd were
protecting them against black people. Such pathological sickness
should not attract a crowd. They need an audience. The people in
Jasper ought to go fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the presence of the New Black Panthers, Jackson said
it is ``the job of government to protect people from terrorism or
threats of terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We should put the burden upon the government, not upon some
well-meaning citizens who themselves could get drawn into something
they would regret the next day,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 60 or so anti-Klan demonstrators _ dwarfed by a far
larger contingent of journalists from around the United States,
Asia and Europe _ came from out of town. They included a Euless
punk-style group called Anti-Racist Action. The two people who were
arrested _ one black and one white, both opposed to the Klan _ were
accused of disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen Klan supporters showed up, also from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Saturdays normally are quiet in Jasper. The day is devoted to
house-cleaning, lawn-mowing and perhaps a run to nearby Lake Sam
Rayburn. But this Saturday, it was markedly anxious and quiet
beyond the 109-year-old courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   A flag-football league game was canceled because of the rally,
as was a reunion of the McQueen family. Local motels reported
cancellations by regular clients, the pristine Shady Creek Park was
empty, and business was off at the Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The rally and blockaded streets, however, did not ruin the
happiest day in the young life of kindergarten teacher Stacy Lyn
Rhames, who married a local undertaker an hour after the tumult
ended just two blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody feels sorry I had to put up with all this,'' she
said before the nuptials.
</P>
<P>
   An uncle from San Antonio cited the Klan action when he
telephoned to say he would not be coming, and Rhames feared others
would not chance driving to the First United Methodist Church for
the wedding and reception.
</P>
<P>
   But a large crowd of family and well-wishers turned up. The
bridesmaids wore watermelon red; the bride was radiant when she
tossed her bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We totally ignored it all,'' Rhames _ now Mrs. Shultz _ said
of the commotion that was a short walk away. ``I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   On a farm-to-market road just a few miles from where James
Byrd's dismembered body was found, the black Twine family didn't
allow the Klan to interfere with its annual reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Children played tug-of-war, and their parents _ 12 grown sons
and daughters jnVn; ssorted spousest6Kav3ht up on family news while
a mammoth smoker transformed beef brisket and chicken into East
Texas barbecue. Some relatives came from as far away as New York.
</P>
<P>
   One daughter, Virginia Twine of Houston, said a friend had urged
her not to travel to Jasper this weekend because of the Klan rally.
She recalled replying, ``I was born and raised in Jasper, Ann. It
isn't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what Jasper is like is not always easy to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Some black residents noted that the town lacks a municipal
swimming pool because it would have to be integrated and that Byrd
was buried in the traditionally black section of the city cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   None could cite a major racial incident before Byrd's killing.
</P>
<P>
   Judy James, a white Jasper schoolteacher, said she had taken for
granted the number of blacks in key positions until the community
of 7,800 _ 45 percent black _ came under media scrutiny. Aside from
the mayor and two of Axd eve City Council members, two school
principals and the Chamber of Commerce president are black. Until
recently, a respected black timber company executive served as the
school board president.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, George Miller, administrator of the town's largest
hospital, who emerged as a unifying figure after the slaying, noted
that he was selected for his job by nine white board members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the Klan and the Black Panthers, there is now no focal
point, so things might finally calm down here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the local Wal-Mart, Stacey Moore, a white Jasper native, said
she is ``proud of Jasper'' and ``how we've responded to all this,''
as she paid for her milk, eggs, Coke and other groceries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KKK and the Black Panthers, all they're doing is stirring
up trouble. And I'm not going to let them affect my routine. We
want peace and time to let the (Byrd) family heal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
