r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LADN     06-27 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG, HOT SUMMER FOR NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Images from the front lines of a labor war:
</P>
<P>
   A free agent who can't find a new team.
</P>
<P>
   A rookie who can't polish his game in summer league.
</P>
<P>
   A general manager left pondering for months how to fill out his
roster.
</P>
<P>
   A country forced to field amateurs in international competition.
</P>
<P>
   A fan forced to watch, er, hockey? Football? Curling on ESPN2?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaires fight multimillionaires over a $1.8 billion
industry, and everyone loses.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the long summer, and possibly longer fall, to come in
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Owners and players are at an impasse over the league's labor
contract, and on Wednesday the league is expected to impose a
lockout of players. Literally speaking, it means the owners lock
the players out of NBA facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But more significantly, it means all NBA business will come to a
halt _ no signings, no trades, no negotiating with free agents _
until a new labor contract is signed. And because the owners and
the players association are miles apart on the key economic issues,
that day could be months away.
</P>
<P>
   The fight in the interim promises to be drawn-out, ugly and,
ultimately, harmful to the league.
</P>
<P>
   The long, hot summer will affect everyone from the GMs to the
rookies and free agents and eventually, the season-ticket holder,
the scalper and the couch potato.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the potential lockout from different perspectives:
</P>
<P>
   THE LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   If the NBA commissioner's office ever emulated its players' art
of smack talking, its crack on other league commissioners might be,
``Well, at least !ital!we've!off! never lost a single
regular-season game to a labor crisis!''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern's best bragging point could soon go the
way of the dodo bird, Marv Albert's broadcasting career and NBA
short shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the union has advised players to plan on missing their
first paychecks, due Nov. 15, implying the season opener is
considered in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says it will take the threat of missing
games to force a compromise on the so-called ``Bird exception,''
which allows teams to spend unlimited dollars on their free agents.
The league hopes otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's huge concern that if we suffer a work stoppage where
we miss games there will be a great deal of damage,'' NBA deputy
commissioner Russ Granik said. ``But that's not a reason to operate
an unprofitable business. You can't use that (concern) as a basis
for continuing a system that doesn't work. I'd be kidding to try to
say we didn't have serious concern about the results.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik and Stern need only look to Major League Baseball's 1994
strike as the perfect example of how to nearly cripple a league
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Major league baseball lost a reported $185 million in 1996, the
first full season year after the 94 strike that killed the World
Series for the first time in history. Baseball teams overall lost
$875 million in the three-year span.
</P>
<P>
   It's only in the last year or so that baseball has seen a
recovery and an upswing in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 93 baseball had a record year as far as attendance ... and
'94 was heading that way until the strike and the cancellation of
the World Series,'' said Katy Feeney, National League senior vice
president. ``It hurt baseball. It's not how you want to do
business.''
</P>
<P>
   THE GENERAL MANAGER
</P>
<P>
   Even the threat of the lockout _ it's been anticipated for
months, and neither side figured it would be avoidable _ has
impacted teams.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to July 1, general managers are
typically in a Monty Hall mentality, dealing their underachievers
for the promise of someone else's spare parts. But the lockout put
a chill on all but a handful of potential deals.
</P>
<P>
   GMs need the flexibility of renouncing rights to their free
agents _ a process that would normally take place in July _ to
clear salary cap room. And then there's the uncertainty over how a
new collective bargaining agreement might change the rules for
re-signing free agents or increase the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, there's a lot more (trade) talk'' than in a
typical June, Lakers GM Mitch Kupchak said two weeks ago, ``but in
my opinion, you won't see as much happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, not much has, with the Lakers' Nick Van Exel trade among
the handful of exceptions. Most trades so far involved rookies in
last week's draft.
</P>
<P>
   The big loser among GMs could be Phoenix's Bryan Colangelo. The
Suns have only three players under contract and if the lockout
stretches into the fall, Colangelo might have as little as two
weeks to put together the other 75 percent of the roster.
</P>
<P>
   THE FREE AGENT
</P>
<P>
   Rick Fox passed up millions of dollars to join the Lakers for a
one-year, $1 million contract and the shot at a championship. His
reward is a fuzzy future.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will be a free agent Wednesday and wants to return to the
Lakers. The team again can't afford his market value due to
salary-cap constraints. But a new labor deal might make Fox a Laker
again.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a half-dozen other teams _ among them
Cleveland, Atlanta, Vancouver, Houston and Orlando _ would like to
offer him a multiyear deal. Two European teams covet him as well
and are willing to pay close to NBA-type money.
</P>
<P>
   But the seven-year pro is caught in a Fox-trap. Under NBA rules,
teams and players can't talk until July 1. And under a lockout,
they can't talk at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard being patient and just waiting, without knowing even
what date he'll be able to sign a contract,'' said Mark Portnoy,
Fox's agent. ``On the other hand, Rick is confident of what he's
done in the past that he'll be able to get his market value. But it
is hard emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   THE ROOKIE
</P>
<P>
   The NBA sponsors pro summer leagues each offseason in order to
get rookies into playing shape and to give young free agent
hopefuls a shot at an NBA contract. It was in the 1997 summer
league that little-known center Keith Closs got the attention of
NBA scouts and snagged a $9 million, five-year contract with the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be no summer leagues, and that's a setback for
the rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just so much to learn and so much to do, especially
with the lockout it's going to be tough,'' said Sam Jacobson,
drafted by the Lakers out of Minnesota last week.
</P>
<P>
   THE FAN
</P>
<P>
   Last, definitely not least. But before the fan embarks on a
summer of self-pity, take heart in this much: The fans eventually
have something to gain from the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, the new labor agreement will tighten the
salary-cap exceptions that have allowed teams to spend freely on
marquee players at the expense of letting other players go.
</P>
<P>
   Under different rules, the Bulls might have paid less to Michael
Jordan and hung onto free-agent center Brian Williams. Under
different rules, the Lakers might have been able to keep Travis
Knight, who they developed as a rookie but immediately lost to free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   And the new labor pact will almost certainly mandate longer
rookie contracts, up to four or five years instead of the current
three years. So the Denver Nuggets wouldn't have had to trade away
Antonio McDyess, fearing the choice of perhaps overpaying an
unproven talent or risking losing him to another team with money to
spend.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the fans might see a little less roster turnover
and a more recognizable home team.
</P>
<P>
   So sit back, relax, and wait. Take up a hobby. Because there
will be a lockout, and it will almost certainly be protracted,
painful and boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lockout unless a miracle takes place,'' said
players association executive Billy Hunter, ``which probably won't
happen. We're probably in for a long summer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980627.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0485 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TILLMAN-AZR &LR;      06-27 2567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TILLMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP'S ANGRY VOICE IN ARIZONA: `I'M NOT HERE FOR PEOPLE TO LIKE
ME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oscar Tillman has a file folder full of death threats.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't worry about the ones that come to his office, which
he stashes and locks in a cabinet. It's the ones that find their
way to his home that disturb him.
</P>
<P>
   Those, he complains, violate a sacred division between his
kick-down-the-door, in-your-face public persona and a gentle
private life devoted to his three children, gourmet cooking and his
wife of 32 years, Sheila.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman is the state's NAACP president and a part-time minister.
He talks like a drill sergeant and has made the Valley his boot
camp. That hasn't made him popular with many of Arizona's White
forces _ or even the ranks of the city's Blacks and other
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here for people to like me,'' says Tillman, who turned
54 in May. ``My job is to call it like it is. To wake people up.
Lots of people don't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, Tillman is a voice in the wilderness in a city where
public dissent is uncommon and where minority communities often
lack effective leadership. Others think he's a disagreeable,
caustic rabble-rouser who usually gets his facts wrong. But all
agree that his outbursts have riled liberals, conser vatives,
people of all classes and even some of his closest backers.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, Tillman angered law-enforcement officials when
he blasted the Phoenix Police Depart ment for arresting a Black
teenager in the fatal shooting of two Apollo High School students,
but letting two White men go. When it turned out the accused
killer's companions were a Black male and a White female, Tillman
acknowledged he made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In April, he angered many Black supporters when he condemned the
appointment of Phoenix's first Black police chief, Harold Hurtt,
for not being an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why'd he have to do that?'' asks one prominent Black leader.
``He just can't keep his mouth shut.''
</P>
<P>
   And at former Gov. Fife Syming ton's lowest moment, when he was
convicted of fraud in U.S. District Court last September, Tillman
couldn't resist giving one last jab to the chief executive who
never granted him a face-to-face audience: ``You can cancel my
request to meet with the governor,'' Tillman told a Symington staff
member minutes after the governor was convicted. &QL; 
WORKS FOR NO PAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For his job with the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, Tillman gets paid nothing _ not even money for gas.
Nor does he get paid for his work as assistant pastor at the New
Home Baptist Church in southwest Phoe nix.
</P>
<P>
   He is retired from the Air Force, and a military pension helps
him pay the bills. Many past NAACP presidents in Arizona have held
full-time jobs. Tillman says this keeps him from running into any
conflicts of interest with an em ployer.
</P>
<P>
   But some people say conflict is what Tillman is all about.
Privately he is soft-spoken and thoughtful, but much of the public
knows him only as an angry sound bite.
</P>
<P>
   At the Coffee Plantation in the Biltmore, several White
customers describe Tillman as inflammatory and racially divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tune him out because he seems so out there,'' says
Marlene Thomas of Phoenix. ``He makes outrageous accusations. I
feel like he isn't willing to work things out. The first thing he
does is call for boycotts.''
</P>
<P>
   Others criticize Tillman for jump ing the gun before getting all
the facts.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hamblin, a radio talk-show host in Denver, cites two
shoplifting cases _ one in Phoenix and one in Denver, when Tillman
was the head of the NAACP there. In both cases, Tillman rallied the
Black commu nity and accused the stores of racism, civil rights
violations and using excessive force. In the Phoe nix case, he even
called for an FBI investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But after all the drama, both women were found guilty of shop
lifting. One was even caught on videotape. &QL; 
`HE NEVER HESITATES' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, some contend Tillman is one of the few leaders in
Phoenix who will speak his mind and stand up for minorities'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anyone else who is willing to take the
stances he has,'' says Stephen Montoya, a civil rights attorney in
Phoenix. ``He never hesitates to come out for what is right.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, he threatened to boycott Scottsdale's popular
Phoenix Open when city officials failed to take harsh action
against the Scotts dale Police Department over allega tions it used
racial slurs and referred to a wealthy area as a ``no nigger
zone.'' Earlier this year, he was the only minority leader
badgering leg islators to pass a bill preserving the attorney
general's authority to en force civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman is seen as a savior to residents of the Valley's
poorest, predominantly Black neighbor hoods, where his no-nonsense
talk appeals to their sense of frustration and injustice. These
residents say his tactics are more necessary than ever as the gap
widens between the Valley's poorest and wealthiest resi dents.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Smith says Tillman helped him settle a discrimination
and harassment case against his em ployer. Smith says he was being
harassed on the job because he asked why he had been bypassed for
a &UR; promotion for someone who had less seniority and an inferior work
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing you know, the guy they had promoted was giving me
a &UR; hard time at work. He was writing me up for things I didn't
even &UR; do. Then he tried to put me on a night shift,'' recalls Smith,
who works for a high-tech manufacturer in Chan dler. ``That's when
I took the matter to the NAACP and Tillman.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillman was swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``He created such an uproar that people were backing up like
crazy,'' recalls Smith, who says they were preparing a lawsuit
against the company. ``They're so afraid to deal with him again
that they don't dare try to pull any &UR; more shenanigans with me.'' &QL; 
PAYS PRICE IN HEALTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For his efforts, Tillman has paid a price, says his wife,
Sheila. In the summer of 1995, he suffered a mild heart attack. His
health &UR; is fine now. But his wife makes certain he relaxes at home
and &UR; leaves his work at the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed that the price of freedom is absolute
vigi lance. Oscar is a great watchman. But there is a tremendous
toll on his health,'' she says. ``I worried about that and I worry
about the death threats. But Arizona needs him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillman spends most days at NAACP offices in south Phoenix,
hearing complaints and calling em ployers and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his railing in public, it is in the office where he
earns his credibility. He spends day after day on the phone,
arguing, cajoling, shouting and listening to people who feel
they've been wronged.
</P>
<P>
   On this afternoon, he is talking up a tirade on the phone with a
human resources director and stat ing the case for a worker
claiming job discrimination. Sitting in his small office, he has
his eyebrows raised and is listening intently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You purposely put him in this environment!'' shouts Tillman,
threatening to sue the company. ``How do you expect someone to
succeed in this condition?''
</P>
<P>
   He lets the other person speak, then erupts: ``Now, you listen
here! This isn't right! I'm not going away until I have some
answers. You can't do this to a person. You better have some
answers next time I call!''
</P>
<P>
   Tillman hangs up. He stares at the phone, takes a deep breath
and begins to tackle other files on his desk when the phone rings.
This time a woman is calling to complain the NAACP isn't doing
enough on her discrimination case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute!'' Tillman yells. ``You never came in here and
filled out that paperwork, did you? Did you get your documentation
ready? Well, don't come complaining to me that we haven't done
anything on your case. We can't do anything if you haven't done a
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He rubs his temples. Sometimes, the job gives him a headache, he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; So why does he do it?
</P>
<P>
   Some say it's the attention. Or the power. Still others find the
answer in his childhood. Tillman's life is full of painful memories
of racial prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Born on May 7, 1944, Tillman grew up in Wadesboro, N.C., &UR; where
his family worked picking crops _ cotton, watermelon, apples, what
ever was in season.
</P>
<P>
   He rattles off the memories: the tired, old Black workers who
were required to give up their seats on buses for White passengers.
Ku Klux Klan rallies. Opportunities his parents were denied. His
first job at a local cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   There he was paid only in tips. Once, a party of 27 adults and
children laughed as they left a penny at each of their plates for
his gratuity.
</P>
<P>
   Such humiliations left a lasting impression _ and later
motivated him to speak out against racial injustices.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of the small-town mentality, Tillman joined the military.
Various military recruiters would set up booths at the local post
office. On the day Tillman went to sign up, only the Air Force was
there. He signed up on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman met his wife while he was stationed at Mather Air Force
Base near Sacramento. It wasn't love at first sight. He was 18 and
she was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought he was so arrogant and brassy,'' Sheila says.
``I really didn't want anything to do with him. I was studious and
quiet. Plus, I was raised that nice girls don't date Air Force
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The two married three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman's vigilance began in 1970s, while he was receiving
training at Fort McClelland Army base in Alabama. Fed up with
military police searches of lockers without cause, Tillman
protested. He says he called the first sergeant on duty and told
him: ``It was illegal and I wouldn't be letting them go through my
locker unless I was ordered to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The searches continued, but Till man only had a few weeks to go
before returning to his Air Force base.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the military, Tillman says, he tried to challenge
injustices whenever he came across them.
</P>
<P>
   JOINED NAACP IN 1980S &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His work with NAACP began in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, he decided to run for the president's seat of the
Tacoma, Wash., NAACP. He won and spent four years there. Then his
wife was transferred to Arizona by her em ployer, US West.
</P>
<P>
   When he came to Phoenix at the end of 1987, Tillman took over
the &UR; local chapter of the NAACP for Maricopa County. Then in 1992,
Tillman moved to Denver. His wife had received a transfer and he
joined the NAACP there.
</P>
<P>
   For many, it was time to cele brate. Throughout the Valley, offi
cials of various races were toasting the news, saying their nemesis
was leaving town.
</P>
<P>
   Their revelry, however, was short-lived. Tillman moved back to
Phoenix after just a year.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's Black community con sidered Tillman too controversial
and never welcomed him. Tillman says the entire time he was there,
only two Black ministers invited him to visit their congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the Black community there was using me and I
didn't like that,'' Tillman recalls.
</P>
<P>
   He moved back to Arizona and has been raising a ruckus ever
since. He became NAACP state president shortly in 1995 and won a
two-year, re-election bid in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman's community ties also are grounded in his role as
assistant pastor for the New Home Baptist Church, located in the
drug-infested streets off Buckeye Road.
</P>
<P>
   As he enters the church's door one recent day, Tillman's caustic
demeanor changes. The anger seems to have vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's touched all our lives with his dedication. Most people of
his status would go to a bigger churches,'' Maggie Holden says.
``But he chose a small church. He likes to help the kids. If the
kids make good grades, he gives them money out of his own pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   On this Sunday, about 50 people sit in the 11-pew church. An
eight-person choir belts out gospel hymns. Outside, a few yards
away from the church parking lot, a drug dealer hangs out on the
street corner.
</P>
<P>
   During the service, there is a special moment for people who
need a group prayer to come forward. Ten-year-old Ianisha Morn ing
shuffles up and takes a chair before the church. The girl, who
lives in Scottsdale, tearfully explains that kids on the playground
have been calling her ``terrible names'' and she needs help coping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is wrong with our society,'' Tillman storms. ``In
1998, there's no reason a child should be asking us to stand up &UR; for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillman also draws support from his wife and family. He and
Sheila live in a historic central Phoenix neighborhood, in a house
that has become a haven from the unsettling world of politics and
racial contro versy.
</P>
<P>
   At the home, a wall is covered with signed watercolor prints by
Seattle artist Danny Mayes. Another wall is strewn with words made
out of wood, such as ``perseverance,'' ``love,'' ``tears,''
``integrity`` and ``honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila shows off pictures of their three children _ daughter
Sharon, 30, and their two adopted sons, Mazuba, 26, and Greg, 25.
And she talks about the demands her hus band is under and the toll
of his stress.
</P>
<P>
   When the stress gets severe, Tillman retreats to his kitchen,
where he is the family's main cook.
</P>
<P>
   The support Tillman draws from family, church and low-income mi
norities is belied by his status as a political loner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a radical. No one (in the Black community) wanted to let
me in. I kept finding myself being left out of important
meetings,'' Tillman says. ``I guess you could say I was an outsider
and kind of a rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   People in power sense that he is an outsider. They try to ignore
him, refusing to invite him to the tables of discussion. Tillman,
they feel, is a flame-thrower, averse to compro mise, and no one
wants to get burned. But in a Valley that is only 3 percent Black,
he is still a force to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Scott Bundgaard, R-Glen dale, is among those who think
Tillman lacks control.
</P>
<P>
   He butted heads with him this year over the legislator's
proposed ban on affirmative action in Ari zona. In testimony before
a Senate committee, Tillman referred to Bundgaard and other
supporters as the type who wear ``white hoods.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to wonder about the way he goes about getting
his message across. He doesn't choose his words very wisely and he
comes across as very extreme. He gets carried away by the emotion
of his debate,'' Bundgaard said. ``But when the mikes are off and
the camera is put away, he's a very nice man. So you almost have to
wonder what's motivating him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillman does have his public allies. They include Maricopa
County Supervisor Mary Rose Wil cox and Montoya, the Phoenix civil
rights attorney. He also has drawn the media's attention because of
his willingness to speak out in anger.
</P>
<P>
   It took Lincoln Ragsdale, the funeral tycoon who died in 1996,
to give Tillman the break he needed to gain a position of influence
in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had just finished a meeting, but everyone was getting into
their cars and heading to a private meeting. He saw me walking to
my car and he came up to me and told me to get into his car,''
Tillman says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew no one would tell him anything. They didn't like me be
cause I was the kick-the-door-down type. But I've never gotten
anything by knocking on doors. Arizona wasn't used to that. I don't
know if it still is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
