<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0486 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RICKYWILLIAMS-HNS     06-27 3570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RICKYWILLIAMS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Minor-league experience a joy for Heisman favorite Williams
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BATAVIA, N.Y. _ From the moment the sky first opens, bringing the
sort of storm you remember, there is no doubt the game will become
a rainout. Within minutes, the perfect grass of Damaschke Field,
the longtime and traditional throwback home of the Oneonta Yankees,
is a swamp. The perfunctory examination of the lagoons in the
infield notwithstanding, there is no chance the O-Yanks and the
Batavia Muckdogs will attempt anything but a rapid run to the bus
for the next minor-league road trip.
</P>
<P>
   But long after both teams, save a few Muckdogs huddled in the
dugout, have escaped to the protection of their clubhouses, Ricky
Williams stands alone and swings a bat, hard and repeatedly. The
rain pounds down around him. But Williams was on deck when it hit,
so he keeps on swinging his bat, stopping only to shout toward a
teammate, once even offering a Singin' In the Rain dance step,
jumping to click his heels, before going back to taking cuts alone
with his soaked black lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly it is obvious. It all makes perfect sense. At that
moment, even the teen-agers in the covered grandstand _ arguing if
that really is the Heisman Trophy favorite in the gaudy, soaked,
candy-apple-red Muckdogs uniform _ can see why Ricky Williams still
plays minor-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to run the bases, but they said we're not allowed,''
Williams says, flashing the smile that someday soon will sell
hamburgers or sporting goods or whatever he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   If he is disappointed to have been restricted to the on-deck
circle, it doesn't show. There will be another game tomorrow, even
if another four hours on the bus must come first. And that _
another game, another chance to hit ground balls and get down the
line impossibly fast, another day to read a curveball correctly, to
steal a base, to simply play _ is all he needs.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 21, could have been ridiculously wealthy by now had
he, as expected, chosen to skip his senior year at Texas to declare
himself available for the NFL draft. His summer living room, he
says, is the team ``arcade.'' He could have had Disneyland. Having
turned down millions, he plays in a league in which players earn a
free sandwich for extra-base hits.
</P>
<P>
   But sitting about 35 miles east of Buffalo in a summer rental
duplex in Batavia, N.Y., a relative shack with no air-conditioning
decorated in early pizza box and Taco Bell wrapper, Williams
wonders how he could have even considered leaving school with a
year left to play.
</P>
<P>
   He could be back in Austin, training for his run at the Heisman
and, with a season to match last, the record as the most prolific
college running back ever. This is no small matter to him; at his
January news conference to announce his decision, he knew the
precise number of yards he needed _ 1,928 _ to surpass Tony
Dorsett.
</P>
<P>
   He could be home in San Diego where it's cool, relaxing for the
football season to come while exercising his competitive fires on
Nintendo, which still inspires him to pump fists and high-five
while bouncing on his couch as happily as Tom Hanks in Big.
</P>
<P>
   But a few days of watching Williams play minor-league baseball
makes it obvious: he could be nowhere else. This fourth season on
the bottom rung of the minor-league baseball ladder, these small
towns _ ``We're really in the boonies now,'' he says after the bus
gets lost in the mountains around Oneonta, N.Y. _ and long bus
rides, even the strikeouts and struggles he could escape so easily
make perfect sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays with a joy,'' says Tigers scout Scott Boras, sitting
in the front row with a stopwatch, a clipboard and 41 years in
baseball. ``It's obvious. He loves to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams couldn't give that up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I?'' he says. ``I've always played baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I contemplated (leaving football) a couple of years ago,''
Williams reveals. ``I really thought about quitting football. I
wasn't very close, but I thought about it a lot. There was just no
way I could call (former Texas) coach (John) Mackovic and say I'm
not coming back to (instead) play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm doing well, I want to just do baseball. When I do
badly, I just want to quit and go play football. But I'm going to
play at least three or four more years. I can see myself playing in
the NFL for four years and saying, `OK, I'm just going to play
baseball.' I could be here for three more years and be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mucks are down 8-0 heading into the bottom of the ninth, and
they are not coming back. Williams has gotten his daily hit and
will stop this night at one. His last at-bat produces only a
routine, two-hop ground ball to second.
</P>
<P>
   It is the most exciting, breathtaking play of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Boras knows instantly what he has seen. He doesn't need the
stopwatch for more than the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran a 3.96,'' Boras reports happily.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has long been signed by another club. But Boras feels
that rush of discovery for which scouts live.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 3.96,'' he says. ``That's unreal. I haven't seen that from a
righthanded batter since Willie Wilson, and that was more than 20
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was out by the first baseman's stretch on the play. But
he exploded out of the far side of the batter's box and disappeared
down the line as few, other than the occasional Mickey Mantle or Bo
Jackson, ever have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gone faster,'' Williams says the next night in
Jamestown, N.Y. ``I was watching to see if (the ball) went through
for a few steps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really a talented kid,'' Boras says. ``I see why the
Phillies have a tremendous interest in him. To look at him move, to
see him run four-flat down the line with that kind of strength just
to see that kind of size, strength and speed in one package is very
rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very difficult game to play. He just needs time. But
scouts are looking all over the country for that kind of size,
strength and speed.''
</P>
<P>
   If the term ``tools'' to describe parts of a player's game were
not already clich, any discussion of Williams' prospects as a
baseball player would make it so. There are so many levels in
minor-league baseball _ Williams plays for one of the Philadelphia
Phillies' four Class A affiliates and has 30 teammates _ that the
search is always on for rare talents that can be honed later to
major-league standards. The organization will teach young prospects
how to hit. Physical talent, and tools that cannot be taught, are
coveted.
</P>
<P>
   In a baseball uniform, especially in the Muckdogs' road red,
Williams looks huge, football muscles testing the seams around his
shoulders and thighs. His teammates, almost all just off college
campuses, seem smaller, younger. Williams looks as if he should bat
cleanup and attempt to damage the ball or fail magnificently with
every swing.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams bats leadoff with a wide, slightly open stance. He
has learned to swing down on the ball with a compact, controlled
stroke. He gets excited over any at-bat in which he makes solid
contact. Batting .345 through the first week of the season, he beat
out more than half of his infield grounders for hits and was the
New York-Penn League's only batter to hit safely in every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are five skills in baseball _ hit for average, hit for
power, throw, run and field,'' Williams notes. ``I'm a pretty good
fielder. And I've got a strong arm and speed, so I've got two of
the five now. And they say you learn how to hit, and power will
come later.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he clearly is vastly improved from his first three
seasons of minor-league baseball, Williams insists he needs to get
better in every facet.
</P>
<P>
   An eighth-round pick out of high school, Williams batted .239 in
1995 at Martinsville, Va., and .188 and .206 the past two seasons
at Piedmont, N.C. But in the last few games of his first week for
Batavia, he has made far more consistent contact than in the past.
And it has involved more than just hitting the ball in the dirt and
sprinting down the line.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, making contact and getting down the line is
enough. Almost every analysis of Williams' long-range baseball
prospects includes the caveat, ``If he played all year '' But even
though he has played fewer than 40 games most summers and failed to
escape Class A ball in three seasons, Williams expects to reach the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky has definitely got tools,'' Muckdogs manager Frank Klebe
says. ``We're giving him the opportunity to play and produce and
improve his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good baserunner, but he can work on getting better
jumps and stealing bases. He can field his position, but he can
improve tracking to the ball. And he's got an average arm. His arm
strength is well above average, but we're working on his release
point and accuracy. At bat, he has to put the ball in play, cut
down on his strikeouts, be patient, don't swing at bad pitches,
understanding the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the tools he has, if he just wanted to concentrate on
baseball, he'd have a good opportunity to play at the big-league
level. He might still do that. He has the tools, talent and the
drive. He works real hard. And he has fun playing the game. And
Ricky wants to be a star. A lot of guys just want to compete at
their level. You have to want to make that jump. You have to look
inside yourself to say, `I don't want to play at this level; I want
to reach the highest level I can.' It's not selfish to say, `I want
to be the best I can be.' Ricky has that.''
</P>
<P>
   But he always knows he can at any time leave the frustrations of
baseball and enjoy his place and prowess as perhaps college
football's best player. A happy trash-talker in football, he rips
himself in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to work hard,'' he says, ``because I'm not any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he doesn't have the same verbal swagger in baseball
that he has in football, Williams responds, ``You can't talk trash
if you can't back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   But when an Erie, N.Y., reporter asks Williams, ``You're
obviously not very good at baseball, so why do you play?'' Williams
is obviously offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people say I'm not going to make it in baseball, it
pushes me harder,'' he says. ``I don't care what people think, but
I use it to push me.''
</P>
<P>
   And his football talent, rather than lure him away from
baseball, inspires him. Even as he recognizes and acknowledges his
baseball shortcomings as would a harsh, impartial observer, there
is an underlying confidence that helps keep him in the minor
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pushes me in baseball because I want to be the best,''
Williams says of his football success. ``I like being the best. I
just keep trying and working hard. I go out there every day and try
to compete in everything I do. I like to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is a plan. He is no longer tempted to give up
football. But when he imagines himself playing only one sport, it's
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so far to go,'' Williams says. ``It's probably five
years before I'm in the major leagues. But I started at 18. I think
the average age to get in the majors is like, 25. So I still have a
few years to get there. If I'm 28 and play until I'm 35, I'd have
seven years in the bigs. I'd be happy with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has already singled up the middle when Nick Punto hits
a sharp grounder to Jamestown shortstop Keith Law. Law flips to Ron
Bush at second, but before Bush can complete his pivot to make the
throw to first, before he has time to realize time is running out,
Bush is airborne. Williams has closed the gap to second too fast
and sent Bush flying. It isn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is immediately called for baserunner's interference,
with Punto ruled out at first. Klebe argues Williams had not left
the baseline to reach Bush, but while Bush struggles to his feet,
the argument really can get nowhere. ``I guess,'' Klebe says later,
``he needed to get in some contact.''
</P>
<P>
   This might be the most important season ever for pitcher Pete
Mondello, who is a long way from the Show. Batavia is, for most, a
starting point. But Mondello is coming back from arm trouble. This
season will be his first since the pain showed up in his shoulder,
threatening a career that was only just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   But when Mondello phoned home to Port Arthur and his family full
of Texas football fans, he happily reported Ricky Williams was a
teammate. Conversation naturally included a progress report on the
arm, but Mondello was told a package of memorabilia was on its way
to Batavia for Williams' signature.
</P>
<P>
   And though professional athletes don't generally gush about one
another, Mondello, as with most of the Mucks, gets a kick out of
finding a college football All-American in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in drills running and I'll think, `OK, all right, I'm
running with Ricky Williams,''' shortstop Matt Denure says. ``Then
I'll look over, and boom, he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than a brush with fame or an up-close look at rare
talent that excites. Virtually every teammate quickly points to
Williams' work ethic and humility, as if they had expected
something very different.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a lot different from a lot of athletes I know,'' Mondello
says. ``He's kind of soft-spoken, but he's smart. I've known a lot
of football players. Leeland McElroy (the former Texas A&AMP;M star
from Beaumont) was kind of a showboat. Ricky is totally different.
He's busting it every day. He does more than I expected. He works
really hard, and he has stayed humble.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams says his lack of mastery in baseball forced that
humility, but he is more than accepted. This is especially
important in the minors, where players are in constant proximity
within the closed confines of buses and Spartan clubhouses.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mucks make their way through the Appalachian Mountains of
upstate New York, few bother to peek out the window. Scenery, no
matter how dramatic, is of little appeal to a bus full of
ballplayers. Usually, the blinds are closed to allow a better view
of the videos that always play. And though they are strong,
testosterone-heavy movies (The Usual Suspects, A Few Good Men,
Heat), most players give them only passing interest.
</P>
<P>
   Williams almost always chooses a game. Nintendo runs constantly
in his temporary living room. Cards, usually spades, are dealt in
the back of the bus.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas, Williams is well-liked, but he has few close friends.
It's different with Batavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get much closer in baseball than football,'' Williams
says. ``In baseball, you're together every single day. You have a
game every day. You practice. You're together for at least six
hours every day, sometimes a lot more. You have to be closer. You
can't be by yourself in baseball. There are times I want to be by
myself, but I can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he becomes another guy on the bus. And when every game
ends with a dozen or so kids crowding past the rest of the Muckdogs
to chase Williams' autograph, pushing copies of Sports Illustrated
and summer football magazines at him, no one seems to mind being
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The scene reminds that there is something special about the left
fielder of the Muckdogs, but since he does not seem impressed by
his gifts, there is no reason to hold them against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought everybody was joking around, saying that
was him,'' first baseman Shane Carnes says. ``I know he's a
football god in college, so I was skeptical. I knew how good he
was. I've seen him run, but when I saw him, I didn't know it was
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, he's a great guy, level-headed. He plays hard,
and he's so fast. If I was a linebacker, I wouldn't want to tackle
him. And I think he's going to win the Heisman. I really hope he
does, too. I got his autograph. A lot of us have.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Williams broke late. A line drive seemed
headed right for him, freezing him for a moment until he had to
take off to his right as the ball hooked. He grabbed it before
there was need for real concern.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, however, there is no doubt, and Williams breaks
immediately, knowing he has plenty of ground to cover. The ball
reaches the alley in left-center when Williams begins to downshift
to settle under it. He makes the catch on the run about five feet
in front of the warning track. Asked later if he had to run
all-out, Williams looks insulted. ``Nah,'' he says. ``I was looking
at it the whole way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bleachers, 19-year-old Randy Carlson of Gerry, N.Y.,
holds the recent Sports Illustrated with the Williams feature in
it, while his friends, who had long since given up such adolescent
pursuits, chase foul balls that will later bear an opponent's
signature.
</P>
<P>
   Jason ``Love Train'' Smorol is drenched in sweat. He has spent
the past 45 minutes sweeping the bleachers of Dwyer Stadium,
unsatisfied with the work of his grounds crew earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We promise Batavia a clean place to watch baseball,'' says
Smorol, the Muckdogs' general manager who two years ago was a
director of special projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what a special project is in minor-league
baseball?'' Smorol asks. ``Cleaning the bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   A clean stadium is not all that is promised. Every half-inning
has another contest, from lawn bowling in Batavia to grape stomping
in Jamestown. There are mascots (Jamestown trots out two and a
clown) and, at every opportunity, giveways, music and sound
effects. When the game reaches the last call mandated by
professional baseball, fans hear a recording of the John Belushi
line from Animal House: ``My advice to you is to start drinking
heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   And in case anyone forgets there is baseball, a Batavia Wall of
Fame of former stars who made it _ including Cito Gaston, Steve
Blass, Doc Ellis, Manny Sanguillen and Kelly Gruber _ greets every
ticket holder entering the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest controversy in Batavia baseball history was the
offseason vote that named the team the Muckdogs. The more dignified
``Clippers'' was determined in a copyright case to belong to the
New York Yankees and their farm team, the Columbus Clippers.
Everything from the Rocks to the Pancakes was proposed for Batavia.
When Muckdogs, suggested in honor of the guardians of the produce
grown in western New York's rich ``muck'' soil, won, the small town
was in an uproar.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Smorol and his three-person staff (which swells to 35 on
game nights) sell everything possible with Muckdogs on it.
Minor-league gear, the more peculiar the better, is hot, and Smorol
estimates he can move at least $50,000 in merchandise this summer.
The most popular contest is the nightly search for the loudest
bark.
</P>
<P>
   Having the Heisman Trophy favorite dropped at the top of the
lineup would seem a minor-league dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't usually get the Houston Chronicle, Dallas Morning
News and CNN around here,'' Smorol said. ``I told him whatever
attention he brings is good for us, and it's good for him, too. But
we won't use it. We won't say, `Now batting, Heisman Trophy
contender Ricky Williams.' That would be too cheesy. We're real
cheesy, but that's too much, even for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to dress him up and take him out to sell
tickets. That's supposed to be our job.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Muckdogs hit Oneonta, they have, as Smorol puts
it, ``stepped back in time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Oneonta, there are no clowns or mascots, no contests, no
cartoon characters on the uniforms. The O-Yanks wear Yankees
pinstripes with a white `O' on a blue hat. Beer is not sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to demean anybody, but we're not the Muckdogs,'' says
Oneonta business manager John Nader, a college economics professor
whose father, Sam, brought the minors back to his hometown in 1966
because he believed small towns should have baseball. ``We're about
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of life in the minors means becoming part of the silly,
intentionally tacky, innocent show. Jamestown sells itself as ``The
Greatest Show on Dirt.'' Batavia is ``Taking a bite out of the
minor leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   But to Williams, and all the Pete Mondellos and Shane Carneses,
none of that matters. Because with the minor leagues comes a chance
to keep a dream going and play ball. Most believe themselves so far
from the majors that they don't even consider the potential riches.
As with Williams, the emphasis is on improvement on every road trip
and with each at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who is much more likely to enjoy hefty professional
paydays, says he knows little of the off-field, real-world
realities of the $2.8 million of insurance he carries. He has $1.8
million in coverage through the NCAA's Exceptional Student-Athlete
Disability Insurance program and another $1 million policy secured
by his family. Unless injured, he will pay $26,000 in premiums.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams says the only insurance he needs is the degree he
his chasing in Elementary Education. Besides, neither football nor
baseball is, he says, his ultimate career. No matter what the NFL
or baseball bring, whether he wins the Heisman or takes Dorsett's
record or ever wears a Phillies uniform, Williams says he would
like to eventually teach elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   And as Williams, one of the nation's most celebrated college
football talents, stands swinging a bat in the rain in Oneonta, it
is difficult to doubt him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
