<HEADLINE>
NBA FANS JUST MIGHT SAY GOOD-BYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA is on the verge of locking out its
players, to which we say, hey, don't forget to throw away the key.
</P>
<P>
   The people safeguarding the league have broken our trust. They
have us unhinged, unsettled, upset.
</P>
<P>
   We're disturbed by a league in which spin doctors are more in
demand than orthopedic surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   The past few months have seen the Golden State Warriors hire a
public relations firm to polish their image, the Warriors' Donyell
Marshall retain an agency to trumpet his candidacy for the league's
most-improved-player award and former NBA coach Bob Hill enlist
outside sources to champion his return to the league.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, former No. 1 draft pick Greg Anderson is being
indicted by a federal grand jury on drug and money laundering
charges and Charlotte forward Anthony Mason is pleading guilty to
misdemeanor child endangerment and Philadelphia guard Allen Iverson
is on probation for misdemeanor charges of marijuana possession and
Washington forward Juwan Howard is suing a woman who accused him of
sexual assault at a 3 a.m. party at his house.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's allegations, Howard said, ``have done irreparable
harm to my reputation and image.''
</P>
<P>
   If Howard can sue for emotional distress, then what's to stop
basketball fans from seeking a divorce from the NBA on the grounds
of irreconcilable differences?
</P>
<P>
   We're really disturbed by the antics of Howard's friend and
erstwhile teammate Chris Webber, who before he was exiled to
Sacramento had the gall to complain because Wizards owner Abe
Pollin's jet wasn't cushy enough. If a private plane left Webber
cramped and cranky, just think how he would have handled playing
back in the days when commercial flights and lengthy layovers were
the norm. Yo, Chris, call a timeout to count your blessings.
</P>
<P>
   We're disturbed by all the players who have millions of dollars
but not one red cent worth of perspective. They look at the
league's $2.64 billion dollar deal with NBC and Turner and the
through-the-roof ratings of this year's NBA Finals and forget that
it wasn't always so. As recently as 1980, the final game of the NBA
Finals between the Lakers and the Philadelphia 76ers was shown on
tape delay.
</P>
<P>
   The younger players, especially, gaze out at Michael Jordan's
vast endorsement empire and demand their own commonwealth just
because they have a few highlight-reel moves, completely
overlooking the fact that Jordan's graciousness and goodness were
as integral to his sovereign rule as his tongue-wagging,
gravity-defying dunks and pit-bull defense.
</P>
<P>
   We're really disturbed by the sneaker officials who do nothing
to sharpen the players' focus. They bestow upon the likes of
Iverson a shoe deal that's worth more than his 76ers contract
before he has recorded his first assist of any significance, then
profess to be shocked and dismayed when he turns out not to be as
polished as a sneaker stuffed with paper and tucked away in a box
in some storeroom.
</P>
<P>
   We're disturbed by everyone who puts the bandwagon before the
horse, then complains that it's not moving. That includes all the
owners who lavish $100 million contracts on players who are long on
potential but short on results.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are saying they need a hard salary cap to curb
payrolls that are eating up 57 percent of the league's
basketball-related income instead of the 48 percent agreed upon in
the last collective bargaining agreement. The owners swear they
need both a ceiling on the amount they're able to spend to re-sign
their own free agents and longer contracts for rookies so they
aren't obligated to lavish huge contracts on still-unproven talent.
</P>
<P>
   What they're really telling us, of course, is they have neither
the restraint nor resolve to balance their own books. They must be
saved not from the players but from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It disturbs us that team officials are throwing a lot of money
into the hands of a relative few. This past season, the 37
highest-paid players accounted for one-third of the total payroll
while 22 percent of the players earned the minimum of $272,250.
</P>
<P>
   We're really disturbed by teams who give short shrift to hard
work and loyalty, whose bright idea of trimming expenses is to cut
out the heart of a team and ship it to one of the sorriest
franchises in the league in return for that old elixir, youth.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks traded veteran role player Charles Oakley, he of the
Herculean work ethic, to Toronto last week for Marcus Camby, a
former No. 1 draft pick who has been called unmotivated by some,
fragile by others and is, by consensus, a player whose promise
remains largely untapped.
</P>
<P>
   The trade is emblematic of an NBA that's at a crossroads, with
players who feel a responsibility to their teams, who believe a
paycheck is earned and not owed, giving way to a generation that
largely presumes teams exist solely for its benefit.
</P>
<P>
   We're disturbed by a league in which Kenny Anderson and Rony
Seikaly exercise the final say over where they'll play even after
they are traded and Latrell Sprewell chokes his coach and a couple
of teams clamor for his services and Washington general manager Wes
Unseld is moved to issue an apology to his fans for his players'
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   If that's all in a day's work in the NBA, perhaps it's just as
well that business be suspended. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
