<SLUG> BC-BKN-VAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN EXEL TO MEET WITH NUGGETS
</HEADLINE>
 EXEL-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nick Van Exel has agreed to report to the Denver Nuggets and is
scheduled to take a physical exam today in order to complete last
week's trade from the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel will meet with the Nuggets and Denver media this
afternoon, nearly four days after the draft-night deal in which the
Lakers shipped out their All-Star point guard for second-year
forward Tony Battie and rookie guard Tyronn Lue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, we're thrilled,'' said Nuggets spokesman
Tommy Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel's agent had indicated in recent weeks that his client
would not accept a trade to certain teams, though he never
specified which ones and maintained that it didn't need to be a
contender.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Exel didn't speak with Nuggets officials until Friday
and, even then, didn't say when he would be reporting, leaving the
trade in doubt. Failure to report for a physical by 4 p.m. Monday
would have allowed the Nuggets to void the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Denver general manager Dan Issel assured Van Exel that the team,
which suffered through a franchise-worst 11-71 season, was
committed to winning and planned to land a major free agent to
complement Van Exel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't promise him we'd win as many as the Lakers last year,
but with his help we'd be improved,'' Issel told the Denver Post.
</P>
<P>
   Both Issel and Van Exel's representatives said it was the trade
itself _ and not the destination _ that had Van Exel upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he was hesitant to come here,'' Issel said. ``I
think he's upset that L.A. would trade him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
