<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND JIANG ENGAGE IN LIVELY DEBATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In an extraordinary exchange aired live on Chinese
television, President Clinton and President Jiang Zemin debated
Saturday the meaning of the Tiananmen Square massacre and the
merits of personal freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-minute news conference at the Great Hall of the People
marked an unprecedented display of openness for the Chinese as
Clinton and Jiang embarked on a summit condemned by many human
rights activists in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beneath an ornate gold base relief of a mountainous
landscape, Clinton and Jiang engaged in a lively give-and-take that
touched on Taiwan, Tibet and the campaign finance scandal in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``As China and the United States have different social systems,
ideologies, values and culture traditions, we have some differences
of views on certain issues. However, they should not become the
obstacles in the way of the growth of China-U.S. relations,'' Jiang
said in his opening remarks.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese leader staunchly defended his country's actions
both in the 1989 massacre of hundreds of democracy demonstrators in
Tiananmen Square and in placing limits on personal expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the Chinese government not taken the resolute measures,
then we could not have enjoyed the stability that we are enjoying
today,'' Jiang insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton countered that stability can best be had through greater
personal freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a lot of personal freedom, some people may abuse
it. But if you are so afraid of ... the abuse that you limit
people's freedom too much, then you pay, I believe, an even higher
price in a world where the whole economy is based on ideas and
information and exchange and debate,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to ease criticism at home, Clinton condemned the
Tiananmen Square crackdown in his opening remarks, saying the two
nations disagree about its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, and the American people believe, that the use of
force and the tragic loss of life was wrong. I believe, and the
American people believe, that freedom of speech, association and
religion are, as recognized by the U.N. Charter, the right of
people everywhere and should be protected by their governments,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang noted the United States is the most developed nation in
the world, with an average income of $30,000 while China is a
developing nation with 1.2 billion people earning less than $700 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``China stresses that the top priority should be given to the
right to subsistence and the right to development,'' Jiang said.
``Meanwhile, efforts should be made to strengthen democracy and the
legal system and to protect the economic, social, cultural, civil
and political rights of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The lengthy news conference, in which the two leaders took four
questions from reporters, marked a highlight for Clinton's nine-day
visit here, the first for a U.S. president since the Tiananmen
incident.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the president's trip has been marred by the arrest of
four dissidents and the attempt by Chinese authorities to stop
Clinton's two Asian-American valets from boarding Air Force One in
Xi'an for the flight to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang defended the detentions while maintaining that in China
``people are the masters of the nation.'' He insisted journalists
were free to conduct interviews ``within the scope of law'' and
that local authorities should take action when ``some activities
that have been detrimental or have prejudiced the security.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters covering the visit got a first-hand look at some
protesters when a man and a woman lay down in front of a bus
carrying journalists from the State Dinner. Authorities dragged
them away before their cause or intentions could be determined. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The series of arrests came on the heels of massive criticism
from liberal and conservative activists in the United States who
wanted Clinton to cancel the trip, or at least bypass the official
welcoming ceremony on the steps of the Great Hall of the People,
which overlooks Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, the president's national security
adviser, hailed the summit sessions as an ``extraordinary day in
the evolution of U.S.-China relations.'' He maintained the two-hour
meeting between the two leaders and the freewheeling news
conference graphically demonstrated the value of engaging China.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, Clinton and Jiang reached a series of agreements,
including the largely symbolic gesture of removing each other's
cities as nuclear targets.
</P>
<P>
   They also agreed that the United States could inspect the uses
of U.S. high technology exports to ensure their use for civilian
purposes, a prelude for greater export of dual-use technology,
items which can be of both military and commercial significance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also reiterated the U.S. one-China policy which does not
recognize independence for Taiwan. But he urged China to engage in
a peaceful dialogue with Taiwanese leaders for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later met with Premier Zhu Rongji, the economic reformer
who promised to hold the value of the yuan currency despite the
pressures from the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, who apologized for taking so much time with his answers
in the news conference, made unprompted comments on the campaign
finance scandal in the United States and the status of the Dalai
Lama and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   He called charges that China tried to influence the 1996 U.S.
elections with illegal campaign contributions ``absurd and
ridiculous and I think they are sheer fabrications.'' He said China
has conducted an ``earnest investigation'' of the charges and
concluded ``there was never such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiang concluded the news conference by announcing he wanted to
say something about the Dalai Lama, Tibet's spiritual leader in
exile. The Chinese president said if the Dalai Lama will make a
public statement recognizing Tibet as an ``inalienable part'' of
China and recognizing Taiwan as ``a province'' of China, then the
``door to dialogue and negotiation is open.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, noting his comments likely would be unpopular,
predicted if the Dalai Lama and Jiang met ``they would like each
other very much.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and first lady later attended an official state
dinner at the Great Hall of the People where Clinton and Jiang took
turns conducting the People's Liberation Army band.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
