<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Notes
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   The New York media never have given the Braves much respect.
When Atlanta visited the Bronx for two games last week, New York
Post writer Joel Sherman wrote a column under the headline:
``Atlanta keeps up its tradition of failure.'' Wrote Sherman on the
Braves' bullpen: ``A 1998 World Series preview was held and a 1996
review broke out. ... This has been an Atlanta formula for disaster
this decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: As long as the Orioles stay within striking distance of
Boston for the wild-card spot, they will not trade either second
baseman Roberto Alomar or first baseman Rafael Palmeiro. ``We still
think we can get to the playoffs, but we have to get our pitching
staff healthy,'' assistant general manager Kevin Malone said. ...
Billy Ashley, a bust with the Dodgers, is back in the majors now
that the Red Sox have traded Jim Leyritz. Ashley, a right-handed
bat who will take Leyritz's DH platoon job, and was hitting .297 at
Class AAA Pawtucket with 10 homers and 45 RBIs in 50 games. ...
George Steinbrenner has won three World Series with the Yankees,
but he aid about the current version: ``I don't know of any better.
But I wouldn't want to put a label on them.'' You just did, George.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   Talk about not handling young pitchers properly: Indians manager
Mike Hargrove made a mistake a grievous error recently when he let
the young Bartolo Colon throw 139 pitches in a start. Hargrove
didn't ask pitching coach Mark Wiley how many pitches Colon had
thrown going into the eighth inning. ``I usually have a good feel
for number of pitches,'' Hargrove said. ``When Bartolo went out for
the eighth, I figured he had about 90.'' Colon actually had 114.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Twins pitcher Bob Tewksbury lasted only five outs in a
9-0 loss at Houston recently. ``They put away all the scalpels in
the trainer's room, so I can't slit my wrists,'' he said. ... When
the Tigers use Paul Bako behind the plate, the club is 14-11.
Bako's the only Detroit player with a winning record when starting.
... White Sox starter Jason Bere, 3-7 with a 6.02 ERA, was demoted
to the bullpen and blamed his problems on manager Jerry Manuel.
``The games he took me out, he didn't give me the benefit of the
doubt,'' said Bere, who was quickly placed on the trading block.
... Twins veteran Paul Molitor (broken rib) is on the disabled list
for the 14th time in his career, the most of any active player.
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are looking frantically for pitching, with a June
ERA of 5.87, after an earlier 12-game stretch at 7.92. The team is
considering several pitchers, including Montreal's Carlos Perez and
Cincinnati's Pete Harnisch. But manager Johnny Oates said, ``We got
to stop thinking that (owner) Tom Hicks and (general manager) Doug
Melvin are going to come in here riding on two big white horses and
bring Mr. X here.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: How has Anaheim taken the division lead from the Rangers,
despite the fact that starters Ken Hill, Jack McDowell and Allen
Watson are on the disabled list? Their replacements _ Omar Olivares
Steve Sparks and Jarrod Washburn _ are a combined 10-2. ... The
Angels already have 21 come-from-behind wins. ... The reason the
A's picked up Bip Roberts from Detroit was to use him at as second
base until Scott Spiezio recovers from a knee injury, which is
expected to keep him out a month. ... Said Barry Bonds on about
Oakland's Rickey Henderson: ``He's the greatest leadoff hitter of
all time, without a doubt. The numbers don't lie. If he's the best
statistically, he deserves to be considered the best. Like Michael
Jordan.'' ... Seattle's new ballpark, which opens in 1999, will
have a grass surface, but this season the team is just 6-25 on the
natural stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
