<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0495 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN28-COX     06-27 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves snapped out thrree-game losing streak with a win over the
Blue Jays
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Atlanta Braves hit the half mark Saturday night,
Greg Maddux using the whip on them as if riding a rented mule. It
was still daylight when he made his 104th and final pitch, which
says everything necessary about how the Braves beat Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Tucker and Ryan Klesko hitting solo homers in the
seventh inning, Atlanta snapped out of a three-game slide with a
2-0 victory over the Blue Jays, and it was inconceivable that
Maddux (11-2) could have pitched better. Striking out a
career-high13, he gave up eight singles and still recorded his
NL-high third shutout and his 100th victory as a Brave. And with
his club treading water in a 3-7 stretch, his timing was
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well,'' said Chipper Jones, ''it's better than the
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves hence closed out the first half of the schedule at
52-29, matching the best start in Atlanta history and giving them a
shot at the franchise victory mark of 104 (set in 1993). Their lead
in the NL East returned to 7 1/2 games over New York and put a
tighter spin on a 13-11 June.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll take the same in the second half,'' said manager Bobby
Cox. ''We had a great first half. We just had a bum week.''
</P>
<P>
   Matched in a remarkable duel with Toronto's Juan Guzman, who
pitched nothing like a man with just seven wins in his last 29
games, Maddux was locked into a scoreless tie the first six
innings. With his change-up unusually effective on the right-handed
hitters, he struck out seven of the first 16 men he faced and he
allowed just two men past first base all night. Still, the Braves
could not give him a lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't ever freaking look back. You can't,'' said Maddux,
who now leads the NL in wins, shutouts and ERA (1.64). ''You have
to keep pitching. The minute you start patting yourself on the
back, you mentally let down. So I don't do it. And you know what?
Guzman was pitching great too. How come he gave up the two home
runs?''
</P>
<P>
   With a highly effective split-finger fastball, Guzman held the
Braves to two singles into the seventh. But Tucker got one up in
the strike zone to lead off the seventh and drove it over the
center-field wall for his 11th homer of the season but just his
second since May 20. Following a Chipper Jones groundout, Klesko
next sent a deep drive into the right-field seats for a 2-0 lead.
The homer was Klesko's 13th homer, his fifth in the last 18 games,
during which he has driven in 14 runs.
</P>
<P>
   And that was it, though Maddux needed a double play to help
escape the ninth when the first two men up singled. As the Braves
filed off the field, most noted after a 1:46 game _ the quickest in
the majors this season _ it was still light out.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was telling the guys,'' said Jones, ``we should go ahead and
get tomorrow's game over with tonight so we could have two days
off. I might as well get my 0-for-7 out of the way real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
