<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood will get some time in bullpen
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Management maintains it has nothing to do with his
recent work on the mound, but with an off-day coming Monday, Kevin
Millwood will skip his next scheduled start and will be available
to work out of the bullpen until the middle of the week. His next
start will fall next Friday, in the first of three games with the
visiting Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to be expected,'' Millwood said. ``It's happened a couple
times already this year. I haven't been throwing real well, to say
the least. It's been on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike recent years, manager Bobby Cox has tried this season to
keep the first four starters on a four-day rotation and with John
Smoltz on and off the disabled list, Millwood's schedule has not
been affected often. Although Millwood has allowed 12 runs (14
hits) in 4 2/3 innings in his last two starts, Cox maintains he
would have made the same decision to pass over him if he had won
his last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's life as a fifth starter,'' Cox said. ``If the other
guys want an off-day, that's fine. But we've done this a lot. Most
starters don't like to be set back.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Monday's off-day, Denny Neagle, John Smoltz and Greg
Maddux will pitch the series at Tampa Bay in order. Millwood hopes
the downtime will give him a chance to work on his pitches,
particularly his breaking ball. After his rapid 7-1 start in his
first 10 outings, he is trying to treat the current swoon as a
matter of course, and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens to everybody,'' Millwood said. ``It's just
something you got to work out.No Cat again
</P>
<P>
   The team has scratched first baseman Andres Galarraga for today
and have set sights on returning him to the lineup Tuesday at Tampa
Bay. Galarraga was able to take ground balls during batting
practice but still has not swung a bat since Tuesday. In the first
three games he missed, the Braves did not drive in a run from the
clean-up position, No. 4 replacement hitters going a collective
2-for-11. It should be noted the Braves did not have a runner in
scoring position in any of those 11 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Time marches on
</P>
<P>
   The club refuses to set any timetable for the possible return of
closer Mark Wohlers, currently on minor-league assignment in
Orlando. But management acknowledges now that Wohlers couldn't
possibly be back until after the All-Star break (July 9) at the
earliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that,'' said general manager John Schuerholz.
``(The break) is only a week away and he hasn't begun to pitch in
competition yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Working overtime
</P>
<P>
   Over the previous 16 innings entering Saturday's game, Atlanta's
bullpen has produced just five 1-2-3 innings. Mike Cather has been
the most effective with two of those innings but has also given up
three runs in his last three appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Canseco was a late scratch from the Blue Jays' lineup,
replaced by Juan Samuel. Canseco strained his back swinging at an
inside pitch from Mike Cather in his last at-bat Friday night and
was troubled by spasms before the game. ... Irene Saez, Miss
Universe 1981 from Venezuela, was at Turner Field before the game
to film an ad with the Braves' Venezuelan contingent. Currently the
mayor of Chacao, a city adjacent to Caracas, Seaz is running for
Venezuela's president and a photo opportunity with Galarraga, Ozzie
Guillen and Eddie Perez couldn't hurt. Incidently, a woman is
ineligible to run for president in Venezuela unless she is married
and Saez is single. For the record, Galarraga, Guillen and Perez
are all hitched.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
