<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On deck:Toronto blue jays
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: 1:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV, radio: TBS, 750-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: LHP Tom Glavine (10-3, 2.72; first
appearance vs. Blue Jays) vs. RHP Chris Carpenter (4-2, 4.65; first
appearance vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The only Braves starter to beat the New York Yankees,
Glavine reached 10 victories in 16 starts. Last year in his season
of 12 no-decisions, Glavine did not win his 10th game until his
20th start on July 16. He has lost only once in his last nine
games, that to Florida 3-2 on June 18. He has worked at least into
the seventh inning 12 times and has yielded more than three earned
runs in just three starts. Seven times, he has given up only one
run or less. His current 2.72 ERA is a half-run less than his 3.40
career rate entering the season. His only experience against the
Blue Jays came in the 1992 World Series when he allowed just three
earned runs in two starts but still went only 1-1. Carpenter,
Toronto's first pick in the 1993 draft, has begun to show the
ability that management hopes will help lead the franchise back
from some medicore seasons. The Jays' fifth starter, he will be
making his ninth start and will show the Braves a fastball that
tops out in the mid-90s. He is still learning to change speeds, a
last step in his development that should help reduce a high hit
ratio (76 hits in 69 2/3 innings). Just 23, he is in his first full
season in the majors.
</P>
