<SLUG> BC-INSIDE-BASEBALL-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Lasorda's team again
</P>
<P>
   By I.J. Rosenberg
</P>
<P>
   c. 19998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- As usual, Tommy Lasorda has won.
</P>
<P>
   While almost every vestige of Dodger tradition has been either
eliminated or stepped on, Lasorda has survived and is back on top.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza. Gone.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell. Gone.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Claire. Gone.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Dodger uniform. Gone next year.
</P>
<P>
   But not Lasorda, not the 70-year-old Hall of Famer who pulled
the perfect power play. Now, instead of running the team from the
dugout, he's the general manager. The man who once was one of the
game's biggest ambassadors _ and best managers _ is calling the
shots again in Chavez Ravine.
</P>
<P>
   They are calling him temporary GM, but getting Lasorda out now
would be like trying to pry a bowl of spaghetti from his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda was sneaky smart, quickly catering to Fox executives
while they were in the process of buying the club. According to
ESPN's Peter Gammons, Lasorda traveled everywhere on the personal
jet of Michael Milken, who brokered the sale and is a
behind-the-scenes power in the ownership. Fox was tired of the
club's bland personalities _ manager Russell and GM Claire _ out
front and was won over by Lasorda's magnetism.
</P>
<P>
   The question is who Lasorda will choose as the next Dodgers
manager. In place right now is the interim Glenn Hoffman, but he is
expected to be back in the minors next year, barring a great
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda would like Mets manager Bobby Valentine to work under
him. Valentine was the Dodgers' first-round pick in 1968 and played
in the minors for Lasorda. Valentine has a three-year, $2.1 million
contract with the Mets, who insist that he doesn't have any escape
clause in the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have one of the greatest jobs in the world,'' Valentine
said. ``I'm not desirous of any other job.'' Another interesting
move Lasorda might make is bringing back Piazza, now with the Mets
and a free agent after the season. Lasorda is Piazza's godfather,
and Piazza's father is Lasorda's closest childhood friend. When
asked about the possibility of going back to L.A., Piazza said, ``I
can't answer about the past. I can't answer about the future. I'm
dealing with the present.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens, don't let the ``interim'' in Lasorda's
title fool you. He's back in charge, back trying to put the Dodgers
on top again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom will be involved in all the decisions from here on out,''
team president Dan Graziano said.
</P>
<P>
   Funny _ isn't that what Claire said earlier this year?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
