<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mast in a Sears groove
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, CALIF. _ Listen to Rick Mast for a couple of seconds and
you wouldn't expect this Virginia farm boy to be a spokesman for
higher education. He's a guy who, at 16, traded a cow for his first
race car.
</P>
<P>
   But here he is at Sears Point Raceway testifying that even at 41
you're never too old to get more educatin'.
</P>
<P>
   Mast starts seventh in today's Save Mart/Kragen 350 at Sears
Point on the basis of a qualifying speed of 97.907 mph. It gives
the 10-year veteran a chance at a decent finish.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon starts on the pole beside the surprising Jerry
Nadeau. Winston Cup points leader Jeremy Mayfield, a winner for the
first time last week at Pocono, Pa., starts fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Mast has had a mostly luckless career. He's started 260 races,
won none. He has seven top-five finishes, 31 top-10s. His best
finish this year is 11th, twice. He's led only 61 laps in the No.
75 Ford Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   His history on this track is just as dismal. Six races, started
as close as 24th once and finished as high as 11th. He didn't even
qualify here last year.
</P>
<P>
   So while other drivers with more impressive overall performances
struggle to make sense of this road course that features right-hand
turns, narrow turns lined with tires and a new configuration called
The Chute, Mast has been performing like an honor graduate of a
road-race driving school.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that hurt me was I guess I was the only
driver that never went to one of these schools,'' Mast said. ``And
I've never been to these places and tested. Those two things seemed
to help me out tremendously this year.''
</P>
<P>
   So two months ago, Mast enrolled in the Bondurant road-racing
school in Phoenix and he feels so enlightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned the technique,'' Mast said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do in oval-track racing, enter the turns where there's
no mark or anything that I use, you drive by feel when you get out
of the gas, slant into the banking. The car does whatever it does
and you try to accelerate as quick as you can to exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In road racing, there's a mark, hit the brakes. There's a
mark, shift. There's a mark, turn the wheel. In road racing, as you
enter the turn, the brake has to do what the banking does to the
car in oval-track racing. That's what always got me into trouble in
qualifying, over-running all the turns, trying to get into the
turns too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience has been a boost to Mast's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an awfully good race car,'' he said. ``This is a new
car. We tested out here with it and I went to the school deal. I
don't know how much has made the difference. I think it's half me
and half the race car.''
</P>
<P>
   He's thinking maybe his luck has changed. He looks over his
winless career and muses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always different things with the car,'' Mast said. ``The
left front apron fell off at Michigan once. Water pump give out at
Charlotte once. We got in somebody's oil at Charlotte once. We lost
a cylinder at Pocono once. Just on and on and on. There's about
13-14 races like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to look back over the last three-four years if I had
no races that I had a shot at winning, I wouldn't be doing this.
Believe me, I would not. Because there's too many people that put
too much into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
