<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-NOTBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lepage bolts Falk for Roush Racing
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Smack in the middle of wine country, sour
grapes were flying everywhere Saturday at Sears Point Raceway
concerning Kevin Lepage, a rookie driver who has yet to win a
Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   In quick order, Roush Racing confirmed that it has hired Lepage
for the 1999 season. Roush, which manages nine Nascar teams
including Winston Cup, Busch and truck series, has a 30-day option
to figure out where to place Lepage.
</P>
<P>
   Still smarting from this development, Lepage's current boss, LJ
Racing owner Joe Falk informed Lepage after second-round qualifying
that he would replace him with Tommy Kendall in the No. 91
Chevrolet for today's Save Mart/Kragen 350.
</P>
<P>
   Lepage balked and quit.
</P>
<P>
   The 91 car goes into today's race as a provisional entry after
its second-round qualifying speed, 95.114 mph, placed it 45th among
the 48 cars trying to make the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Falk ain't the richest guy in this garage, but I've got
enough money to run this car for the rest of the year,'' Falk said.
``We were close to signing a sponsor. That sponsor wanted Kevin, so
I wouldn't doubt if you see a Roush car with that sponsor.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Lepage: ``Joe Falk is trying to get a sponsor but with
the way he handled the situation like this people got to wonder if
it was a wise decision from a business standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Lepage and Falk had a handshake agreement that came undone last
week when Lepage gave his car owner a two-week notice. Falk will
now get help from Team Sabco owner Felix Sabates, whose No. 46
Chevy Kendall had failed to qualify in. Lepage was heading home to
North Carolina, without a ride for next weekend's Winston Cup race
at Daytona Beach and certain his status as second in rookie point
standings will have diminished. Rumor, however, has him replacing
Ted Musgrave in Roush's No. 16 Ford as early as next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping it wouldn't come down to this,'' Lepage said.
``If it wasn't for me being part of the race team and working hard,
we wouldn't be in a position for a provisional. But obviously they
felt that with Tom Kendall having road-race experience they would
be in a much better situation with him behind the wheel. I'm
disappointed.'' Kendall becomes the beneficiary in all of this. He
won 11 straight road races on the SCCA circuit last season and
wound up without a ride this year. He's started 11 Winston Cup road
races with a best finish of eighth at Watkins Glen in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Martin sets pace
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin led the competition in the second round of
qualifying Saturday with a lap of 98.147 mph. He'll start 26th.
Martin's practice-lap speed of 98.983 mph was faster than Jeff
Gordon's pole speed of 98.711
</P>
<P>
   Speed hurts
</P>
<P>
   Lake Speed, who bruised ribs in a practice accident Friday, ran
four practice laps Saturday before quitting because of discomfort.
He'll decide on his status for today's race in the morning. Butch
Gilliland qualified the No. 9 Ford Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   Pedersen takes Yahoo
</P>
<P>
   Ken Petersen, driving a Chevy, won the 64-lap Yahoo! Sports 200
Nascar Featherlite Southwest Series race, his third win in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
