<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NLNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League Notes
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   With Todd Hundley close to returning, the Mets aren't sure where
they are going to play him. Because he underwent reconstructive
elbow surgery and the club wants to take some work off that part of
the body, it's doubtful that he would return to catcher. ``That
could be 1,400 throws (to the pitcher) in a week, when you figure
in all the throws before innings,'' Hundley said. With Mike Piazza
catching, Hundley might end up in left field.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The new Hall of Fame program is out, and Braves announcer
Don Sutton figures prominently on the front in a Dodgers uniform,
and, yes, he's wearing curls. Sutton will be the 62nd pitcher
inducted. The ceremonies are July 26. ... The Phillies' Bobby Abreu
has 11 assists, tops among major-league outfielders. ... Since July
28 of last season, the Phillies have the third-best record in the
league at 77-58, trailing the Braves (86-49) and Giants (78-57).
... The Marlins are considering replacing the slumping Derrek Lee
at first base with minor-leaguer Kevin Millar
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs are disappointed with center fielder Lance Johnson.
Many of his teammates think that nothing is physically wrong with
Johnson, who insists he has a hand problem and can't play. He is
starting to become a distraction in the clubhouse, and the team may
try to trade him. But moving Johnson will be difficult because he
makes $4.9 million this year and $5.1 million in 1999. One report
has Johnson going to Colorado, which needs a center fielder and
leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Pirates catcher Jason Kendall has become a master of the
plunking. Kendall was hit by a pitch 31 times last year and has
been struck 11 times this season. ``I'm one of those players who's
going to do anything I can to help the team win,'' he said. ...
Proving that St. Louis has never seen much power before Mark
McGwire, only three Cardinals over the last half century have hit
33 home runs in one season. McGwire already has 35. Those three old
Redbird longballers were Stan Musial, Dick Allen and, most
recently, Jack Clark. ... Speaking of the Cardinals, an interesting
quote about draft choice J.D. Drew comes from his manager in the
Northern League. Marty Scott of the St. Paul Saints: ``Money is not
a driving force in his life, as far as I can tell.'' ... Cubs first
baseman Mark Grace is 33-for-89 this month but has just two RBIs.
The reason is that Sammy Sosa, hitting ahead of him, has 19 homers
in June.
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   With Bobby Bonilla on the disabled list, the Dodgers have
promoted from Class AA San Antonio power-hitting third baseman
Adrian Beltre, perhaps the top prospect in the organization.
Beltre, 20, was hitting .321 with 13 home runs and 56 RBIs. If he
can handle major-league pitching, he may end up as the club's
starter at third, no matter what happens with Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Padres starter Kevin Brown is 6-0 in his last seven
starts. ... When San Diego's Tony Gwynn recently went hitless for
14 at-bats, it was the longest drought of his career. He broke out
of it by going 3-for-4. More Gwynn: He has just one fewer home run
(seven) than strikeouts (eight) and is threatening to become only
the second player since 1958 to finish with more homers than
strikeouts. In 1980, Kansas City's George Brett hit 24 homers and
struck out only 22 times. ... Giants slugger Barry Bonds hit his
391st home run, putting him 29th on the all-time list. Next to pass
is Dale Murphy, at 398. ... There hasn't been a 20-game loser since
Brian Kingman for Oakland in 1980, but Arizona's Willie Blair is
headed that way. Going into the weekend, Blair was 2-11.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
