<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-SPORTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FOOTBALL'S POPULARITY CAN BE FELT AT ITS INTERNET SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story isn't new: Internet site with down-home appeal finds
transplanted souls yearning for a taste of back home.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case with ``Dave Campbell's Texas Football''.
</P>
<P>
   The annual magazine's international popularity has become a
pleasant yet costly surprise for its producer, Host Communications
of Dallas. It all started when the online version of ``Texas
Football'' (www.texasfootball.com) began accepting orders for the
352-page print magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Dave Stephenson said it has always been evident that
transplanted Texans who follow college and high school football in
Texas have wanted a way to order the magazine online.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, Stephenson had no idea how many would take advantage
or from where they would be ordering.
</P>
<P>
   As such, ``Texas Football'' has had to reconfigure its online
system to accommodate domestic and international orders. And
shipping the magazine around the world is going beyond the quoted
$3 first-class charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're biting the bullet,'' Stephenson said. ``We're
charging $3 for first-class mailing when it's costing us $20.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to peruse ``Texas Football'' for free on the
Internet, be warned that the online version doesn't have all of the
content for which the 39-year-old magazine is known. But it does
have enough to make it a worthy companion publication.
</P>
<P>
   New online features at ``Texas Football'' include cover choices
(featuring Texas or Texas A&AMP;M) for online magazine buyers and a
collection of links to high schools with Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Football'' online also includes news about
football-related events in Texas, a chat area, schedules for every
high school and back issues. During the season, the site will
compile statistics and standings of the state's high school
football teams, Stephenson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it to be a huge undertaking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson said his company gets several calls from readers
wanting the entire magazine to be online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could transfer things over pretty simply, but we only want
portions of it on there, like the Super Team and the Texas Top
300,'' he said. ``When we run out of room \Rin the magazine\S, we
want the Web site to always be an extension you can go to.''
</P>
<P>
   Being online means immediate feedback, Stephenson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear our share of criticism and get a bunch of critiques,''
he said. ``The magazine has such a tradition, the community gets a
feeling of ownership, and they tell you what they like or don't
like.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about the Internet, there's someone out there who
always wants a little more.''
Bytes Downloads: America's Health Network (www.ahn.com), the
3-month-old company that brought us the first public online
broadcast of a live birth, has entered into a content-sharing
alliance with ESPN SportsZone and ABCNEWS.com. AHN will sponsor and
provide exclusive content for SportsZone's new Training Room health
and fitness section in partnership with the Association of
Professional Team Physicians ... The Sporting News Online is
launching an online contest for baseball fans who can't get enough
coverage of Mark McGwire's assault on the single-season home run
record. At McGwire Mania (www.sportingnews.com/mcgwire),
contestants can compete for prizes by guessing the total distance
of McGwire's home runs this season ... Some interesting figures for
the month of May from MediaMetrix, a New York-based company that
tracks Internet use: While the NHL was in the midst of its
playoffs, NHL.com attracted 1.2 million at-home users, but the NFL
had 1.1 million users in its off-season. The leader was NBA.com
with 1.7 million at-home users, ahead of Major League Baseball
(www.majorleaguebaseball.com) with 1.4 million ... CBS SportsLine
has redesigned its site with fewer graphics to reduce download time
and provide faster access.
</P>
<P>
   Chat highlights: Larry Hughes, the Philadelphia 76ers'
first-round draft choice, is a scheduled chat participant at 1 p.m.
tomorrow on ESPN SportsZone. Former Kentucky star Nazr Mohammed, a
draft-night acquisition by the 76ers, is scheduled to chat an hour
later.
</P>
<P>
   Ride for Life: Details, maps and registration forms for the
Leukemia Society of America's Ride for Life bicycling fund-raiser
on July 11 in Westlake are available at a site
(members.aol.com/ridelife98) created by Steve Krieger.
</P>
