<HEADLINE>
GENTLEMEN NOT USED TO UNDERDOG ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  INGLEWOOD _ The (begin ital)other(end ital) horse in the
Hollywood Gold Cup today is the defending champion, the one whose
trainer has won the past six runnings of the major Southern
California races for older thoroughbreds, the one whose jockey is
the latest Hall of Fame inductee, and the one whose owner runs the
track.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen doesn't fit the usual description of an underdog, even
if he and entrymate Puerto Madero are 7-5 second choices behind
even-money Skip Away on the morning line for the eight-horse Gold
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't just enter (Gentlemen) so I'd have a seat up in the
Director's Room,'' trainer Richard Mandella said on the eve of the
$1 million race.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away flew here from his New York base this week with a No.
1 ranking and a six-race winning streak in his suitcase. Although
East-to-West shippers traditionally struggle, Skip Away has made
this trip with success before, winning the Breeders' Cup Classic at
Hollywood Park last November.
</P>
<P>
   But Gentlemen has a few things going for him:
</P>
<P>
   _Gentlemen is at least the equal of Skip Away on their best day.
He won their only meeting, the 1997 Pimlico Special in Baltimore,
by half a length while carrying three more pounds. Everybody
carries 124 today.
</P>
<P>
   _Mandella can do no wrong in the Gold Cup, the Santa Anita
Handicap and Del Mar's Pacific Classic. The trainer's six straight
victories include Dare and Go's upset of Cigar, two wins by
Gentlemen and a pair of 1-2-3 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   _Jockey Gary Stevens is bent on taking the Eclipse Award away
from Skip Away's East Coast-based rider Jerry Bailey, who won it
the past three years. Having recently decided not to spend the rest
of the year in the East, accepting an offer to ride first call on
Bob Baffert's powerful stable here, Stevens will be eager to
upstage Bailey in a nationally televised intersectional showdown.
</P>
<P>
   As for the fact Gentlemen owner R.D. Hubbard is the Hollywood
Park chairman, that shouldn't really be an advantage for the horse.
Still, Hubbard had his usual swagger at the ceremony where post
positions were drawn Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to tell you,'' he said to Carolyn and Sonny Hine, Skip
Away's owner and trainer, ``what's going to happen to you Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gentlemen hasn't raced since suffering from respiratory
bleeding and finishing last in the March 7 Big 'Cap. Skip Away has
won twice since then.
</P>
<P>
   Can Gentlemen fire his best shot after a 3{-month layoff?
Actually, with Mandella training, he'll be expected to.
Horse-watchers who saw Gentlemen this week said he looks
tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Mandella) is a good horseman, he pays attention to
details,'' Sonny Hine said this week. ``That's why I worry about
Gentlemen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 2255EDT &QL; 
