<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK STOPS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Hitchcock was so good, it was scary.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Padres pitcher Sterling Hitchcock took a no-hitter
into the eighth inning Saturday afternoon before the Angels' Phil
Nevin homered leading off the inning to spoil the no-hit bid. But
it didn't stop the Padres from beating the Angels for the second
day in a row 5-1 before 31,948 at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Angels' second in a row, marking the first time
they have lost back-to-back games in a month _ they lost May 25 and
27 to the Royals. The Padres have won 16 of 19.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, the Angels maintained their 1{-game lead in
the AL West over Texas. San Diego remained 6{ games ahead of San
Francisco in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock (4-1) finished with a complete-game two-hitter,
striking out nine and walking one. The Angels' only other hit was
an infield hit by Damon Mashore that could have been ruled an error
when Hitchcock failed to pick up a roller in front of the mound.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Angels came to a hit through seven innings came
on Dave Hollins' low liner toward shortstop Chris Gomez in the
fourth inning. Gomez backhanded the ball on a shorthop, then began
a 6-4-3 double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he missed a spot all day,'' Nevin said. ``He
pitched to his spots, and he didn't throw many balls right down the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin actually broke his bat on the home run, hitting a
curveball _ Hitchcock's only mistake of the afternoon and his first
pitch of the eighth inning _ over the fence in left.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the kind of guy today you didn't want to fall behind
(in the count),'' Nevin said. ``I wouldn't say I was looking for a
curveball, but he left it up in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had thrown some curveballs over the plate for first-pitch
strikes, and I tried to get it over,'' Hitchcock said. ``I hung it,
and that's where hanging curveballs go.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly a big part of the Angels' inability to hit Hitchcock
was their scouting report. Angels manager Terry Collins said
Hitchcock had a good changeup working, but Hitchcock said he only
threw one changeup all day.
</P>
<P>
   That was his splitter the Angels struggled with, and Collins
said there was no mention of a splitter in their report on
Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly with (pitching coach) Dave Stewart over there, some
guys are going to have it I'm sure,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   After Nevin's homer in the eighth, the Angels put runners on
first and second with one out on Mashore's single and an error by
Gomez at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   But Gomez made up for it by fielding Paco Martin's chopper up
the middle, stepping on second and throwing to first for the
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got a decent performance from starter Omar Olivares
(5-3), who stayed close until the later innings. With a 1-0 lead in
the sixth, the Padres had a couple of seeing-eye groundballs find
holes in the infield on their way to a two-run inning. They scored
another run off Olivares in the seventh when Tony Gwynn rolled one
down the right-field line for an RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt real good. I felt I was doing everything right,
Olivares said. ``A couple of groundballs got through the infield.
It's part of the game. There's nothing I can do about that. I was
happy with the way I pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock was that much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you only get two hits, it's pretty hard to say anything
about anything else, except the guy pitched a good ballgame,''
Collins said. ``Certainly we didn't play the way we've been
playing. One thing we've done during the month is spread out our
offense. Today, we didn't get anything from anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
