<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GIANTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDFUL OF ERRORS DOOMS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Consider Rangers first baseman Will Clark armed
and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Rangers' season-high five errors appeared as
significant as the one Clark committed in the seventh inning of a
6-5 loss to the Giants in 10 innings yesterday at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's errant throw _ the first of three seventh-inning errors
by the Rangers _ resulted in two unearned runs on an afternoon in
which defensive deficiencies opened the door for a game-winning
single by Giants center fielder Darryl Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a ballgame that we had every opportunity to win,''
Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers began the seventh inning with a 5-3 lead, but
Hamilton, who was 4-for-6 and scored twice, started the inning with
a single. Left-hander Eric Gunderson appeared to remedy that
situation with an apparent pickoff, but Clark's throw toward
shortstop Kevin Elster glanced off Hamilton's left shoulder and put
a runner in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sign of a decent pitcher is picking up your infielders
when they don't make a play,'' Gunderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to record an out proved costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed the whole complexion of the inning,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson surrendered consecutive two-out, run-scoring singles
to right fielder Stan Javier and third baseman Bill Mueller, who
sent home first baseman J.T. Snow with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough play for Will,'' Oates said, referring to Clark's
sore left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clark also has a below-average arm for a major-league
first baseman, and that is often apparent. Clark, though, said his
arm did not play a role on the error.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said Hamilton, whom he called a ``veteran runner,'' ran
out of the baseline and into the infield grass to thwart his throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw the ball right where I wanted, and he ran right over
into the middle of it, but that's not what cost us the game,''
Clark said. ``They got a bunch of two-out base hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Television replays and Elster suggested otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was within a foot of the baseline,'' Elster said of
Hamilton. ``He came inside, but he didn't come way inside. Will
made a nice throw in a gusty wind, but it was just one of those
things that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Those things happened often yesterday for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   A first-inning throwing error by third baseman Fernando Tatis
hit Hamilton in the back before he crossed the plate with the
Giants' first run, and center fielder Roberto Kelly fumbled
seventh-inning singles by Javier and Mueller. Kelly's misplays
allowed runners to advance an extra base.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Luis Alicea, who replaced Tatis as a pinch hitter
in the ninth inning, committed the fifth and final error, which led
to the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea missed a one-out ground ball off the bat of catcher Brian
Johnson. The ball went under the glove of Alicea, who played the
ball to his left side, resulting in a two-base error.
</P>
<P>
   Giants left-hander Shawn Estes replaced Johnson as a pinch
runner and scored the winning run from second base on Hamilton's
single off right-hander Danny Patterson. It was the Giants' fourth
unearned run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't our best ballgame of the year,'' Oates said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
