<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO ROOM FOR WATSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Pitcher Allen Watson, who had a strained flexor
muscle in his left elbow, has proclaimed himself ready to rejoin
the rotation. The only problem for the lefty is there is no spot
available for him.
</P>
<P>
   Watson has made three rehab starts and will be activated next
week, but since the Angels starters _ primarily Jarrod Washburn and
Steve Sparks _ have done so well as fill-ins, Angels manager Terry
Collins might be reluctant to make changes.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said if that's what Collins wants, he'll pitch in the
bullpen _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are doing well, I don't want to disturb the team,''
Watson said. ``If they need me before the (All-Star) break in the
bullpen, I want to do what's best for the team. But I don't want to
be in the bullpen for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys filling in have done a great job, but I'm not going
to root against them. I'm not hoping someone gets hurt. That's not
my style. But when I'm healthy, I win. If I don't play here, I'll
play somewhere else. My main goal is to be healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson had good numbers in his rehab start Friday for Triple-A
Vancouver _ 6 IP, 3 R, 6 H, 8 K, 2 BB _ but the number that stood
out to Collins and his staff was 98.
</P>
<P>
   That was the number of pitches Watson threw, which exceeded the
limit of 90 the club had set for him going in. But Watson felt fine
Saturday and said he's feeling the best he's felt in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is I could throw my breaking pitches. It's something
I couldn't do the whole year,'' he said. ``I went back to my old
mechanics. Everything felt strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough calls: In Friday night's game against the Padres, the
Angels struck out 12 times, nine of them coming on called-third
strikes by plate umpire Angel Hernandez. Was Hernandez a bit
liberal with the strike zone? Collins wouldn't say.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins did say that any time an American League team plays
with National League umps, and vice versa, figuring out the strike
zone can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``After being in this league a couple of years, I can tell you
that every umpire's different,'' Collins said. ``When you're not
familiar with them, it makes it hard to know what you're approach
is going to be. We didn't know (Hernandez). When we're playing in
the AL, we know what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres starter Sterling Hitchcock had nine strikeouts Saturday,
but only three were called.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National League strike zone is a little bigger, it's not a
secret,'' Angels catcher Phil Nevin said. ``If our guy gets those
pitches, that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra innings: The Padres Tony Gwynn was 1 for 20 lifetime
against Angels starter Omar Olivares going into Saturday's game,
but he went 2 for 4 on Saturday.... The Padres have never had a
no-hitter in club history, although Hitchcock has thrown one. In
1990, Hitchcock threw a no-hitter for the Single-A Greensboro
Hornets in the South Atlantic League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-98 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
