<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LEVENSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMANUEL LEVENSON, 81, MUSIC EDUCATOR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Emanuel Levenson, who shared his love of opera with
schoolchildren across the country, died on June 9 at the University
of Michigan Hospital in Ann Arbor. He was 81 and lived in
Ypsilanti, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Levenson, a graduate of Columbia University, studied piano with
Joseph Adler and taught piano and vocal techniques. He directed an
opera workshop at the New School for Social Research, and he was
music director of the After Dinner Opera Company.
</P>
<P>
   He founded the Pennybridge Opera Company in Brooklyn and the
Berkshire Pro Musica in Pittsfield, Mass., and was a founder of the
Becket Arts Center in Becket, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   He was the director of the music organization called Young
Audiences when the group brought opera performers into schools.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Fay; a stepdaughter, Davi Napoleon;
a sister, Judith Corin, of Anacortes, Wash.; a brother, Mickey, of
Castro Valley, Calif.; and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
