<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-CHURCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS ATTEND CHURCH  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ On Sunday morning, president and Mrs. Clinton attended
services at Chongwenmen Church, the largest officially-sanctioned
church in Beijing, with nearly 3,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation presented Clinton with a bilingual Bible and
invited him to speak to the overflow crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We celebrate with you the growth of the practice of our faith
in China,'' Clinton said in remarks that lasted less than five
minutes. ``I believe our faith calls upon us to seek unity with
people across the world with different backgrounds and races and
creeds.''
</P>
<P>
   The president added: ``I believe Chinese and Americans are
brothers and sisters as children of God. We come here in that
spirit today.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's schedule for Sunday included a tour of the
Forbidden City palace in Beijing and a trip to the Great Wall. In
the evening, Clinton and Jiang were to hold a private dinner at the
Zhongnanhai government compound.
</P>
</TEXT>
